<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RighttoDie     03-11 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Right to Die,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family Says Patient Would Want to Die</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA BRYSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARTHAGE, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The victim of a 1983 traffic accident would
not want to be kept alive in the helpless state in which she has
been maintained, the woman's older sister testified at a
right-to-die trial Thursday.
   Last year, the parents of 30-year-old Nancy Cruzan, who is in
what doctors call a ``persistent vegetative state,'' sued the state
to force doctors to allow her to die by removing a feeding tube
from her stomach.
   It is the first case in Missouri to address the question of
whether food and water can be denied patients like Ms. Cruzan.
   Assistant Attorney General Robert Presson contends Missouri law
prohibits such a step. Staff members at the State Rehabilitation
Center at Mount Vernon said removing the feeding tube would violate
their medical mission.
   Doctors say Ms. Cruzan's brain stem was nearly the only part of
her brain left intact after she was deprived of oxygen for several
minutes after the accident.
   On Thursday, the second day of trial in Jasper County Probate
Court, her older sister, Christy White, testified that Ms. Cruzan
was a vital, sometimes headstrong, woman who had said on at least
two occasions that she would not want to live if she could not do
so independently.
   Her father, Joe Cruzan of Carterville, said he could ``see no
purpose in forcing her to go through the indignities she's going
through now.''
   ``When she has a bowel movement, they have to change her
diaper,'' he said. ``I know the hospital does the best it can, but
Nancy drools. Sometimes ... her hair will be wet, the pillow, her
gown. I just feel like it's beneath her dignity to continue like
this.''
   Lisa Perrin, a nurse at the rehabilitation center who said she
has seen Ms. Cruzan daily for the past three years, testified: ``I
was trained to preserve life and I don't want to enhance death.''
   Dr. James C. Davis, Ms. Cruzan's physician, said that a legal
ruling would help him make a decision but that he still would
hesitate to counsel the Cruzan's to pursue their plan.
   ``Mentally, they're going to have problems somewhere down the
line that they brought about the death of their daughter,'' he
said. ``And if they don't do it, they will have the same problem
with her continued suffering. Either way, they're going to have
problems.''
</TEXT>
