<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Afghanistan-Violations     03-11 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan-Violations,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Human Rights Groups Report Continued Atrocities in 1987</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The people of Afghanistan continued to suffer
human rights abuses at the hands of both government and rebel
forces last year, according to a report by two groups that monitor
human rights.
   The March report of the U.S. Helsinki Watch Committee and the
Asia Watch Committee is based on a September-October fact-finding
mission to Pakistan, Afghanistan's neighbor to the south and a base
for opposition forces fighting the Soviet-backed government.
   The report's authors said all requests to visit Kabul or other
cities under the government's control went unanswered.
   ``Afghanistan has been the scene of some of the most serious
human rights violations on record,'' the report said. ``About
one-half of the country's prewar population ... is either in
emigration, or internally displaced, or dead.''
   The report, the committees' fourth on human rights violations in
Afghanistan since 1984, noted that most abuses reported previously
had continued. The government is guilty of most of the abuses, it
said.
   ``Indiscriminate warfare in the countryside combined with
totalitarian controls in the cities have brought incalculable
suffering to the Afghan people,'' it said.
   Resistance groups also were accused of violations, as in
previous reports.
   ``We continue to deplore the execution of prisoners of war by
the resistance, often after a trial that is lacking in most aspects
of what we consider due process,'' the report said.
   It specifically mentioned abuses by the Hezb-I-Islami resistance
group, led by Gulbaddin Hekmatyar.
   ``Abuses by this group seem to have become even more extreme in
the past year and reportedly include politically motivated
assassinations, the taking of hostages,'' the committees said.
   If a settlement is reached in Afghanistan's civil war, the
committees said, the Hezb-I-Islami and other groups ``guilty of
gross human rights violations'' should not be given much influence
in a new government.
   The report noted ``seemingly positive developments'' in 1987,
including the government's call for refugees to return to
Afghanistan and amnesty declarations for thousands of prisoners.
   The New York-based U.S. Helsinki Watch Committee was founded in
1979 to promote domestic and international compliance with human
rights provisions of the 1975 Helsinki accords.
   The Washington-based Asia Watch Committee was founded in 1985 to
promote internationally recognized human rights in Asia. Both are
private, non-profit groups.
</TEXT>
