<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JFKNote     03-11 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-JFK Note,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President's Missile Crisis Note Auctioned for $10,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A page of notes jotted by President John F.
Kennedy during the 1962 Cuban missile crisis sold for $10,000 at
auction Thursday.
   The unsigned page includes the words ``bombers'' and
``Alpha-66,'' code for a group of Cuban exiles who conducted
commando raids on the country, said auctioneer Herman Darvik.
   At the bottom of the note is the start of a draft of a letter to
Soviet leader Nikita Khruschev, Darvik said.
   The note, which had been owned by a private dealer, was
purchased by the American Museum of Historical Documents, a private
dealer in Las Vegas that has a large Kennedy collection, he said.
   Other items sold Thursday by Herman Darvik Autograph Auctions
were a signed photograph of Sitting Bull, which brought $3,500; a
signature of George Washington clipped from a document, $2,750, and
a letter from Marilyn Monroe to her lawyer, $1,650.
   A photo of Air Force One signed by Presidents Ronald Reagan,
Richard Nixon, Jimmy Carter and Gerald Ford went for $2,750, Darvik
said.
</TEXT>
