<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CigaretteMortality     03-11 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cigarette Mortality,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One in Three Smokers Dies Prematurely, Cancer Society Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 35 percent of smokers die prematurely
because of tobacco, the American Cancer Society estimates.
   ``If smokers could just think of those odds as twice as bad as
those for Russian roulette, they might understand how dangerous the
cigarette habit really is,'' Harmon Eyre, national society
president, said in a statement.
   The estimate refers to all tobacco-related causes of death, such
as lung cancer and heart disease, a cancer society spokesman said.
   It appears in the society's new publication, ``Cancer Facts &
Figures _ 1988.''
   Some 40 percent of male smokers and 28 percent of female smokers
die prematurely, the society said.
   The estimate is derived from population data, and the higher
percentage for men reflects the fact that men have historically
smoked longer and in greater amounts than women, rather than any
significant sex-based difference in risk for individual smokers,
the society spokesman said.
   The society estimates that smoking is related to 320,000 deaths
a year, including 30 percent of all cancer deaths. It blames
cigarettes for 85 percent of lung cancer cases among men and 75
percent among women.
   Among males, smokers run more than twice the rate of non-smokers
for cancer death, while among women the difference is 67 percent,
the society says.
   The society also said lung cancer remains the nation's leading
cancer killer within each sex. Some 152,000 new cases are expected
this year, with 139,000 deaths.
</TEXT>
