<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Guatemala-Police     03-11 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Guatemala-Police,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Treasury Police Head Fired After Suspected `Panel Truck of Death'
Found</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALFONSO ANZUETO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government fired the director of the
treasury police after authorities found his agents in a truck
believed to have been used in several recent kidnappings,
authorities said Friday.
   Six of those abducted in the ``panel truck of death'' were
killed, a human rights group said.
   The firing of Oscar Diaz Urquizu, a former security chief for
President Vinicio Cerezo, came after the truck was discovered by
national police.
   Army Col. Julio Caballeros Seigne, the national police director,
said he and members of his personal security guard found the truck
Thursday parked eight miles east of the city.
   The six men inside were wearing treasury police uniforms,
Caballeros Seigne said.
   Baudilio Hichos, third in command of the treasury police,
arrived at the scene to try to free his men.
   The dispute continued at a downtown Guatemala City police
station, where about 100 treasury policemen arrived to defend the
six. After arguing with national police for an hour, they left.
   Interior Minister Juan Rodil Peralta announced the firing Friday
after meetings with heads of both security groups. He named Miguel
Equizabal, second in command, as his interim replacement.
   The six treasury policemen were in custody for questioning on
Friday but had not been charged. Their names were not disclosed.
   Treasury police are assigned to deal with customs matters, but
are said to be involved in other operations. Diaz Urquizu was chief
of security for the campaign of Cerezo, who took office Jan. 14,
1986 as the first civilian president since 1970.
   The Mutual Support Group, an organization of relatives of people
who disappeared in political violence, says six of nine people
known to have been abducted this year by men using a white panel
truck with darkly tinted glass were killed.
   Three others were released, said Herlindo Hicho, a spokesman for
the group.
   It called the vehicle ``the panel truck of death.'' Authorities
had said for several weeks that they were looking for the truck and
had seized or stopped several of the same description.
   Police said they believed the truck stopped Friday night was the
one they had been seeking.
   The number of disappearances and political killings in Guatemala
has declined from the early 1980s when there were as many as 500
killings a month, but cases continue to occur.
   Left-wing insurgents have been fighting the government
sporadically for 25 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
