<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Shamir 2dLd-Writethru a0827 03-11 0882</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Shamir, 2d Ld - Writethru, a0827,0907</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir Attacks U.S. Peace Plan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs after 7th pvs bgng: Foreign Minister ... with
report Arafat also rejects U.S. plan. Pick up 12th graf: In Cairo
...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir on Friday
attacked U.S. peace proposals for the first time in public, saying
they were ``fraught with danger'' and incapable of bringing peace
to the region.
   U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz shuttled through the
region last week to urge Arab and Israeli acceptance of the plan.
   ``The only word I agree with in the U.S. plan is the name
Shultz,'' Shamir was quoted as saying by the Israeli daily
newspaper Haaretz.
   Shamir previously has criticized elements of the U.S. proposal
in private meetings with party officials, but statements published
Friday in a series of interviews constituted his first rejection of
the plan as a whole.
   Shamir's comments on the plan were criticized by a high-ranking
official in Israel's left-of-center Labor Party, which shares power
in a shaky coalition with Shamir's rightist Likud bloc.
   ``It would be extremely artificial if the American people hear
only one unauthorized version,'' former Foreign Minister Abba Eban
told Israel radio.
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, Shamir's rival and a leader of
the Labor Party, supports the plan.
   Yasser Arafat, chairman of the Palestine Liberation
Organization, has rejected the U.S. plan, The New York Times
reported in its Saturday editions. It said that in an interview
Thursday in Tunis, Tunisia, where the PLO has its headquarters,
Arafat said the PLO would no longer settle for indirect
representation through a joint Jordanian-Palestinian delegation as
suggested by Shultz.
   Earlier this week, Arafat's Fatah branch of the PLO had
criticized the U.S. plan.
   Israel and the United States consider the PLO a terrorist
organization. Israel has declared it will never negotiate with the
PLO but would consider talks with a combined delegation of
Jordanians and non-PLO Palestinians.
   In Cairo, President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt and Jordan's King
Hussein said Friday that Shamir would pit himself against world
opinion if he rejects the U.S. peace plan.
   ``I don't think that this (Shamir's comments) will lead to a
comprehensive settlement or a comprehensive peace which is very
important for the whole area and the whole world,'' Mubarak told
reporters after a 3{-hour meeting with the Jordanian leader.
   ``I agree,'' Hussein said.
   Shultz has requested an Israeli decision on the plan by the time
Shamir arrives in Washington on Monday and has publicly complained
that both the Arabs and the Israelis are unwilling to compromise.
   The plan calls for Israel to give up land in the occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip in exchange for peace in the region.
   Shamir said he was particularly disturbed by the part of the
U.S. proposal that calls for kicking off direct negotiations with
an international conference.
   That, he told the English-language Jerusalem Post, ``obligates
me to resist ... with all my power. And my power to resist is very
great.''
   He said the United States had changed its position on the
convening of such a conference without reason and he warned the
proposal was ``fraught with danger.''
   Shamir told Haaretz that while the United States is undeniably a
friend to Israel, ``every bit of it (the U.S. plan) was an attempt
to satisfy the Arabs.''
   The right-wing leader has twice blocked Cabinet votes on whether
Israel should approve the plan.
   The issue is expected to come up a final time before the Shamir
trip during a Cabinet meeting Sunday.
   Eban, a member of Peres' Labor Party, announced Friday he would
travel to the United States hours before Shamir to explain Labor's
position on the peace plan to the Americans.
   ``The fact is that Mr. Shamir did not get any authorization to
refuse the peace plan. No parliament, and no Cabinet agreed to this
refusal,'' Eban said on Israel radio.
   Speaking on Israel radio, Shamir said he would explain to Shultz
``that his plan, as it is seen today, can't solve the problem of
peace in our area and can't guarantee the safety and security of
the state of Israel.''
   Despite Shamir's tough stand, U.S. officials are still hopeful
that Shultz and Reagan may be able to persuade the prime minister
to change his mind, diplomatic sources said.
   Shamir, however, stressed that he will bring the Americans his
own suggestions on how to make the plan more acceptable.
   ``This paper (the plan) given to us is not Moses' commandments
from Mt. Sinai,'' Shamir said on the radio.
   Shamir aide Yossi Ahimeir told The Associated Press the prime
minister would suggest implementing Palestinian self-rule in the
territories on a step-by-step basis, testing the idea in a single
city, for example.
   In addition, the prime minister will suggest that instead of an
international conference, peace talks be held under Soviet-American
auspices, Ahimeir said.
   Finally, Ahimeir said, the prime minister wants a more flexible
timetable than that sought by Washington, which has called for
starting talks on an interim solution in the territories by May and
opening negotiations on the final status of the West Bank and Gaza
by December.
   Shamir wants to delay talks on the final status until self-rule
is implemented throughout the territories, his aide said.
</TEXT>
