<DOCNO> AP880311-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 0202EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-GibraltarBomb     03-11 0761</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gibraltar Bomb,0784</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Discovery Of Car Bomb Eases Political Embarassment</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The discovery in Spain of a car bomb destined for
Gibraltar was a relief to the British government, helping ease
political embarrassment by proving a tragedy had been averted by
the killing of three unarmed IRA members.
   Thwarting the Irish Republican Army operation in the British
colony through pooled British, Irish and Spanish intelligence was a
triumph for international cooperation against terrorism, but the
circumstances raised questions:
   Was it necessary to shoot the guerrillas dead when they were
unarmed? Why did Britain wait 24 hours to declare the falsity of
official reports that a car bomb already had been parked at the
Gibraltar governor's residence?
   The guerrillas were shot Sunday. On Tuesday, Spanish police
found a car laden with explosives in a parking lot at Marbella, a
resort about 45 miles up the coast of southern Spain from the
fortress colony.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's supporters said the discovery
vindicated the army in the shootings.
   ``I am delighted,'' said lawmaker Ivor Stanbrook, who heads a
Parliament committee on Nothern Ireland. ``This confirms all the
evidence which showed that the actions of the British security
services were absolutely justified.''
   Two men and a woman were shot down at midday Sunday as they
walked from a car they had parked at the governor's residence,
called The Convent. A public changing of the guard ceremony was
scheduled for Tuesday morning, involving a British army unit just
transferred from Northern Ireland.
   Men dressed in jeans did the shooting, and were said to be
members of the elite Special Air Services undercover unit. The SAS
has been involved in several operations against the outlawed IRA, a
mainly Roman Catholic group fighting to drive the British from
Protestant-dominated Northern Ireland.
   Protests came from the Irish Republic and from inside Britain.
   The mass-circulation press backed Mrs. Thatcher but the Daily
Telegraph, usually pro-government in Irish matters, said Britain
should ``give ill-wishers no further grounds to suggest that the
authorities operate a `shoot-to-kill' policy against terrorists.''
   In Dublin, the respected Irish Times commented: ``There is
emerging a profound difference between British and Irish attitudes
on the proper response which is demanded by terrorism.''
   Immediately after the shootings, Spanish police and British
officials in Gibraltar spoke of a ``gun battle'' and a ``car bomb.''
   Then the IRA said early Monday the slain trio were in Gibraltar
``on active service,'' reinforcing Britain's contention that the
bomb was in place.
   Britain's armed forces minister, Ian Stanley, described the car
parked near the governor's residence as a ``car bomb'' and British
press reports spoke of hundreds of pounds of explosives.
   Not until Monday afternoon did Sir Geoffrey Howe, the foreign
secretary, tell a surprised House of Commons there were no
explosives in the car and police were searching for another vehicle.
   Official British sources say confusion arose because of
assumptions based on Spanish intelligence and underlined by the IRA
reference to ``active service.''
   Why the immediate resort to gunfire? The response was that
security forces could not be sure the guerrillas were not armed.
   Reporters in London were told Mairead Farrell, an IRA veteran,
``fumbled in her handbag,'' and ``could have been going for a gun,
for some explosive device, anything.''
   On Tuesday, the Irish government said it was ``gravely
perturbed'' that unarmed Irish people ``should have been shot dead
... when it appears they could have been arrested.''
   This enraged British officials and one said privately: ``A lot
of British people are beginning to wonder if they (the Irish) are
serious about combating terrorism.''
   British officials said the 145 pounds of explosives packed into
the car found at Marbella, timed to explode during the military
ceremony Tuesday, could have killed more than 100 people. The
guerrillas apparently parked the first vehicle to secure a space
for the car bomb when arrived later.
   The shooting came at an awkward moment in Anglo-Irish relations.
   Tensions arose in January when Britain announced it would not
prosecute Northern Ireland police officers involved in killing six
Roman Catholics, five of them guerrillas but unarmed, in three
incidents at the end of 1982.
   Those shootings had ``remarkable similarities'' to that in
Gibraltar, the Irish Times said.
   Soon after the government announcement, a British soldier in a
watchtower shot an unarmed Catholic civilian dead at a checkpoint
on the Irish border. The soldier, who is in custody, said it was an
accident but the Irish government ordered its own inquiry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880311-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 0203EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-EasternAirlines     03-11 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern Airlines,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern to Appeal Contempt Citation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines says it will appeal a
contempt-of-court citation imposed by a judge who ruled that plans
to transfer the airlines' shuttle operations to a new corporate
entity violate a 1987 injunction.
   U.S. District Judge John H. Pratt ruled Thursday that the
Miami-based airline was in contempt of his July 2, 1987 order that
it maintain the status quo in working conditions for 12,000
employees represented by the International Association of
Machinists and Aerospace Workers.
   Although the preliminary injunction issued last summer dealt
with a separate labor dispute, Pratt said his order also applied to
any plans to change the working conditions of union workers that
would create a major dispute as defined by the Railway Labor Act.
   The judge scheduled a March 18 hearing to determine what
sanctions to impose against Eastern. The judge could impose a daily
fine to force Eastern to halt its plans to transfer the shuttle to
a new corporate entity under its parent, Texas Air Corp.
   In a complicated financial deal announced last month, Texas Air
will purchase the shuttle operation for $225 million. The Federal
Aviation Administration must approve the transaction and give an
operating certificate to the new operator to take over the shuttle,
which operates between Washington, New York and Boston.
   Airline spokesman Robin Matell said ``Eastern's view is that the
court's ruling is incorrect and we intend to file an expedited
appeal in the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia.
We are confident the court will rule in our favor.''
   The union, meanwhile, said in a statement that ``the court's
order today sends a message to Texas Air that it is not above the
law and it too must comply with the Railway Labor Act.''
   Pratt found that the ``proposed transfer to Texas Air
significantly changes the working conditions of IAM members.''
   ``We find that the proposed `spin off' of Eastern's air shuttle
operations to the new Air Shuttle is not fundamentally different
from the proposed `spin off' of Eastern's fleet services employees
to Air Ground Services,'' the judge's opinion said.
   That spinoff, which was barred last summer, involved plans to
transfer ground crews and baggage handlers to a new subsidiary
called Air Ground Services Inc.
   Eastern's serious financial problems ``do not change the fact
that it proposed a `spin off' of the air shuttle ... is in clear
violation of our July 2, 1987 order, which, whatever doubts Eastern
had as to its meaning and application, it made no attempt to have
clarified or modified,'' the judge said.
   The judge noted that Eastern announced the deal a day after it
dropped its appeal of the preliminary injunction in the Air Ground
case.
   Pratt accepted the union's contention that spinning off the air
shuttle could undermine the machinists' bargaining position with
the company. If fewer than 50 percent of the Air Shuttle's
employees opt to join the IAM, machinists who transferred to the
new subsidiary from Eastern would be without union representation,
the judge noted.
   The decision is the latest in a series of complicated and often
bitter legal fights Eastern is having with its union.
   In a separate action, the Air Line Pilots Association is trying
to bar Eastern from contracting with an air freight hauler to train
pilots to operate the company's planes in the event of a strike
this spring.
   The pilots' union has asked another federal judge here to issue
a temporary restraining order to prevent the use of Eastern
aircraft by Orion Air Inc.
   So far, one plane has been leased to Orion to train pilots who
would fly Eastern aircraft in the event the pilots honor a strike
by the machinists union, according to court testimony. The union
contends this arrangement circumvents the labor contract that
specifies that only its members can operate Eastern planes.
   Eastern contends that the labor agreement does not prevent it
from leasing its aircraft to other companies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880311-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 0209EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-PorkBarrel     03-11 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Pork Barrel,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Releases List of `Pork Barrel' Projects He Wants Cut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has released a symbolic wish
list of projects he wants Congress to strike from its spending
plan, but there appears little chance Capitol Hill will pay much
attention.
   James C. Miller III, director of the Office of Management and
Budget, said that if the list were adopted the savings for fiscal
1988 alone would amount to $1.15 billion.
   Miller, who released the list Thursday, said the money saved
could be used either to reduce the deficit or pay for more
meaningful projects.
   The items were included in the $600 billion catch-all spending
bill approved at the end of last year's congressional session.
   ``I'm hopeful Congress will respond to it,'' Miller said when
asked whether the cuts had any chance of gaining congressional
attention.
   The list, which has no legal power, has no effect unless
Congress moves to adopt it. The president's request was not in the
form of legislation and even when he has made such requests
formally, they have received little support in Congress.
   Reagan's effort appears to fall short of the pledge he made in
his State of the Union address in January.
   In his speech, Reagan repeated his longstanding request for the
line-item veto, which would allow him to delete specific items from
Congress' spending bills.
   In lieu of such power, Reagan said he intended to send back to
Congress, ``in 30 days ... those items, as rescissions, which if I
had the authority to line them out, I would do so.''
   Instead of sending the formal rescissions to Congress, Reagan
sent the informal list.
   Miller explained that the president decided not to send the
formal rescission list because many members of Congress had argued
such an action would upset the bipartisan agreement on the budget
reached last year by the White House and Congress.
   ``This is not an ordinary year,'' Miller said, referring to the
lengthy negotiations that produced the budget agreement.
   GOP sources on Capitol Hill, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said the strategy was adopted to avoid election-year
clashes with Republican lawmakers who won spending projects for
their home districts last year.
   In proposing a formal rescission, Reagan freezes spending on
those items for 45 days and gives procedural advantages to those in
Congress supporting the effort. After the 45-day period, the
spending would be restored unless the rescissions were approved.
   In his 46-page informal list, Reagan cited a myriad of projects
from around the country, including the construction of a ski lift
in Idaho, 15 building projects at universities or medical schools
and even a program to establish a fund to preserve lighthouses.
   Sen. James McClure, R-Idaho, won approval for $6.4 million for a
Kellogg, Idaho, gondola in the $600 billion spending bill approved
late last year. The money was in appropriations for a Forest
Service program that is supposed to pay for development and
management of forests.
   The 15 construction projects included $4 million for a cancer
research center at the Medical University of South Carolina and
$7.5 million for a pediatric research center at the Children's
Hospital of Pittsburgh.
   The list also included historic preservation grants with the
National Park Service that would establish a Bicentennial
Lighthouse Fund to distribute matching grants for the preservation
of lighthouses. The list did not give an exact amount for the item,
saying only that it amounted to ``less than $50,000.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
