<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dole-Endorsement     03-11 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dole-Endorsement,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chicago Tribune Endorses Dole</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Tribune, Illinois' largest newspaper,
endorsed Republican Bob Dole in the state's presidential primary
even as the Kansas senator's campaign appeared to falter.
   In an editorial titled ``Why Illinois Should Pick Dole,'' the
newspaper said in its Friday editions that Dole needs a big primary
win to stay alive in his race against Vice President George Bush
for the GOP presidential nomination.
   ``The vice president's impressive qualifications and his
commanding lead notwithstanding, the Tribune hopes that Sen. Dole
gets that big win, and endorses him in the Illinois Republican
primary on Tuesday,'' the editorial said.
   Dole's campaign has been reeling from its dismal showing in the
Super Tuesday primaries. He pulled television commercials off the
air in Illinois and laid off more than half his staff Thursday.
   Campaign spokeswoman Dale Tate said Thursday that Dole intended
to remain a candidate, but a campaign aide, speaking on condition
of anonymity, said campaign officials were discussing whether the
Senate minority leader should withdraw from the Illinois contest.
   The very lead that Bush amassed on Super Tuesday was cited by
the Tribune as one of its reasons for endorsing Dole.
   ``The combination of Mr. Bush's incumbency and the personal
popularity of President Reagan has brought the vice president to
the brink of nomination without the kind of campaign test both he
and the Republican Party need to have a chance in November,'' the
editorial said.
   ``So far, the fight for the 1988 Republican nomination has been
a replay of the 1984 Democratic one, in which former Vice President
Walter Mondale muscled out all the challengers early and sailed on
to a mighty debacle in the general election.''
   While saying that Bush's identification with the administration
and policies of President Reagan gives him strength among
Republican primary voters, the Tribune suggested that
identification with Reagan might backfire in the general election.
   ``Nowhere have the Republican candidates asked or answered the
kind of harsh questions the Democrats surely will raise in November
about the Reagan administration, whose colors Mr. Bush has been
able to wave more furiously than anyone else,'' the editorial
continued.
   ``Yet voter concern over these issues shows up in opinion polls
that often reflect Sen. Dole as a stronger party standard-bearer
than Mr. Bush in match-ups with Democrats,'' it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
