<DOCNO> AP880311-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 0030EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Democrats-Illinois     03-11 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats-Illinois,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Few Harsh Words As Democrats Meet At Illinois Dinner, Forum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two home-state favorites in the Democratic
presidential fields got the most applause Thursday as five of the
party's presidential contenders appeared at an Illinois Democratic
Party dinner a few days before the state's critical primary.
   Right after the dinner they participated in a low-key forum
sponsored by the Roosevelt Center for American Policy Studies.
   Unlike in the candidates debates held throughout the campaign,
there was no byplay between the contenders and not a cross word
about each other's positions.
   During both events, the candidates stuck closely to their
standard stump speeches.
   At the dinner, Illinois Sen. Paul Simon, known for his trademark
bow ties and horn-rimmed glasses, drew laughter and applause when
he said, ``I want your vote in a beauty contest, believe it or
not.''
   Simon went on to say, ``I offer you not a 30-second commercial
but 30 years service to the people of this state and this nation.''
   ``You will not meet me through a commercial,'' said Jackson, the
other Illinois resident in the presidential race.
   Both Simon and Jackson and running bare-bones campaigns with
little or no money left for advertising. Dukakis is the only
Democrat with the funds to run a full-scale advertising campaign
directed at Illinois voters.
   Simon, who bypassed the Super Tuesday contests earlier this
week, is hoping to get back into contention with a strong vote from
his home state.
   Jackson did well on Super Tuesday and is regarded as a storng
contender in Illinois.
   Gov. Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts, Rep. Richard Gephardt of
Missouri and Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee also are bidding for
support in the primary.
   At the forum, Gore called for ``an all-out war on drugs'' and
repeated his new campaign theme that he wants to bring ``the
Democratic Party back to the neighborhoods.''
   Dukakis described himself at the forum as ``a full-employment
Democrat.''
   On foreign policy, he said, ``We've got to get a lot tougher on
South Africa,'' saying that ought to include tougher sanctions to
press that country to do away with its racial segregation policies.
</TEXT>
