<HEAD>Pipeline Spill Was Bigger Than Believed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ruptured pipeline Feb. 17 spilled nearly
twice as much of a toxic chemical as thought, Sun Pipe Line Co.
said Thursday.
   In a statement from its Tulsa, Okla., headquarters, Sun said
that 176,000 gallons of toluene were missing after the break in the
pipeline, which leads from a Sun refinery in Toledo to one in
Marcus Hook, Pa.
   Earlier, officials estimated that between 80,000 and 100,000
gallons had leaked into a marshy area and made its way into the
Sandusky River.
   The spill forced the city of Fremont to evacuate 5,000 people
and impose a water emergency for several days until a method was
devised to filter the chemical out of the drinking water the city
draws from the river.
   Sun said a significant share of the additional amount that
spilled evaporated.
