<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WritersStrike 1stLd-Writethru a0878 03-11 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers Strike, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0878,0619</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks Break Down in Scriptwriters' Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with producers' comment; PICKS
UP 6th graf pvs, `In view ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talks aimed at ending a four-day strike by
film and TV scriptwriters broke off Thursday.
   In New York, meanwhile, two unions representing 100,000 actors
set a March 21 deadline for a strike against makers of TV and radio
commercials.
   Talks between the Alliance of Motion Picture and Television
Producers and the striking Writers Guild of America had gone on
here under the auspices of a federal mediator.
   Marty Waldman, a guild spokesman, said the producers broke off
the talks.
   A spokesman for the producers, Herb Steinberg, said the
scriptwriters' demands are so unrealistic that ``further talks
would be fruitless. ... They're not even in the same neighborhood
in an assessment of the economics involved.''
   No new negotiations were set. The 9,000 scriptwriters walked out
Sunday over creative control and royalties from reruns.
   ``In view of the seriousness of the strike and its impact on the
industry, we had hoped that continued talks might bring us better
results,'' said Mona Mangan, executive director of the Writers
Guild of America-East.
   ``We deeply regret that the companies do not view these talks as
moving us closer together,'' she said.
   The strike, in its fourth day Thursday, has not yet had a
widespread effect on the movie and TV industry, but has delayed the
debut of at least two series and has forced the David Letterman and
Johnny Carson shows into reruns.
   It could shorten the TV season if producers failed to stock
enough scripts or discovered the need for extensive rewriting.
   In New York, leaders of the Screen Actors Guild and the American
Federation of Television and Radio Artists announced a March 21
deadline for a strike against the American Association of
Advertising Agencies and the Association of National Advertisers.
   Union members voted 93 percent to 7 percent March 2 to authorize
a walkout, according to a statement from the unions. The last
strike of its kind lasted seven weeks in 1978-79.
   The current contract expired Feb. 6 but was extended while
negotiations continued over such key issues as the industry's
insistence on removing cost-of-living increases, and the union's
demand for higher compensation for commercials shown on cable
television, the union said.
   There was no answer Thursday night at the New York offices of
the American Association of Advertising Agencies. The unions
negotiate in the field of TV commercials. Radio commercials are
under AFTRA's jurisdiction.
   In a strike, SAG and AFTRA members would be asked not to perform
or audition for commerciials, and to terminate the producers' right
to use any commercial beyond its maximum period of use, the unions
said.
   Some of the most popular shows were near the end of their work
schedules when the scriptwriters went on strike. The episode
closing out the popular eight-year run of ``Magnum P.I.'' has been
written.
   ``I have a lot of projects that are jeopardized now,'' said
executive producer Jennifer Alward. ``There are options on books
that will run out if the scripts aren't delivered on time. If the
strike goes three months, what do I do?''
   Wes Kenney, executive producer of the ABC soap opera ``General
Hospital'' said: ``I have enough scripts to last me through any
strike.''
   Writers working on the Academy Awards ceremonies slated for
worldwide broadcast April 11 said they left its script half written
when they walked out. But producer Samuel Goldwyn Jr. said: ``The
show must go on, and it will.''
</TEXT>
