<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TextileSentencing     03-11 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Textile Sentencing,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Defense Employee Sentenced in Scam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former government employee, once
responsible for $1.3 million a year in Pentagon clothing contracts,
was sentenced Thursday to 10 years in prison for taking at least
$331,000 in bribes from manufacturers.
   Frank Coccia, for 15 years head of the Clothing and Textile
Directorate at the Defense Personnel Support Center, also was fined
$50,000 by U.S. District Judge Edmund Ludwig.
   The 55-year-old resident of Medford, N.J., had pleaded guilty to
racketeering and conspiracy in a plea bargain under which he also
agreed to forfeit $331,000 in bribe money.
   Coccia, whose crimes began in 1976 and continued for 10 yeras,
was charged in a corruption investigation, begun four years ago,
that has resulted in the conviction of nine companies and 15
individuals.
   Among them was former New Jersey legislator Joseph Chinnici, 68,
of Bridgeton, N.J., who faces sentencing April 8. He was convicted
of paying Coccia thousands of dollars to get contracts for his
clothing firm.
   ``Coccia influenced the awarding of hundreds of millions of
dollars in military contacts to corrupt companies'' in exchange for
cash, money orders, gold coins and securities he hid in his home,
said Assistant U.S. Attorney Linda Hoffa.
   Coccia's crimes began in 1976 and continued for 10 years.
   ``The damage to the integrity of the military apparel
procurement system is incalculable,'' Ms. Hoffa said. ``It is
impossible to know whether the product or the integrity of the
product being purchased by the government was compromised.''
   Coccia told the judge: ``My one and only objective in my job was
to support the armed forces and I think I did that very well. I did
not compromise the quality of any product that was brought in.''
</TEXT>
