<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Panama Bjt   03-11 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama, Bjt,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Pays Military But Faces Payroll For Public Servants</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PAN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military regime of Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega made its army payroll, but Panama's deposed
president and economists predicted it will not be able to pay civil
servants next week.
   That could further erode support for the general, chief of the
15,000-strong Panama Defense Forces and considered the real power
behind Panama's civilian government.
   The government had to withdraw substantial funds from the
central National Bank of Panama and divert receipts from
state-owned utilities in order to back the army payroll Thursday,
diplomatic sources said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   In other developments Thursday, Panama's banks defied a
government order to reopen on a limited scale, saying there simply
wasn't enough cash available to do business.
   In Washington, the House voted overwhelmingly to demand
Noriega's ouster, and the Reagan administration considered imposing
sanctions on Panama, including withholding payments for Panama
Canal operations due by March 15.
   Also, the Panamanian government ordered five private television
stations to close indefinitely, but did not say why.
   Eric Arturo Delvalle, whose Noriega-orchestrated removal from
the presidency Feb. 26 led to U.S. economic pressure, predicted the
government would not be able to meet its mid-March payrolls for
public employees.
   ``The government will not be able to pay all civil servants and
that will create another problem,'' Delvalle said.
   Delvalle, who has been in hiding since his ouster, made the
statement in a tape-recorded response to written questions from The
Chicago Tribune.
   He was dismissed hours after he tried to fire Noriega, who is
under federal indictment in the United States on charges of
trafficking in Colombian cocaine and money laundering.
   Attorneys representing Delvalle, who still is recognized by the
United States as Panama's legitimate president, have blocked the
transfer of an estimated $50 million in Panamanian government funds
held in U.S. banks.
   Popular resentment toward Noriega's regime could rise if it
cannot meet its obligations to workers after paying the military.
   Public school teachers and other government workers are
scheduled to receive their semimonthly paychecks Monday and
Tuesday. The total payroll, including the military's, is estimated
at more than $38 million, about six times the amount of money the
government reportedly has on hand.
   Private economists estimated the government's reserves at about
$5 million, making it unlikely it will be able to meet next week's
payroll.
   The National Banking Association, which represents 97 of the 118
financial institutions that make Panama a major international
banking center, said Thursday that its members ``are in no
condition to resume'' operations.
   The association on Wednesday had ordered its members to reopen,
but only to accept deposits and make transfers of funds between
banks, calling the move a ``first step'' toward resumption of full
banking services.
   But in a statement the following day, it said the government
still had not been able to guarantee its members enough money. A
run on deposits that began with opposition demonstrations last
summer and accelerated after Delvalle's ouster prompted the banks
to close on March 1.
   The government ordered the banks to close last week, saying it
could not provide them with enough money because of the legal
action in the United States.
   Panama's currency is the U.S. dollar.
   In an interview shown Thursday on the Caracol television chain
in Colombia, Noriega again denied drug trafficking charges and said
his accusers were paid $1.5 million to make their claims. He did
not elaborate.
   Noriega rejected ``for reasons of sovereignty and dignity'' the
possibility of his going to Florida to respond to the indictments.
   He said ``the North American assistant secretary of state for
Latin American affairs (Elliott Abrams) would not come to Panama to
confront a trial here for his confabulation against the Panamanian
state.''
</TEXT>
