<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WeaponsPlants     03-11 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weapons Plants,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Say Cleanup Costs At Weapons Plants Staggering</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmental cleanup at the nation's nuclear
weapons production plants could cost as much as $100 billion,
Department of Energy officials told a congressional panel.
   ``Cleaning up DOE's nuclear facilities may be the federal
government's biggest challenge,'' J. Dexter Peach, an assistant
comptroller general of the General Accounting Office, said in
testimony Thursday before the House Energy and Commerce hazardous
materials subcommittee.
   Joseph Salgado, undersecretary at the Energy Department, told
the panel that $100 billion in cleanup costs for all of the federal
facilities ``is probably in the ballpark.''
   The subcommittee is considering a number of bills designed to
strengthen enforcement of environmental laws at the nation's
weapons production plants, which are operated for the department by
private contractors.
   In a related development, The New York Times quoted Energy
Department officials in today's editions as saying the department
would sharply scale back the amount of radioactive material it
plans to bury in the nation's first permanent nuclear waste
repository.
   Department engineers said in interviews with the newspaper that
the department would entomb less than a quarter of the 125,000
barrels of plutonium-contaminated wastes the government earlier
intended to place in the planned $700 million repository in New
Mexico over the next five years.
   The decision came four months after scientists told a
congressional committee that enough water was seeping into the
repository to threaten its ability to safely store wastes that
would remain radioactive for hundreds of thousands of years.
   Last week, a panel of experts from the National Academy of
Sciences confirmed that water was entering the chamber and
recommended that the Energy Department entomb only enough waste for
experiments to determine the significance of the seepage.
   The water leaks are to be studied further to determine whether
current plans for the repository to receive even more waste can be
put into effect. The repository is being dug from salt beds 26
miles east of Carlsbad, N.M. and is to open next October.
   Winston Porter, assistant administrator for the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency, acknowledged Thursday in the
hearing that the EPA has lost one of its levers in forcing
facilities to comply with environmental laws. The reason, he said,
is that the Justice Department has prevented the agency from using
its authority to go to court or issue unilateral orders.
   He said the administration has brought no court suits, issued no
unilateral orders, and entered into a handful of consent orders,
two enforceable compliance agreements and three unenforceable
agreements as part of its cleanup efforts.
   But Salgado told the subcommittee that the Energy Department has
recently made significant progress toward addressing environmental
contamination and has increased funding for cleanup by 62 percent
in fiscal 1989.
   Salgado said he has been told it will likely cost $1 billion to
begin cleanup at the Feed Materials Production Center in Fernald,
Ohio. The aging foundry processes uranium for use in nuclear
weapons.
   Joseph Legrone, the Energy Department's operations manager at
Oak Ridge, Tenn., said $105 million was budgeted for environmental
work at Fernald in fiscal 1988, more than the $102 million for
production. And he said $145 million has been earmarked for fiscal
1989.
   Legrone told Rep. Thomas Luken, D-Ohio, he hopes to be able to
assure that there is no leakage from Fernald's waste pits into
groundwater within a year and a half.
</TEXT>
