<2ND_LINE>AM-Grenade Blast,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hand Grenade Injuries Group Gathered To Watch Bulls On TV</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hand grenade exploded Thursday night in an
apartment, injuring three of about a dozen people who had gathered
to watch a pro basketball game on television, police said.
   An unidentified man apparently pulled a pin from a grenade while
the group was watching the Chicago Bulls play the Los Angeles
Lakes, said police Sgt. David Schweiger.
   The blast injured the man who pulled the pin, a teen-ager and a
28-year-old woman, Carolyn Dyson of Chicago, who was hospitalized
in good condition with shrapnel in her eyes, authorities said.
   The man and the teen-ager, whose names were not immediately
available, were listed in serious condition at Loyola University
Medical Center in suburban Maywood, said spokeswoman Carol Prevatt.
   Police didn't know why the man had the grenade, but thought it
was ``either real old or homemade,'' said Schweiger.
   The explosion didn't cause extensive damage to the apartment, he
said.
</TEXT>
