<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Senators-BankProbe     03-11 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Senators-Bank Probe,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Riegle Returns American Continental Money; Colleagues Say No</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Donald Riegle has returned campaign
contributions made by employees and officers of an Arizona company
on whose behalf he met with federal bank regulators conducting an
investigation.
   Riegle said Thursday he wanted to avoid the appearance of a
conflict of interest and so was giving back $76,100 in
contributions from people associated with American Continental Co.
of Phoenix, Ariz., and its subsidiaries.
   Three other senators present at the meeting last year said
through aides they saw no reason to return the money. An aide to a
fourth senator was unable to say whether the contributions would be
returned.
   ``While there was no conflict of interest involved, before or
after these contributions, even the appearance of such a personal
conflict should be enough to warrant the return of these
contributions, and that is what I have done,'' said Riegle, a
Michigan Democrat up for re-election this year who sits on the
Senate Banking Committee.
   Riegle and Sens. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz.; Alan Cranston,
D-Calif.; John Glenn, D-Ohio; and John McCain, R-Ariz., met last
April 9 with Federal Home Loan Bank Board examiners and discussed
the investigation of an American Continental subsidiary, Lincoln
Savings and Loan Association of Irvine, Calif.
   There was no connection between the meeting and the agency's
decision to end its probe of high-risk investments made by the
subsidiary, Riegle said last month.
   The meeting was called by DeConcini, said Riegle's press
secretary, Mike Russell. DeConcini had received $43,000 in campaign
contributions from American Continental officers and employees.
   Cranston received $41,900 in contributions; Glenn, $34,000; and
McCain, $112,000.
   ``It is foolishness to assume that just because employees of a
company make a contribution to a DeConcini campaign, that that
company can no longer go to Sen. DeConcini and request the same
kind of constitutent service that any other individual or company
would expect,'' said DeConcini's press secretary, Bob Maynes.
   Aides to McCain and Glenn also said the senators would not
return the contributions because they saw no reason to do so.
   Cranston's press secretary, Victoria Lion, said the senator was
out of the country and she was unable to determine whether he had
or intended to return his American Continental campaign
contributions.
   The contributions were legal under federal election laws.
   Russell said Riegle believed returning the contributions would
put to rest questions about the propriety of his having accepted
the money.
   ``He made a personal decision last weekend,'' Russell said.
``This was the first time in his 22 years of public service that a
conflict of interest had been raised.''
   American Continental owns Detroit's Pontchartrain Hotel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880311-0033 </DOCNO>
