<HEAD>Stocks, Dollar Dip In Tokyo</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with closing figures, EDITS to conform. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar dipped against the Japanese yen in
trading in Tokyo Friday, while stock prices fell following an
overnight decline on Wall Street.
   The dollar opened at 127.85 yen, down 0.35 yen from Thursday's
close of 128.20 yen, and closed for the day at 127.80, down 0.40
yen from Thursday.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which gained 12.43 points Thursday, lost 74.09
points or 0.02 percent to close at 25,543.73.
   ``Although nothing has changed in regard to Japan's improved
investment environment, a 48.24-point fall in the Dow Jones
industrial average dampened the mood of investors,'' said Masahiro
Umemori of Nomura Securities, Japan's largest brokerage.
   A dealer at a major commercial bank in Tokyo, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said the currency market ``generally
remained listless.'' He said the market was waiting for the release
of U.S. retail sales and producer price figures, due out Friday in
Washington.
