<2ND_LINE>PM-Illinois Poll,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Holds Wide Lead Over Dole In Illinois, Poll Suggests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush leads Senate GOP
leader Bob Dole by a wide margin among Republicans likely to vote
in Illinois' presidential primary, according to survey results
published today.
   The Washington Post-ABC News telephone poll conducted Wednesday,
six days before the primary election, showed Bush with the support
of 58 percent of 395 likely Republican voters, while Dole, of
Kansas, was backed by 31 percent.
   Former television evangelist Pat Robertson was the choice of 6
percent while Rep. Jack Kemp of New York, who dropped out of the
race on Thursday, had 4 percent, according to the survey, which was
published in today's editions of the Post.
   In the Democratic race, native sons Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois
and civil rights leader Jesse Jackson of Chicago led with 38
percent and 33 percent, respectively, among 402 likely Democratic
voters. The difference between the two was within the poll's margin
of error.
   Massachussets Gov. Michael Dukakis trailed with 16 percent and
Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri had 6 percent. Former Sen. Gary
Hart of Colorado, who was expected to withdraw from the contest
today, was picked by 3 percent of the respondents and Sen. Albert
Gore of Tennessee was chosen by 2 percent.
   The newspaper said the survey had a margin of error of plus or
minus eight percentage points.
</TEXT>
