<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 0737EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Robertson     03-11 0675</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Robertson,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Says May Use Matching Funds Even as He Nears Spending
Limit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson, the biggest-spending candidate of
the presidential race so far, says he'll use his federal matching
funds after all, even though he has said he is philosophically
opposed to the idea.
   Robertson said Thursday that ``short of what would amount to an
absolute miracle in the state (of Illinois), it looks as if I'll
have to use them.''
   He also said at a news conference that he is within about $2
million of the $27 million spending cap that election rules set for
those who get matching funds. That could pose serious strategy
problems for him, because it means he will be unable to continue
the kind of high-spending campaign he has conducted so far and will
be forced to skimp along for the remainder of the primary season.
   ``It's going to mean that it's going to be me the candidate and
not a lot of travel and everything else the volunteers,'' he said.
   Robertson said he had made deep cuts in his national staff, but
he declined to give specific numbers. He said the reductions had
cut deeply into his press and office staff.
   ``Everybody is bucking up around the federal (spending) limit
... so we want to stay lean and mean,'' he said.
   Robertson has received $7.2 million in federal matching funds,
more than any other candidate, including Vice President George
Bush, who has received $6.6 million.
   Robertson's campaign has put the money into an escrow account
and was keeping open the option of not using the money and later
giving it back to the government. In that case, campaign attorney
Marion Harrison had contended, Robertson would not be bound by the
spending limits imposed on those who accept matching funds.
   Whether the Federal Election Commission would have accepted that
point of view is now moot since Robertson has indicated he will not
try that approach.
   FEC officials had pointed out that the law requires a candidate
to sign an agreement to abide by the limits at the time of
application for matching funds. There is no language in the
regulations that addresses whether a candidate actually spends the
money.
   Robertson had used the money as collateral for a $5.5 million
loan in January, and a $1.5 million loan in December.
   ``We put the (matching) funds in escrow and borrowed against
them. We're still trying to keep our options open, but the options,
I might say, narrowed considerably after Super Tuesday,'' Robertson
said in an interview following a brief Chicago news conference
kicking off his effort in Illinois.
   Robertson said that the matching funds are, ``in a sense,
already spent.
   ``That money would just go to pay off loans. The truth is, in my
estimation, that all the major campaigns are bumped up against the
limit. There is not much money left for anybody,'' said Robertson.
   ``We're trying to husband our resources as hard as we can and
hold on through June,'' he continued.
   Robertson said cash problems would not deter him from continuing
the GOP fight.
   ``I am more and more being urged by conservatives to stay in the
race as a rallying point for conservatives and conservative
principles,'' he said.
   As of the most recent campaign financial reports, through Jan.
31, Robertson had spent more against the limit than any other
candidate _ more than $22 million. That was before the most
intensive spending period began for the Super Tuesday primaries and
caucuses in 20 states on March 8.
   By contrast, Bush had spent $15.3 million and Sen. Bob Dole,
R-Kan., $18.1 million.
   The matching funds are provided from a fund supported by the $1
voluntary checkoff on individual income tax returns. Each donation
of $250 or less that a candidate raises is matched by the public
fund. To qualify initially, a candidate must raise at least
$100,000 across 20 states in contributions of $250 or less.
   Robertson had said he was not in favor of the publicly supported
campaign finance system.
</TEXT>
