<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 0411EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater 1stLd-Writethru a0869 03-11 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0869,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Revival of `A Streetcar Named Desire' Opens on Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs with other critics; no PMs planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The complicated relationship between the
ethereal Blanche Du Bois and the earthy Stanley Kowalski in
Tennessee Williams' ``A Streetcar Named Desire'' is one of the most
fascinating in the American theater.
   Blanche, the epitome of neurotic southern gentility, flutters to
her doom at the hands of Stanley, her crude but practical
brother-in-law. It's a destructive flight, one that she resists
until the very end of the play but then accepts almost willingly.
   That strange bond between the two is ignored in the new,
straightforward revival of Williams' classic drama that opened
Thursday at Broadway's Circle in the Square Theater.
   This ``Streetcar'' is riding on one rail _ Blythe Danner's
dangerous, on-the-edge performance as the desperate Blanche. Just
when you think she may veer out of control, Miss Danner takes
charge.
   The actress recites Williams' poetry _ and that's what much of
his dialogue is _ with an intensity that is very moving. She also
can handle the more lurid permutations of the plot, bringing a
conviction to melodramatic moments such as as the story of the
death of her young husband. It's a commanding portrait.
   That conviction is lacking in Aidan Quinn who plays Stanley.
Quinn is an intelligent actor but he's miscast, both physically and
vocally.
   His Stanley is brash rather than brutish, more wise guy than
tough guy. That approach works when he's playing poker with his
pals, but when he comes up against an aggressive Blanche, Quinn
falters.
   Blanche keeps referring to Stanley as ape-like, but Quinn's
characterization is anything but animalistic. He's too boyish and
bears more than a passing resemblance to the young newsboy Blanche
attempts to seduce late in the first act.
   Blanche and Stanley become little more than a bickering couple.
Their lack of electricity doesn't ruin the production, but it does
make this revival a lopsided, unsurprising evening of theater.
   Danner works better with Frank Converse, who projects an innate
decency as Mitch, Stanley's good friend and Blanche's one last
chance. There's a genuine regret about their inability to make
something of their relationship. Equally appealing is Frances
McDormand, a ripe, voluptuous Stella who gamely puts up with
Stanley's crudeness because she loves him.
   Nikos Psacharopoulos, the country's foremost interpreter of
Williams' plays, directs at a leisurely pace. Between scenes, there
are a lot of saxophone moans in the night. Designer John Conklin
spills a French Quarter setting, much of it wrought iron, across
the elongated stage to create an evocative New Orleans apartment.
   The set is tantalizing and so is Miss Danner. She just doesn't
have anyone to go up against.
   In other reviews:
   Frank Rich of The New York Times called the production ``a
staging that may not deface Williams's masterpiece but often
sanitizes it. ...
   ``What is most absent from the evening, and not just in Blanche
and Stanley's showdown, is sex. Miss Danner and Mr. Quinn _ both
fine actors, both erotic figures in other circumstances _ shed no
sparks here.''
   In the Daily News, Howard Kissel writes that the production
lacks ``a sense of an old world decaying, of desire hanging
palpably, urgently in the air. ... Without this tangled undergrowth
of anxiety and nervous longing, the play loses its force.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880311-0041 </DOCNO>
