<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NewBedfordRape     03-11 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-New Bedford Rape,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Supreme Court Upholds Convictions in Big Dan's Gang Rape
Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecutor who handled the Big Dan's
pool-table rape trial says he hopes a state Supreme Court ruling
affirming the convictions will end the furor touched off by the
case.
   ``It was a worldwide case. Literally the whole world was
watching,'' Bristol County District Attorney Ronald Pina said
Thursday after the high court affirmed the convictions of four men
in the 1984 trial.
   ``If anything, it has heightened the awareness of rape victims
that they can come forward and testify. They now know that they
should report rapes,'' he said.
   In a pair of unanimous rulings, the Massachusetts Supreme Court
turned aside defense objections on Pina's handling of evidence,
Judge William G. Young's decision to avert television cameras from
the victim and other issues.
   The victim's dramatic account of the barroom rape and the
lengthy televised trial in Superior Court drew national attention
to the working-class neighborhoods of New Bedford, where the attack
occurred, and sparked an intense debate over rape.
   The case also brought agony to New Bedford's large
Portuguese-American community. The six young men charged in the
case were of Portuguese descent, as was the victim.
   The high court upheld the punishments handed out to Daniel
Silvia, John Cordeiro and Victor Raposo, who were sentenced to nine
to 12 years in the state maximum-security prison at Walpole, and
Joseph Vieira, who drew six to eight years. The two other
defendants were acquitted.
   The victim died in a car crash outside Miami in December 1986 at
age 25.
   According to court records, she entered Big Dan's tavern on
March 6, 1983, to buy cigarettes. She ordered a drink, spoke with
another woman and watched a game of pool. When she declined an
offer of a ride from Cordeiro and Raposo, the court said, she was
knocked down, dragged to the pool table and raped.
</TEXT>
