<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks, Dollar Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange fell 74.09
points in heavy trading today, while the U.S. dollar fell slightly
against the yen.
   Traders said most of the 1.8 billion shares traded involved the
top 10 stocks, prompting concern that investors were again turning
to speculation to fuel the market.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues fell 0.02
percent to close at 25,543.73, after gaining 12.43 points on
Thursday.
   The dollar closed at 127.80 yen, down 0.40 yen from Thursday's
close.
   Stephen Jennings, a salesman for Kleinwort Benson, said trading
today was concentrated in two stocks, Nippon Steel and IHI,
accounting for a half a billion shares.
   ``There is a fear that quality is deteriorating,'' and that much
of today's trading was based on speculation, Jennings said.
   He said investors are now looking toward the U.S. trade figures
to be released later this month.
   Another dealer at a major commercial bank in Tokyo, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said the currency market ``generally
remained listless'' and said the market is waiting for the release
of U.S. retail sales and producer price figures.
