<DOCNO> AP880311-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 0453EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     03-11 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says He Will Campaign Hard In Illinois; Urges Party Unity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush says he will
continue to campaign hard in the Illinois primary despite a poll
putting him comfortably ahead of GOP rival Bob Dole.
   ``I'm not going to be out-hustled as we prepare to go the polls
Tuesday in Illinois,'' Bush told a Republican dinner on Thursday
night.
   A Washington Post-ABC News poll published in today's editions of
the Post said Bush led Dole, 58 percent to 31 percent.
   Bush had little to say about major staff cutbacks by the Dole
campaign, coupled with a move by the Dole forces to pull television
spots off the air in the state. Dole campaign sources said the
Kansas senator had talked about the possibility of pulling out of
the race, but had decided to stay in at least through Tuesday's
primary here.
   Bush's chief of staff, Craig Fuller, said the vice president's
reaction to reports about Dole was: ``We'll go about our business,
do our job.''
   Dole, reeling from a dismal showing on Super Tuesday, insisted
Thursday night that he was ``not a dropout'' and would continue to
campaign.
   Meanwhile, Bush appealed to more than 700 Republicans at the
Champaign County dinner to help him win the state's primary and the
82 GOP delegates at stake.
   He also urged party factions to prepare to put their differences
aside.
   ``It's important to remember that we are all Republicans,'' said
Bush. ``We shouldn't get so negative we can't close ranks in the
fall.''
   Bush, speaking in one of the nation's top agricultural counties,
said as president he would ask that a world economic summit
scheduled in France focus on agriculture.
   He said he would fight for open markets and fair trade so U.S.
farmers could sell their products abroad.
   Bush said he would not use food ``as a foreign policy weapon''
as the Carter administration did with its 1980 grain embargo, and
he said he would oppose protectionist legislation.
   ``If you protect a textile industry, the first thing to be
retaliated against is American agriculture,'' said Bush.
   Earlier, during an appearance in Chicago, Bush said he was
``tired of being embarrassed'' by scandals surrounding public
officials and unethical behavior by high government officials _
though he named no names.
   He pledged to create a special White House ethics panel and give
it ``a new and specific code of ethics.''
   ``When a congressman goes bad or someone in the executive branch
violates the public trust, it hurts,'' Bush told the Governor's
Club luncheon at the Chicago Hilton. ``I'm tired of being
embarrassed. People at all levels of government should come to
serve, not to profit.''
   Bush has steadfastly refused to critize any Reagan
administration officials, including Attorney General Edwin Meese,
who is under investigation by several grand juries.
   Former top White House aides Michael K. Deaver and Lyn Nofziger
have been convicted in court cases involving their lobbying
activities after leaving the administration.
   Bush, asked at a news conference whether he was criticizing the
Reagan administration, said he was not. He added that no one ``has
a higher standard of personal ethics than the president _ always
above any possible conflict of interest.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
