<1ST_LINE>r i PM-FreedHostage     03-11 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Freed Hostage,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Freed Oxfam Worker Recounts Arguing `For My Life'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relief worker Peter Coleridge, released after six
days of questioning by Palestinian gunmen in Lebanon, returned and
said the long-term hostages there must be going through something
``very close to hell.''
   ``It was thoughts of my family which kept me going,'' Coleridge
told a news conference after he was reunited with his wife and
three children at Heathrow Airport on Thursday, two days after his
captors freed him.
   Coleridge, 44, Middle East coordinator of the British charity
and relief organization Oxfam, was seized in Sidon March 3 after
taking photographs at the Ein el-Hilweh refugee camp there.
   Also captured was his Syrian aide, Omar Traboulsi, 31. After
daily interrogations, they were both released Tuesday.
   ``I was very much aware that I was arguing for my life,'' said
Coleridge. ``If they were in any way not convinced, it wold not
have turned out as well as it has.''
   ``I developed quite an interesting kind of relationship with
those interrogating me,'' Coleridge said. ``I felt that by the end,
we had reached quite a level of understanding of what my
organization does and the kind of work we get involved in.''
   Coleridge said the ordeal gave him an insight into what other
hostages must be experiencing.
   ``They must be going through something very, very close to hell.
I wouldn't wish it on anyone at all _ and I had only six days of
it.''
   ``I was kept in one room with a blanket and bucket and fed
adequately, although I didn't have much of an appetite,'' he said.
   Twenty-two foreigners, including nine Americans, are known to be
missing in Lebanon after being kidnapped.
   Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The
Associated Press, is the longest-held hostage. He was kidnapped
March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
