<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson-Drugs     03-11 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-Drugs,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Unveils Drug-Fighting Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential candidate Jesse Jackson
is calling for a 71 percent increase in spending on drug
interdiction and treatment over the 1989 Reagan administration
proposal.
   Jackson released a detailed position paper Thursday saying the
government should spend $6.7 billion to fight drugs, a topic which
has emerged at the top of his list of campaign issues.
   ``It's overrunning our borders, it's undermining our
productivity, it's killing our children, it's corrupting our
government,'' he said at a campaign stop at Wheaton College. ``We
must stop the flow of drugs into our country.''
   His spending program includes increases in the interdiction
budgets of the Justice Department, Customs operations, Coast Guard,
Pentagon, and State Department, and prevention and treatment
programs.
   For treatment, according to Jackson's position paper, he would
spend $1.7 billion, compared to $425 million proposed by President
Reagan.
   Jackson contends the drug issue is a hidden benefit for him in
his presidential campaign, because it strikes a responsive chord
wherever he speaks about it. He said in an interview last week that
the media and political analysts have failed to take note of how
important the drug issue is to the American people.
   Jackson tells his audiences that the drug problem is the
nation's No. 1 threat to national security, killing young people,
corrupting police departments and making banks into partners with
drug kingpins.
   He often asks members of the audience to stand if they know
someone who has died because of drugs, who is in jail because of
drugs, or who has tried drugs.
   Jackson has previously said he had no specific numbers on how to
implement his suggestions to fight drugs. But his new position
paper breaks down totals for each government agency.
   ``It is time to put up the necessary resources to meet this
national security threat head on,'' he said in his statement.
   ``We have 325,000 troops in Europe but only 269 drug enforcement
agents overseas to fight the war on drugs.''
   He would tie U.S. foreign and trade policy to the drug problem,
persuading drug-producing allies to install new anti-drug programs
or face trade and diplomatic penalties. These countries should be
rewarded with crop diversification plans and increased U.S.
training, equipment and material assistance. he said.
   Jackson proposed a Western Hemisphere summit on drugs, and said
``international troops may be needed in countries like Colombia to
deal with the crisis.
   Jackson also would name a Cabinet-level ``drug czar.'' And he
would beef up the border patrol and other agencies to stop drugs at
the border, he said.
   Jackson also proposed a school-based education and prevention
program, led by the secretary of education, and a public awareness
campaign similar to the one that warns people about the danger of
smoking cigarettes.
</TEXT>
