<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AbortionRuling     03-11 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abortion Ruling,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Administration Appeals Ruling Striking Down Abortion Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration has asked an appeals
court to overturn a judge's order barring federal regulations that
would cut off funding to family planning clinics that offer
abortions or abortion counseling.
   The administration said it was seeking a reversal from the 1st
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in U.S. District Judge Walter Ray
Skinner's March 3 ruling, which declared the regulations
unconstitutional.
   Skinner's ruling was announced the day the new guidelines were
to have taken effect, and forced the U.S. Department of Health and
Human Services to order regional offices to suspend enforcing them.
   That order will remain in effect while the appeal is considered,
said HHS spokeswoman Lucy Eddinger.
   In a memo accompanying his ruling, Skinner said the regulations
violated a woman's right to choose to have an abortion and her
First Amendment rights to free speech.
   Federal judges in Colorado and New York had issued temporary
injunctions against the regulations, but Skinner was the first to
rule on their constitutionality, and said his order applied
nationwide.
   He granted an injunction requested by the state of
Massachusetts, the National Family Planning and Reproductive Health
Association and 13 other local and national family planning groups.
   About 5 million low- and moderate-income women receive services
at 4,000 clinics nationwide which would have been affected by the
regulations announced last month by HHS Secretary Otis R. Bowen.
   The new rules would have prevented federally funded family
planning programs from providing abortion counseling, abortion
referrals, and engaging in lobbying or legal action to increase the
availability of abortions.
   If a clinic performed abortions, it would have been forced to
maintain separate facilities for each type of patient if it wanted
to continue to receive funding under Title X of the Public Health
Service Act of 1970.
</TEXT>
