<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Panama,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Banks To Wait For Interest, Principal Payments From
Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese banks will ``wait for the time being'' for
overdue interest and principal payments by Panama of $40.6 million
in bonds, a Japanese banking official said today.
   Panama missed Thursday's deadline for the payments owed to an
unspecified number of Japanese commercial banks _ $39.06 million in
principal and $1.56 million in interest, said a Bank of Tokyo
official who insisted on anonymity.
   The Bank of Tokyo, along with Yamaichi Securities Co., are the
lead agents for the 10-year bonds, which Panama issued in March
1978.
   ``We will wait for the time being as the Panamanian side has
recently confirmed it is delaying the payments'' because of a
freeze on Panamanian assets held by U.S. banks, the official said.
   According to Japanese banking sources, Panama earlier told its
Japanese creditors a freeze in U.S. aid money to the country in the
wake of a confrontation between Washington and the military regime
of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega would make it difficult to honor the
transaction.
   The United States is attempting to oust Noriega, who has been
indicted in Florida on drug trafficking charges.
