<1ST_LINE>r i PM-ElSalvador     03-11 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-El Salvador,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unionists Occupy Government Building, Leave Without Obtaining
Concessions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty union activists demanding
higher pay and reinstatement of fired workers occupied the Interior
Ministry for nine tense hours, then left the police-ringed building
under church protection.
   The Roman Catholic church was able to mediate the evacuation
Thursday after a judge inspected the building and confirmed the
workers were neither armed nor holding hostages, said Monsignor
Gregorio Rosa Chavez, the metropolitan auxiliary bishop.
   The Workers Solidary Coordinate protesters were unable to win
any concessions and took a bus, under military escort, to a local
church office for the night.
   Officials with the National Salvadoran Workers Unity, the
largest opposition union, said soldiers captured and beat their
leader, Humberto Centeno, when he arrived to seek an end to the
occupation.
   Both unions are leading opponents of the government of President
Jose Napoleon Duarte, who claimed the ministry takeover was part of
a recently-discovered guerrilla plan to stir up mass protests in
the country.
   The 50 unionists took over the building to demand a $60 monthly
wage hike, reinstatement of dismissed workers and other conditions.
They spoke with Labor Minister Lazaro Tadeo Bernal, but he gave
them no satisfaction, said Gerardo Diaz Henriquez, the Coordinate's
director.
   Centeno had arrived on a bus with several other union activists,
who soldiers forced back onto the vehicle before shooting out its
window, said Guillermo Rojas, a Workers Unity official.
   One worker was injured by flying glass, he said.
   Duarte, at a news conference with Bernal, said the government
did not talk with the protesters, who he said would be jailed if
captured.
   The president said the incident confirmed the existence of a
rebel plan to widen the scopeof its leftist insurgency by having
urban-based mass organizations engage in disruptive activity.
   The government has said the plan calls for constructing
barricades, occupying public buildings, provoking riot police and
burning buses and other government vehicles.
</TEXT>
