<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 0609EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-Afghanistan     03-11 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Afghanistan,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Reject U.S. Demand For Simultaneous Cut-off To Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet envoy rejected a U.S. demand that Moscow
cut off military aid to Afghanistan if Washington stops aiding
Afghan rebels after a Soviet troop pullout.
   Moscow's ties to Afghanistan are seven decades old and the U.S.
demand is tantamount to the Soviets calling for an end to U.S. aid
to Pakistan, said Nikolay Kozyrev, ambassador-at-large and senior
Soviet specialist in Asian affairs.
   Kozyrev, who spoke to reporters at a news conference Thursday,
heads a visiting team of Soviet specialists to follow the latest
round of the peace talks in Geneva between Pakistan and Afghanistan.
   U.N. Undersecretary-General Diego Cordovez is mediating the
6-year-old peace talks, the latest round of which began March 2.
   Pakistan is representing Afghan guerrillas who have been
fighting for nine years against the government in Kabul, the Afghan
capital. Soviet troops were sent into Afghanistan in 1979 to prop
up the Marxist government.
   Robert Peck, assistant deputy Secretary of State, is also in
Geneva to follow the talks and has been in touch with Kozyrev. A
U.S. Mission spokesman said Peck had no immediate comment on the
Soviet's comments.
   The United States has given the Afghan rebels millions of
dollars in aid, including ground-to-air Stinger missiles claimed to
have downed more than 200 Soviet and Afghan aircraft.
   Kozyrev said the talks ``bogged down'' of Pakistan's insistence
that an interim government replace the one headed by Soviet-backed
President Najib.
   He said Islamabad will bear the responsibility if there is no
final agreement despite completion of all main elements of the
``peace package.''
   The interim government, Pakistan argues, could guarantee
implementation of the settlement and ensure the safe return of more
than 5 million Afghan refugees from Pakistan and Iran.
   Kozyrev said the draft agreements from the peace talks do not
commit his country to halt aid to the Kabul government, except to
stipulate that no new troops must be sent to Afghanistan after the
withdrawal of the estimated 115,000-strong ``limited Soviet
contingent.''
   Kozryev avoided a direct answer when asked whether negotiations
would continue after next Tuesday, the target date set by Mikhail
Gorbachev last month. The Soviet leader said that Moscow will begin
the troop withdrawal May 15 if the settlement is signed by March 15.
   Sources close to the talks said the date was not considered a
deadline after which the Kabul representatives would walk out.
   The U.S. demand for ``symmetrical cessation'' of military aid
was spelled out at a State Department briefing on March 4. It was
the latest of seemingly uncoordinated signals from Washington
concerning the issue.
   It followed a non-binding resolution, unanimously adopted by the
U.S. Senate last week, urging the White House to continue such aid
until all Soviet troops have left.
   Peck said before his departure from Washington that a decision
on the timing of the cut-off should be left to President Reagan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
