<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Poland-Massacre     03-11 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Massacre,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmaker Demands Truth About Wartime Massacre of Polish Officers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a dramatic speech in parliament, an
independent deputy demanded the truth be told about the World War
II massacre of 4,000 Polish officers in a forest in the Soviet
Union.
   The official version is that Nazi troops committed the Katyn
forest massacre, but many Poles blame the Soviet Union.
   Deputy Ryszard Bender, raising the taboo issue for the first
time in parliament, said Thursday that full disclosure is needed if
Poland and the Soviet Union are to have genuinely friendly
relations.
   ``The word `Katyn' must be spoken out in this high chamber,''
said Bender, addressing Foreign Minister Marian Orzechowski. ``This
is required by the honor of the Polish people, by its martyrdom
throughout'' the war.
   Bender spoke after Orzechowski praised a Soviet-Polish agreement
on ideological cooperation signed last year that stresses the need
for a more truthful history of Polish-Soviet relations.
   Bender said Soviet interests were not served by ``making Poland
a dependent nation'' but by having ``a sovereign, self-governing,
economically strong Poland'' as its neighbor.
   He said the friendly relations between Poland and the Soviet
Union ``must be genuine ... Not just facade-like propaganda.''
   On Tuesday, 59 Polish opposition activists and intellectuals,
including Solidarity leader Lech Walesa, issued an open letter
appealing to Soviet intellectuals to speak out about Katyn.
   Bender called on Communist authorities to open up to historians
archives of classified documents so ``blank spots'' in
Polish-Soviet relations can be filled. He said these included the
1939 non-aggression pact through which the Soviet Union and Germany
divided Poland.
   That September, the Nazis invaded from the west and the Soviets
from the east. Tens of thousands of Poles were deported to Siberia.
   ``There are persons in this chamber with painful experiences of
those deportations,'' said Bender.
   The phrase ``blank spots'' has become shorthand in Poland for
topics so controversial that go unmentioned or are distorted in
official histories.
   Last week, a joint Soviet-Polish commission of Communist party
historians met in Warsaw to review research on the ``blank spots.''
   The panel discussed such sensitive topics as the fate of Poles
deported to the Soviet Union in 1939-41, but reported no progress
in elucidating all the circumstances behind the Katyn massacre.
   Polish and Soviet official versions of the massacre say the
4,000 officers whose bodies were found in the forest near Smolensk
were murdered by the Nazis in 1941 after they invaded the Soviet
Union.
   Most Poles and Western historians maintain the officers were
slain in 1940 on orders of Soviet dictator Josef Stalin.
   The 4,000 were among 15,000 Polish officers detained after the
Soviets invaded Poland and held in three separate camps in western
Russia. The fate of the remaining 11,000 officers has never been
revealed, and the issue remains a sensitive point in Polish-Soviet
relations.
   In his speech, Orzechowski said the ideological cooperation
agreement ``will be conducive to overcoming the negative phenomena
which have accumulated in history'' between two countries.
   He said Poland fully supported the ``revolutionary changes''
being introduced by Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev, adding that
Polish-Soviet relations are ``closer than ever before.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
