<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Marine Linked With Soviet Embassy Sex-Spy Case Leaving Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cpl. Arnold Bracy, a Marine embassy guard who
for a time figured prominently in last year's Moscow spy scandal is
leaving the military next month, and a source said he would be
honorably discharged.
   The Marine Corps announced Thursday that Bracy, 22, of Woodside
Queens, New York City, will be formally discharged on April 4. A
Marine official who asked not to be named said Bracy would receive
an honorable discharge.
   Bracy served as an embassy guard in Moscow with Sgt. Clayton J.
Lonetree, 26, who was convicted last August of passing classified
information to Soviet agents after becoming involved with a Russian
woman.
   For a time last spring, Bracy also faced a military
court-martial because Navy and federal agents were convinced he had
conspired with Lonetree and allowed Russian KGB agents inside the
embassy late at night to roam at will.
   Those allegations were based in part on a confession signed by
Bracy after a lengthy interrogation. Bracy later recanted that
statement, saying it had been coerced, and all charges against him
were dropped when military lawyers concluded they did not have any
corroborating evidence to prosecute.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>NASA Official Opposes Diverting Money From Space Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The retiring head of NASA's space station
program is warning that the program could be destroyed if money
budgeted for that purpose is diverted to pay for an unmanned
scientific and manufacturing facility in space.
   Andrew Stofan told a House subcommittee Thursday he would oppose
any attempt to take money from the space station budget to pay for
a commercially developed ``Industrial Space Facility.''
   ``I see no use for it (the ISF) as far as developing the space
station is concerned,'' said Stofan, who is retiring after 30 years
at the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
   Meanwhile, Rep. Edward P. Boland, D-Mass., told a House
appropriations subcommittee that more money is needed for housing
programs next year and that if the money is not allocated, then
Congress will ``kiss goodbye to the space station.''
   Boland's subcommittee handles financing for housing programs as
well as independent agencies including NASA.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Witnesses Testify About Poor Work At Clinical Laboratories</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of a House subcommittee says
fraud, overcharging and kickbacks are rampant among clinical
laboratories, and witnesses at a hearing called for better federal
oversight.
   Rep. John Dingell, a Michigan Democrat who chairs the House
Energy and Commerce subcommittee on oversight and investigations,
said at a hearing Thursday that problems are ``rampant in this
industry and federal oversight has been non-existent.''
   Witnesses at the hearing said unregulated laboratory procedures
have resulted in problems such as a 20 to 40 percent error rate in
Pap tests used to detect cervical cancer in women.
   Other problems include piecework pay systems that encourage
production at the expense of careful diagnosis and pressure to
accept inadequate specimens and call them negative so doctors won't
send their business elsewhere, said Shirley Greening, representing
the American Society for Cytotechnology.
   She and others recommended mandatory proficiency testing for all
diagnostic lab technicians, workload limits, more federal money to
monitor labs through the Medicare and Medicaid programs, and
required public disclosure of lab caseload volume, staffing, fees,
quality control methods and results.
</TEXT>
