<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against other major foreign
currencies in Europe early today in moderately active trading. Gold
bullion rose.
   A trader in Frankfurt, West Germany, said market participants
were limiting dollar exposure ahead of the weekend.
   The British pound, whose value leaped by 4 percent against the
dollar this week, gained further ground on the U.S. currency,
trading at $1.8465, up from $1.8435 late Thursday.
   But traders said the rally appeared to be running out of steam
on a statement by Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson on
Thursday that sterling would be unable to sustain a further advance.
   Other midmorning dollar rates in Europe, compared with late
Thursday:
   _1.6620 West German marks, down from 1.6640
   _1.3740 Swiss francs, down from 1.3785
   _5.6665 French francs, down from 5.6725
   _1.8683 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8720
   _1,235.00 Italian lire, down from 1,236.63
   _1.2560 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2564
   The dollar closed in Tokyo at 127.80 Japanese yen, down from
Thursday's close of 128.20 yen. In later London trading Friday, the
dollar slipped to 127.45 yen.
   London's major bullion houses fixed a recommended gold price of
$444.10 a troy ounce at midmorning, up from $443 late Thursday.
   In Zurich, gold was bid at $444.15, up from $442.50.
   Earlier, the metal closed in Hong Kong at a bid of $445.48
dollars, up from $438.42.
   Silver bullion was quoted in London at a bid of $6.31 a troy
ounce, down from $6.36.
</TEXT>
