<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LaRoucheTrial     03-11 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-LaRouche Trial,0642</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Secord Denies Any Role In Anti-LaRouche Plot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard Secord, a key
figure in the Iran-Contra scandal, denied any knowledge of an
alleged Reagan administration plot to infiltrate the organizations
of political extremist Lyndon LaRouche.
   Secord said Thursday he was relaying a message from an associate
when, in a memo to former National Security Council aide Oliver
North, he mentioned an apparent effort to collect information
against LaRouche.
   Secord, a principal in North's private Contra supply network,
said in a telephone interview that he was not aware of any
government plot to infiltrate LaRouche organizations.
   Defense lawyers for LaRouche and his supporters, on trial here
on fraud and conspiracy charges, contend LaRouche was a target of
the FBI and CIA. They cite the North-Secord memo and other
documents as support for the claim.
   The defense lawyers contend that North, the Marine lieutenant
colonel fired for his role in the Iran-Contra scandal, supported
the CIA and FBI infiltration as part of a Reagan administration
plot to ruin LaRouche because he opposed aid to the Contra rebels
in Nicaragua.
   In addition to the Secord-North memo, LaRouche defense lawyers
have been given an FBI document, declassified Wednesday, that
quotes three intelligence operatives as saying they were directed
by top FBI and CIA officials to infiltrate LaRouche groups.
   U.S. District Judge Robert E. Keeton halted trial testimony this
week because of the newly discovered documents.
   He ordered Assistant U.S. Attorney John Markham to review
classified FBI files from which the declassified material was taken
and determine if additional information should be given to defense
lawyers.
   In a May 1986 memo to North that was declassified this week,
Secord said he was told by ``our man here'' that retired Army Sgt.
Maj. Fred Lewis ``has collected info against LaRouche.''
   Defense lawyers have said the prosecutor in the case told them
``our man'' referred to FBI executive assistant director Oliver
Revell. But Secord said he was referring to John Cupp, who worked
for a company that provided clandestine air transport for
government operations, including the Contra resupply effort.
   Cupp on Thursday agreed with Secord's characterization that
``our man'' referred to him, but defense lawyers maintained their
position that the reference was to Revell.
   Cupp said he had relayed to Secord details of a conversation he
had with Lewis, whom Cupp described as a longtime friend.
   ``Fred came to me and said he had been approached by Mr.
LaRouche to conduct some very questionable activities and he kind
of went along with it to get information because he thought he was
a Froot Loop,'' Cupp said in a telephone interview.
   ``He knew I was working in Washington and looked me up because
he thought I would be able to get the information to an authority
who would be able to take some kind of action,'' Cupp said.
   Cupp said Lewis told him that LaRouche wanted to rescue
dissidents from the Soviet Union, including Andrei Sakharov and his
wife, Yelena Bonner.
   ``Lewis hung around for a while to check him out and see what he
was doing but he wasn't doing anything official,'' Cupp said.
   Cupp said he agreed to discuss the matter as a favor to Secord.
   The three operatives quoted in the declassified FBI material are
Lewis, Gary Howard and Ron Tucker.
   LaRouche, six aides and five LaRouche political organizations
are charged with conspiring to obstruct a grand jury investigation
of alleged credit card and loan fraud by LaRouche followers during
his 1984 presidential campaign. Four of the organizations also are
charged with fraud.
   Defense attorneys claim evidence of the fraud was fabricated by
FBI and CIA plants in the organizations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
