<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blizzard Blasts High Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A powerful storm system centered near the Nebraska-Wyoming line
churned up snow and wind from the western Dakotas across western
Nebraska and much of Wyoming and Colorado today.
   Blizzard warnings continued today in eastern Wyoming and were
issued today for northeast Colorado, northwest Nebraska and western
South Dakota.
   Many roads were closed in central and eastern Wyoming, where up
to a foot of snow was on the ground, winds of 20 to 40 mph gusted
to around 50 mph, visibility was near zero at times, and subzero
wind chills were reported.
   In Nebraska, the blizzard buffeted Kimball, Alliance, Chadron
and Sidney, with snow totals ranging to 8 inches southwest of
Scottsbluff and up to a foot near the Wyoming state line.
   In western South Dakota, there were 10 inches of snow on the
ground in Deadwood. More than 18 inches of snow was expected in the
Black Hills by tonight, and 4 to 8 inches elsewhere in western
South Dakota.
   The high country of Colorado and Utah also received heavy snow,
including up to 3 feet Thursday at elevations above 6,500 feet in
Utah.
   The storm system was expected to move east, spreading snow
across much of the northern half of the Plains. Its effects,
however, were felt as far west as Southern California, where
northerly winds of 25 to 35 mph and gusts to 45 mph occurred in
higher elevations.
   Elsewhere, a few snow showers lingered in the mountains of
Montana and Idaho. Rain extended from eastern North Dakota into
northwest Minnesota, with snow over northeast Minnesota.
   Dry weather prevailed east of the Mississippi River, across the
southern third of the country, and west of the Rockies.
   Late night temperatures were mostly in the teens and 20s over
the northern and central Rockies and northern Nevada. Readings in
the 20s were also common in the northern and central High Plains,
and from the lower Great Lakes across the northern and central
Appalachians.
   Today's forecast called for strong winds and locally heavy snow
across the northern Plains and Minnesota. Strong, gusty winds also
were expected in the Texas Panhandle and the lower and middle
Mississippi Valley. Snow showers should linger over the northern
and central Rockies, and scattered snow was predicted in northern
Wisconsin and upper Michigan.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 40s, 50s or 60s, except
for 20s and 30s from the northern and central Rockies across the
northern Plains into upper Michigan, and in western and upstate New
York and northern New England. Temperatures should reach the 70s in
the lower Mississippi Valley, Alabama, Florida and the Southwest
deserts, and 70s and 80s across much of the southern Plains.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 11 at
Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 67 at Laredo, Texas, and Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 36 fair; Boston 31 fair; Buffalo 26 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 41 fair; Cincinnati 29 fair; Cleveland 28 partly
cloudy; Detroit 34 cloudy; Miami 57 partly cloudy; New York 34
fair; Philadelphia 27 fair; Pittsburgh 27 fair; Portland, Maine 26
fair; Washington 36 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 33 snow; Chicago 35 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
62 fair; Denver 30 cloudy; Des Moines 39 fair; Indianapolis 32
fair; Kansas City 50 windy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 39 fair; Nashville
33 fair; New Orleans 48 fair; St. Louis 42 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 31 fair; Anchorage 38 partly cloudy; Las
Vegas 45 fair; Los Angeles 55 fair; Phoenix 47 fair; Salt Lake City
28 cloudy; San Diego 53 fair; San Francisco 55 windy; Seattle 36
fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 23 fair; Toronto 27 partly cloudy.
</TEXT>
