<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     03-11 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YUCAIPA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   San Juan Capistrano, which welcomes
migrating swallows every year, has some competition from another
Southern California city, but the winged creatures returning here
buzz instead of flap.
   The city Advisory Council recently proclaimed April 1 the ``80th
Anniversary of the Day the Flies Return to Yucaipa,'' according to
Chairman Burrell Woodring.
   In San Juan Capistrano, the swallows are greeted as they return
to an old Spanish mission. In this city about 75 miles east of
downtown Los Angeles, some people have suggested an April Fools Day
welcoming ceremony for the flies at an old dump.
   Many blame chicken and horse ranches for attracting the pesky
insects, which make their comeback as spring temperatures rise.
   ``I think I'd rather have the swallows,'' said council member
Gary Pitts, who also sits on the San Bernardino County Fly
Abatement and Appeals Board. ``You open your door and you're
inundated.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Henry Miller's typescript of ``Tropic of
Cancer'' sold for $165,000, so aspiring author Alan Rosenberg
figures a manuscript of his new novel should fetch at least $2.75.
   Rosenberg's 415-page bound manuscript of ``Run Red Riding Hood
Run'' is one of 17 items to be placed on the block next month at a
New York auction billed as ``the first futures market in literary
memorabilia.''
   Acknowledging that authors whose memorabilia are considered
worthy of sale are already famous and usually dead, the 34-year-old
Portland writer said Thursday an investment in a Rosenberg memento
would give potential buyers ``a chance to get in on the ground
floor.''
   The items to be offered for auction April 7 include Rosenberg's
dog-eared dictionary, photos and letters, tapes of his dictated
notes, manuscripts of two previous, unpublished books _ and 30
rejection letters from publishers.
   Bids for all items open at $2.75, except for the portable
computer on which he wrote his latest work, Rosenberg said.
   The author, who hired a New York publicist and an auctioneer
specializing in rare books and manuscripts, admits the event is
intended to draw publishers' attention to his new novel.
   ``I don't expect to make enough here to cover my costs,'' the
author said. ``I do expect to make a point. It's tough to break in,
no matter how much talent, determination and patience you have.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Organizers of this Mississippi River
city's annual barbecue contest say it's time the cookoff was
officially titled the world's largest, and they're going whole hog
for the billing.
   The May 12-14 competition is called the World Championship
Barbecue Contest, but that title has no independent verfication.
   The National Pork Producers Council is mounting a cooking
contest June 12 in Des Moines, Iowa, and is seeking a nod from the
Guinness Book of World Records for the most pork barbecue cooked in
a day, said Ida Eleazer, a program director for the Memphis in May
festival.
   The pork producers hope to attract 300 cooking teams and crank
out 20,000 pounds of pork barbecue, she said.
   ``I guess we've been challenged,'' said Becky Landers, an
organizer of Memphis' cookoff.
   In an informal survey two years ago, the Memphis barbecuers
cooked 75,000 pounds of pork in two days, Ms. Landers said.
   This year, participants will be required to keep records of how
much pork they cook.
   ``We never really felt like it was an issue before. We knew we
were the largest barbecue contest in the world,'' Ms. Landers said.
</TEXT>
