<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SuffocatedBoy     03-11 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Suffocated Boy,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teens Found Guilty In Boy's Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense attorneys expressed disbelief after
a judge convicted two 13-year-old girls of being accessories in the
death of a 12-year-old boy forced to drink lighter fluid and
suffocated with a plastic bag.
   Montgomery County Juvenile Court Judge Arthur O. Fisher on
Thursday found the girls guilty of involuntary manslaughter and
grand theft because they helped two 15-year-old boys get into the
apartment of victim Antonio R. Cooley.
   ``I had never envisioned her as anything but a material
witness,'' defense attorney Daniel O'Brien said of his client,
whose name, like that of the other youngsters in the case, was not
released because of their age.
   Attorney Risa McCray, who represented the second girl, said
Fisher ignored the girls' claims they tried to warn the victim and
testimony by a 13-year-old boy backing them up.
   ``He even ignored the state's own evidence,'' Ms. McCray said.
   The defense attorneys contended the 13-year-old boy kept the
girls in a back room while two older boys killed Cooley Feb. 8.
   O'Brien said the two older boys had threatened the girls with
harm even while in the county detention center.
   Cooley was sprayed with insecticide and forced to drink charcoal
lighter fluid before being suffocated with a plastic bag, according
to a deputy coroner.
   Fisher said the girls did nothing to alert authorities, although
they knew the boys were angry because Cooley had denied them use of
his videocassette recorder, and knew they intended to beat Cooley
and steal several items, including the VCR and a stereo.
   O'Brien said he would consider an appeal based on the sentence
Fisher is to impose on the girls at an unspecified date.
   Fisher could order them held for a year, and state officials
then could decide to continue to hold them until age 21, assistant
prosecutor Debra Armanini said.
   The 13-year-old boy has pleaded guilty to deliquency involuntary
manslaughter and theft, and will be sentenced later.
   The 15-year-old boys face delinquency charges of aggravated
murder, aggravated robbery, child endangerment and intimidation,
and may be tried as adults.
   ``I think the verdict sends a message across this city that the
courts are not going to permit anyone, no matter what their age, to
take part in a scheme or plan to snuff out another life,''
assistant prosecutor Mathias Heck Jr. said.
   The girls' mothers sobbed, and one called the verdict unfair.
   ``I know she didn't do it,'' the woman said. ``He (Fisher) was
against them in the very beginning, regardless.''
</TEXT>
