<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bolivia-US 1stLd-Writethru a0484 03-11 0702</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bolivia-US, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0484,0717</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>30 U.S. Military Aid Bolivia in Fight Against Drug Operations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to ADD recent calls in the U.S. for
military involvement. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, `The mission...'
^An AP Extra</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER MCFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The use of U.S. military personnel to
help in anti-drug operations has bolstered Bolivia's ability to
foil trafficking, but also has shown the difficulties of curtailing
a billion dollar industry.
   There are 30 U.S. military trainers and advisers, sent from the
U.S. Southern Command in Panama, now working with Bolivian
anti-narcotics police units and air force pilots, according to the
Interior Ministry.
   There have been recent calls in the United States for the
military to be deployed in the war on drugs and Bolivia is a
country in which the use of U.S. soldiers is being tried.
   The mission is a follow-up to the presence of 175 U.S. soldiers
and six Black Hawk helicopters in July 1986 for a three-month
operation known as Blast Furnace, says David Greenly, chief of
mission at the U.S. Embassy in La Paz.
   ``Blast Furnace demostrated that a concerted U.S.-Bolivian
effort could make a difference in Bolivia, that Bolivian operations
could have a similar impact and we are beginning to see such an
impact is possible,'' Greenly told The Associated Press.
   During the 1986 operation, 22 major cocaine processing labs were
destroyed and cocaine shipment and processing were seriously
disrupted. Farmers could not sell their coca leaves because
processing was snarled, and prices dropped from $1.20 a pound of
coca leaf to 40 cents, the estimated cost of production.
   Cocaine is processed from the leaves of the coca plant, which
peasants in Bolivia grow for its profitability.
   After the troops pulled out in November, coca leaf prices shot
up and trafficking operations returned to normal, Bolivian and U.S.
drug officials say.
   Since then, the U.S. trainers have prepared 720 elite anti-drug
police and taught pilots to fly five Huey helicopters on loan from
the United States. The helicopters, carrying Bolivian police, now
fly regular missions in the tropical lowlands where cocaine labs
are located.
   Bolivian police are disrupting operations in the Chapare
coca-growing region, where most of the cocaine is processed into
paste.
   This is reflected in a drop in coca leaf prices, the U.S. Drug
Enforcement Agency says. It says prices are down to 30 cents a
pound of coca leaf, even lower than Blast Furnace days.
   The volume of cocaine reaching U.S. and European markets has not
decreased and the price of cocaine has dropped, evidence of a glut.
   Bolivian cocaine production, which accounts for one third of
what reaches U.S. and European markets, has increased 10 percent a
year to an estimated 80 metric tons in 1987, according to a report
from the U.S. State Department.
   The cocaine produced in Bolivia has a U.S. street value in the
billons of dollars, the DEA says.
   Despite the concerted effort by Bolivian and U.S. forces,
traffickers have moved their operations to remote and hidden jungle
areas that are difficult to reach by road or even helicopter.
   ``The U.S. government, with all its military might, could only
make a dent on cocaine operations in Bolivia during Blast
Furnace,'' said Information Minister Herman Antelo.
   But he said that dent was important because it showed Bolivia
was serious about combating cocaine despite political problems that
Blast Furnace caused for the government.
   During Blast Furnace, marches were held to protest the U.S.
presence and opposition congressmen and political leaders attacked
the government, describing the U.S. military presence as an
interference in the internal affairs of Bolivia.
   When Bolivian police, DEA agents and pilots took over the
village of Santa Ananin in October 1986 looking for traffickers,
almost the entire town of 5,000 joined in forcing them to leave
under threat of death. Townspeople knew in advance about their
arrival, although officials say the planning was handled with
utmost secrecy.
   Bolivian and U.S. officials hope the presence of the 30
trainers, who are based near the city of Trinidad in the Chapare
region, will reduce corruption of officers by traffickers and
increase the effectiveness of Bolivian police and pilots.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
