<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 0807EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SunLaser     03-11 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sun Laser,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chicago Scientists Set World Record for Concentrating Solar Energy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two scientists set a world record for
concentrating the sun's energy with a homemade silver device that
could help make a practical, solar-powered laser, officials said.
   ``We consider this a breakthrough because it just hasn't been
achieved before,'' said Bimleshwar Gupta of the U.S. Energy
Department's Solar Energy Research Institute in Golden, Colo.,
which paid for the $150,000 project.
   Roland Winston, a University of Chicago physics professor, and
Philip Gleckman, a graduate physics student, used a borrowed mirror
and their solar concentrator to focus sunlight to 60,000 times its
normal intensity on Earth, the university announced Thursday.
   That concentration is about three times the previously achieved
range of 16,000 to 20,000 times normal intensity, said Gupta, the
institute's program manager for solar thermal research.
   ``This work opens whole new areas for applications of solar
energy,'' he said. ``Perhaps the solar concentrator could be used
to power lasers.''
   Most conventional lasers run on electricity, he said. There are
no commercially available solar-powered lasers because the
technology hasn't been developed to harness the sun's rays
efficiently.
   In theory, Gupta said, a solar-powered laser would be cheaper to
operate because conventional lasers require large amounts of
expensive electricity.
   And those advantages would be greater in space, he said, where
solar energy isn't weakened by clouds and is more accessible than
electricity or other types of energy.
   Gleckman, 26, who helped design the solar concentrator on a
computer, said scientists have used sunlight to power lasers
before, ``but not very efficiently.''
   ``We believe this solar concentrator we've built has the
potential to make a more efficient solar-powered laser. ... It
would be less costly and more practical,'' said Gleckman.
   The solar concentrator he helped design was made from an ounce
of silver in a university machine shop. It is hollow and
cone-shaped, about half an inch high and a half-inch wide at the
base, he said.
   It has a one-centimeter opening at the wide end and a smaller
opening, measuring about one millimeter, at the tip, Gleckman said.
   The device is fitted with a lens and contains a special oil that
boosts light refraction, he said.
   The 16-inch diameter mirror _ a standard astronomical telescope
mirror _ was borrowed from the university's Yerkes observatory,
Gleckman said.
   The solar concentrator's design was based on the principle of
``non-imaging optics'' developed by Winston nearly 15 years ago,
the university said.
   In a test Feb. 12 on the roof of a university physics building,
the solar concentrator achieved an intensity of six kilowatts per
square centimeter, the statement said. The previous record was less
than one kilowatt per square centimeter, it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880311-0067 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 0820EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HarvardTenure     03-11 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Harvard Tenure,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Rejects Faculty Vote on Tenure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the second time in a year, Harvard
University President Derek Bok has gone against a majority of
tenured law professors and will not recommend tenure for a
professor who is an adherent of critical legal studies.
   The critical studies philosophy _ that the legal system is
biased in favor of the rich and powerful _ is an issue that has
divided Harvard Law School.
   Bok, who was dean of the law school before he became president
of the university in 1971, announced his decision Thursday in the
case of Clare Dalton, 37, who has taught for seven years.
   ``My record was strong enough for tenure, and there was
political and gender discrimination involved in my being denied,''
she told The Boston Globe Thursday night.
   Bok would not answer questions about the decision, and the
prepared statement he issued did not give a specific reason for his
action, the newspaper said.
   The American Association of University Professors will
investigate, according to a spokeswoman in Washington. The American
Association of Law Schools also has been asked to investigate.
   Last May, Bok went against the law school faculty in not
recommending tenure for professor David Trubek.
   Tenured members of the law school faculty voted 29-20 last
spring in favor of granting Ms. Dalton tenure, four votes short of
the two-thirds needed under a rule change earlier in the year.
   Some faculty members say the rule is used by conservative
professors to block tenure for faculty with whom they disagree
politically. Daniel Tarullo, who also was recommended by a majority
but not a two-thirds vote, was denied tenure then.
   Last October, Ms. Dalton filed complaints against Harvard with
the Massachusetts Commission Against Discrimination and the federal
Equal Employment Opportunity Commission.
   She and a representative of the university asked the state
commission not to investigate until Bok completed a review of the
case. Her lawyer, Nancy Gertner, said Ms. Dalton has ``an extremely
strong gender discrimination case and an extremely strong political
discrimination case.''
   Last December, Bok appointed an outside committee to review the
case.
   The Globe said that according to a letter Bok reportedly sent to
law school faculty Thursday, the committee and Harvard Law School
Dean James Vorenberg and two Harvard law professors met for seven
hours Sunday, reviewed Ms. Dalton's scholarship, and decided that
her ``record was not sufficient to merit tenure.''
</TEXT>
