<1ST_LINE>r i PM-IRA-Gibraltar     03-11 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-IRA-Gibraltar,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Secretary Defends Shootings; More Violence In Belfast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary George
Younger defended British soldiers who shot dead three unarmed IRA
guerrillas in Gibraltar as violence over the slayings erupted in
Belfast for a fourth night.
   Younger said on the British Broadcasting Corp.'s television
program ``Question Time'' broadcast from Belfast Thursday night
that the soldiers challenged the three guerrillas before opening
fire on Sunday.
   ``They were challenged, we understand. If you challenge
somebody, in that second they convince you that they are about to
kill you, my goodness you have a right to defend yourself and my
goodness you always should,'' Younger said.
   The killing of the guerrillas, who authorities say were plotting
a huge car bomb explosion in the British colony, enraged IRA
supporters. The Irish government has complained about the alleged
lack of any attempt to arrest them.
   On the British mainland, 60 legislators of the opposition Labor
Party and some newspapers have also questioned the slayings.
   Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe said Monday that the
guerrillas _ a woman and two men _ were shot when they made
movements that made the soldiers involved think their own lives
were in danger.
   Witnesses said the soldiers were wearing jeans.
   The IRA said the three guerrrillas were ``on active service,'' a
euphemism for a bombing or shooting attack as part of the outlawed
group's guerrilla war to end British rule in Northern Ireland.
   The mainly Catholic IRA wants to unite the predominantly
Protestant province with the overwhelmingly Catholic Irish Republic
under socialist rule.
   The IRA commandos were shot in the street by the British
soldiers believed to belong to the crack Special Air Services
regiment after parking a car near the governor's residence.
   Police said they believed the car was parked to reserve a space
for a car bomb that was later found outside the fortress colony on
Spain territory.
   Violence erupted in Roman Catholic areas of Belfast for the
fourth straight night Thursday. A press officer at Belfast police
headquarters said it was markedly lighter than on the previous
three nights of rioting.
   He said an army patrol escaped injury in a bomb attack in West
Belfast and two vans and a car were stolen and set on fire.
   He also reported some shooting and a gasoline bomb attack on an
ambulance, but said nobody was hurt in any of the attacks and that
army explosives experts safely defused two bombs found in the city.
   The officer, by regulation speaking on condition of anonymity,
said that in Londonderry, Northern Ireland's second largest city,
Catholic youths hurled gasoline bombs at a joint army and police
patrol but again nobody was hurt.
   By Friday, 60 of Labor's 229 legislators in the 650-seat Commons
denounced the killings in a motion as ``an act of terrorism....
tantamount to capital punishment without trial.''
   The motion charged: ``There was no attempt to apprehend or
arrest these people before killing them.''
   Labor's foreign affairs spokesman, Gerald Kaufman, has written
to Howe repeating Labor's demand for an inquiry.
</TEXT>
