<HEAD>Panama Envoy Says He Was Fired, Refuses To Step Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama's ambassador to Belgium said
today that he has been fired but is staying on in defiance of
Panamanian military leader Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Angel Riera Diaz said his aide, Navidad Moron Zanet, was
promoted from attache to charge d'affaires.
   ``But I am not relinquishing my office,'' Riera said in a
telephone interview. ``I do not recognize the authority of Noriega.
I recognize the authority of President (Eric Arturo) Delvalle,''
whose Feb. 26 ouster was engineered by the military strongman.
   Riera said Ms. Moron is a Noriega ally and had a hand in a
``break-in'' of his office Wednesday while he was in Strasbourg,
France, to lobby for a European Parliament resolution condemning
Noriega.
   He said five men whom he said had been sent from Panama,
``forced the door of my office'' and rummaged through his papers.
   Ms. Moron said the men were ``officials of the central bank of
Panama who needed the room for a meeting.''
   Riera said the men ``were a delegation sent by Noriega to
terrorize diplomats and to see if everyone is under control.''
   Similar disputes among Panamanian diplomats divided over the
Noriega-Delvalle imbroglio have occurred in other foreign capitals
including in London, Washington and Mexico City.
   The United States, where a federal jury last month indicted
Noriega on drug trafficking and money laundering charges,
recognizes Delvalle.
   The Belgian government had no immediate reaction to the change
of command at the Panamanian Embassy.
