<HEAD>Students March In Two Cities, Textile Workers Stage Work Stoppage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials let 2,000 students rally in
Krakow for the right to form an independent students' union, but a
bid to start a march in another southern Polish city was blocked,
opposition spokesmen said.
   The Krakow rally occurred Thursday evening after a Mass marking
the 20th anniversary of 1968 student demonstrations against
censorship that were brutally crushed by police and Communist
Party-allied worker activists.
   In another development, an opposition spokeswoman said more than
1,000 textile workers near Wroclaw staged a three-hour strike
Wednesday and won a promise of talks with managers in a pay dispute.
   In Krakow, students carrying banners of the banned Independent
Students' Union, Solidarity trade union and Confederation of
Independent Poland marched from the Mass to dormitories about 500
yards away and held a rally, said spokesman Zygmunt Lenyk.
   ``There were lots of police around the church but they did not
intervene,'' he said.
   Students who tried to march to the center of Krakow on Tuesday
were repeatedly charged by police wielding clubs, according to
opposition spokesmen.
   In Gliwice, meanwhile, five youths were arrested Thursday
evening when students attempted to form a march after a Mass also
commemorating the March 1968 disturbances, said Jan Mazurkiewicz, a
local activist.
   Plainclothes officers moved in immediately when some students
emerged, unfurled banners and tried to march after the service, he
said.
   At the Hanka textile plant near Wroclaw on Wednesday, 90 percent
of the 1,200-strong female workforce took part in the work
stoppage, said opposition activist Barbara Labuda.
   She said workers were angry that a portion of a $16 monthly pay
increase intended to compensate for recent price rises was being
deducted by management for the plant's vacation and recreation fund.
   Managers agreed to meet with the women on Monday, she said.
