<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 0832EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CDC-InjuryGoals     03-11 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CDC-Injury Goals,0594</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Many Of Feds' 1990 Goals For Injury Death Prevention Likely To Be
Met</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six of the nation's nine goals for reducing
fatalities from injuries by 1990 will probably be achieved, federal
health officials predict.
   The national Centers for Disease Control reported Thursday that
the fatality rates from many types of injuries, including car
accidents, house fires and drownings, have dropped since 1979, when
the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services announced its 1990
goals for the nation.
   However, some rates have not fallen as far as the government had
hoped, the CDC said. Although some of the 1990 injury-related goals
_ reducing deaths from car crashes, childhood household accidents,
house fires and gun accidents _ will be met, others _ such as
reducing deaths from falls and drownings _ won't.
   ``Achieving the 1990 objectives ... will require the coordinated
efforts of federal, state and local agencies ... academic
institutions, professional associations and private entities,'' the
Atlanta-based CDC said in its weekly report.
   Here, from the CDC report, is a look at the nation's 1990 goals
for reducing deaths from injuries, and the progress being made:
   _Reducing the nation's annual motor vehicle fatality rate, from
23.6 such deaths per 100,000 Americans in 1978 to 18 per 100,000 in
1990. By 1984, the rate had fallen to 19.6, and the goal is
projected to be met, in part because of a reduction in
alcohol-related fatalities.
   _Reducing the motor vehicle fatality rate for children under 15,
from nine per 100,000 in 1978 to 5.5. By 1984, the rate had fallen
to 6.6, and the goal is projected to be met.
   _Reducing the death rate from falls from 6.2 per 100,000 in 1978
to two. The rate had fallen only to 5.1 by 1984, and the goal is
not expected to be reached. People over 65 continue to have high
death rates from falls _ for example, in 1984, 10.2 such deaths per
100,000 people age 65-74, and 147 per 100,000 people over 84.
   _Reducing the death rate for children under 15 in home injuries
from six per 100,000 in 1978 to five. The 1984 rate was 4.9,
already meeting the objective.
   _Reducing the drowning rate from 3.2 per 100,000 in 1978 to 1.5.
The rate had fallen only to 2.3 in 1984, and the goal is not
expected to be met.
   _Reducing the number of deaths in residential fires from 5,401
in 1978 to 4,500. The objective was reached in 1984, when 4,466
Americans died in such fires.
   _Reducing the number of deaths in firearm accidents from 1,806
in 1978 to 1,700. The goal was met in 1984, when 1,668 such deaths
were reported.
   _Reducing the suicide rate among 15- to 24-year-olds from 12.1
per 100,000 in 1978 to 11. The rate is going up, not down; it was
12.2 per 100,000 in 1984, up slightly from 1978 and up about 200
percent from 1950. CDC noted that various suicide prevention
approaches have been tried in U.S. communities, but their
effectiveness is not known.
   _Reducing the homicide rate among black males aged 15-24 from
70.7 per 100,000 in 1978 to 60. This goal will probably be met,
according to CDC researcher Dr. Richard Sattin; the rate had fallen
in 1984 to 61.5. This goal was set recognizing the high homicide
rate among young black men, Sattin said, noting that the national
homicide rate in 1984 was 8.4 per 100,000 Americans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
