<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Haiti-Drugs     03-11 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Haiti-Drugs,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Extradition Of Haitian Colonel Will Be Difficult</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Haitian colonel accused of conspiring to import
100 kilograms of cocaine into the United States is unlikely to come
to trial, U.S. officials have conceded.
   ``At present there is no extradition treaty between the United
States and Haiti,'' Ana Barnett, an executive assistant to U.S.
Attorney Leon Kellner, said Thursday after the indictment accusing
Col. Jean-Claude Paul was unsealed.
   ``This leaves a substantial question of how the extradition of
Colonel Paul could be accomplished,'' she said.
   A statement Haiti's President Leslie Manigat issued Thursday
through a Washington public relations firm called the indictment
``a matter of concern'' that will be handled in Haiti by military
courts.
   Paul, head of a battalion in the Haitian capital of
Port-au-Prince, is accused of conspiring to import 100 kilograms of
cocaine into the United States. His brother, Antonio Paul, and his
former wife, Marie Merielle Delinois, also were named as defendants
in the indictment.
   Jean-Claude Paul, 40, had close ties to the military-dominated
ruling junta that replaced President Jean-Claude ``Baby Doc''
Duvalier after he fled the impoverished island nation in February
1986. The officer seldom appeared in public during the junta's
two-year rule, which ended when Manigat was inaugurated last Feb. 7.
   When he did, it often was to serve as bodyguard for Lt. Gen.
Henri Namphy, the junta president and now military chief, and Brig.
Gen. Williams Regala, now defense minister.
   The indictment charged that in December 1986 the accused
traffickers used a landing strip on Paul's farm 90 miles from
Haiti's capital to load and fly the cocaine shipment to the
Bahamas, where it was lost or stolen.
   Both men named in the indictment are charged with conspiracy to
distribute, distribution and attempted importation of cocaine. They
could face up to 45 years in prison and $375,000 in fines.
   Ms. Delinois, already a federal fugitive after jumping bond on a
related March 1987 indictment in Miami, faces the same three
counts, plus charges of jumping bond and attempting to extort a
fellow conspirator with violence. She faces up to 75 years in
prison and $410,000 in fines.
   The extortion count grows out of the unexplained loss of the
cocaine shipment on Spanish Key in the Bahamas, where it allegedly
was flown from Haiti for shipment to the United States.
   Osvaldo Quintana, a conspirator and now a principal government
witness, went to Spanish Key in an attempt to locate the cocaine,
the indictment said.
   When he failed to find it, according to the indictment, Ms.
Delinois told him ``his family would be killed if he did not pay at
least $250,000 of the money owed for the lost shipment.''
   Quintana, in a news conference here last month, said there were
two attempts on his life by armed Haitians, but no shots were fired.
   Quintana has testified for the government at previous drug
trials. In January, outside of a federal courtroom, he told
reporters he had once seen 9,000 kilograms of cocaine stuffed into
duffel bags in the Haitian presidential palace during the
administration of Duvalier.
</TEXT>
