<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Indonesia 1stLd-Writethru   03-11 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Indonesia, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0534,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suharto Aide Elected Vice President After Moslems Drop Candidate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to ADD background. No pickup. One name for
Suharto and Sudharmono</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GHAFUR FADYL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Parliament today elected a close
aide of President Suharto as vice president despite opposition from
a Moslem faction and some members of the military.
   The five factions in the 1,000-member People's Consultative
Assembly reached a consensus to elect State Secretary Sudharmono,
61, to the post after the Moslem United Development Party dropped
its candidate, Jailani Naro, who is party chairman.
   The Moslem party had opposed Sudharmono.
   Sudharmono's election came hours after Suharto was sworn in as
president for a fifth five-year term. Suharto has been president of
Indonesia for 22 years.
   The assembly, the nation's highest policymaking body,
unanimously reelected Suharto on Thursday. He was the only
candidate.
   Suharto, 66, reportedly told party members late last month the
next vice president should be able to lead the nation should he
become incapacitated.
   Sudharmono was nominated by the ruling GOLKAR party, an acronym
for the Indonesian words ``Golongan Karya'' or functional group.
   He was also supported by three other factions in the assembly _
the government-nominated military faction, the government-nominated
provincial faction and the nationalist Christian Indonesian
Democratic party faction.
   Military sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said some
members of the army had opposed Sudharmono's nomination and wanted
to nominate the newly appointed armed forces commander, Gen. Try
Sutrisno, 52, a popular figure and a former Suharto aide.
   The assembly meets every five years to elect a president and
vice president and issue a decree on the guidelines for state
policies.
   Sudharmono, 61, a retired army lieutenant general, is a military
lawyer. He is one of the country's leading bureaucrats after years
of government apprenticeship, first under the late President
Sukarno and then as a founding member of the Suharto administration.
   Suharto is expected later this month to form a new Cabinet,
which will have to tackle economic development and cope with a
hefty foreign debt of $42.1 billion.
   The country's economy was hit hard by the collapse of oil
prices, a drop in prices in commodities and the 1983 economic
recession.
</TEXT>
