<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines     03-11 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tough Negotiations Predicted On U.S. Bases; Rebels Raid Police
Station</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FIL C. SIONIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. military bases here are
essential for both nations' defenses, but difficult negotiations
are ahead on how much Washington will pay the Philippines to keep
them, a senior American diplomat said today.
   Also today, the military said about 200 communist rebels dressed
in fatigues raided a police station, killing three policemen and a
civilian before making off with weapons and a radio.
   The rebels attacked Thursday afternoon in the town of St.
Nicholas in Pangasinan province, 100 miles northeast of the capital.
   In Manila, Kenneth Quinn, the U.S. deputy chief of mission,
denied allegations by the Philippines' foreign secretary that the
United States will step up political pressure on President Corazon
Aquino to extend the current bases agreement.
   Quinn told a civic club that the U.S. installations, including
Clark Air Base and the Subic Bay Naval Base, contributed to global
security and played a major role not only in the defense of the
Philippines but in providing jobs to Filipinos.
   ``The bases are important because they provide for our bilateral
protection and for the external defense of the Philippines,'' Quinn
said.
   ``We think they're important because they make an enormous
contribution to the economy of the Philippines in terms of the
68,000-plus Filipinos who are hired there and the $500 million a
year which is spent in your economy,'' he added.
   Quinn described as ``absolutely false'' a claim by Foreign
Secretary Raul Manglapus that the United States was pressuring Mrs.
Aquino to say whether she wants the bases agreement extended.
   On Thursday, Manglapus, who spent more than 10 years as a
political refugee in the United States, accused the Americans of
``arm-twisting'' Mrs. Aquino ``because they have decided to stay.''
   The current agreement provides that after Sept. 16, 1991, the
Philippines can order the bases closed within one year. Mrs. Aquino
has said she will honor the current agreement but refuses to say
whether she will agree to an extension.
   Under the new constitution, any extension must be approved by
two-thirds of the 23-member Senate and may be subject to a national
referendum.
   The U.S. and Philippine governments are to begin reviewing the
current agreement within the next two months. Filipino officials
are expected to demand a substantial increase in the $180 million a
year which the Manila government receives in aid for use of the
bases.
   Quinn said he expected a ``full and frank discussion'' on the
issue of compensation, using diplomatic language which refers to
tough bargaining.
   Some Filipino congressmen have suggested that the United States
agree to pay off the country's nearly $29 billion foreign debt as
the price for keeping the bases.
   About 70 members of the radical League of Filipino Students
rallied in front of the Senate building today demanding the bases
be closed.
   They carried placards reading: ``Save the earth from nuclear
destruction; dismantle all U.S. bases.''
   On Thursday, Rep. Lorna Yap, a member of the House foreign
affairs committee, said the panel reached a consensus to enforce a
provision of the constitution against nuclear weapons.
   The constitution states that: ``The Philippines, consistent with
the national interest, adopts and pursues a policy of freedom from
nuclear weapons in its territory.''
   Some government officials argue the phrase ``consistent with the
national interest'' would give Mrs. Aquino flexibility to allow
such weapons at the American bases. Others see it as a ban on such
weapons.
   The United States refuses to say whether it maintains nuclear
weapons at the installations here.
</TEXT>
