<1ST_LINE>r p PM-MysteryCandidate     03-11 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mystery Candidate,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Little Known Candidate Makes Congressional Runoff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAXAHACHIE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A candidate seldom seen or heard from
collected enough votes in a Democratic congressional primary to
make it into the runoff, but his two challengers in the contest
have cried foul.
   Johnny Welch, who has called for a manned space flight to Saturn
and a requirement that every American perform civil service,
captured 34 percent of the vote in the 6th Congressional District
primary Tuesday.
   He faces an April 12 runoff against N.P. ``Pat'' Kendrick, and
the winner of that race will take on Republican incumbent U.S. Rep.
Joe Barton.
   But Kendrick and ousted candidate W. Alton Parish think they've
been the victims of some sort of Republican conspiracy. Registered
Republicans can vote in either party's primary, as long as they
don't cast ballots in both.
   ``They did it intentionally,'' charged Parish, a Fort Worth
economics professor.
   ``There's something very suspicious here,'' he said. ``Mr.
Kendrick and I worked very hard on this campaign. We never took him
(Welch) seriously. Kendrick thought I was his opponent, and I
thought he was mine.''
   Gary Koops, Barton's press secretary, denied that Republicans
were behind the voting for Welch, and he noted that Barton had
worked with local officials throughout the district to produce a
record-breaking GOP turnout Tuesday.
   There was some speculation that perhaps voters confused Welch
with Louie Welch, the former longtime mayor of Houston who twice
waged a high-profile campaign against incumbent Kathy Whitmire.
   Johnny Welch's address and home phone number are listed with the
secretary of state's office, and a check with both the telephone
book and directory assistance confirmed the number is correct.
   But calls to the home address have gone unanswered; there is no
campaign office listed, and party activists in two districts say
they have never heard of Welch.
   Welch's three-point platform called for launching a manned space
flight to Saturn, mandating that every American participate in
civil service unless they pay a fee to the government, and feeding
and sheltering the hungry and homeless.
</TEXT>
