<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0533,0844</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Blocks City Entrances On Moslem Sabbath</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to UPDATE with five wounded. PICKS up 2nd
graf, `The mufti ...' INSERTS 3 grafs after 15th graf ` In Nablus
...,' to UPDATE with details of unrest. PICKS up 16th graf `In Gaza
...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HEBRON, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army blocked off some
cities in the occupied territories to media coverage during Moslem
noon prayers today after destroying at least four homes of
suspected Palestinian activists.
   At least five Palestinians were wounded during protests in the
West Bank and Gaza, hospital officials and Arab reports said.
   The mufti of Jerusalem, the city's top Moslem religious leader,
issued a statement lashing out at Israel for blocking some mosques
from worshippers, raiding others and confiscating loudspeakers used
to summon Palestinians to prayer.
   The mufti, Sheik Said Adin Alami, called on worshippers ``to
defend the mosques by all possible means despite the attackers.''
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, meanwhile, reiterated his
opposition to a U.S. peace plan for the region in the strongest
statement he has made so far.
   Shamir, speaking on Israel radio, said when he arrives in
Washington next week he would ``explain to our friend Secretary of
State George Shultz that his plan, as it's seen today, can't solve
the problem of peace in our area.''
   The army destroyed one home overnight in Hebron, 20 miles south
of Jerusalem in the occupied West Bank, and three others in Biddya,
30 miles northwest of Jerusalem.
   In Hebron, the destroyed home where 22 Palestinians live
belonged to Ahmed Mahmoud Abdullah Kawasmeh, 57, whose 22-year-old
son is accused of stabbing an Israeli settler from nearby Kiryat
Arba five months ago in Jerusalem.
   ``The soldiers came. They woke us about 11:30 at night and
ordered us out of the house,'' Kawasmeh, wearing an Arab headdress
and wrapped in a ragged blanket, told The Associated Press.
   ``I said, `But my son has not even been tried yet.' But it did
not make any difference,'' he said.
   The latest demolitions brought to 14 the number of Palestinian
homes destroyed by Israeli troops since the unrest began in the
territories more than three months ago, the Palestine Press Service
said.
   At least 87 Palestinians have been killed by Israeli gunfire or
beatings during the unrest, and hundreds have been wounded.
   The army turned back journalists from Hebron and Nablus, but the
clampdown was not as severe as last Friday, when roadblocks
prevented journalists from entering nearly all major cities, towns
and refugee camps in the West Bank.
   Friday is the Moslem Sabbath.
   In Hebron, about 10 Israeli settlers with rifles slung over
their shoulders patrolled a Jewish neighborhood near Al Ibrahimi
Mosque during noon prayers.
   In Nablus, the West Bank's largest city, noon prayers passed
without incident and Israeli soldiers kept largely out of sight,
although an army helicopter circled overhead.
   In the southern district of the West Bank, 60 of 250 Arab
policemen resigned after being urged by PLO leaflets to quit
working for the Israelis.
   In Ramallah, about 200 protesters threw rocks at soldiers after
noon prayers. Soldiers fired rubber bullets and tear gas to quell
the demonstrators.
   The Jerusalem Post reported, meanwhile, that the army is
currently holding about 2,600 Palestinian prisoners.
   In Gaza City, the army closed the main Al Amari Mosque for the
first time, creating what Palestinian residents said was ``deep
anger'' in the city. Some 2,500 worshipers usually pray at the
mosque.
   In other mosques in Gaza City, special ``Salat al Ghaib'' or
``Prayers for the Missing'' were held at the order of the PLO to
honor the Palestinians who have been killed by Israelis since the
uprising began.
   In Jerusalem, about 200 Palestinians protested after noon
prayers at the Dome of the Rock and Al Aqsa Mosques, raising
several Palestinian flags, which have been outlawed by Israel.
   On Thursday, Foreign Minister Shimon Peres said the Jewish state
would lose an opportunity to make peace by passing up the Shultz
initiative.
   Peres, head of the left-centrist Labor Party, said upon
receiving an honorary doctorate from Hebrew Union College in
Jerusalem that Israel would be making a fateful decision in the
next few weeks.
   ``In 40 days time there is a chance that direct negotiations may
start between a Jordanian-Palestinian delegation and an Israeli
delegation,'' he said. ``In 40 days we may lose the opportunity as
well, and the grayness of hesitation, of suspicion, of postponement
may cover our skies again for time to come.''
   Shamir flies to Washington next week to discuss the initiative
one more time before announcing whether he accepts it or not.
   The plan calls for negotiations on the final status of the
occupied lands to begin in December, elections for Palestinian
self-rule in the West Bank and Gaza Strip by late 1988 and
implementation of self-rule for Palestinians in three years.
</TEXT>
