<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Austria-Anschluss 3rdLd-Writethru   03-11 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Austria-Anschluss, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0520,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Austria Marks Annexation by Nazi Germany</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with protests, Greens boycotting
Parliament. CORRECTS spelling of fascism. Edits to tighten. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH JAUTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Austria today marked the 50th anniversary
of its annexation by Nazi Germany, capping a bitter two-year debate
about its World War II past that has polarized politics at home and
tarnished its image abroad.
   About 60 protesters gathered outside the chancellery to demand
the resignation of President Kurt Waldheim. Members of the liberal
Greens party boycotted a special parliamentary session marking the
annexation, known as the Anschluss.
   During World War II, Waldheim served as a lieutenant in a German
army unit in the Balkans that has been linked to Nazi atrocities.
He has denied any wrongdoing.
   Fewer than 100 people turned out in a light rain as Waldheim and
other political leaders laid wreaths in separate ceremonies at
monuments honoring Austria's unknown soldiers and victims of
fascism.
   During the ceremonies a dozen protesters gathered outside the
chancellory building 500 yards away, carrying a banner that asked:
``Who Will Make Waldheim Resign?''
   Until two years ago, Waldheim had not admitted that he served in
the Balkans unit. Since then, he has resisted mounting pressure to
resign.
   Greens delegates handed out pamphlets saying they were
protesting Waldheim's presence at the hour-long session. The
pamphlets said Waldheim ``is not representative of the Austria that
we want to commemorate.''
   The Greens said they would instead travel to Mauthausen, site of
a former Nazi concentration camp near the city of Linz, to honor
the victims of Nazi Germany.
   Chancellor Franz Vranitzky told a special Cabinet session that
the events of 1938, when this Alpine nation was forcibly annexed to
Adolf Hitler's Third Reich, were a central theme of Austrian
politics today.
   ``The events of 50 years ago pose relevant, fundamental
questions about the essence of politics,'' Vranitzky said. ``If one
attempts to avoid them, they sooner or later return with greater
emphasis.''
   Vranitzky said Austrians must recognize that crimes were
committed by their countrymen during World War II.
   ``We must recognize the fact of historical guilt ... because as
politicians we must draw lessons from the past failures of
society,'' he said.
   Vranitzky did not mention the Waldheim controversy.
   Waldheim, originally to speak at a Hofburg palace ceremony, was
to remain out of the spotlight throughout the day.
   Instead, Waldheim commemorated the annexation with a nationally
televised speech Thursday in which for the first time he apologized
for crimes committed by Austrian Nazis during the war. But he
ignored the debate surrounding him.
   ``We must not forget that many of the worst Nazi hangmen were
Austrians,'' Waldheim said in the 12-minute speech. ``There were
Austrians who were victims and others who were perpetrators.''
   The president added that ``as head of state of the Republic of
Austria, I wish to apologize for Nazi crimes committed by
Austrians.''
   Austria's Nazi past _ largely suppressed here over the past four
decades _ has dogged this country since the disclosure in March
1986 of Waldheim's wartime service in the Balkans.
   As a result, the U.S. Justice Department last year placed
Waldheim on a list that effectively bars him from entering the
country.
   In April 1938, the Nazis said 99 percent of Austrians approved
of the Anschluss in a nationwide vote widely believed to have been
rigged.
   More than half a million Austrians joined the Nazi party, and
250,000 turned out to cheer Hitler when he came to Vienna shortly
after the Anschluss.
   Last month, an international panel of historians found that
Waldheim had been in ``close proximity'' to war crimes during World
War II, knew they were going on and made no attempt to prevent them.
   The panel's report did not support allegations Waldheim
committed atrocities, but left open the question of whether he was
guilty of any crime. Waldheim claimed the report vindicated him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880311-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 0943EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JamaicanDrugs     03-11 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jamaican Drugs,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arrests Break Up Violent Crack Ring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A violent Jamaican crack ring that operated in
New York, Philadelphia and Washington and was responsible for a
series of murders and other brutal crimes has been smashed by the
arrests of several alleged drug dealers, authorities say.
   The arrests were the result of an intensive investigation
focusing on an epidemic of murders and shootings by Jamaican drug
rings in Brooklyn, said U.S. Attorney Andrew Maloney on Thursday.
   The alleged ringleader, described as ``one of the most feared
crack organization enforcers in the nation,'' and six others were
named in federal complaints, Maloney said. One defendant remains at
large.
   ``The level of trafficking has risen and the level of violence
by Jamaican posses is very high,'' said Robert Stutman, head of the
federal Drug Enforcement Agency's New York office.
   The 50-member drug ring dealt up to $100,000 of crack, a highly
addictive cocaine derivative, each day in Brooklyn alone, Maloney
said. The ring, which had been in operation since 1983, also
allegedly ran less extensive operations in Philadelphia and
Washington.
   The complaint alleged the defendants were responsible for five
murders, 15 shootings, one abduction and one beating.
   The leader was identified as Delroy ``Uzi'' Edwards, 29, of
Brooklyn, who is a Jamaican national. Edwards, who drove a
Mercedes, got his nickname because he used to carry a submachine
gun under his trenchcoat, authorities said.
   Edwards allegedly murdered two of his dealers in Washington
because one of them had stolen money from the organization, the
complaint said. He also allegedly shot and injured three New York
members for the same reason.
   Another grisly murder described in the complaint was that of a
man who was beaten with baseball bats and then tied with chains to
the ceiling of a crack location. The next morning the man was found
dead, his body wrapped in garbage bags and dropped off on a street.
   After his arrest on a Brooklyn street corner Wednesday, Edwards
was turned over to the Brooklyn district attorney's office, where
he was wanted on an outstanding warrant for an unrelated murder.
   The other defendants were identified as Patrick Williams, Erroll
Thorpe and Ricky Nelson, all Jamaicans; and John Barry Russell,
Conroy Green and Stanley McCall, who were said to be U.S. citizens.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Jonny Frank said there was only sketchy
information about the defendants, but that most were in their 20s
and they all lived in Brooklyn.
   McCall is the only defendant still at large, Frank said.
   Stutman said violent Jamaican drug rings known as ``posses'' can
be found in many Eastern cities.
   ``They are constantly seeking out new weapons or tactics,'' he
said. ``More and more, especially the Jamaicans, are starting to
shoot back at police.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
