<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Iran-Iraq 3rdLd-Writethru   03-11 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0525,a0521,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Fires Missiles At Iran; Bombs Ship</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with Iraq firing 11 missiles at
Iran. PICKS up 9th graf, `The agency ...' EDITS to tighten
thereafter.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said it fired 11 missiles today into
Tehran and Qom, seat of Iran's religious hierarchy, undermining
efforts to halt the 12-day-old bloody ``war of the cities.''
   The official Iraqi News Agency also said Iraqi warplanes bombed
a tanker off the Iranian coast.
   The news agency, monitored in Nicosia, reported that the 11th
missile was fired at the Iranian capital at 3:44 p.m., 16 minutes
before Baghdad had said it would stop its deadly barrages on
Iranian cities.
   Iraq had offered to end the bombardments if Iran halted its
barrages on Baghdad and other Iraqi cities. Baghdad also demanded
that it be allowed to fire the last shot.
   In all, the Iraqi agency said eight missiles were fired into
Tehran today and three into Qom, 60 miles south of the Iranian
capital.
   Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency confirmed five of the
attacks and said there were numerous casualties.
   The agency said that in one attack, homes of two Jewish families
surnamed Odishiv and Roshan were demolished, killing and wounding
women and children.
   There were no reports of Iranian attacks on Baghdad. But the
Iraqi news agency said Iranian F-4 Phantom jets struck hard at
residential targets in the northern Iraqi city of Sulaymaniya,
killing and wounding several civilians.
   It also said Basra, in southern Iraq, and a cluster of towns
along the border were shelled by Iranian long-range artillery, but
gave no precise casualty figures.
   Iraq said that during the night its warplanes bombed a ``large
maritime target,'' a reference to an oil tanker, off the Iranian
coast, and seven Iranian cities today _ Baneh and Ardabil in the
north, Kermanshah and Hamadan in the west; Arak and Broujerd in
central Iran; and Dezful in the southwest.
   The agency did not identify the stricken ship, but said the
planes ``scored accurate and effective blows'' on all their targets.
   Iran's agency confirmed the raids on the cities, saying they
were aimed at civilian targets.
   ``This is a further proof to the Tehran rulers, who are filled
with evil intentions and hatred, that they should not have started
the war of the cities,'' the Iraqi News Agency said.
   It said the attacks ``were designed to avenge the innocent blood
shed in Baghdad'' and other Iraqi cities in the unprecedented
missile duel.
   Before today, Iran and Iraq had claimed firing 78 missiles at
each other's capitals since Feb. 29. Fifty-one were fired by Iraq
at Tehran and 27 by Iran at Baghdad.
   According to the Iranian agency, the previous attacks on Tehran
have killed at least 157 civilians and wounded more than 420. Iraq
has not provided exact casualty figures.
   Several missiles have struck other Iranian cities, including Qom
and central Isfahan, while Iranian gunners kept up a steady barrage
of artillery fire on Iraqi border communities.
   Turkish Prime Minister Turgut Ozal said in Ankara that Iran and
Iraq had agreed to halt the duels at his request.
   Iraq announced Thursday that it would stop attacking Iranian
cities at 4 p.m. Baghdad time today, which is 4:30 p.m. Tehran time.
   Iran gave two times Thursday when it said it would stop its
attacks, but both deadlines passed with continued attacks. Today,
however, Iran has not reported firing any missiles.
   Iran's U.N. envoy, Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati, offered to honor
an unconditional truce if the U.N. chief called for one.
   Mahallati told a news conference in New York that Iran would not
fire back if Iraq got in the last shot before any deadline set by
U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   Perez de Cuellar had no immediate comment.
</TEXT>
