<1ST_LINE>u a PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0405 03-11 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0405,0594</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wholesale Prices Down in February</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with Producer Price Index,
retail sales reports, picking up 3rd graf pvs, `Declining issues
....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Declines in the costs of food and energy pushed wholesale prices
downward last month, while retail sales were boosted by strength in
autos, the government said today.
   Wholesale prices fell 0.2 percent in February, the Labor
Department said as it released its monthly Producer Price Index.
   Food prices fell 1.1 percent and energy prices declined 0.8
percent, the department said.
   For the first two months of 1988, prices rose at an annual rate
of 1.1 percent, half the modest 2.2 percent rate for all of last
year. Prices rose 0.4 percent in January after a 0.4 percent
decline in December.
   Meanwhile, the Commerce Department said retail sales rose 0.6
percent in February. The increase was generally in line with
expectations.
   The government also revised its January retail sales report to
show a small decline of 0.2 percent instead of an originally
reported increase of 0.5 percent.
   Even with the January decline, analysts said the sales report
generally reflected that the October stock market crash has had
little effect on consumer buying plans.
   Since consumer spending accounts for two-thirds of overall
economic activity, any significant faltering in this area could
topple the country into a recession.
   On Thursday, nervousness over Wall Street's strength yanked down
stock prices, but pessimism disappeared in the energy markets,
where oil futures rose sharply over expectations that OPEC will
take steps to avert another 1986-style price collapse.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell 48.24 points
to 2,026.03, its largest loss since falling 57.20 on Jan. 20.
Broader market indicators also declined.
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by nearly 3 to 1 on the
New York Stock Exchange, and the Wilshire 5000 Equity Index
measuring the value of 5,000 U.S. stocks fell nearly $40 billion.
   Analysts said the selloff reflected continued anxiety about the
aftermath of the Oct. 19 market crash, which persistently has
undermined investor confidence.
   The mood contrasted sharply with a buying spree on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, where contracts for April delivery of West
Texas Intermediate, the main U.S. crude, rose 51 cents to close at
$16.00 a barrel. Refined products traded on the exchange also rose
sharply.
   Petroleum analysts linked the oil rally to reports that the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries _ aware it can't
sustain relentless price discounting and excessive output _ will
shave 5 percent off the production of all members except Iraq,
which has resisted cartel discipline.
   The reports reflected hopes that after three months of price
erosion reminiscent of the cataclysmic market plunge two years ago,
OPEC and non-OPEC producers were taking steps to avoid another
uncontrollable drop.
   Since January, prices for Persian Gulf oil have fallen as low as
$13 per 42-gallon barrel, compared with OPEC's official price of
$18. West Texas Intermediate has dropped from about $18 to as low
as $15.
   In other financial markets, gold prices rose sharply in reaction
to the sudden strength in the oil market, which could portend
higher inflation. Gold is considered a good hedge against rising
prices.
   In the bond market, a barometer of interest rate trends, prices
fell in reaction to higher oil and metal prices. The Treasury's
30-year issue fell $5 per $1,000 in face amount and its yield rose
from 8.51 percent to 8.55 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
