<1ST_LINE>u i PM-CopterCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0526 03-11 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Copter Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0526,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Two Men Killed In Crash Of Copter From Ship Prince Andrew Is
Aboard</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with identities of dead,
statements from Portuguese officials. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men were killed when a British Royal
Navy helicopter crashed off the Portuguese coast after taking off
from a warship that Prince Andrew was aboard, Portuguese and
British officials said today.
   Commandante Antonio Monteiro Coelho, a Portuguese navy
spokesman, said the Lynx helicopter crashed Thursday night less
than three-fourths of a mile from the training ship Engadine, where
Andrew was on duty as a helicopter warship instructor.
   Andrew, 28, is the third eldest of Queen Elizabeth II's four
children and a naval helicopter pilot.
   A British Defense Ministry spokesman identified the dead pilots
as Lt. Cmdr. Anthony Peter Gardiner Davies, 37, and Acting Sub. Lt.
Richard Alan Hand Cawthorne, 23.
   An informal lunch that President Mario Soares was to have put on
for Andrew today was canceled because of the accident, the
president's office said.
   On Thursday, Prince Charles, Andrew's brother and heir to the
British throne, narrowly escaped an avalanche that killed a close
friend skiing with him in Switzerland. The accident prompted calls
in the British press for the royal family to abandon dangerous
pursuits.
   The Defense Ministry spokesman, who was not indentified in
keeping with British custom, refused to say whether Andrew was
involved in the planning of the helicopter's test flight.
   ``It is normal practice not to reveal who is involved in the
planning of operations,'' he said. ``The whole thing will go before
the Board of Inquiry.''
   Monteiro Coelho said the helicopter crashed into the sea around
9 p.m., 50 miles west of the Cabo da Roca, a cape west of Lisbon.
   He said the cause of the crash was unknown. ``The sea was calm
and weather conditions were not adverse,'' he told the Associated
Press.
   The helicopter was badly damaged by its impact with the water,
but it did not sink, he said. The Portuguese navy answered a
distress call from the Engadine and sent the Portuguese corvette
Batista de Andrade from Lisbon to assist, he added.
   The spokesman said Portuguese naval divers helped recover the
bodies.
   Monteiro Coelho said Portuguese naval authorities had been told
that because of the crash, Andrew's ship would not put into Lisbon
for the weekend as scheduled. He said he did not know whether the
vessel would return to Britain or remain at sea.
   Monteiro Coelho said the helicopter was too far from the
Engadine went it crashed for those aboard the ship to have
witnessed the accident.
   Andrew, a combat helicopter pilot who saw action in the
Falklands war, was on regular sea duty as a helicopter instructor
aboard the Engadine, British officials said.
   The 6,500-ton helicopter support ship used for training was
carrying 73 crew members of the Royal Fleet Auxiliary, the
logistical support arm of the navy, and an unspecified number of
Royal Navy personnel.
</TEXT>
