<HEAD>Police: Officers, Civilians Wounded By Leftist Guerrillas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas sprayed a police station with
submachine-gun and rocket fire, wounding two officers and three
civilians in the most serious of several nighttime attacks, police
said.
   The attacks late Thursday came hours before President Augusto
Pinochet was to address the nation in a speech marking the seventh
anniversary of his controversial Constitution, which allows him to
seek re-election this year for another eight-year term.
   Police said they believed the guerrillas were leftists.
   Security was stepped up today in this capital city of 4.5
million people. Army patrols in full combat gear occupied strategic
points.
   In the most serious attack, according to police, guerrillas
launched two rockets and shot submachine guns at a suburban police
station in southern Santiago.
   Two officers and three civilians were wounded. Police said one
of the officers was in ``extremely serious condition,'' wounded in
the stomach by rocket shrapnel.
   Another station and a patrol car were also attacked during the
night, but no victims were reported.
   At least three bombs damaged electric power installations during
the night and blacked out some sectors of the city, police said.
   Pinochet, who has ruled Chile since a bloody 1973 coup, has so
far refused to confirm whether he is running for re-election, but
he appears to be seeking the nomination.
