<HEAD>Subway Commuters Refuse to Leave Train Delayed By Man Run Over</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commuters on a subway route plagued by problems
today refused to leave a train that was delayed after a man fell
under the wheels. It was the fourth such revolt in two weeks.
   London Underground officials demanded an end to mutinies on its
Northern Line, where passengers staged three sit-ins last week.
   Subway staff asked passengers to leave the train at the Old
Street station after the unidentified man was taken to the hospital
with multiple injuries, Underground officials said. Most passengers
left but a dozen refused to do so until police arrived.
   ``The action of passengers didn't delay the removal of the man
from underneath the train,'' said London Underground spokesman
Roger Shire. ``But it's extremely disturbing that a dozen people
wouldn't get off.
   ``I can understand their frustration in being delayed, but not
in these circumstances,'' he said. ``They're not doing anyone any
good. Sit-ins are not the answer.''
   Spokesman Derek Salter said the man fell from the platform onto
the tracks just after 8 a.m. as the train was pulling into the
station.
   After the man was taken to St. Bartholomew's Hospital, a station
guard walked through the crowded train telling passengers they had
to get off and could take another waiting just behind.
   ``The (halted) train had to be taken out of service. We have to
check for damage after such incidents for obvious reasons,'' Shire
said.
   Passengers complain of rudeness by staff, breakdowns, delays,
dirt, crime and crowds on the London Underground, which carries 2.5
million people a day.
   The sit-ins on the Northern Line, among the most antiquated and
inefficient routes, began on March 1.
</TEXT>
