<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 1041EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CDC-Condoms     03-11 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CDC-Condoms,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CDC Reports on Failure Rate of Condoms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twelve percent of U.S.-made condoms and 21
percent of foreign-made ones failed in recent testing, say federal
researchers. The prophylactics have been advocated as a means of
slowing the spread of AIDS.
   As of February, the Centers for Disease Control reported
Thursday, the Food and Drug Administration had tested samples from
430 batches of condoms _ 165 batches manufactured in America, and
265 manufactured abroad.
   The FDA reported previously that as many as one in five batches
of latex condoms it tested fail to meet federal standards.
   The FDA rejects a batch of condoms if more than four per 1,000
fail in water-leakage tests. If two or more batches from a foreign
manufacturer fail, future shipments from that manufacturer are
stopped at their port of entry into the United States.
   The CDC in its report on condoms and sexually transmitted
diseases stressed that condoms can help prevent such diseases, but
that they don't always work.
   ``Individuals likely to become infected or known to be infected
with (AIDS) should be aware that condom use cannot completely
eliminate the risk of transmission,'' the Atlanta-based agency said.
   Lab tests have shown that latex condoms are effective barriers
to the spread of AIDS, hepatitis B, gonorrhea, chlamydia and other
sexually transmitted diseases. However, breakage or other mishaps
during use can negate their disease-fighting effectiveness.
   The CDC said condoms ``should be made more widely available''
through STD clinics, family planning clinics and drug treatment
centers.
   Those clinics and centers should ``become more assertive'' in
warning clients about STDs, and ``emphasize that the risk of
infection is most effectively reduced through abstinence or sexual
intercourse with a mutually faithful, uninfected partner.''
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is caused by a
virus that damages the body's immune system, leaving victims
susceptible to infections and cancer.
   It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or
syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products,
and from pregnant women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880311-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 1044EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Tibet 1stLd-Writethru a0578 03-11 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Tibet, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0578,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armed Police Patrol Tibetan Capital in Tense Calm</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 3rd graf, `The Western ...,' to UPDATE
with China warning Tibetans to turn selves in. PICKS up 4th graf,
`She said ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHARLENE L. FU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armed police guarded Tibet's main temple and a
military vehicle broadcast warnings against separatist activity
during a tense calm today in Lhasa, a Western tourist in the
Tibetan capital said.
   The tourist, speaking on condition of anonymity, reported seeing
20 armed police in central Lhasa in front of the Jokhang Temple,
the holiest site of Tibetan Buddhism. She said seven armed police
were also seen on the roof of a police station in the central
market square.
   The Western tourist, who speaks Tibetan, said she was told up to
200 people may have been arrested since thousands of Tibetans
rioted Saturday to protest Chinese rule.
   Chinese authorities broadcast warnings to Tibetan rebels today
to turn themselves in by March 20 or face punishment, the traveler
said.
   The tourist said vans with loudspeakers were driving through the
city every hour repeating the message.
   ``They're warning people to do their duty, report troublemakers.
They'll be rewarded if they give information,'' she said in a
telephone interview. She said one announcement called ``for people
to surrender _ people who were involved in the disturbances _
before the 20th, otherwise they would be punished.''
   She said Tibetans reported mass arrests, beatings and torture.
She was told details of the arrests of 10 people, but she was
unable to confirm other arrests.
   Most arrests were made Saturday and Sunday as Chinese police
pulled people from their homes during the night and beat them as
they were dragged away, she said.
   Other Westerners in Lhasa earlier reported at least 300 arrests
since Saturday's all-day clash between police and Tibetans
demanding independence. Monks and lay Tibetans stoned and knifed
Chinese police and lit bonfires throughout the city on the last day
of a major prayer festival, the reports said.
   Official reports have said two people, a Tibetan and a police
officer, died in Saturday's violence. There have been no official
reports of arrests.
   A Western source in Lhasa reported Thursday that Tibetans
reported 21 Tibetans and three police killed.
   It was the first major confrontation between Tibetans and
Chinese authorities since a series of anti-Chinese protests in
September and October that left at least 14 dead.
   Authorities have warned Tibetans not to speak to foreigners, the
Western tourist said today. Foreign reporters have been denied
access to the Himalayan region this week.
   A military vehicle patrolled Lhasa streets today broadcasting a
warning to Tibetans not to join separatists and to report any
suspicious activity, the tourist said.
   ``It's much quieter, but the military presence is still
obvious,'' she said.
   She confirmed earlier reports that the city was quiet Thursday,
the 29th anniversary of a Tibetan rebellion against Chinese rule.
The uprising led the Dalai Lama, Tibetans' god-king, to flee into
exile in India with 100,000 followers.
   China sent troops into Tibet in 1950 to take control, but it
contends the remote mountainous region has been an integral part of
China for seven centuries.
   Tibetans hold deep antagonisms toward the Chinese because of the
communist government's past suppression of Tibetan language,
customs and religion.
</TEXT>
