<1ST_LINE>r i PM-HongKong-Elections     03-11 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hong Kong-Elections,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democratic Coalition Beats Pro-Beijing Candidates in Hong Kong</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coalition for democratic change beat
pro-Beijing candidates in this British colony's first
territory-wide election in three years, the government-funded radio
reported today.
   Radio-Television Hong Kong said candidates backing democratic
change, such as the speedy introduction of direct legislative
elections, won more than 50 of 74 contested seats in Thursday's
voting for neighborhood advisory board seats.
   Although the boards carry no executive or legislative powers,
their members are the only directly elected officials in the colony.
   The radio said pro-Beijing candidates, numbering about 50 in a
field of 459, did not do as well as the reform coalition. But no
specific numbers were given.
   Activists who sought direct legislative elections this year say
the administration delayed the plan under pressure from China.
   Under a 1984 pact, Hong Kong will revert to Chinese sovereignty
in 1997 when Britain's 99-year lease on the bulk of the territory
expires. The pact also says the colony's capitalist way of life
will be maintained for 50 years afterward.
</TEXT>
