<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GangViolence     03-11 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gang Violence,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Los Angeles Officials Want More Federal Money To Fight Gang
Warfare</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Law enforcement officials are pressing for
more federal funds to fight gang warfare in the nation's
second-largest city, where seven more people were wounded in the
last day.
   City and Los Angeles county officials received $2.73 million in
federal grants Thursday to help battle the gang violence
responsible for more than 50 slayings in the county so far this
year, police said.
   The grant will be divided between the city, which will receive
$1.35 million, and the county, which will receive $1.38 million.
   But Los Angeles Police Chief Daryl F. Gates described his
department's $949,639 share as ``teeny weeny,'' and Mayor Tom
Bradley complained that the federal government is ``in effect
sending us out to fight a war with nothing more than pop guns.''
   Three suspected gang-related shootings left seven people wounded
in the Los Angeles area Thursday night.
   Four people were wounded when a rifleman opened fire from a
passing car in south-central Los Angeles, police said.
   Two of the four victims were believed to be bystanders waiting
to use a public telephone, witnesses told police. The apparent
intended victim was a suspected gang member standing in a telephone
booth, said Sgt. Rich Gammel.
   ``I heard the shots and I went outside and I saw people lying
there bleeding and other people trying to help them,'' said Jason
Chung, owner of a liquor store near the shooting scene.
   ``I called the police and got my gun and went back outside. Most
of those people were my customers. They were just waiting to use
the telephone.''
   Witnesses said between 16 to 20 rounds of ammunition were fired.
   None of the wounds appeared to be life-threatening, Sgt. Steve
Faulk said.
   The gunman apparently used a .22-caliber semi-automatic rifle,
he said.
   In Compton, southeast of downtown, two drive-by shootings about
six blocks apart Thursday night wounded three more people,
including a 10-year old boy.
   The same car was described in both incidents, said Compton
police Sgt. John Garrett said. It was not known if the victims were
gang members.
   Gang warfare in Los Angeles gained national attention in January
with the death of a woman who was caught in gang crossfire on a
street in affluent Westwood.
   The death spurred racial tension in the city after more officers
were put on the streets in Westwood. Residents in poorer areas
complained that police were overlooking daily gang activity in
their neighborhoods.
</TEXT>
