<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 1114EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dole 2ndLd-Writethru a0570 03-11 0789</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dole, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0570,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Denies He'll Abandon Presidential Bid</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Dole on reassessing campaign, inserting 3 grafs
after 2nd graf pvs, ``I am</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Sen. Bob Dole today denied
he was dropping out of the presidential race, and he criticized the
news media for concentrating on such matters as his campaign staff
cuts, saying, ``I never thought that a campaign was a jobs
program.''
   ``I am running for president,'' Dole told a group of Illinois
Farm Bureau leaders, trying to stop rumors that he was about to
pull out after suffering crushing defeats to Vice President George
Bush on Super Tuesday.
   However, he told reporters after the speech, ``We will reassess
after Illinois. I am going to be very realistic about this.''
   Dole said the question of pulling out of the Illinois primary
was not discussed by him and his aides, but he conceded they did
discuss canceling some campaign activities ``to heighten whatever
we're going to do later.''
   He said his campaign had more than $1 million on hand to finance
its Illinois efforts. His problem, he said, ``is not money. We've
got the staff we need. What we need is to slow down this Super
Tuesday momentum.''
   ``It's hard to focus on the issues sometimes because the press
won't let us do that,'' he said. ``They would rather write about
how many staff you reduced your numbers by.''
   News reports also have noted that he has taken his television
ads off the air in Illinois.
   Dole made his remarks at the start of a day-long trip across
central and western Illinois to shore up his support in farm
country, which is considered his strongest territory.
   In a statement issued Thursday night in Illinois and Washington,
Dole had ``categorically denied rumors'' that he was about to drop
out in the face of Bush's big delegate lead and polls that show
Bush ahead in Illinois, which has its primary next Tuesday. Dole
has taken all his TV ads off the air in Illinois.
   ``I'm not a dropout. I'm a candidate,'' Dole told a suburban
Chicago veterans group Thursday night.
   ``We're going to be in this race all the way to New Orleans. And
now we're looking for an upset next Tuesday in Illinois.''
   Although Dole sought to shoot down reports that his presidential
quest was ending, several campaign sources said that option had
been discussed.
   The sources, speaking on condition that they not be identified,
said Dole met with campaign manager Bill Brock and other aides in
the past few days in Illinois and talked about the possibility of
abandoning the race because of Bush's commanding lead in delegates
for the GOP nomination.
   Dole, however, decided to press on in Illinois.
   ``I'm the underdog. The odds are great, but I've tackled great
odds before and I'm still here,'' Dole said.
   Bush's sweep of 16 Super Tuesday primaries has clearly wounded
Dole's campaign.
   One Dole aide, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Dole's
private polls indicated Bush held a lead of between 15 and 20
percentage points in Illinois. That was described as a significant
increase for the vice president in the 48 hours following his
victories on Super Tuesday.
   A Washington Post-ABC News poll published today said Bush led
Dole in Illinois by a wide margin _ 58 percent to 31 percent.
   Although Dole had not said whether he would remain in the race
if he lost Illinois next Tuesday, one aide said: ``I think it's
clear to Dole that it's do or die.''
   ``I'm a fighter. I'm also a realist. I've looked at the delegate
count, and I've got to do well in Illinois,'' Dole said at one
Chicago stop Thursday.
   ``And I'm not in this race to see how long we can extend it. I'm
in this race to win.''
   Mari Maseng, Dole's press secretary, said 130 staff members in
Super Tuesday states were being cut because the campaign no longer
needed them. In addition, she said more than half of the staff in
the campaign national headquarters was laid off to provide money
for ``media and essential travel'' for the Illinois effort.
   There were no staff cuts in states with primaries after next
Tuesday.
   Maseng confirmed Dole had ordered his television ads stopped in
Illinois because ``we've changed our media strategy.'' Dole had
planned to spend about $500,000 on TV spots in the state.
   Maseng said campaign advisers were trying to draft a new
advertising battle plan to ``draw the contrast between Bob Dole and
George Bush as dramatically as we can.''
   The campaign, according to one source, is considering a
30-minute paid broadcast near the end of the Illinois campaign.
</TEXT>
