<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SriLanka     03-11 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group of Assailants Massacre Bus Passengers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A band of men wielding guns, swords
and daggers ambushed a bus carrying Tamils today and killed at
least 16 people, officials said.
   Police believe the attack was in retaliation for the killings of
Sinhalese by Tamil guerrillas last week.
   Today's killings occurred in the northeastern district of
Trincomalee and the victims all were believed to be Tamils, said a
military official. He could not be identified under military
regulations.
   The official said the attackers stopped the bus near the village
of Horawapatana, 28 miles west of the port city of Trincomalee, and
attacked the passengers.
   ``Our reports are that eight passengers were shot and butchered,
seven more were forced to remain inside the bus when it was
torched. Another died on the way to a nearby hospital.
   ``We have unconfirmed reports that the total dead could be more
than 22,'' the official said. ``All of them are reported to be
Tamils.''
   Police investigating the bus attack believe it was carried out
by Sinhalese in retaliation for the killings last week of 45
Sinhalese and Moslem villagers.
   Twenty-seven people, most of them Sinhalese, died when a truck
was blown up Saturday near Sitaru, and 18 more Sinhalese were
killed when Tamil rebels raided the Morawewa village Wednesday.
Both villages are in Trincomalee.
   Militant Tamils have been fighting since the summer of 1983 for
a separate state in northern and eastern Sri Lanka, where most
Tamils live.
   India has an estimated 45,000 soldiers in Sri Lanka to try to
enforce an Indian-sponsored peace accord signed last July to try to
end the war.
   Tamils, most of whom are Hindus, make up 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million population. They claim they are discriminated
against by the majority Sinhalese Buddhists, who control the
government and the military.
   India has become involved because it has 60 million ethnic
Tamils in its southern states.
</TEXT>
