<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Coma-FeedingTube     03-11 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Coma-Feeding Tube,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Appointed Guardian Recommends Feeding Tube Removal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court-appointed guardian for a
48-year-old comatose woman is supporting her family's request to
remove a feeding tube that is keeping the woman alive.
   Boston College law professor Paul R. Tremblay concluded that
although tube feeding was once considered an ``ordinary measure''
that a patient could not refuse, a considerable body of legal and
medical expertise suggests that is no longer true.
   Doctors for the family of Marcia V. Gray and the state, which is
fighting the family's request, say the woman will die within a
period of days to a few weeks if the feeding tube is removed.
   In a similar case, a family in Carthage, Mo., is suing the state
to force doctors to disconnect Nancy Cruzan, 30, from a feeding
tube because she would not want to live in a hopeless state. Her
parents rested their case today after they and another daughter
testified.
   The woman was left in what doctors call a ``persistent
vegetative state'' after a 1983 automobile accident. She is being
cared for at the State Rehabilitation Center at Mount Vernon.
   Mrs. Gray has been in a coma since suffering a cerebral
hemorrhage in January 1986. Last January, the Roman Catholic bishop
of Providence, Louis E. Gelineau, said it would be morally
permissible to withdraw nutrition from Mrs. Gray, who is a Catholic.
   ``It is in Marcia Gray's best interest that the feeding tube be
removed, once the benefits of continued feeding are weighed against
the burdens of that treatment,'' Tremblay said in a report
submitted Thursday to U.S. District Judge Francis J. Boyle.
   Tremblay concluded that if state officials at General Hospital
continue to oppose allowing Mrs. Gray to die, they should quickly
transfer her to a hospital that would grant the family's request.
   If no hospital were found, Tremblay said, the court should order
state officials to comply.
   The state asserts that honoring the family's request would be
tantamount to sanctioning euthanasia.
   Family members, Tremblay said, have provided ``adequate data ...
to satisfy the standards that courts have used'' to permit the
discontinuance of life-support systems for terminally ill patients.
   ``She was very persistent in her wishes, and insisted that I
promise not to keep her alive in a coma where there was no hope of
recovery,'' her husband, University of Rhode Island professor H.
Glenn Gray, said in an affidavit.
</TEXT>
