<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 1155EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NewfoundFamily     03-11 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Newfound Family,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman With Leukemia Learns Family Is Larger Than She Thought</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON HEIGHTS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Betty Flosky might never have
learned the truth about her life if she hadn't developed leukemia.
   The suburban Detroit woman learned late last month that her
parents were really an adoptive aunt and uncle and that her
supposed brothers were cousins.
   ``Everyone just held the secret all these years,'' said Gene
Wise, one of her cousins. ``I'm glad it's out. I wish it was under
better circumstances.''
   She also learned she had three brothers and a sister, all
unknown to her, who might be able to help her undergo a life-saving
bone marrow transplant.
   ``I'm shaking like a leaf,'' Flosky, 32, said after meeting
Lynne Kern, the sister who had just arrived from Denver.
   Flosky's mother died four days after giving birth to her. She
was taken in by an aunt and an uncle and never told about her
mother or father, who later died.
   Last month, doctors told Flosky about her leukemia, which could
be fatal within three years. She also learned that a bone marrow
transplant from a sibling was her best chance at survival.
   Wise and his brother, Norm, told her they would be tested to see
if they could donate marrow, despite knowing that cousins don't
make the best donors. Then on Feb. 25, Joe Flosky told his wife she
had been adopted.
   ``When he told me I sat there and said, `Is that it?''' she
said. ``I said, `I thought you were going to tell me I was going to
die.'''
   Since then, her brothers and sister have been contacted and are
being tested to see whether they can donate marrow. If any of them
tests positive, Flosky and the donor are ready to fly to a Seattle
hospital that frequently performs bone marrow transplants.
   ``It's like `The Twilight Zone' or something, isn't it?'' Flosky
said. ``Instead of my family shrinking, it's growing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
