<DOCNO> AP880311-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 1201EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TruckExplosion     03-11 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Truck Explosion,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Say Bomb Expert Set Off Explosion</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Willi is cq in 3rd graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PERRY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators say an Air Force bomb
expert who had been absent without leave for several weeks
apparently set off a blast in his pickup truck that killed him and
damaged a motel where he was staying.
   But officials said it was unknown if Staff Sgt. Donald Lawrence
Lunger detonated the bomb intentionally or accidentally March 4.
   Forensic psychologists will study Lunger's medical records and
talk with family and friends to determine why he placed a 10-pound
to 15-pound package of explosives behind the seat of his pickup
truck and attached it to a blasting cap, said Willi Ellison, agent
in charge of the Jacksonville office of the Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms.
   The explosives, wires and other materials found at the blast
scene indicated they were the type used at Eglin Air Force Base,
where Lunger was stationed. An investigation at the base was under
way to determine if any explosive materials were missing, Ellison
said Thursday.
   ``It has been determined that the explosion that resulted in the
death of Lunger was a deliberate act initiated by actions
intentionally or unintentionally taken by him,'' officials said.
   The charge could have been electrically detonated by the
cigarette lighter in the truck or flashlight components, Ellison
said.
   He said there was no indication that Lunger was involved in any
criminal activity, narcotics or espionage. He said he could not
speculate on whether Lunger was under mental distress at the time
of the blast.
   Lunger, 30, had been staying at the Southern Inn Motel for
several days before the explosion, motel employees said. He was
reported AWOL from Eglin on Feb. 22.
   Lunger, originally of Endicott, N.Y., had been in the Air Force
13 years. He was married and had two children.
   A national team of investigators was dispatched the day after
the blast, which smashed about 65 windows at the motel and caused
minor damage to railings and other exterior structures at the
two-story motel. There were no other reported injuries.
</TEXT>
