<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FlagDispute     03-11 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Flag Dispute,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alabama Defendants Claim Legislative Immunity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY REEVES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state NAACP president and 13 other
black lawmakers argued today that they were protected by
legislative immunity when they tried to remove the Confederate
battle flag from atop the Alabama Capitol.
   The trespassing arrests of the legislators raised ``serious
constitutional questions and serious questions of state law,'' said
Fred Gray, who represents Thomas Reed, head of the state National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
   Gray also said at the court hearing that Gov. Guy Hunt lacked
the right to instruct officers to arrest anyone who attempted to
enter the Capitol grounds through a locked, chain-link fence since
the building is under the control of the Alabama Historical
Commission. The building is closed for renovation.
   Prosecutors from the district attorney's office did not comment
on the defense motions.
   District Judge Craig Miller granted defense attorneys' request
to file briefs and gave the district attorney's office 10 days to
respond. He said he would set a trial date later.
   Reed, speaking with reporters before the brief hearing began,
repeated his contention that the state should not fly the flag over
the Capitol. Reed and the other legislators maintain that the
Confederate banner represents racial oppression and slavery.
   ``People can fly it on their pickup trucks _ I have no problem
with that,'' said Reed, a state representative from Tuskegee.
   Reed and his co-defendants were arrested Feb. 2, minutes after
the Legislature's opening gavel.
   Capitol police and state troopers pulled down Reed and the
others as they made at least symbolic efforts to scale the 8-foot
fence. The lawmakers never got near the building and the Dixie flag
still flies atop the Capitol dome. Some merely put their hand on
the chain-link fence when they were arrested.
   Each lawmaker was charged with second-degree criminal
trespassing and released from the county jail on $300 bond.
Conviction on the misdemeanor count carries a maximum penalty of
three months in jail and a $500 fine.
   Reed had vowed for weeks to remove the flag. Hundreds of people
_ ranging from Ku Klux Klansmen carrying Rebel flags to black
students singing ``We Shall Overcome'' _ gathered outside the
Capitol for Reed's attempt.
   Hunt, who contends the flag is historic and not a symbol of
racism, has refused to remove the standard, saying the Legislature
should decide the issue. Hours after Reed and the other Democrats
were arrested, the state House defeated a resolution to remove the
flag.
   The NAACP also is trying to remove the banner above South
Carolina's statehouse and change the state flags of Georgia and
Mississippi, which bear versions of the Confederate battle flag in
their designs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
