<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Hostages     03-11 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Hostages,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Magazine Says Higgins Will Be Freed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kidnappers of U.S. Marine Lt. Col.
William R. Higgins have pledged to free him but set no specific
date for the release, the Beirut magazine Ash-Shiraa said today.
   The weekly quoted unidentified knowledgeable sources in south
Lebanon as saying the kidnappers made the pledge ``in secret
contacts undertaken by more than local and regional parties.''
   There was no way to verify the report independently.
   Ash-Shiraa gained international fame for disclosing the secret
U.S. arms sales to Iran in November 1986. But many of its reports
about foreign hostages held in Lebanon have proved inaccurate.
   Higgins, 44, of Danville, Kentucky, who served with a U.N.
observers group in south Lebanon, was kidnapped near the ancient
southern port of Tyre on Feb. 17.
   A pro-Iranian Shiite group, the Organization of the Oppressed on
Earth, claimed responsibility for his abduction, charging he was a
spy for the U.S. Central Intelligence Agency. U.S. and U.N.
officials have denied the charge.
   ``The sources did not reveal an approximate date for Higgins'
release, saying this has been left for the kidnappers to set,'' the
magazine said.
   ``The sources have said that the important thing in this regard
is that a decision has been taken by the kidnappers to free
Higgins, such as what happened with (former) West German hostage
Ralph Schray, who was freed last week,'' Ash-Shiraa added.
   Schray, an industrial engineer who was abducted in Moslem west
Beirut Jan. 27, was released by his pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem
captors March 3 in west Beirut.
   Syrian troops in charge of security in west Beirut's whisked him
the same day to the Syrian capital of Damascus, where he was handed
over to the West German Embassy. He returned to resume his life in
west Beirut two days later.
   Twenty-two foreigners, including nine Americans, are missing and
believed kidnapped in Lebanon. The longest held is American Terry
Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press.
He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
