<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FatalRobbery     03-11 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fatal Robbery,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Sought By Police After Bank Robbery Kills Self With Own Gun</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspected bank robber pursued by police calmly
pulled over his van, stepped from the driver's seat and fatally
shot himself, authorities said.
   ``The man opened his van door and stood on the running board,''
witness Cynthia Everett said Thursday. ``I heard the pop of the gun
and then saw smoke coming over his head.''
   The man died about 10 miles from the bank robbery scene and
roughly 30 minutes after the holdup at the First Interstate Bank of
Texas in Seabrook, police said. Inside the van, police found a
briefcase with $10,550 in cash.
   The robbery occurred about 11:35 a.m. Thursday when a man handed
a teller a note demanding money, said Seabrook police Sgt. Nona
Holomon. The note claimed the man was armed, but no weapon was
seen, and the man left within minutes carrying the money, she said.
   A bank official followed the suspect in his own car, then
alerted police using a mobile phone. Three police cars followed the
van and finally surrounded it, police said.
   Houston patrolman Bobbie Miller said he had parked his patrol
car in front of the van to block it from escaping.
   ``As I was getting out of the (police) vehicle, I heard a shot,
turned around and he was falling to the ground,'' said Miller.
   Bank officials refused to comment on the holdup.
</TEXT>
