<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Olympic-Condoms     03-11 0158</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Olympic-Condoms,0163</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Condom Plan For Seoul Olympics Under Study</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposal to distribute condoms at
the 1988 Olympics Games in order to combat AIDS is being studied,
officials said Friday.
   Seoul Olympic Organizing Committee officials said they were
considering plans to provide condoms at the Olympic village and
sports facilities.
   Health authorities are concerned that the 270,000 foreign
visitors expected for the Games could spread AIDS in South Korea.
   The government has ruled out suggestions that all Olympic
participants and visitors should be required to take AIDS tests.
   South Korea has one reported AIDS case and about 15 cases of the
AIDS virus. The government recently passed legislation to try to
prevent the spread of the disease.
   Olympics officials, who asked not to be identified, denied press
reports that AIDS tests would be provided free of charge to Olympic
visitors who request them. The Games run from Sept. 17 through Oct.
2.
