<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Italy-Seatbelts     03-11 0156</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Italy-Seatbelts,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italy Passes Seatbelt Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament has approved a law requiring the
installation and wearing of seatbelts, bringing Italy into line
with the rest of Western Europe.
   ``From today on we are more European,'' said Antonio Testa,
president of the Chamber of Deputies transport commission following
approval of the bill Thursday after four years of study and debate.
   The law requires all cars registered in the last 10 years to be
equipped with seatbelts in the front seats by March 1989. By
September 1989, drivers and front-seat passengers will be required
to wear them.
   The law will also require child safety seats to be used for
children up to age 4 in the back seat and for children aged 4 to 10
in the front seat.
   Fines for not wearing seatbelts will range up to $160.
   An estimated 10,000 people die annually in traffic accidents in
Italy and 200,000 are injured.
</TEXT>
