<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NickelSwindle     03-11 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nickel Swindle,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crackdown on U.S. Airmen Cheating on Long-Distance Calls Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BENTWATERS, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The telephone company is cracking
down on U.S. Air Force personnel who have been using nickels
instead of British 20-pence coins to make cheap calls home, an Air
Force spokesman said Friday.
   It seems airmen stationed in Britain have for some time known
that a nickel works like a 20-pence coin in pay phones. A 20-pence
coin is worth 37 cents, so every nickel used for a call to the
United States saves 32 cents.
   Using the nickel swindle, a trans-Atlantic call that should have
cost about $24 would only cost $3.
   British Telecom, the telephone company, estimates the scam has
cost it about $52,000 in the past several months.
   Two airmen at the U.S. Air Force base in Bentwaters in eastern
England have been charged with cheating on long-distance calls, and
the Air Force is helping the telephone company end the swindle.
   ``We have warned everyone here that British Telecom is looking
out for people making fraudulent use of the phones,'' said Capt.
John Boyle, a spokesman at Brentwaters.
   ``The United States takes very seriously anything of this nature
and we fully support British Telecom in its efforts to track down
offenders,'' he said.
</TEXT>
