<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 1225EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FamilySlain     03-11 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Family Slain,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigators To Begin Excavation In Kunz Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYANN MROWCA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WAUSAU, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities said they will begin excavating
a site Monday in search of evidence in the shooting deaths of four
members of a family and the disappearance of a relative eight
months ago.
   Authorities on Friday would not identify the site or specify
what they might find.
   ``This site has possibilities but no certainties,'' Marathon
County Sheriff's Lt. Elwood Mason said Friday.
   Authorities believe 500 to 700 cubic yards of material will be
removed, Mason said. He would not comment on whether that material
might be dirt or concrete.
   ``It is not on land that is owned or under control by any
suspect in this case,'' Mason said, adding that was one reason for
choosing to dig at this site rather than any others under
consideration.
   Four members of the Kunz family were found shot to death and a
fifth family member disappeared from their rural Athens home last
July.
   ``Circumstances and events surrounding July 4 and 5 give this
site some probabilities but by no means create a certainty that
there would be something there,'' Mason said.
   District Attorney Rand Krueger said Thursday he did not plan to
file charges in the case this week and no one was in custody. He
said the number of suspects, which he had described earlier as more
than one but fewer than 12, remained the same.
   Helen Kunz, 70, has been missing since her relatives' bodies
were discovered in the family home. Ms. Kunz's brother, Clarence
Kunz, 76; their sisters, Irene, 81, and Marie, 72; and Helen Kunz's
son, Randy, 30, were shot dead.
   Krueger would not comment on whether a murder weapon had been
recovered.
</TEXT>
