<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NaziSuit     03-11 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nazi Suit,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Restaurant Violated Rights of Swastika Wearers, Judge Rules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A German restaurant violated the civil rights
of three patrons by refusing them service for wearing Nazi swastika
lapel pins, a Superior Court judge ruled.
   But Judge Kurt Lewin said Thursday it would be up to a jury to
determine whether Alpine Village Restaurant in Torrance was wrong
in refusing the three service in October 1985 after they caused a
disturbance when told to leave.
   Lewin said state law prevented the restaurant from refusing
service because of what the men wore.
   The suit, on behalf of Joe Fields, 24, of San Pedro; Stanley
Witek, 54, of Los Angeles; and Harold Follin, 28, of Anaheim had
sought unspecified damages as well as an injunction preventing the
restaurant from refusing service to customers based on their
political views. Damages would only be awarded if the jury sides
with the plaintiffs.
   Attorney Julia Tachikawa, who represented the restaurant, said
she didn't know if Alpine Village would want to appeal.
   She expressed disappointment that the judge ruled against the
restaurant's contention that it did not have to serve the men if
they wore things patrons might find offensive.
   Ms. Tachikawa said Lewin failed to take into account the
restaurant's constitutional right of freedom of association.
   ``In this case I was trying to argue that it was a German
restaurant, and the association was so obvious, the restaurant was
compelled to speak up that we don't hold that view,'' she said.
   The swastika was the emblem of Adolf Hitler's National Socialist
Party.
   Ms. Tachikawa said the restaurant contended the men were thrown
out not because of the pins but because they caused trouble after
being asked to either remove the pins or leave.
   American Civil Liberties Union attorney Carol Sobel, who
represented the men, said it didn't matter whether they created a
disturbance after they were refused service.
   She argued that the only issue to be resolved was whether a
restaurant could exclude someone because it disapproved of what the
person was wearing.
</TEXT>
