<DOCNO> AP880311-0116 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 1227EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-StubbornIsraeli     03-11 0734</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stubborn Israeli,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir May Surprise The Critics</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: This was the Washington Wire column for Fri PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Judging by what Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir had to say in his letter to skeptical senators, this
tough-minded Middle Eastern leader may climb aboard Secretary of
State George P. Shultz's peace shuttle after all.
   Shamir reaffirmed his commitment to the 1978 Camp David approach
to negotiations over the West Bank and Gaza. The way Shultz has
structured the talks that would suffice for the first stage.
   But Shamir's resistance to the concept of trading the
territories or even part of them for Arab recognition is a
potential roadblock. So is the refusal of King Hussein of Jordan to
commit himself to recognizing Israel until the territories are
vacated.
   Shamir, who will be here Monday to see President Reagan, Shultz
and members of Congress, has a reputation for intransigence. So did
Menachem Begin, the last leader of the Likud coalition to serve as
Prime Minister of Israel.
   But Begin turned every inch of Sinai over to Egypt, stripping
Israel in the meantime of all its oil resources, dismantling a
first-class military airfield and uprooting Jewish settlers. Begin
gave it all away in exchange for a 1979 peace treaty with the most
formidable Arab country.
   The treaty was based on the Camp David agreements former
President Jimmy Carter worked out with Begin and the late Egyptian
President Anwar Sadat in the Catoctin Mountains of Maryland.
   Israel offered self-rule, or autonomy, to the 1.5 million
Palestinian Arabs who live on the West Bank and in Gaza as an
interim arrangement. All options, including statehood, would be
open during a second stage of negotiations.
   The first round ended in 1981 in failure. Jordan and the
Palestinians did not participate. The Arab world shunned Sadat for
his treaty with Israel and only lately has begun to repair
relations with Cairo.
   Sens. Carl Levin, D-Mich., Rudy Boschwitz, R-Minn., and 28 other
senators criticized Shamir for not being willing to give up
portions of the territories in exchange for Arab recognition of
Israel.
   But the prime minister, in his reply, left the option open _ as
the Camp David agreements do. He said the formula Begin and Sadat
devised ``would grant the Palestinian Arabs self-rule, following
which the sides would negotiate the final status of the territories
in question in a vastly improved setting of coexistence and
cooperation between Jordan, Israel and the Palestinian Arabs.''
   In other words, Shamir still wants a trial period of Palestinian
autonomy before taking up a final settlement. He may harbor hopes
the Palestinians would elect to remain under Israel's security
control while running their own daily affairs.
   In a letter to Shultz in January, the Israeli leader excluded
only security and foreign relations as functions of autonomous
Palestinian Arabs.
   The scheme Shultz presented to Shamir and Hussein in Jerusalem
and London envisions a three-year interim arrangement. That should
be attractive to the Prime Minister.
   Also, negotiations for an overall settlement would begin only if
Israel and a mixed Jordanian-Palestinian delegation succeeded in
working out interim arrangements.
   That means Shamir could say ``yes'' next week to the president
and the secretary of state without committing himself to yielding
the territory Israel won in the 1967 Six-Day War.
   The prime minister's letter to Levin and Boschwitz suggests
getting him to give up even parts of the West Bank and Gaza would
be more difficult than persuading Begin to yield the Sinai.
   Shamir reminded the senators that Jordan's occupation of the
West Bank from 1950 to 1967 was never recognized internationally.
Egypt held Gaza during the same period, but unlike Sinai, the strip
along the Mediterranean was occupied ``militarily and illegally,''
Shamir said.
   ``We have sought peace relentlessly, but our Arab neighbors,
except Egypt, still have to prove in deeds that they are willing to
negotiate peace with us,'' the Israeli leader said.
   Shultz tried to pierce Hussein's decades-long resistance by
proposing to hold the negotiations in an international setting.
This is designed to give the king the support he seeks.
   But Shultz obviously could not guarantee Hussein that Israel
would withdraw from the West Bank and Gaza. So there's a big
question mark over Hussein's participation in the peace talks as
well.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Barry Schweid has covered U.S.-Middle East
diplomacy over the past 15 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
