<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FBI-Presser     03-11 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FBI-Presser,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Upholds Suppressing Evidence in Presser Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court ruled today that
prosecutors illegally obtained statements from a former FBI agent
charged with lying about his role in handling Teamster President
Jackie Presser as an informant.
   The U.S. Court of Appeals upheld a lower court's decision that
suppresses as evidence the statements that former FBI agent Robert
S. Friederick made to government prosecutors in early 1986.
   The statements that Friedrick made to federal prosecutors
constituted the linchpin of the government's case against him. The
former Cleveland FBI agent is charged with five counts of making
false statements to federal agents.
   The appeals court panel upheld a finding by U.S. District Judge
George Revercomb that federal prosecutors failed to inform
Friederick that unlike previous interviews in 1985, statements he
made to them during the January 1986 session could be used as
evidence against him.
   Friederick's lawyer, William Beyer, said the decision eliminates
the only evidence that prosecutors have against his client.
   ``I don't know of any other evidence that they have to support
their claim,'' Beyer said in a telephone inteview from Cleveland.
   Friederick is charged with lying by telling FBI agents and
prosecutors that he was aware that Presser had been authorized by
the Cleveland FBI office to put ghost employees on the payroll of a
local Teamsters union.
   The case stems from an FBI investigation of payroll padding in
Teamsters Local 507 in Cleveland that resulted in convictions of
Jack Nardi and Allen Friedman in 1983.
   Presser has been indicted on charges that he authorized the
payment of union funds to so-called ``phantom employees.'' As a
defense, Presser claims he was acting under the authority of
Cleveland FBI agents as an informant.
   Friederick, who was head of the Cleveland FBI's organized crime
squad, was questioned in 1984 and again in 1985 about his handling
of Presser as an informant.
   It was during a 1984 interview with Friederick and other
Cleveland agents that the FBI learned that Presser was an
informant. During a June 26, 1985, interview at FBI headquarters in
Washington, Friederick signed an FBI form that said he was required
to answer questions but that the government could not use his
statements against him in a criminal prosecution.
   Friederick was questioned on two other occasions that summer in
connection with the FBI's internal investigation of the handling of
Presser as an informant.
   The appellate court upheld Revercomb's finding that Friederick
was not warned during a Jan. 6, 1986, interview that statements he
made could be used against him.
   The prosecutors ``made a conscious decision prior to the
interview not to furnish Friederick with or even mention (the FBI
form); indeed they hoped that Friederick would make incriminating
statements that they could use against him in a subsequent
prosecution,'' the court said in an opinion by Judge Kenneth Starr.
   During the January interview, Friederick made statements
contradicting his previous assertion that he was aware that Presser
had been authorized to put ghost employees on the local's payroll.
The next day he failed a lie detector test.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
