<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Textbooks-Indians     03-11 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Textbooks-Indians,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Textbook Commission Rejects Indians' Pleas to Ban Textbooks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Textbook Commission has rejected
American Indians' pleas to remove from elementary schools a book
containing stories by Washington Irving and John Smith that depict
Indians as blood-thirsty savages.
   The commission refused Thursday to withdraw approval for ``What
Joy Awaits You'' by Open Court Publishing Co., and said teachers
can offset negative images by teaching children to think critically.
   An Open Court representative said a supplemental text is being
prepared to help teachers discuss how perceptions of native
Americans have changed. The company also will revise the text in
1989 to include treaty violations and atrocities against native
Americans, but will not remove classical writings.
   The company said 10 other states have approved the book,
including Idaho and California.
   Commission member Clark Cox, superintendent of Alpine School
District, said removing or deleting offensive passages would ``make
pablum of literature.''
   Wil Numkena, education specialist at the State Office of
Education, said Irving's derogatory story of Indians may be
considered a classic, but ``at whose expense?''
   Numkena recalled that as a boy a teacher told his class that
Indians were bad, raided white people and took away white people's
land.
   ``Thanks to my mother and father who reinforced my understanding
of who I am, I was able to continue my education, understand my
identity and build self-esteem,'' he said. ``But many children
don't have that support system.''
</TEXT>
