<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MotelStandoff     03-11 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Motel Standoff,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Sentenced To 25 Years In Lake City Siege</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who held a teen-age girl captive
in a motel room and fired at FBI agents has been sentenced to 25
years in prison on extortion, assault and firearms violations.
   Richard Lee Brown received the maximum sentences in federal
court Thursday for charges stemming from the siege in September in
Lake City, about 50 miles west of here. Brown held 17-year-old
Stacey Ann Sapp of Savannah, Ga., hostage during the siege.
   Brown, who had been traveling around the country with Miss Sapp
for several weeks, called her father and threatened to harm her
unless the father paid $30,000 in ransom. But authorities
intervened after Miss Sapp's father called the FBI, and a 21-hour
standoff followed at the motel.
   In January, Brown pleaded guilty to two charges of assaulting a
federal officer with a deadly weapon, as well as one count each of
using a firearm in a violent crime and transmitting an extortion
demand across state lines.
   Brown, of Tallahassee, had told officials he was possessed by
demons and had angels inside his body. A court-appointed
psychiatrist said he suffered from several personality disorders.
   He was judged competent to stand trial, however, after the
psychiatrist said he understood right from wrong and the charges
against him.
   Brown also had been charged with extortion in Georgia, but those
were dropped as part of his plea-bargain agreement.
</TEXT>
