<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-PLO     03-11 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-PLO,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Department Says It Will Close PLO Mission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States told Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar today it will move next week to close the
PLO's observer mission at the United Nations.
   Perez de Cuellar replied with a ``strong'' protest to U.S.
Ambassador Herbert Okun, according to U.N. spokesman Francois
Giulaini.
   Okun's letter to the U.N. chief says the Justice Department will
initiate legal action to close the Palestine Liberation
Organization mission around March 21.
   It also says the United States will not try to close the mission
until the litigation is resolved.
   Giuliani said Perez de Cuellar's legal staff is ``studying
options,'' but he refused to describe them or say if the United
Nations would join the litigation on behalf of the PLO.
   The United Nations released copies of Okun's letter to the
secretary-general during a press briefing after the two diplomats
met this morning.
   Giuliani said Perez de Cuellar ``strongly protested this
violation of the headquarters agreement'' during the meeting.
   The letter also says that the United States refuses binding
arbitration of the dispute over the mission, the worst
confrontation ever between the United Nations and its host country.
   The 159-nation General Assembly, in a special meeting last
month, asked the World Court in the Hague to rule on whether the
United States must agree to arbitration. Oral arguments are
scheduled for April 11.
   U.N. officials and diplomats regard the threat to the PLO
mission as a challenge to the independence of the United Nations.
   They and the State Department have said the 1947 treaty under
which New York became U.N. headquarters obliges the United States
to let all accredited missions operate.
   Even the United States' closest allies have denounced the
attempt to close the mission and several Arab diplomats have
suggested that the General Assembly move to Geneva if the mission
here is closed.
   It was not clear if the assembly would convene again to consider
the dispute.
   Last year, the State Department closed down the only other PLO
office in the United States, an information office in Washington,
in what turned out to be a futile attempt to head off legislation
ordering the U.N. mission closed.
   Despite this and despite the headquarters treaty, Congress
passed an anti-terrorism law in December ordering the mission
closed by March 21.
   The United States and Israel consider the PLO a terrorist
organization. But the United Nations recognizes it as the only
legitimate spokesman for Palestinians.
</TEXT>
