<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DardenExecution 1stLd-Writethru a0528 03-11 0769</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Darden Execution, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0528,0790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governor Declines To Meet With Amnesty International Officials</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with news conference today,
picking up 5th graf pvs, `Sparks and ....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DIANA SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two people who claim they have
information that could clear a condemned murderer said today they
were disappointed the governor refused to meet with them to discuss
the case, which has become a rallying point for death penalty
opponents.
   The Rev. Sam Sparks, a Baptist minister, and Christine Bass, a
Lakeland secretary, appeared at a news conference with Amnesty
International officials to discuss about information they believe
might clear Willie Jasper Darden of murder.
   Darden is under his seventh death warrant and is scheduled for
electrocution Tuesday for the 1973 slaying of a furniture store
owner.
   No other Florida inmate has survived as many death warrants and
only one other prisoner has been on Florida's death row longer.
   ``I know Willie Darden is innocent. It is not a belief; it is a
knowledge,'' said Ms. Bass, who said her attempts to give vital
information to Darden's trial attorney 14 years ago were rebuffed.
   Gov. Bob Martinez refused to meet with the two, and an aide said
the governor is satisfied that the evidence Sparks and Ms. Bass
were talking about had been considered and rejected by the courts.
   ``This is not about public sentiment. It's about the law and
carrying out the law,'' press secretary Jon Peck said in explaining
why Martinez decided against the meeting.
   ``I think a lot of people in Florida are wondering why he won't
sit down for even 15 minutes with Ms. Bass and me. That seems
reasonable,'' Sparks said at the news conference.
   Sparks and Ms. Bass, who have signed affidavits that raise
questions about whether Darden could have committed the crime, have
appeared on television news programs to repeat those statements.
   Supporters say Darden, who is black, was the victim of racial
prejudice in his trial.
   He was convicted of killing Lakeland store owner James Turman
during a robbery that netted $15. A store employee also was shot
and permanently disabled, while Turman's wife had to fend off a
sexual attack as her husband lay dying.
   Sparks said Turman's wife had told him that all blacks looked
alike to her and that her identification of Darden was unimportant
because the lawyers had told her that Darden committed the crime.
   Helen Baum, formerly Helen Turman, recently denied having made
that statement to Sparks and reaffirmed her identification of
Darden as the man who shot her husband.
   Ms. Bass, a Lakeland secretary, said Darden's car had broke down
near her home, and he waited for a tow truck from 4 p.m. to 5:35
p.m. on Sept. 8, 1973. Her house was eight miles from the furniture
store. Prosecutors say the crime occurred about 6 p.m.
   As Ms. Bass and Sparks made their claims, a sixth warrant
against Darden was stayed and the U.S. Supreme Court agreed to
consider his appeal for the fourth time.
   On Monday, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled 6-3 that Darden had
received a fair trial and had been properly sentenced.
   The governor siged a seventh death warrant Tuesday, which gave
the inmate's attorneys less than a week to prepare his case.
Usually, at least 30 days are allowed.
   Amnesty International officials said Martinez was rushing to
execute Darden for political reasons.
   ``I think what the governor is looking for some kind of
ritualistic sacrifice that he can go through to prove he's tough on
crime,'' said Magdaleno Rose-Avila, national director of Amnesty
International's campaign to abolish the death penalty.
   She said the governor's popularity waned after the controversy
last year over a state sales tax on services. The governor
originally backed the tax but later repudiated it.
   Peck, the governor's spokesman, said politics had no bearing on
the new death warrant.
   Peck said Martinez had instituted a new policy recently to
schedule executions on subsequent warrants within 20 days, rather
than 30 days, which he said would have put the execution near the
Good Friday and Easter holidays.
   ``It seemed like kind of an inappropriate time,'' Peck said.
   Darden attorney Mark Olive said he wasn't sure when he would
file an execution appeal.
   When Martinez signed the sixth death warrant in Darden's case
earlier this year, Soviet dissident Andrei Sakharov, American
actress Margot Kidder and British rock star Peter Gabriel urged
clemency for Darden.
   Darden, 54, has been on death row since Jan. 29, 1974. A
prolific writer, he is nicknamed the ``poet of death row.''
</TEXT>
