<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Hung     03-11 0679</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Hung,0700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam's Premier Dies of Heart Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam's Premier Pham Hung, who joined
the communist movement when he was 16 and played a key role in
defeating the United States in the Vietnam War, has died of a heart
attack. He was 75.
   The domestic Vietnamese radio, quoting official communiques,
said Hung died early Thursday afternoon ``while working in Ho Chi
Minh City (formerly Saigon) and other southern provinces.''
   It said the Council of Ministers named a vice premier, Vo Van
Kiet, as acting premier until the national assembly chooses a
permanent successor.
   Kiet, in his late 70s, is chairman of the State Planning
Commission and is regarded by Western analysts as the leading
proponent of Western-style reforms aimed at resolving the country's
economic crisis.
   Hung was a member of the ``old guard,'' a small group of
revolutionaries who took up radical politics in their teens, joined
the Communist Party in the 1930s and over the next half-century
guided it to victory over the French, Japanese and Americans.
   Some Western diplomats say that in recent years, Hung had been
in bad health and did not have a central role in important policy
decisions.
   His death was the latest in a series of recent major upheavals
in the Vietnamese leadership.
   Party chief Le Duan died in mid-1986. His successor, Truong
Chinh, and two other top party officials resigned in December 1986,
when the Sixth National Party Congress elevated more pragmatic
party officials to positions of power.
   In June 1987, Hung replaced Pham Van Dong, who had been premier
since 1955.
   The radio said that ``in the last minute of his life, Comrade
Pham Hung ... has closed his eyes like a combatant who has fallen
in the battlefield.''
   The broadcast announced three days of national mourning, from
Sunday to Tuesday, when the funeral will be held.
   Hung was born on June 11, 1912 in Vinh Long province, now called
Cuu Long province, in the Mekong River Delta of southern Vietnam.
   At the age of 16, he declared himself a radical, his activities
eventually leading to his expulsion from secondary school.
   He joined the Indochinese Communist Party in 1930, the year it
was founded by Ho Chi Minh. The following year, Hung was arrested
by French authorities and sentenced to death.
   After the penalty was commuted, Hung spent the next decade and a
half in hard labor at the notorious prison island of Poulo Condore.
   Hung was released when communist forces came to power in North
Vietnam in 1945 and spent the next nine years of the war against
the French in key party positions in South Vietnam.
   After the French defeat at Dien Bien Phu, Hung rose rapidly in
party and government ranks and returned to North Vietnam. He
entered the Politburo in 1956 and two years later became vice
premier of North Vietnam.
   Hung played key roles in the 1960-75 war against the U.S.-backed
government of South Vietnam. He was sent south in 1967 as secretary
of the South Vietnam Commission of the party's central committee
and as political commissar of the South Vietnam Liberation Armed
Forces, commonly known as the Viet Cong.
   In 1975, he served as the political commissar of the Ho Chi Minh
Campaign, the final North Vietnamese offensive which climaxed with
the capture of Saigon on April 30.
   He became a vice premier in 1976, and in 1980 was named Interior
Minister, a powerful post that deals with internal security. At the
December 1986 party congress, he moved up to the No. 2 slot in the
party Politburo, behind the newly-chosen party general secretary,
Nguyen Van Linh.
   In 1987, he was replaced as Interior Minister in a major
government reshuffle. That June, the national assembly named Hung
to replace Dong, a veteran diplomat who was the only premier
communist Vietnam had ever had.
   Given his age and conservative reputation, Western diplomats
said Hung probably was elevated as a ``transitional'' figure who
would pave the way for younger technocrats to preside over economic
reforms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
