<HEAD>Senegal Extends Post-election State of Emergency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAKAR, Senegal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Assembly on Friday extended a
state of emergency invoked Feb. 26 during post-election riots in
the capital of this western African nation.
   The violence broke out after the announcement that Senegalese
President Abdou Diouf, of the Socialist Party, had won re-election
to a second five-year term. Police waged running battles with
stone-throwing protesters, and city businesses and homes of
governing party officials were damaged.
   Diouf's chief opponent, Abdoulaye Wade, of the Senegalese
Democratic Party, was charged by the government Wednesday with 12
other opposition leaders in connection with the violence.
   Diouf's party holds 103 of 120 seats in the assembly. Under
Senegalese law, the president is required to gain its approval to
extend the state of emergency.
   Senegal has a democratic tradition with 17 political parties and
a press that often criticizes the government.
</TEXT>
