<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bangladesh     03-11 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bangladesh,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>About 6,000 Jailed Since Opposition Campaign Launched</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 6,000 political activists have
been imprisoned since the opposition launched its anti-government
campaign last October, it was reported Friday.
   Holiday, an independent English-language weekly, said that about
6,000 people were ``languishing'' in jails.
   Home Secretary Kamaluddin Choudhury denied the report and said
the figure was too high.
   ``Most of the political prisoners arrested in recent months have
been freed,'' he said.
   Choudhury, however, declined to say how many activists were in
jail.
   Bangladesh's top opposition leaders, Sheik Hasina and Khaleda
Zia, claim that more than 10,000 people have been detained by the
security forces since late October.
   The women have been spearheading an opposition campaign to oust
President Hussain Muhammad Ershad, a former army general who seized
power in a bloodless coup in 1982. Their parties, the Awami League
and the Bangladesh Nationalist Party, boycotted the March 3
parliamentary elections along with other major opposition groups.
   Ershad's Jatiya Party gained a majority in the polls.
   The opposition parties will observe March 16 as ``Release the
Detainees Day'' to pressure the government to release the political
workers, most of whom are being held under the Special Powers Act.
The Act allows imprisonment for one month without the filing of
formal charges.
</TEXT>
