<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Arias     03-11 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arias,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Tells Superpowers To Lay Off Central America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Oscar Arias, winner of the
1987 Nobel Peace prize for his Central American peace plan, said
the United States and Soviet Union should give the region a chance
to work out its problems on its own.
   In an interview with The Associated Press, Arias said he also
has urged President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev
to include Central America as a topic in their next summit.
   Stressing that the purpose of his peace plan was to ``build
bridges,'' Arias said he had received indications from both United
States and Soviet Union that the superpowers will discuss the issue.
   ``I went to the U.S. Congress to ask congressmen to give us
Central Americans an opportunity to work out our problems,'' Arias
said in the interview, conducted Thursday. ``But I cannot do the
same thing in the Soviet Union because of the nature of its regime,
radically different from the pluralistic democracy system of the
West.''
   Arias said he was pleased that Nicaragua's Contra rebels had
agreed to meet with Nicaraguan government representatives inside
that country and without a mediator for cease-fire talks. Previous
peace talks have been held outside the country and were mediated by
Nicaragua's Roman Catholic bishop.
   Arias described a Nicaraguan cease-fire as the ``key ... that
would then open other possibilities'' for peace.
   But he expressed regrets that the Soviet Union continued to
provide aid to leftist guerrilla movements in Central America.
   ``I cannot use the Soviet Union's media and ask its government
to give us the same chance I requested from the U.S. Congress. I
see where the Soviet Union continues to help guerrilla movements in
Central America and, in the last few months, as never before, is
helping the Sandinista governemnt militarily,'' he added.
   The war in Nicaragua is one of the Central American conflicts
that Arias hopes will be resolved as a result of his peace plan,
which also seeks to end guerrilla wars in El Salvador and Honduras,
bring democracy to the entire region, and end foreign aid to
insurgents.
   The presidents of Nicaragua, El Salvador, Honduras, and
Guatemala joined Arias in signing the plan last August.
   Arias said that if the United States and Soviet Union include
Central America's armed conflicts in their summit agenda, ``it
would be very important for us to show between now and then that
some progress has been made toward reaching a regional political
solution.''
   ``We have an opportunity, as never before, to find peace in
Central America,'' Arias said. ``If we do not, those who come after
us will feel less of a commitment to search for it.''
   Arias said a problem with making the peace plan work has been a
lack of consistency between what is being said and done.
   ``There can be no peace without democracy in our region. They
must go hand in hand,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
