<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 1314EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RitalinLawsuits     03-11 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ritalin Lawsuits,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Human Rights Group Announces Filing of Lawsuits Stemming from
Ritalin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group formed by the Church of Scientology has
filed five medical malpractice lawsuits in Massachusetts against
physicians who prescribed the drug Ritalin to children to control
supposed hyperactivity.
   The Citizens Commission for Human Rights claims Ritalin is
dangerous and over-prescribed.
   The maker of the drug, not named in any of the suits, denied all
the group's claims Friday.
   Dennis Clarke, president of the commission that was formed in
1969, read aloud from medical and psychiatric journals to back up
the group's claims when the group announced the suits Thursday with
attorneys and two mothers who are plaintiffs. The suits do not
request specific damages.
   Too often, Clarke said, teachers and school officials complain
that a child is too active and suggest to parents that the child be
taken to a pediatrician who recommends Ritalin without careful
examination.
   Clarke said Ritalin use requires increased dosage over time.
Withdrawal results in depression and can sometimes result in
suicidal behavior, he claimed. He also cited medical journals in
his claim that Ritalin has been shown to cause psychotic episodes
in children.
   Such claims were all denied Friday by Ciba-Geigy Corp.
spokeswoman Gloria Martini in Summit, N.J., who said she has never
seen in medical journals any of the claims Clarke cited.
   ``Ritalin has been out there for over 30 years and it has a long
history of experience for physicians who use it,'' Mrs. Martini
said. ``There is no evidence that it is addictive when used as
directed.''
   She said it has a potential for abuse, however.
   Ciba-Geigy introduced Ritalin to the U.S. market in 1955. In
1987 it was used by an estimated 600,000 to 700,000 patients, Mrs.
Martini said.
   Clarke said he spoke briefly to attorneys representing Rod
Matthews, the 15-year-old Canton boy convicted of second-degree
murder in the bludgeoning a classmate with a baseball bat.
Matthews' attorneys claimed the teen-ager had been taking Ritalin
and that it may have triggered the violent episode.
   Susan Marshall of Hingham, mother of a child placed on Ritalin
and a plaintiff in one of the suits, said Ritalin was prescribed
for her ``normal, happy, well-adjusted'' son when he began to have
slight handwriting problems in the first grade.
   ``I was not given any diagnosis, I was never told about any side
effects,'' said Mrs. Marshall.
   Her son took the drug for six months and became angry, hostile,
moody and stopped eating most meals, she said. A neurologist later
discovered his problem stemmed from slight brain damage.
   Rita Lassiter of New Bedford said her son, Matthew, was first
described as ``too active'' by his kindergarten teachers and was
given Ritalin after a 10-minute examination by a pediatrician.
   Bernard Portnoy, who prescribed the drug for Matthew Lassiter,
said he was unaware of the lawsuit against him.
   Of Ritalin, he said, ``I think it can be of help when it's used
properly. It can be helpful in many cases.''
   Mrs. Lassiter said Matthew's condition worsened after taking the
drug but said she did not make the connection until a few years
later. When Matthew was taken off the drug, he became so
disoriented and troubled that he had to be hospitalized. Now 11, he
is unable to attend school, his vision is blurred and his growth is
stunted, Mrs. Lassiter said.
</TEXT>
