<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Mecham 1stLd-Writethru a0465 03-11 0779</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0465,0800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governor's Lawyer Challenges Senator's Impartiality</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with today's testimony, picking
up 3rd graf pvs, `Usdane `ought ...;' SUBS 14th-15th grafs pvs,
`The governor ...,' with 2 grafs to conform.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PN5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former top aide to Gov. Evan Mecham
testified today that he believed the governor was loyal to a state
official accused of making a death threat because the man had been
an effective campaign fund-raiser.
   Former special assistant Sam Steiger, who faces a criminal
extortion charge unrelated to Mecham's case, testified at the
governor's impeachment trial that Mecham has a ``dangerous tendency
of extreme loyalty'' to people who have helped him.
   Mecham felt such loyalty toward Lee Watkins, who is accused of
making a death threat against former Mecham aide Donna Carlson,
Steiger said. Ms. Carlson was about to testify before a grand jury
investigating the governor's campaign finances.
   Mecham is accused of trying to thwart an investigation of the
alleged threat.
   During Thursday's testimony, Mecham's defense lawyer angered
senators by accusing the Senate majority leader of showing
``overwhelming'' bias against the governor during his impeachment
trial.
   Jerris Leonard lashed out at Majority Leader Bob Usdane when the
Republican lawmaker questioned whether the impeached governor's new
lawyers erred when they said weeks ago they were ready to defend
Mecham.
   Usdane ``ought to show a little more impartiality,'' said
Leonard. ``His bias and prejudice are overwhelming,'' and under
normal trial circumstances he should be disqualified, the attorney
said.
   For months, Usdane has been accused by some lawmakers of being
too accommodating toward Mecham's GOP administration.
   Leonard's attack came during testimony on an accusation that
Mecham tried to block an investigation of an alleged death threat
by a state official. Testimony on that charge was expected to
continue today.
   Usdane called the lawyer's blast ``ill-conceived.''
   ``I don't think I'm biased,'' the majority leader added. ``I
swore an oath to go (make a decision) based on the evidence and
that's what I'll go on.''
   Minority Leader Alan Stephens also took issue with Leonard's
statement.
   ``Maybe they figured they've lost their case, and are going to
go one by one trying to create controversy,'' Stephens said. ``If
that's so, we're all in for a very unpleasant time.''
   The controversy arose when Usdane challenged Leonard's
contention that he should be allowed to question a witness on
matters not specified earlier because there had not been enough
time to prepare for trial.
   The senator asked whether that countered an affidavit by
Mecham's new lawyers certifiying they were ready shortly before the
trial began Feb. 29.
   Leonard joined Mecham's defense team a week before the trial
opened, and the governor's original defense lawyer resigned three
days later.
   Mecham, 63, is also accused of concealing a $350,000 campaign
loan and misusing $80,000 from a state protocol fund by loaning it
to his auto dealership. He faces an April 21 criminal trial on
charges of hiding the $350,000 loan, and a May 17 recall election.
   The governor is accused of ordering Department of Public Safety
Director Ralph Milstead not to cooperate with a probe of the
alleged threat last November against Ms. Carlson, a former Mecham
aide about to testify before a grand jury about the $350,000 loan.
   Peggy Griffith, head of the Governor's Office of Women's
Services, testified last week that Watkins, then the state prison
construction chief, threatened Ms. Carlson's life during the second
of two conversations Nov. 12.
   The defense sought Thursday to discredit Mrs. Griffith with
testimony from her secretary, Terri Fields, who said her boss
``tends to exaggerate things a little'' and was not thorough in her
work.
   When asked for an example of an exaggeration by Mrs. Griffith,
Ms. Fields said she could not think of one. Ms. Fields testified
she did not believe the second conversation between Mrs. Griffith
and Watkins ever happened.
   ``Maybe she did have the conversation with Lee Watkins, but I
don't believe that a threat came out of it,'' Ms. Fields said.
   Ray Russell, the only one of Mecham's original special
assistants still on his staff a year after the governor took
office, testified that administration officials felt that ``every
time you turned around it looked like somebody was investigating us
for breaking the law.''
   ``I know what's in his (Mecham's) heart,'' Russell said. ``I
find him to be an honest, sincere man.''
   Mecham is the first U.S. governor to be impeached in six decades
and the first ever in Arizona. A two-thirds vote of the 30-member
Senate is required for a conviction that could bar him from ever
holding public office again.
</TEXT>
