<2ND_LINE>PM-South Carolina Democrats, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0440,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Clear Front-runner In South Carolina Caucus</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Top 3 grafs new with Jackson appearance; pick up 3rd graf pvs
bgng ``There's more...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Favorite son Jesse Jackson, looking for a
warm homecoming in South Carolina in Saturday's Democratic
caucuses, said today ``it's get out the vote time'' in the state
that gave him one of his few 1984 wins.
   Jackson told about 250 supporters at the University of South
Carolina that the new challenge for the South is to ``find common
ground where the people can come together.''
   Most political experts and campaign officials in the state
agreed that Jackson was the clear front-runner in the caucuses.
   There's more suspense over how close Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore
Jr. can come to Jackson and the division of delegates, 44 of which
are at stake Saturday.
   South Carolina's Democratic leaders decided against following
the crowd on Super Tuesday, when all of the other Southern states
held primaries.
   The candidates are relying on grass-roots organizing, telephone
banks and direct mail to lure Democrats to the caucus; Gore is also
buying television advertisements.
   Gore, who was campaigning in Greenville, Columbia and Charleston
today, has the largest organization in the state and the most
endorsements from elected officials, who wield strong influence at
the caucuses.
   Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt, who traveled across the state
Wednesday and Thursday, has a skeletal organization. But his few
endorsements from elected officials are the biggest _ former Govs.
Dick Riley and Robert McNair and all of the South Carolina
Democratic congressmen who have chosen sides.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis has an even smaller local
organization and virtually no endorsements from elected officials.
   But Dukakis' strong Super Tuesday showing will help earn him a
chunk of votes Saturday, Barry Weiner, Dukakis' national campaign
co-chairman, said Thursday in Columbia.
   All of the competing state campaigns except Gore's have conceded
that Jackson will win the lion's share of the 44 delegates at stake.
   ``I don't think there is any doubt that Jesse Jackson will
win,'' said Bill Prince, Gephardt's state coordinator.
   House Speaker Robert Sheheen, Gore's state chairman, said
``there's really no way of knowing'' whether the Tennessee senator
can upset Jackson. ``We're not conceding anything to anybody.''
   Gore is promoting his strong ties to the South and a strong
defense, which plays well in the Palmetto State.
   Gephardt is hoping to use his trade policy to gain votes in the
state, which has seen its largest industry _ textiles _ severely
weakened by cheap foreign imports. His first stop Wednesday was a
textile plant in Aiken County that is scheduled to close next month
and put 420 people out of work.
   Between a quarter and a half of South Carolina Democrats
traditionally remain uncommitted at the caucus meetings to give
themselves more maneuvering room through the nominating process.
They usually choose a candidate at the county or state convention.
   That leaves relatively few delegates for the candidates to
divide up Saturday. But in a tight national race in which no
candidate has been able to take a decisive lead, every one helps.
   ``This certainly increases the importance of South Carolina
because the delegate count is so close,'' said Kevin Gray, state
coordinator for Jackson.
</TEXT>
