<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Refugees     03-11 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Refugees,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thailand Fears Lower Refugee Quotas in Favor of Armenians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thailand's envoy urged the United States on
Friday not to cut quotas for Indochinese refugees to make room for
Armenians fleeing the Soviet Union.
   If more Armenians are permitted into the United States the
quotas for Eastern Europe should be raised and the quotas for
Indochina should be left alone, Ambassador Arsa Sarasin told a news
conference.
   The U.S. budget currently permits the annual entry of 68,500
refugees from around the world, including 23,000 from Indochina.
Thailand, where 400,000 Indochinese refugees reside, mostly in
camps, is pressing continuously for higher quotas.
   ``The United States must not cut the quota and give it to
Eastern Europe,' Sarasin said.
   The Reagan administration is in the process of deciding what to
do about a massive increase in applications for entry from
residents of Soviet Armenia.
   According to State Department records, Armenians are applying
for asylum at a rate of 1,500 a month, compared with 200 applicants
in all of 1985 and 200 to 300 a month as recently as 1987. Up to
12,000 Armenians are reportedly waiting to come to the United
States.
   A current wave of ethnic protests in Armenia has highlighted
some of the dissatisfaction there toward Soviet government policies
in the region.
   Sarasin said he felt better about the situation after Jonathan
Moore, director of the State Department's division of refugee
affairs, told a congressional hearing Feb. 24 that no decision to
alter quotas had been made.
   A U.S. official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
however that changes were possible under some of the options being
considered by an interagency group.
   The group may decide to reallocate quotas, grant emergency
quotas for the Armenians, or slow down processing of refugees to
pay for the influx from Armenia.
   Relations between the United States and Thailand have been in a
somewhat sour state lately, mostly because of the refugee problem.
After years of providing asylum to people fleeing Cambodia, Vietnam
and Laos, resistance is growing in Thailand to the continuing
influx.
   Leaders there have accused the United States, Australia, Canada
and other resettlement countries of failing to live up to
commitments to find new homes for the refugees.
   ``Thailand cannot bear the burden indefinitely,'' Sarasin said.
``There is a limit to our capacity.''
   Moore and other U.S. officials have been sympathetic to
Thailand's concerns and have sought higher refugee quotas. At the
same time, they have criticized inhumane treatment of refugees in
Thailand.
   Such treatment has included the closing of some camps, the
pushing of boats laden with refugees out to sea and the forced
repatriation of Lao tribesmen seeking a haven in Thailand.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
