<DOCNO> AP880311-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 1332EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CrashHearing 1stLd-Writethru a0607 03-11 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash Hearing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0607,0622</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigation Turns Spotlight On Pilot's, Co-Pilot's Experience</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with morning testimony, picking
up 6th graf pvs, `Bruecher had ....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DENIS SEARLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The captain of a Continental Airlines
flight that crashed last November, killing 28 people and injuring
54, generally performed well when he was tested on a DC-9, a flight
trainer testified today at a federal hearing.
   However, the co-pilot, First Officer Lee Bruecher, 26, was at
the controls of Continental Flight 1713 when it crashed at Denver's
Stapleton International Airport on Nov. 15. Both the pilot and
co-pilot were killed.
   On Thursday, a different flight trainer testified that Bruecher
had trouble with takeoffs and landings during his simulator
training on the DC-9.
   In testimony today before National Transportation Safety Board
officials investigating the accident, Continental Capt. James
Edward Madsen said Capt. Frank Zvonek did a good job on a test ride
from Denver to Albuquerque, N.M., but he did not give himself as
long a final approach as Madsen would have liked and did not allow
enough visual clearance behind a small aircraft.
   ``I would have given myself another mile or two of spacing,''
said Madsen, but added, ``It was not a down or unsatisfactory
flight at all.''
   Continental pilot trainer J.E. Summerville's testimony Thursday
about Bruecher's performance highlighted the third day of the
four-day NTSB hearing. The board is trying to identify factors that
caused the DC-9 to crash moments after takeoff.
   Bruecher was a good student but had problems with takeoffs and
landings, and Summerville once had to ``freeze'' the training
simulator to avoid a crash during a practice landing, he said
Thursday.
   Bruecher ``had trouble controlling altitude and airspeed within
reasonable limits,'' Summerville wrote, and repeated one course of
the seven-part flight simulator training.
   However, at the conclusion of the training, Summerville said, he
recommended Bruecher for the Federal Aviation Administration
proficiency test needed to fly a specific kind of airplane.
   Bruecher finished a proficiency check on Sept. 14, 1987, with
another instructor who graded his performance ``average'' and began
his initial operating experience as a line pilot with Continental
on Oct. 2. At the time of the crash, he had only 36 hours piloting
DC-9s, NTSB investigators have said.
   Zvonek had 198 hours on a DC-9 with only the previous 33 hours
as captain.
   NTSB officials on Thursday also questioned Capt. Dave Dickerson,
manager of Continental's DC-9 program at Houston, about training
procedures. Dickerson said he saw no correlation between Bruecher's
level of experience and the problems he experienced.
   De-icing was another subject of testimony.
   Summerville said he instructs pilots during training to
re-evaluate the condition of their aircraft if 20 minutes or more
elapse between the time the plane is de-iced and takeoff.
   ``I tell them to look at the parts you can see from the cockpit,
including the nose, the windshield wipers, unheated windows and any
aircraft around you.''
   Depending on the weather conditions, Summerville said, he
sometimes would advise pilots to go into the cabin and look out at
the wings. ``But we all know that's not the best way to look to see
if you've got ice on the wings.'' A mechanic's inspection at the
gate would be better, he said.
   Earlier testimony showed that a mixup by air traffic officials
delayed Flight 1713's takeoff by minutes, but no conclusions were
drawn on whether that had any role in the crash.
   Also under investigation is the possibility that a wing vortex,
or swirling wind triggered by another plane's wing moving through
the air, could have contributed to the crash.
</TEXT>
