<HEAD>Trucker Surrenders After Firing Shotgun Blasts, Jackknifing Rig on
Freeway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd with police saying Stone involved in
similar incident 10 years ago; INSERTS 2 grafs after 7th graf, ``He
has ...,' with two visits to house, details. INSERTS 2 grafs after
14th graf, `Finally, he ...,' with negotiations. DELETES outdated
5th graf pvs, ``So far ....'
^By STEVE GEISSINGER</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VACAVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A truck driver surrendered to police
this morning after he stormed into his estranged wife's home and
fired six blasts from a shotgun, then jackknifed his rig on a busy
freeway, authorities said.
   One shot was fired a short time before the incident ended about
7:25 a.m., but police said it was not aimed at them and nobody was
injured.
   Ronald Stone, 34, was taken to Solano County Jail to be booked
for investigation of attempted murder, according to police Lt. Gary
Mallory.
   It was a replay of a similar incident from a decade ago,
according to police Chief Gary Tatum, who said Stone then held off
police with a gun in a domestic dispute and spent some time in jail
as a result.
   The truck driver had threatened to shoot anyone who approached,
police said. Officers from three agencies surrounded the section of
Interstate 80 where Stone sat in the vehicle with ``lots of
ammunition,'' said Mallory.
   A special weapons and tactics unit from the police department,
California Highway Patrol officers and Solano County sheriff's
deputies rushed to the area.
   ``He has a 12-gauge shotgun and he fired six rounds while at his
wife's home, four inside and two outside,'' Mallory said.
   Tatum said Jackie Stone first called police at 12:46 a.m. to
report her husband was at the door and appeared to be drunk. By the
time officers arrived, he was gone.
   Tatum said they received a second call about half an hour later
saying Stone had returned.
   Stone, who separated from his wife about a month ago, kicked in
the front door of the house.
   After telling the couple's three children it was time for their
mother ``and him to die,'' Stone began beating his wife, Mallory
said.
   His mother-in-law and the children fled from the house, and
Stone's wife managed to escape soon after, police said.
   When officers arrived, Stone threatened to kill himself, holding
the shotgun beneath his chin with a finger poised on the trigger,
Mallory said.
   Finally, he leaped into his unmarked tractor-trailer rig and,
with police pursuing, headed for the freeway, the officer said.
There, Stone jackknifed the truck, leaving the cab stuck in the
median and the trailer jutting into traffic.
   Police talked with Stone, first by CB radio and then, after he
stopped, via a field telephone tossed into the cab.
   After firing a final blast out the window of the truck, Stone
gave up. He suffered minor powder burns from the shotgun, but was
otherwise unhurt.
   The highway patrol closed the freeway in both directions,
jamming one of the main arteries leading to the San Francisco Bay
area and the state capital in Sacramento.
</TEXT>
