<2ND_LINE>PM-Alaska Caucuses, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0487,340</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 8 grafs new with Jackson win, other results; pick up 8th
graf pvs bgng ``The precinct delegates...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEAN FOSDICK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson finished first in
Alaska's Democratic precinct caucuses, posting a narrow victory
over Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis in a nonbinding preference
poll announced today.
   With about 90 percent of Alaska's 442 precincts reporting,
Jackson claimed 872 delegates, or 35 percent of the total, to
Dukakis' 769 delegates, or 31 percent.
   A close third, however, were 768 delegates, or 31 percent, who
were uncommitted.
   Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. finished a distant fourth, with
47 delegates or 2 percent, followed by Illinois Sen. Paul Simon
with 18 delegates, less than 1 percent, and Missouri Rep. Richard
Gephardt, 16 delegates for less than 1 percent.
   Henry Lancaster, statewide coordinator for the Jackson campaign,
said that with blacks comprising just 3 percent of Alaska's
population, his candidate's appeal came from the anti-drug and
economic issues he's been voicing around the nation.
   ``This state has a lot of working-class people who've come from
the South, the Midwest and the Northwest,'' Lancaster said. ``In
down times, people are looking for solutions. And this is a down
time.''
   That reference was to the collapse of Alaska's oil-fired
economy. About 85 percent of the state's budget is supported by oil
revenues, and world oil prices are less than half what they were
three years ago.
   The Democrats chose 2,496 delegates in caucuses around the state
Thursday night. The caucuses were open to any registered Democrat
and anyone who wished to register at the door.
   The precinct delegates selected Thursday will meet at 27
district caucuses on April 9-10. They will select 390 delegates to
attend the state convention in Fairbanks on May 13-15.
   None of the delegates chosen before the state convention is
bound to a particular candidate.
   The 12 delegates emerging from the state convention will attend
the national convention in Atlanta in July. Those delegates will be
bound to a specific candidate for at least the first ballot.
</TEXT>
