<1ST_LINE>r p AM-SouthDakota-Democrats     03-11 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Dakota-Democrats,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Democratic Caucus Canceled Because Of Snowstorm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PIERRE, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A snowstorm caused South Dakota Democrats to
postpone a statewide caucus called for Saturday, when the party was
to decide how to apportion 15 of the state's national convention
delegates.
   ``It's a quality snowstorm,'' said Rick Hauffe, acting director
of the South Dakota Democratic Party. ``It really dumped.''
   The Friday storm was expected to leave from 4 to 18 inches of
snow across the state.
   Hauffe said the caucus has been rescheduled for March 19.
   Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt won the state's Democratic
primary on Feb. 23, but national party rules would not permit the
election to have any directly binding effect on the national
convention delegates.
   The dispute with the national party centered on the timing of
the primary, which came two weeks earlier than allowed by national
party rules.
   The statewide caucus, meeting within the time allowed by the
national rules, was to decide whether to allocate the delegates
among the presidential candidates in proportion to the primary
results. Under the rules, the caucus is free to use the primary
results or reject them entirely, basing the allocation instead on
the presidential preferences of the people attending the caucus.
   If the caucus decides to use the primary results, only Gephardt
and Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis would qualify for any
delegates.
   Based on the primary results, Gephardt would receive nine pedged
delegates to the Democratic National Convention and Dukakis would
get six, party officials have said.
</TEXT>
