<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Indonesia     03-11 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Indonesia,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Vice President Takes Office Over Moslem, Military Objections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GHAFUR FADYL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A close aide to President Suharto was
sworn in as vice president Friday despite opposition from the
parliament's Moslem faction and some members of the military.
   State Secretary Sudharmono was elected to the post earlier in
the day, hours after Suharto was sworn in for a fifth five-year
term. The five factions of the People's Consultative Assembly
reached a consensus to elect Sudharmono after the Moslem United
Development Party dropped its candidate, party chairman Jailani
Naro.
   The decision to withdraw Naro's candidacy came after Suharto
named the 61-year-old Sudharmono as his choice for vice president
in a meeting with the assembly leadership.
   Sudharmono was formally nominated by the governing GOLKAR party,
an acronym for the Indonesian words ``Golongan Karya'' or
functional group. He was also supported by the assembly's
government-nominated military faction, the government-nominated
provincial faction and the nationalist Christian Indonesian
Democratic Party faction.
   Suharto, 66, reportedly told GOLKAR members last month that the
next vice president should be able to lead the nation should the
president become incapacitated.
   Military sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said some
members of the army had opposed his nomination. They supported
instead the newly appointed armed forces commander, Gen. Try
Sutrisno, 52, a popular figure and a former Suharto aide.
   An army general took to the podium following Suharto's
re-election Thursday to protest nominating procedures for the vice
president.
   ``We Indonesian soldiers who believe in God and defend honesty
and justice have heard rumors that the nomination of the vice
president is not being fairly and correctly carried out,'' said
Brig. Gen. Ibrahim Saleh, an assembly member from the
government-nominated military faction.
   ``There are certain things that we feel are against our
consience,'' said Saleh, who was escorted out by assembly officials
before he could finish his statement.
   Sudharmono, a retired army lieutenant general, is a military
lawyer by training. He became one of the country's leading
bureaucrats after years of government apprenticeship, first under
the late President Sukarno and then as a founding member of the
Suharto administration.
   Addressing the parliament after he was sworn in, Sudharmono said
an ability to work closely with the president was of extreme
importance.
   ``I extend my deepest gratitude to President Suharto for giving
me this honor and trust to work with him in the coming five
years,'' he said.
</TEXT>
