<HEAD>Greek-Turkish Relations Apparently in U.S.-Greek Base Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Athens has linked its improving relations
with Turkey to its talks with the United States on military bases
in Greece, a government spokesman said Friday.
   Greece and the United States ended their fourth round of
negotiations on a new agreement to replace one expiring in December.
   ``The talks were also dedicated this time to the exchange of
views between the two sides on issues of principle that have been
put forward by the Greek government,'' said spokesman Sotiris
Kostopoulos.
   Kostopoulos apparently was referring to Greek demands linking a
new accord to progress on Greek-Turkish problems.
   Relations between the two neighboring allies have been steadily
improving since Premier Andreas Papandreou's recent meetings with
Turkish Prime Minister Turgut Ozal. Greece and Turkey have
quarreled over Aegean airspace and seabed rights.
   The United States has said it wants to avoid regional politics
in the bilateral base negotiations.
   There are four U.S. bases in Greece: two near Athens and two on
the southern island of Crete. Greece receives more than $300
million a year in military credits as payment.
   More negotiations are scheduled in Athens next month and in
Washington in May.
