<1ST_LINE>r p AM-IllinoisDelegates     03-11 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Illinois Delegates,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delegate Races, Not ``Beauty Contest'' Important in Illinois</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DOWLING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Sen. Paul Simon asked local
supporters this week to cast nine votes for him in Illinois'
Democratic primary, it wasn't an incitement to vote fraud.
   Simon's plea reflected Illinois' two-part presidential ballot: a
non-binding ``beauty contest'' preference vote and dozens of local
races for the Democratic and Republican delegate slots that are the
real prize on Tuesday.
   Unlike many states in which delegates are apportioned on the
basis of a statewide vote, Illinois' delegates are elected directly
by voters in congressional district races.
   It's a key feature of the political terrain for presidential
candidates in Illinois, offering advantages to Simon, George Bush
and Bob Dole and posing daunting problems for others, political
obervers say.
   The 82 Republican and 113 Democratic delegate slots to be filled
Tuesday are apportioned among the state's 22 congressional
districts on the basis of relative strength in previous primaries.
   For example, in the heavily Democratic 1st District on Chicago's
South Side, Democratic voters will select nine delegates and three
alternates, while Republicans will choose two delegates and two
alternates.
   Recruiting delegate-candidates is a key organizational hurdle
for the presidential campaigns. Without backers on the delegate
ballot, a candidate can't translate Illinois support into
convention votes.
   The system is further complicted this year by the crowded
presidential field, leaving voters in some areas to choose among as
many as 70 delegate candidates.
   ``I am asking for nine votes,'' Simon told backers at a
Springfield fund-raiser on Wednesday. ``Six for delegates, two for
alternates and one for that beauty contest. All nine votes are
important.''
   Simon's political roots in Illinois gave him an edge in
recruiting well-known delegate-candidates with a voter appeal of
their own. His slates are studded with state legislators, labor
leaders and party activists.
   ``Basically, we looked for people that have well-known names or
would bring in a supporting group: a labor-union leader, a person
from nuclear freeze, an elected official or party leader,'' said
Mike Kreloff, Simon's Illinois delegate coordinator.
   ``They'll help him hold off (Michael) Dukakis, but their impact
is minimized by the fact that the presidential candidate's name
appears on the ballot'' alongside the delegate-candidates, said
Steve Copple, Jesse Jackson's national delegate coordinator. ``The
bulk of the people are going to vote for their presidential
candidates' supporters.''
   Illinois' delegate selection system is a handicap for Jackson,
whose stronghold is three predominantly black districts in Chicago.
Those districts will elect 24 of the 113 Democratic delegates, but
his chances of success elsewhere are questionable.
   Simon's other Democratic foes had little success in recruiting
big names, and only he and Dukakis have full slates in every
district. Albert Gore has no supporters on the ballot in three
districts and Richard Gephardt is short of a full slate in five
districts.
   Even favorite son Jackson has no delegate slate in the heavily
Republican 12th District, and is short of a full slate in three
other districts.
   ``We were looking for people who had a fundamental commitment to
Al Gore and his philosophy,'' said Larry Perlman, who runs the Gore
campaign in Illinois. ``That meant we didn't get a lot of people
who have been around party politics for a long time.''
   On the GOP side, Bush and Dole both assembled impressive slates
with the help of their state chairmen, Gov. James R. Thompson and
Illinois House Republican Leader Lee Daniels. Pat Robertson also
has a full slate in every district, but virtually all of his
candidates are political unknowns.
   Bush operatives acknowledge that well-known Dole
delegate-candidates such as former Gov. Richard Ogilvie and former
U.S. Attorney Dan K. Webb might help Dole revive his candidacy
   ``I don't think name recognition alone is going to win for the
delegates,'' said Ed Murnane, deputy director of Bush's Illinois
campaign. ``But in the really close, tight races, that's where name
recognition probably does have some impact.''
</TEXT>
