<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PriestDeposition     03-11 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Priest Deposition,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Lifts Stay Against Deposition In Priest Sex Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rhode Island Supreme Court on Friday
refused to block efforts to get a deposition from a priest
regarding talks he had with another pastor later convicted of
sexually molesting young boys.
   The Roman Catholic Diocese of Providence is being sued for $12
million by a Narragansett woman and her son who contend the diocese
knew the Rev. William C. O'Connell was molesting boys but did
nothing about it. As a result, the suit contends, the boy became
one of O'Connell's victims.
   The family's attorney, R. Daniel Prentiss, has been trying to
take a deposition from the Rev. Richard C. Bucci. But Bishop Louis
E. Gelineau and Auxiliary Bishop Kenneth A. Angell, named as
defendants in the suit with O'Connell, argued any conversations
between Bucci and O'Connell are privileged.
   The diocese contended the discussions are protected by a state
law that prohibits a priest from testifying about ``confidential
communication entrusted to him in his professional capacity.''
   Prentiss contended the state law is intended to prevent a priest
from divulging what he is told in confession.
   ``My interpretation was that a statutory privilege absolutely
does not apply and cannot be used to silence a witness the way they
were trying here,'' Prentiss said Friday.
   Monday, a Superior Court judge denied the diocese's request to
permanently block the deposition, but granted church attorneys a
temporary stay pending a Supreme Court appeal.
   Prentiss and diocese attorney William T. Murphy met in chambers
Friday with Supreme Court Associate Justice Florence K. Murray.
   ``About an hour later or less, I got a telephone call from the
court saying there was not going to be a stay of the deposition,''
Prentiss said.
   There was no elaboration on the decision, Prentiss said.
   He said Bucci is scheduled to give his deposition Monday.
   Murphy indicated he would not appeal the high court's decision.
   O'Connell was arrested in 1985 on charges of sexually assaulting
three boys. He was accused of fondling them in the rectory of St.
Mary's Church in Bristol and in his South Kingstown summer cottage
between 1982 and 1984.
   He pleaded no contest to 26 separate counts in 1986 _ seven of
them involving the plaintiff in the civil suit _ and was sentenced
to one year in jail. He also agreed to spend two years in therapy
at a church-run program for clergy members with alcohol and
psychological problems.
   The woman and her son contend the diocese and the bishops failed
to remove O'Connell from his position as pastor of St. Mary's after
being informed of his sexual involvement with boys, some of them
altar boys.
   Buccci, an assistant pastor at St. Mary's in 1984 and 1985, has
not publicly admitted discussing O'Connell's behavior with diocesan
officials. But he did file statements with police about O'Connell,
and he provided information to the state Department for Children
and Their Families.
</TEXT>
