<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 1443EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ChildHealth     03-11 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Child Health,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eradicating Polio The Goal For 1991</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLOIRES, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forty million children in 34 countries
will be vaccinated in the next four years under a program to
eradicate polio in Latin America and the Caribbean, a doctor said
Friday.
   Dr. Ciro A. de Quadros, an adviser to the World Health
Organization, said governments in the region have committed $350
million to the project, which is expected to cost $450 million.
   The rest is to be donated by other groups such as the U.S.
Agency for International Development, UNICEF, WHO, and the private
Rotary International.
   Quadros spoke at a three-day meeting of development experts,
doctors and health ministers in this Alpine town. The conference is
sponsored by the Task Force for Child Survival, whose members
include UNICEF, WHO, the U.N. Development Program, the World Bank
and the Rockefeller Foundation.
   Quadros told the group that the polio campaign expects to reach
10 million of the 11 million children born in Latin America each
year between now and 1991. The goal is to reach 85 percent of the
children in every country in Latin America, either through
established health care systems or special immunization days.
   The campaign is an intensified version of a project already
under way.
   In Paraguay and the Dominican Republic, health workers have gone
door-to-door administering the oral polio vaccine. Nine countries
last year held special immunization days, including El Salvador,
where government troops and rebels called a one-day truce to allow
children to be immunized.
   ``We are four years away from wiping out polio and we are very
confident,'' Quadros said, adding that the incidence of the disease
is already low when compared to other childhood diseases.
   Fourteen Latin American countries last year reported about 900
cases of polio, he said, three times more than in Europe.
   The United States has been virtually free of the paralyzing
virus for a decade.
   ``So, the long-term goal of the polio project not just to wipe
out polio,'' Quadros said in an interview. ``It is to establish an
infrastucture, a health care system in developing countries that
can be used for other types of immunization and for delivering
other care.''
   In addition, success in fighting polio is expected to boost the
morale of health care workers and communities struggling against
the enormous medical problems that confront the impoverished Third
World.
   Dr. William H. Foege, executive director of the Task Force and
former head of the Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta, said
lessons learned in South America will be used to set a date for
eradicating the disease in Asia, Africa and elsewhere.
   Among those attending the meeting at a 16th century stone
monastery in the French Alps are World Bank President Barber
Conable, UNICEF Executive Director James P. Grant, WHO Director
General Halfdan Mahler, leaders of more than a dozen other
international aid agencies and health ministers from 11 countries.
   Since the early 1980s, Task Force organizations have been
cooperating to vaccinate children against diptheria, whooping
cough, tuberculosis and neonatal tetanus, in addition to polio. The
project, aimed at developing countries, has raised immunization
from 5 percent to 50 percent of the world's children in less than a
decade.
</TEXT>
