<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 1445EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PeriledPact     03-11 0719</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Periled Pact,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Department Official Defends Nuclear Pact With Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior State Department official on Friday
defended an agreement giving Japan access to U.S. nuclear wastes
and disputed reports that negotiations with Congress to avert a
move to kill it had broken down.
   ``We're more than prepared to continue the discussions with the
Congress to see if there is a basis for moving forward on the
agreement,'' Fred McGoldrick, director of the Office of
Non-Proliferation and Export Policy, said.
   McGoldrick said the agreement concluded last November with Japan
and facing a disapproval vote next week in the Senate has adequate
safeguards against proliferation and terrorism.
   ``We think the agreement is very much in our interest,'`
McGoldrick said. ``If we do not have this kind of agreement, the
Japanese will simply go elsewhere to buy their enriched uranium.
That not only has commercial implications _ we would lose export
revenues _ it means we do not have nonproliferation controls and
influence that we have in this agreement.''
   Two former Pentagon officials and the congressional General
Accounting Office have been sharply critical of the pact, which
allows Japan to retrieve plutonium, the primary ingredient of
nuclear weapons, from U.S. nuclear fuel once the fuel has been used.
   Critics of the nuclear cooperation agreement said Thursday they
may move to kill the accord next week in Congress.
   The former Pentagon officials, Richard N. Perle and Frank J.
Gaffney Jr., said the Defense Department was not given a
significant role in negotiations and considers the agreement
``seriously flawed.''
   ``The strong position that the department has taken against
nuclear proliferation would have helped to shape the accord
differently,'' they said in a letter written to Sen. John Glenn,
D-Ohio, and obtained by The Associated Press. ``That, we are quite
sure, is why the Department of State went to such lengths to work
around us.''
   Perle and Gaffney cited two provisions of the agreement as
``especially troublesome.'' First, they said, the pact gives Japan
advance U.S. consent for 30 years to reprocess and use American
plutonium in any Japanese facility without restriction on the
amount or the purpose.
   Second, they said, the pact ``imposes extraordinary and
unprecedented restrictions on the right of the United States to
suspend that prior consent.''
   Perle and Gaffney said they were the Pentagon officials
responsible for non-proliferation issues while the agreement was
negotiated.
   A GAO report, meanwhile, said the agreement would leave the
United States without ``effective control'' over reprocessing of
the hazardous material.
   The Feb. 29 report also found fault with the agreement's
provisions to guard against proliferation and said it deprived
Congress of its oversight function.
   Congressional opponents want the United States to have the right
to review Japanese use of plutonium on a case-by-case basis, and to
be able to suspend the agreement to counter terrorism threats or
address other national security concerns.
   The congressional foes also want the agreement to be reviewed
every five years.
   These changes would require renegotiating the terms with Japan,
which the State Department declines to do, said a congressional
source, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   McGoldrick said the United States has ``an unfettered right to
suspend our approval to use plutonium that would result in a
significant increase in the risk of proliferation or a threat to
the national security.''
   And, he said, the pact includes ``defined safeguards'' against
misuse of the plutonium.
   McGoldrick said Canada and Australia, which have strong
non-proliferation policies, have entered into similar agreements
with Japan and West European countries without case-by-case
restrictions.
   The GAO report said the agreement did not meet various
requirements of the Atomic Energy Act. It said giving blanket
approval to Japan for reprocessing plutonium ``would leave the
United States with no effective control over the life of the
proposed agreement.''
   In December, the Senate Foreign Relations Committee voted 15-3
to return the pact to President Reagan and asked that it be
renegotiated. Opponents argued that it sets a precedent to
encourage potentially hazardous trade in plutonium, which is a
potent cancer-causing agent.
   Under the agreement, Japan would ship the spent nuclear fuel
from the United States to reprocessing plants in Britain or France,
which would separate plutonium from the waste. The plutonium then
would be shipped to Japan by air.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
