<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Sniffer Dogs-Contract,0176</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drug Traffickers Put Out `Contract' On Sniffer Dogs, Authorities
Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dogs that helped seize $135 million
worth of drugs in less than a year have enraged drug traffickers
who are offering $30,000 to anyone who kills the animals, federal
authorities say.
   The threats are aimed mostly at one dog, nicknamed Rocky, who
has become a sort of mascot in the fight against drugs and is used
in many drug awareness programs for children, according to Terry
McIntosh, deputy regional chief of the U.S. Border Patrol in Dallas.
   However, McIntosh said Wednesday, the threats made by telephone
a few months ago to the McAllen office cover all 14 dogs used by
the Border Patrol.
   ``The callers said they have put out the word they will pay to
have the dogs killed,'' McIntosh said.
   The dogs are stationed in McAllen and Laredo as well as in
Marfa, El Paso and Del Rio.
   McIntosh said the dogs have been guarded round the clock since
the threats.
</TEXT>
