<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     03-11 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Negotiators to Return Monday With `Strengthened Instructions'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Informal meetings were held Friday in the
Afghanistan peace talks after what U.N. mediator Diego Cordovez
said was a week spent tackling ``enormous difficulties'' in the
proposed settlement to end nine years of fighting.
   He told reporters that he asked the Afghan and Pakistani
representatives to seek ``strengthened instructions'' for the next
session scheduled Monday in the indirect talks between the two
sides.
   This would be just one day before a March 15 target date set for
the negotiations by Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev last month. He
said Moscow would bring home its troops beginning May 15 if the
settlement was signed by March 15.
   However, sources close to the talks have said the date was not
meant as a deadline after which the Soviet pullout might be in
doubt.
   In Peshawar, Pakistan, meanwhile, a moderate faction that split
from the alliance of Moslem Afghan guerrillas last week rejoined
the alliance Friday.
   Sibghatullah Mojaddedi told members of his Afghan National
Liberation Front that assurances from other leaders and from
Pakistani officials persuaded him to rejoin the guerrillas' effort
to hammer out an interim government to oversee the withdrawal of
Soviet troops from Afghanistan.
   Mojaddedi split with the alliance because he was worried that
Moslem extremists would dominate the interim government.
   In Geneva, Cordovez reiterated that agreement existed ``on the
substance of things.''
   The problem now concerns the sequence of actions in Afghanistan,
leading up to and including the withdrawal of the 115,000 Soviet
troops.
   It also hinges on Pakistan's insistence that an interim
government be ready to take control in Kabul before the Soviets
begin their withdrawal.
   Emerging with him from a closed-door meeting was the chief
Pakistani delegate, acting Foreign Minister Zain Noorani, who said
the negotiations were ``inching slowly.''
   Pakistan's position about the interim government came under new
fire from the Soviet Union Thursday with Moscow's special envoy,
Nikolay Kozyrev, saying the talks had ``bogged down'' because of it.
   Kozyrev warned that Islamabad would bear the responsibility if
there was no final agreement despite completion of all the main
elements of the settlement.
   He also said that Moscow felt free to continue military
assistance to Afghanistan even after the troop withdrawal. He
rejected a U.S. demand that military aid should be cut off
simultaneously to both the Kabul government and the anti-communist
guerrillas. Kozyrev said assistance to the government was not
covered in the draft agreements.
   Sources close to the Pakistani delegation said the cut-off issue
was among items discussed with Cordovez at the informal meeting
Friday but they did not dsclose details.
</TEXT>
