<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FordRecalls     03-11 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ford Recalls,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Recalling 214,900 Cars To Fix Pollution-Control Equipment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. is recalling 214,900 cars of
various designs from the 1982 and 1983 model years to fix
pollution-control equipment, the Environmental Protection Agency
said Friday.
   The company has begun notifying owners of 185,000 cars from 1983
equipped with the 1.6-liter four-cylinder engine to bring them in
for adjustment of the exhaust air-injection systems. These cars
were sold as the Ford Escort, Escort EXP and Escort Wagon and the
Mercury Lynx, Lynx LN-7 and Lynx Wagon. About 4,000 cars originally
were sold in California, which has stricter standards than those
applying in other states.
   Cars with this engine equipped with fuel injection, or
designated ``high output,'' are not affected.
   These cars have been exceeding the federal emission standards
for carbon monoxide and unburned fuel, EPA said.
   The agency said Ford also will recall 29,900 cars from the 1982
model year to fix an exhaust gas recirculation system which can
cause excessive emissions of nitrogen oxides.
   The cars affected all have 2.3-liter four-cylinder engines and
automatic transmissions. They were sold as the Ford Mustang,
Granada and Fairmont and the Mercury Capri and Zephyr. Cars
originally sold in California are not affected.
   Dealers will check the carburetor spacer plates, which allows
some exhaust to enter the intake manifold, and clean them of
deposits if necessary.
</TEXT>
