<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 1511EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-RiskySkiing     03-11 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Risky Skiing,0611</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Skiing Off Trails a Daring, Controversial Sport</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Royals, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LORENZ WOLFFERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alpine skiers who seek out daring runs
on unmarked trails accounted for half of all Swiss avalanche deaths
last winter and also pose problems for the environment, officials
said Friday.
   Maj. Hugh Lindsay, a close friend of Britain's Prince Charles,
was killed Thursday by a snowslide while skiing outside the normal
slopes above Klosters, Switzerland, the traditional royal winter
resort.
   The heir to the British throne escaped unhurt.
   The Swiss Federal Avalanche Research Institute had warned
Thursday of considerable avalanche danger above 5,250 feet in the
region. The party was skiing at about 5,900 feet.
   ``One obviously doesn't like seeing anyone getting killed. But
when you ski off the path, that is your own responsibility,'' said
David Bramwell, a British skier vacationing in this remote village
90 miles southeast of Zurich.
   In a statement before leaving Switzerland, Charles said everyone
in his group understood the dangers before they embarked into the
avalanche-prone area.
   ``I would like to emphazise that all members of my party,
including myself, were skiing off the piste (trail) at our own risk
and we all accepted ... that the mountains have to be treated with
the greatest respect,'' Charles said.
   But many vacationing skiers and residents in Klosters indicated
they thought Charles should have not been so willing to lead his
companions down the dangerous slope.
   Last winter, eight of the 16 people killed by snowslides in
Switzerland were off-trail skiers, said Claude Francois Jaccard,
director of the avalanche research institute atop Mount
Weissfluhjoch.
   Over the long-term, they make up about 30 percent of all
avalanche deaths. The toll is highest among ski hikers who tour
across mountains on skis often for days, Jaccard said.
   About 1 million skiers, including many foreigners, cut loose on
unmarked runs every year, the Swiss National Association for Sports
says.
   Christian Tischauser, chief ski warden at Corvatsch, about 30
miles south of Klosters, recently called on the Swiss government to
consider legislating curbs on off-trail skiing.
   Neighboring Austria has banned the practice as of this year,
with violators facing fines.
   Switzerland has not followed suit. But one recent outing became
expensive for three Swiss who set off an avalanche as they skied
off marked trails near Zermatt.
   A court last month made them pay the cost of sending out search
teams.
   Swiss authorities, tourism offices and sports associations have
taken the tack of appealing to skiers' responsibility when
venturing off regular runs.
   Some resorts in the Grisons region, where Klosters is located,
already have limited such skiing.
   A nationwide information campaign was launched late last year to
make off-trail skiers aware of safe areas to practice the sport.
   ``The basic capital for tourism is unblemished nature,'' said
Peter Anrig of the Swiss Tourism Association.
   Inexperienced skiers are known to rip through saplings,
ultimately killing off a future tree in a country concerned about
widespread forest damage from pollution, he said. Snow tourists
also tend to litter in the otherwise virgin areas.
   Alpine animals are jolted by off-trailers, experts say, citing
the example of the snow grouse. Skiers often scare the birds out of
snow caves in which they hibernate, leaving them to die of cold and
consumption in glacial temperatures.
   Swiss avalanches have killed an average of 27 people each year
over the past 50 years, according to the federal institute. Six out
of 10 victims are skiers.
   Lindsay's death brought this winter's toll to 12.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
