<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Pollard     03-11 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Pollard,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>70 Israeli Legislators Ask Reagan To Pardon Pollards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seventy members of the Israeli parliament on
Friday presented a petition calling on President Reagan to pardon
Jonathan J. Pollard, the Navy analyst who was convicted of passing
secrets to Israel.
   The petition, presented to U.S. Ambassador Thomas Pickering, was
signed by most of the right-wing Likud bloc in the Knesset, or
parliament, and by the left-wing MAPAM faction. It was a rare
display of unity among Israel's divided legislators.
   The Committee for Justice for the Pollards released news of the
petition in the United States.
   It called on Reagan to pardon Pollard, a civilian Navy
intelligence analyst convicted last year of selling secrets to
Israel and sentenced to life in prison. The petitioners also asked
Reagan to pardon Pollard's wife, Anne Henderson-Pollard, who was
sentenced to five years in jail for being an accessory.
   ``It is very rare for an issue to so cut across party lines as
does the plight of the Pollards,'' according to the petitioners.
``All Israel is praying for their release.''
   The Israeli government was severely embarrassed by Pollard's
arrest outside its Washington embassy in 1985, saying it had not
authorized the spying operation. Public pressure, however, forced
the government to foot the bill for some of Pollard's legal fees.
   The Pollard committee noted that the Pollards' punishment was
particularly harsh in view of the fact that he spied for a U.S.
ally.
   In general, ``spies for allies are treated more leniently, if
they are prosecuted at all,'' the committee said.
</TEXT>
