<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--FertilizerProtest     03-11 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Fertilizer Protest,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Local Chinese Party Official Expelled for Corruption</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A local official in southwestern China was
expelled from the Communist Party after his use of influence to buy
up scarce fertilizer led to a protest by 400 farmers, a newspaper
reported Friday.
   The party expelled Liu Xingdong, deputy secretary of Tiefeng
Township in Sichuan province, according to the official China
Daily. It said Liu was under investigation for using the ``back
door'' to buy up chemical fertilizer.
   Such fertilizers are in chronic short supply in China, and there
are reports in the official media of widespread corruption in their
sale and distribution.
   The report said Liu last October asked the local supply
cooperative to sell him 990 pounds of fertilizer for family
members. The report said cooperative workers and truck drivers took
that cue to use their own connections to obtain fertilizer before
it was distributed to local farmers.
   When distribution began in December, farmers reportedly broke
into the cooperative to get fertilizer and remained there for three
days until county officials persuaded them to hand it all back, the
daily said.
   The report said four farmers who led the protest will face trial.
</TEXT>
