<DOCNO> AP880311-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 1531EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Senators     03-11 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Senators,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Senators Suggest Soviets Cut Tanks, Artillery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of U.S. senators told Mikhail S. Gorbachev
on Friday that Soviet superiority in tanks and artillery scared the
West into a nuclear defense, so cutbacks in those arms should
precede strategic missile reductions.
   The senators said they sensed the Soviet leader is less worried
about President Reagan's Strategic Defense Initiative, but they
said they doubted that signaled greater tolerance of it.
   ``I think there has been a lessening of Soviet apprehension
about SDI,'' said Sen. Sam Nunn, chairman of the Senate Armed
Services Committee. ``I think they recognize that it is a long-term
project.''
   The senators met with reporters after a weeklong exchange with
high-level Soviet military and political officials.
   The Kremlin wants to link a superpower agreement on reduction of
strategic weapons to compliance with the 1972 Anti-Ballistic
Missile treaty. The treaty outlaws space-based defense systems like
that seen under SDI, popularly known as the ``Star Wars'' program.
   Nunn said the Americans pressed for ``delinkage'' of the two
issues, but they ``did not get any encouragement at all along that
line.''
   The official news agency Tass, in its account of the meeting,
said Gorbachev reiterated the Kremlin's ``allegiance to its
position on a direct linkage'' of missiles cuts with ABM compliance.
   ``Violating it destroys the entire machinery of the agreement,''
Tass quoted Gorbachev as saying. ``We shall never be able to bridle
the rabid charger of the arms race if it is let loose in outer
space.''
   Gorbachev and Reagan signed an agreement eliminating all
medium-range nuclear weapons at their Washington summit in December.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., said he assured Gorbachev that the
treaty was likely to be ratified this spring ``with no crippling
amendments'' and that the concern of the Congress and
administration had turned to the issue of how to cut strategic, or
long-range nuclear arms.
   U.S. and Soviet negotiators are at work in Geneva on a proposed
treaty to eliminate 50 percent of the superpowers' long-range, or
intercontintal nuclear missiles.
   Both sides have said they would like the treaty ready for
signing in late May or early June when Reagan visits Moscow, but
the senators expressed doubt it would be ready in time.
   Nunn said the Kremlin should first cut its overwhelming
superiority in conventional weaponry such as tanks and artillery.
   ``There is a great correlation between our first-use reliance on
nuclear weapons and their massive conventional forces,'' Nunn said.
   He said he explained to Gorbachev during the group's meeting,
which lasted more than three hours, that a Soviet rollback of tanks
and artillery from Eastern Europe would go far in reducing the
fears of America's European allies about a Soviet military threat.
   The North Atlantic Treaty Organization nations, which will lose
their medium-range missiles under the agreement signed in December,
have balked at further nuclear cuts without prior reductions in
Soviet conventional arms.
   ``We would like to see the Soviet Union save some money so it
can devote it to their economic development,'' Nunn said he told
Gorbachev.
   The Senate group, which also included Sens. William Cohen,
R-Maine, Alan Simpson, R-Wyo., and Carl Levin, D-Mich., also met in
the past week with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze,
Communist Party foreign affairs secretary Anatoly F. Dobrynin and
Army Chief of Staff Sergei F. Akhromeyev.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
