<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     03-11 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0666</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dissident Reports Tanks, Soldiers in City Hit By Ethnic Riots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet dissident said Friday he saw scores of
tanks and soldiers, police and militia keeping order in a
frightened southern city where ethnic rioting killed at least 32
people.
   Andrei Shelkov, who works on the independent political
publication Glasnost, said residents of Sumgait were still
``hysterical'' about the rioting that broke out there two weeks ago.
   Shelkov told a news conference in Moscow that he was in Sumgait,
in the republic of Azerbaijan, for about five hours on Wednesday.
He returned to Moscow the following day.
   Shelkov said that on one street, ``there was a solid line of
light tanks. I counted 47 of them.''Nearby were about 40 civilian
buses full of soldiers, he said.
   Streets were full of soldiers, police and civilian militia. A
curfew was in effect, but businesses and schools were operating,
Shelkov said. He said he talked to Azeris, as the natives of
Azerbaijan are called, and Russians in Sumgait but did not meet any
of the estimated 18,000 Armenians who lived in the industrial city
of 160,000 people.
   Tensions between Armenians and Azeris, whose republics are next
to each other, erupted in violence in Sumgait on Feb. 28. The
rioting was believed sparked by Armenians demands that
Nagorno-Karabakh, an Armenian-dominated region of Azerbaijan, be
annexed to Armenia.
   An hour-long general strike had been proposed in Armenia on
Friday, but a Communist Party official in the Armenian city of
Kafan told The Associated Press it was canceled to avoid stirring
up unrest.
   Gamlet Kocharyan, a member of Armenia's party Central Committee
and of Kafan's governing body, said by telephone that tanks and
troops remained in regions where ethnic tensions had erupted, but
that ``the situation is quieting down a little.''
   ``We are waiting for the 26th,'' when a party and government
meeting on the fate of Nagorno-Karabakh is to be held, he said.
   Kocharyan said Armenians are convinced the Moscow leadership
will make ``the only just decision'' and return Nagorno-Karabakh
region to Armenia.
   Former political prisoner Sergei Grigoryants, the editor of
Glasnost, said he traveled to the Armenian capital, Yerevan, to
witness a march Tuesday by hundreds of thousands of fellow
Armenians in memory of those killed in the Sumgait rioting.
   He showed journalists photographs of streets packed with people
and said they were taken at the march.
   Some Armenians claim the death toll in Sumgait was 350 to 400,
but the government has put the official death toll at 32.
   Shelkov said he could not reach the cemeteries in Sumgait
because they are outside the city, and roads were blocked off.
   Western reporters have not been allowed to travel to the region.
   Shelkov said he was told by a nurse who worked in a maternity
hospital that Azeris broke in during the riots and threw babies out
the window, and that one woman had been disemboweled.
   A man who addressed a gathering of Armenians in Moscow on
Tuesday also said he had seen the body of a slain pregnant woman
and her mutilated unborn baby.
   Neither report was confirmed.
   The army arrived on March 2 to restore order to Sumgait, Shelkov
said.
   ``It was simply a hysterical scene,'' he said of his
conversations with residents of the city.
   The Russians and Azeris claimed that the violence was the work
of Azeris who came to Sumgait from throughout Azerbaijan.
   Grigoryants said Armenians at Tuesday's memorial march did not
blame average Azeris for the killings.
   ``Almost every Armenian family will recall how Azerbaijanis hid
them or tried to hide them,'' he said.
   But he said Armenians were angry with the Moscow media for
portraying as extremists those who demonstrated in favor of
annexation of Nagorno-Karabakh.
   Azeris are predominantly Shiite Moslems and most Armenians are
Christians.
</TEXT>
