<HEAD>Robbers Escape With $2.3 Million Of Watch Movements</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven knife-wielding men robbed a watch company
Friday and stole about $2.3 million in spare parts in the biggest
recorded robbery in Hong Kong's history, police said.
   Police said the robbers entered the watch company on the 12th
floor of a factory building and tied up five employees before
escaping with 13 cartons of watch movements.
   No one was injured in the heist which occurred in the Kwai Chung
industrial area in the New Territories. There were no arrests
reported.
   Friday's robbery broke a record set last month when a gang of
masked men snatched $1.65 million in gold and cash from a trading
company's van on its way to the airport.
</TEXT>
