<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica     03-11 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prominent Minister Receives Death Threats, House Is Stoned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A clergyman who is a leading
anti-apartheid activist said Friday he received two death threats
in the past week and that his house and office were stoned.
   The Rev. Allan Boesak, president of the World Alliance of
Reformed Churches, said he received a call Friday on his private
telephone line from a man who said: ``We are going to kill you.''
   A similar call was received Monday, Boesak said.
   Boesak said a stone was thrown through a window of his office
near Cape Town while he was at a meeting there Thursday night. His
children called 15 minutes later from the family home nearby to say
a brick had been thrown through a front window, Boesak said.
   Boesak, Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu and other church
leaders have pledged to lead opposition to the white-led
government's recent crackdown on black anti-apartheid organizations
and activists.
   In a series of tough moves starting last month, the government
banned political activity by 18 groups, imposed restrictions on
individual activists and introduced legislation to prohibit foreign
funding of political activity.
   The clergymen plan a series of protest rallies Sunday and have
indicated they may defy any attempt by authorities to stop them.
   Pro-government newspapers have assailed the church leaders'
stance and suggested that authorities should not tolerate civil
disobedience.
   Boesak, 42, is of mixed-race and is one of the co-founders of
the United Democratic Front, the nation's largest anti-apartheid
coalition. The UDF was one of the 18 organizations banned from
political activity.
   The ban was challenged in court papers filed Thursday by three
of the groups _ the Congress of South African Trade Unions, the
Detainees Parents Support Committee and the Release Mandela
Committee.
   Peter Harris, a lawyer involved in the challenge, said the
groups contend that the new restrictions ``comprise so fundamental
an inroad into the ordinary rights of citizens that they could
never have been contemplated by Parliament.''
   A Supreme Court hearing on the challenge is expected in late
April or early May.
   The country's Roman Catholic bishops held a news conference in
Johannesburg to express ``profound dismay'' at the crackdown.
</TEXT>
