<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     03-11 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The drive-in church can move, but
when the spririt moves its members, they'll have to keep their
hands off the horn.
   The city's planning commission on Thursday approved the new
location for the drive-in church on the condition that its mobile
worshipers abandon a tradition of honking their horns when they are
compelled to make a joyful noise.
   For 18 years, Sunday services have been held at the Woodland
Drive-in theater. But the drive-in is being torn down, causing the
Fifth Reformed Church to hunt for a new locale.
   City officials said the threat of increased Sunday traffic and
the possibility of a particularly moving sermon causing a racket at
the new site prompted some opposition to the plan.
   So church officials said they'd tell the faithful to flash their
lights when they felt particularly illuminated during services.
Commissioners thought that idea was OK, but wrote a no-horn-honking
provision into the resolution supporting the proposal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wheels of bureaucracy sometimes
grind slowly, but the passage of a 199-year-old resolution that has
``more mold on it than 6-month-old bread'' may be setting a record.
   The West Virginia Legislature has approved the legislation, 197
years after the mother state endorsed it. The 1789 federal
constitutional amendment allows Congress to approve a pay raise for
itself, but the raise would not be effective until the following
congressional session.
   The amendment was approved by eight states before it dropped by
the wayside in the 1790s, said the sponsor, Del. David McKinley.
Virginia, which divided to form West Virginia in 1863, approved it
197 years ago.
   But Congress neglected to put an expiration date into the
proposal and it has hung around ever since, McKinley said.
   The House of Delegates approved it last month and the Senate
followed suit on Thursday, endorsing it on a 34-0 vote.
   Del. Jim Humphreys balked at the proposal. ``It's got more mold
on it than 6-month-old bread,'' he said. ``I just don't think it's
serious. It's a waste of our time is what it is.''
   But McKinley defended the resolution. ``It's a classy little
piece,'' he said. He added of the nearly 200-year-old proposal,
``It's a sleeper.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT NEWS, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The news around Newport News isn't good
for those who are tired of having their hometown mistaken for a
newspaper.
   Lawmakers in the southeastern Virginia city have rejected a
proposal that would drop the cryptic ``News,'' making the city's
name simply Newport.
   ``Based on historical facts and information, it would serve no
good purpose to change the name of Newport News to Newport,'' the
city's Historical Commission said Thursday.
   The suggestion for the name change came from Councilman Joseph
C. Ritchie, who said he was tired of going on business trips and
saying he was from Newport News, which invariably brought the
response, ``How do you like working for a newspaper?''
   The committee discovered that around the turn of the century,
the city tried to persuade officials of Newport, Va., near
Blacksburg, to change their hamlet's name. Then Newport News could
become the Newport.
   But the original Newportians resisted, taking their case to
court, where, as the current names suggest, they won.
   In its research, the commission also established that the
``Newport'' in the city's name came from explorer Capt. Christopher
Newport, but where the ``News'' came from is anybody's guess.
</TEXT>
