<HEAD>Premier Goria Resigns; Third Time In Seven Months</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with Cossiga asking Goria to remain as caretaker
premier and ADDS details. ADDS byline. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Giovanni Goria resigned Friday as the leader
of Italy's 47th postwar government, saying there was no reason to
delay the fall of the shaky coalition for talks to smooth the
transition of power.
   It was the third time the Christian Democrat quit since taking
office in August, but President Francesco Cossiga rejected his
earlier resignations and persuaded him to stay on.
   Goria handed in his latest resignation to Cossiga on Friday
night. Cossiga asked him to stay on as a caretaker premier until a
new government can be formed.
   Goria, who at 44 was Italy's youngest premier, resigned for the
first time in November in a dispute with the tiny Liberal Party.
   He quit again Feb. 10 after defectors in his own party caused
him to lose a series of secret votes on the budget. However,
Cossiga talked him into returning to office to help pass the
national budget before the April 30 deadline.
   The lower house of Parliament gave final approval Thursday night
to a budget that includes a deficit of 122 trillion lire, or $98.8
billion. The spending plan was very different from the original
proposed by the coalition, which forecast a deficit of $83.3
billion.
   With the budget passed, Goria's days were numbered as the head
of the coalition of Christian Democrats, Socialists, Republicans,
Social Democrats and Liberals.
   Throughout Goria's seven months in office, political infighting
and defections in secret votes made it difficult for him to govern.
   Goria was expected to resign next week with the start of
consultations among leaders of the various political parties about
his successor.
   But Goria said he decided to step down immediately because it
was clear that the ``intentions of some parties was not to reach an
understanding that had the interest of the country'' at heart.
   He did not specify any political party, but Cabinet ministers
from various parties said Goria quit because of Socialist Party
opposition to the government's plan to resume construction at a
nuclear power plant.
   The government announced a moratorium on the construction of the
plant after voters in a referendum expressed their opposition to
nuclear power.
   The government's decision Wednesday to go ahead with the project
angered the Socialist Party leaders.
   At the time of his resignation in February, analysts suggested
some Christian Democrats wanted to undermine Goria and make party
secretary Ciriaco De Mita the premier.
</TEXT>
