<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 1637EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Fugitive-Police     03-11 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fugitive-Police,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fugitive Lived With Police Officer, Wooed Daughter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man convicted in the slaying of a drug
dealer later fell in love with a police officer's daughter and
lived with her family for several months before his secret was
revealed.
   Ross Basurto, 24, was sentenced Thursday to 10 years to life in
prison for his role in the November 1985 killing of Mark B.
Borgerson, 25. Basurto admitted in January that he was present when
Borgerson was killed.
   Officer Jose R. Lopez and his daughter, Rachel, testified for
leniency on behalf of Basurto at sentencing, before Multnomah
County Circuit Judge Richard L. Unis.
   Lopez, a 20-year police veteran, told the judge Basurto, using
the name Jay Adams, came to live with his family in July 1986.
Basurto, who met Rachel after the killing, was her boyfriend before
he moved in with the family.
   ``He told me that he had just moved up from California,'' Lopez
said. ``He lived with us four or five months.''
   As a police technician, Lopez had collected evidence at the
scene of the Borgerson killing. But Lopez said he never suspected
Basurto of wrongdoing.
   Basurto, he said, had a good record as an employee of a gas
station and later a towing company.
   Testimony indicated that Rachel Lopez, who is nine months
pregnant with Basurto's child, learned her boyfriend's real name
and read police reports on the killing while working that summer at
the Police Bureau's records department. She said she hopes to marry
Basurto.
   She never revealed what she had discovered to her father, who
learned Basurto's real identity only after his arrest last October.
Basurto was recognized by an individual who had read an item about
the crime in a newspaper.
   Between the time he moved in with the Lopez family and his
arrest, Basurto also lived in Yuma, Ariz., and Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
   Basurto is the third and last defendant convicted in the killing.
   Basurto admitted carrying a gun and being present when a
co-defendant shot Borgerson after the two had gone to the victim's
apartment to steal drugs.
   Defense lawyer Gary Carlson said Basurto was a peaceful,
industrious person ``who got swept away'' by an unfortunate
friendship.
   But prosecutor John Foote characterized Basurto as a man of many
sides who had shown his best side to his family and friends.
</TEXT>
