<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 1642EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ContinentalTrial     03-11 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Continental Trial,0574</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Govt Weaves a Tale of Greed as Continental Trial Opens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former bank executives were portrayed Friday
as greedy men hungry for wealth as prosecutors began presenting
their case in a fraud trial linked to the near-demise of
Continental Illinois Bank and Trust Co.
   U.S. District Court jurors, who may sit through six weeks of
testimony, listened to detailed descriptions of alleged fraud that
involved millions of dollars and stretched from the oil fields of
Oklahoma to Continental's offices in Chicago.
   The government has accused former Continental Vice President
John Lytle of buying high-risk loans from now-defunct Penn Square
Bank in Oklahoma City in exchange for nearly $600,000 in kickbacks
between 1980 and 1982.
   Defendant William Patterson, former head of energy lending at
Penn Square, gave the kickbacks to Lytle in the form of unsecured
loans, the government contends.
   A third defendant, Tulsa oil driller Jere Sturgis, is accused of
making payments to Lytle in hopes of getting future loans from
Continental.
   The three men have pleaded innocent.
   ``Ladies and gentlemen, you're going to hear evidence that will
prove that John Lytle was not serving the interests of his
employer,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney Mark L. Rotert said.
   He contended Lytle ``was completely financially dependent on
Bill Patterson.''
   Lytle's lifestyle, Rotert said, involved the kind of
``consumption of goods that is associated in this country with the
wealthy, the well-off.''
   ``He was adding rooms to his home in Northbrook. He took
vacations _ not one-week vacations, not two-week vacations, but
month-long vacations,'' Rotert said.
   Lytle, who worked at Continental from 1959 until his dismissal
in 1982, bought furs and rare automobiles, took trips to the French
West Indies and stayed in a luxurious condominium in Vail, Colo.,
where he liked to ski, the prosecutor said.
   ``He had a hot tub there with a retractable roof. He could sit
back and see the craggy peaks of the Rocky Mountains,'' Rotert said.
   Patterson, meanwhile, was the third-largest shareholder in the
First Penn Corp., parent company of Penn Square Bank, the
prosecutor said.
   ``The success of Penn Square Bank was his future, his career,
his livelihood,'' Rotert said.
   Patterson is accused of paying Lytle to ensure Continental's
involvement in loans with Penn Square.
   Continental would be the principle lender in most cases, but
Penn Square benefited from finder's fees worth thousands of
dollars, Rotert said.
   Continental and Penn Square became lending partners on millions
of dollars in loans, largely because of the relationship between
Lytle and Patterson, the prosecutor said.
   Lytle's job as the head of Continental's gas and oil lending
operation in Oklahoma did not involve routine loan approvals, but
he constantly overruled loan officers who opposed risky deals with
Penn Square.
   ``Mr. Lytle did what Mr. Patterson wanted him to do,'' Rotert
said.
   Lytle, 52, and Patterson, 37, are charged with misapplication of
bank funds and wire fraud.
   Sturgis, 40, charged with wire fraud, is acccused of joining the
alleged scheme by helping Lytle cover the unsecured loans from
Patterson after Continental discovered Lytle's personal dealings.
   Penn Square collapsed in July 1982 under the weight of energy
loans it could not collect. In 1984, Continental survived the
largest run on deposits in banking history, with the help of a $4.5
billion government bailout.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
