<2ND_LINE>AM-Football Fugitive,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fugitive Claimed He Was Football Player, Police Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who apparently was living in the
attic of a Marshall University dormitory and told students he was
the football team's new quarterback was arrested as a fugitive,
police said Friday.
   Perzell Dinkins, 22, was taken into custody Thursday on a
fugitive from justice charge, said campus Security Capt. Gene
Crawford. Dinkins was being held Friday pending $500 bond,
officials said.
   Dinkins faces felony charges in Lawrence County, Ohio, for
allegedly receiving stolen property, Crawford said. He also has
outstanding arrest warrants in Ashland, Ky., and Jackson, Miss.,
but the charges in those cities were not immediately known, he
added.
   Campus security searched the attic of Hodges Hall after
residents reported a man living there, Marshall's student
newspaper, The Parthenon, reported Friday.
   ``He had some clothing there _ he left it there and would come
in frequently to take a shower and change clothes,'' Crawford said.
   The Parthenon reported that Dinkins told residents of Hodges
Hall he was the new quarterback for the football team. The mens'
dormitory houses most of the school's male athletes and residents
had seen Dinkins there for several days, the paper said.
   Crawford said Dinkins didn't tell police he was on the football
team, ``but he did say he was trying to get a football
scholarship.''
   Dinkins said he had been living in the Huntington area since
January but denied living in the dormitory, police said.
</TEXT>
