<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 1701EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DardenExecution     03-11 0610</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Darden Execution,0627</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witnesses Say Darden Couldn't Have Killed Furniture Store Owner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANA SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Baptist minister and a secretary
insisted Friday that a convicted killer who has escaped Florida's
electric chair six times is innocent and should not be executed
next week.
   The Rev. Sam Sparks and Christine Bass also said they were
disappointed that Gov. Bob Martinez refused to meet with them
Friday to hear evidence they hoped would clear Willie Jasper Darden.
   ``I think a lot of people in Florida are wondering why he won't
sit down for even 15 minutes with Ms. Bass and me. That seems
reasonable,'' said Sparks.
   Meanwhile, Darden's attorneys filed a last-ditch appeal on his
behalf Friday in the Florida Supreme Court. No immediate ruling was
issued.
   The governor said he was satisfied the courts had reviewed
Darden's case thoroughly.
   ``There is nothing that would change my mind. ... The evidence
was clear, the rulings were proper by the courts,'' Martinez said.
   Sparks and Ms. Bass appeared at a news conference called by
Amnesty International, which has tried to focus international
pressure on the governor, who signed a seventh death for Darden
this week, one day after the U.S. Supreme Court turned down an
appeal.
   Soviet dissident Andrei Sakharov, American actress Margot Kidder
and British rock star Peter Gabriel are among those opposing his
electrocution.
   Amnesty International delivered to the governor's office
petitions bearing the signatures of 10,000 people in the
Netherlands who opposed Florida's system of capital punishment. The
group also urged its supporters to call or cable the governor's
office Friday.
   ``It is a violation of human rights,'' said Magdaleno
Rose-Avila, head of the group's campaign to abolish the death
penalty.
   Darden, 54, has survived more death warrants and has been on
Florida's death row longer than any other inmate except one. His
case has become a focal point for capital punishment opponents who
say his trial was tainted by racial prejudice. Darden is black, and
the man he was convicted of killing was white.
   Sparks and Ms. Bass have issued affidavits about the events of
Sept. 8, 1973, that conflict with the versions of the killing
related by the victim's wife and prosecutors.
   Darden was convicted of killing Lakeland furniture store owner
James Turman during a robbery that netted $15. A store employee
also was shot three times and crippled, and Turman's wife had to
fend off a sexual attack.
   Sparks said Turman's wife had told him all blacks looked alike
to her and that her identification of Darden was unimportant
because the lawyers had told her that Darden committed the crime.
   Helen Baum, formerly Helen Turman, recently denied having made
that statement to Sparks and reaffirmed her identification of
Darden as the one who shot her husband. Mrs. Baum said it was her
sister who made the statement Sparks quoted, but Sparks insisted
that it was Mrs. Baum.
   Ms. Bass, a Lakeland secretary, said Darden had an accident near
her house and that he waited for a tow truck until 5:35 p.m. Her
house was eight miles from Turman's store and prosecutor say the
crime occurred at about 6 p.m.
   ``Willie Darden is innocent, and I know it,'' Ms. Bass said.
   Ms. Bass said she tried to meet with Darden's attorney to tell
him what she knew, but was rebuffed.
   Sparks said he did not come forward sooner because he had been
told by Mrs. Baum about a month after her husband's death that
Darden confessed to the crime. Sparks said he didn't know otherwise
until he started talking to Ms. Bass and they compared notes on the
crime.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
