<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MissingDoctor     03-11 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Missing Doctor,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Father Told Missing Son Still Alive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A doctor who taped a suicide note to
the wheel of his van at Niagara Falls and disappeared after he was
charged with attempted murder of his estranged wife has telephoned
his father.
   ``He has contacted me and I told the FBI and the court and so
forth,'' Howard Johe, a Charleston architect, said Friday of his
son, Dr. David Johe. ``I don't know what will happen now. I think
the less said, the better.''
   Johe said his son got in touch with him in the past few weeks.
   Until that call, the family had believed that David Johe, 35,
had committed suicide in July.
   In June, authorities arrested Johe and accused him of breaking
into the Bradford, Pa., home of his estranged wife, Blair Plott
Johe, and trying to strangle her.
   Several days after his release on bond, police in Niagara Falls
found Johe's van parked in a motel parking lot. A note taped to the
steering wheel read: ``Goodbye. I hope the water's not too cold. I
guess I'll never know. David.''
   Both the elder Johe and his daughter, Sara Johe, said a note
left in David Johe's home and articles sent to the family convinced
them he had planned to kill himself.
   A body was never recovered.
   Bradford Township, Pa., Police Chief David Doyle has maintained
that he didn't believe the doctor was dead.
   Johe, an orthopedic physician, specialized in reattaching
severed limbs, fingers and toes.
</TEXT>
