<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PowerLine-Wyeth     03-11 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Power Line-Wyeth,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Power Line Planned Through Farm Made Famous By Wyeth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHADDS FORD, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 50 conservationists and residents
of this scenic Philadelphia suburb gathered Friday to protest a
planned power line through a farm made famous by artist Andrew
Wyeth.
   Wyeth, who is from Chadds Ford, used the Kuerner farm for more
than 1,000 studies and at least five paintings over 45 years.
   ``He spent as much time here as I did farming. He painted while
we worked,'' said Karl Kuerner Jr., 61, who raises cattle and grows
hay on the 35-acre farm.
   Philadelphia Electric Co. plans to place wooden utility poles on
a 250-foot stretch of the farm as part of a 11-mile power line
between a Concord substation and Kennett Square, said Bill Jones, a
spokesman for the company.
   Growth in the area southwest of Philadelphia near the Delaware
state line makes the new line necessary before peak demand in the
summer, he said.
   ``The existing lines in the area were overloaded almost daily
when the temperature got over 90 last summer,'' Jones said, adding
that there were several brief blackouts because of the demand.
   Philadelphia Electric serves 1.4 electric customers in
southeastern Pennsylvania and northern Maryland.
   A power line already traverses the Kuerner farm, with three
100-foot metal towers standing on a meadow near a shingled barn.
The new line would come within 35 feet of the barn, Kuerner said.
   Demonstrators holding signs outside the entrance to the Kuerner
farm said an alternate route along a nearby highway would have less
of an impact on the environment.
   ``Route 1 has already got poles and everything. It's not going
to affect the aesthetics,'' said Harry G. Haskell Jr., a former
mayor of Wilmington who grew up with Wyeth in Chadds Ford.
   Wyeth was ill with the flu and could not attend the
demonstration, said John Sheppard, a spokesman for the Brandywine
River Museum, where many of Wyeth's paintings are displayed.
   J.L. Peters, a division manager for Philadelphia Electric, said
the route over the Kuerner's farm had the least impact.
   ``We are cognizant of the natural beauty of the Chadds Ford area
and we have spent considerable time and effort looking at all the
possible routes through the area so as to minimize the impact on
the aesthetics,'' Peters said.
   ``We are convinced the route we have selected achieves that,''
he said.
   Wyeth's paintings using Kuerner's farm include ``Snow
Flurries,'' which is on display at the National Gallery in
Washington; ``Evening at Kuerners''; ``Trodden Weed''; ``Pine
Baron''; and ``Young Bull.''
   ``He has a special feeling for the land,'' Haskell said.
   Kuerner said Wyeth still paints at the farm.
   ``He comes quite often, mostly snow scenes,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880311-0189 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 2015EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DevelopmentBank     03-11 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Development Bank,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Increased Loans Predicted For Latin America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Outgoing President Antonio Ortiz Mena of the
Inter-American Development Bank predicted on Friday that its loans
to Latin America will increase from last year's $2.361 billion to
between $2.5 billion and $3 billion in 1988.
   ``We can continue on this level until the end of the century,''
Ortiz Mena told a news conference.
   The bank, owned by 44 governments, is a major source of loans to
raise the living standards of Latin American countries, most of
which have seen declines in recent years from their already low
levels.
   After 17 years with the bank, Ortiz Mena is returning to his
native Mexico. He will be succeeded by Enrique Iglesias of Uruguay.
   Ortiz Mena blamed the drop in the bank's lending in part on the
drop in the value of the U.S. dollar, which he said cost the bank
$1.2 billion last year and will cost it another $2 billion in 1988.
   The bank is deep in a dispute with the U.S. government, its
biggest shareholder, which is seeking more control over its lending.
   Ortiz Mena denied that he had blocked a U.S. effort to place a
new man as the bank's executive vice president _ James W. Conrow,
deputy assistant secretary of the Treasury for developing nations.
He said the report was a ``fabrication.''
   Ortiz Mena will not be going to a meeting of the bank's board of
governors to be held in Caracas, Venezuela, on March 21. He said
there would be discussion there of additional resources for the
bank from Japan. He would not give a figure.
   He added that there would also be discussion of increasing
Japan's voting strength in the fund, now 1.08 percent of the total.
The United States, the largest contributor, controls 34.5 percent
of the votes.
   Ortiz Mena said the major challenge for the inter-American bank
is to help reverse the present situation in which capital is
flowing out of Latin America instead of into it. The outflow, much
of it interest on old debts, is estimated at $15.7 billion for 1987.
   ``Latin American countries can not fulfill theur debt
commitments unless there is economic growth,'' Ortiz Mena said.
``To achieve growth, it needs investment. There can be no
investment if it is exporting capital. It needs to import capital.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
