<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Hart-Chronology     03-11 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hart-Chronology,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Hart Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of Gary Hart's 1988 campaign for the
presidency:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1987</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   APRIL 13 _ Hart declares candidacy, promising voters ``a
presidency you can be proud of.''
   APRIL 24 _ Hart aides confirm Federal Election Commission is
questioning legal status of $421,000 debt still owed at end of 1986
from Hart's 1984 campaign.
   MAY 3 _ Miami Herald reports young woman, later identified as
part-time model Donna Rice, spent much of weekend with Hart. Hart
denies she stayed at his Washington apartment. Des Moines Register
says poll of Democrats in Iowa shows Hart with 65 percent support.
   MAY 6 _ Hart's wife, Lee, says she believes her husband when he
says nothing happened between him and Rice. Poll of New Hampshire
Democrats shows Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis leading Hart, 27
to 17 percent. A week earlier, same poll showed pair tied at 32
percent.
   MAY 8 _ Hart withdraws from presidential race.
   SEPT. 8 _ He says in television interview, ``I am not running
for president. I'm out.''
   DEC. 15 _ He re-enters Democratic race, filing for New Hampshire
primary. ``Let the people decide,'' he says. He immediately jumps
to top of Democratic field in national and Iowa polls.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1988</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   JANUARY _ Hart's campaign suffers another blow when reports
surface that Hollywood producer Stuart Karl improperly bankrolled
campaign. Hart later acknowledges several contributions were
illegal and returns money.
   FEB. 8 _ He wins only 1 percent of vote in Iowa caucuses.
   FEB. 16 _ He wins 4 percent of vote in New Hampshire primary.
   MARCH 8 _ He finishes with 3 percent of vote overall on Super
Tuesday.
   MARCH 9 _ Federal Election Commission announces Hart has not
received enough support to be eligible for matching federal
campaign funds.
   MARCH 11 _ Hart withdraws from race for second time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
