<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CoedWheaton     03-11 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Coed Wheaton,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angry Over Coeducation, Wheaton Alumnae Plan to Fight in Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine Wheaton College graduates go to court Monday
in an attempt to prevent the school from using funds raised by
alumnae for new coeducational purposes.
   The group claims to represent hundreds of alumnae around the
country upset by the school's plan to admit men this fall for the
first time in its 154-year history.
   At issue is $10.7 million raised by alumnae from 1983 to 1985 in
a telephone fund drive marking Wheaton's 150th anniversary, says
alumna Mary Anne Marsh.
   ``The theme of the drive was preparing women for the 21st
century,'' said Marsh. ``We had been given no idea they planned to
make the school coed.''
   Alumnae first received letters informing them of the plan to go
coeducational in January 1987, Marsh said. But she added, ``It's
very clear that this plan was conceived before the first phone was
picked up.''
   The trustees of this college of 1,200 students 30 miles south of
Boston endorsed the move last May. At that time, President Alice
Emerson said the change was not being made for financial reasons
but because of a nationwide decline in high school graduates and
studies showing a waning interest in single-sex colleges.
   Nancy McCann, another of the nine alumnae, expressed anger about
the plan.
   ``It's important to keep women's colleges alive,'' she said.
``There should be options. Women's colleges afford women the chance
to take a real leadership role while they are trying out their
wings before they go into the real world.''
   Wheaton spokeswoman Lisa Byrnes said the school would ``seek
judicial approval to use these funds for coeducational purposes''
at Monday's hearing in Bristol County Probate Court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
