<DOCNO> AP880311-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 2023EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Biaggi-Wedtech     03-11 0794</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Biaggi-Wedtech,0818</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Says Biaggi and Co-defendants Plundered Wedtech</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Mario Biaggi and six co-defendants
were greedy thieves who plundered a now-defunct Bronx defense
contractor for millions of dollars, the government charged Friday
as the Wedtech Corp. racketeering trial unfolded.
   ``This is a case about corruption and greed and the purchase and
sale of public offices. It is a case about public officials who
want to get paid twice, once by the people who elected them to do
their job, again by someone else,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney Howard
Wilson told the jury in U.S. District Court in Manhattan.
   ``This case involves the story of the rise of a little company
in the Bronx'' that began in 1965 as a machine shop and grew by
1978 to $1.5 million in sales by taking advantage of laws that
promoted the growth of minority-owned enterprises, Wilson said.
   ``Seven years later, this company had grown like Topsy'' to a
defense contractor with 1,000 employees and $117 million in
revenues, becoming ``the biggest single employer in the Bronx,'' he
said.
   ``The success was achieved through corruption and lies.''
   This case is part of a scandal that also led to the indictment
of former White House aide Lyn Nofziger and two former associates
of Attorney General Edwin Meese III.
   Nofziger was convicted last month of lobbying former White House
associates within one year after he left the government on matters
including a federal contract for Wedtech.
   Defendants in the Manhattan trial are Biaggi, 70: former Bronx
Borough President Stanley Simon, 57; Bernard G. Ehrlich, 59, of
Bedford, Biaggi's former law partner and a former major general in
the New York National Guard; Biaggi's son Richard, 38, of Fort Lee,
N.J.; Peter Neglia, 39, of Armonk, the former regional
administrator of the Small Business Administration; John Mariotta,
57, Scarsdale, former Wedtech chairman; and Ronald Betso, 39, of
Brooklyn, a former cop and friend of Neglia's.
   ``They all treated this company like a gold mine,'' said Wilson.
``Some took a lot. Some took a little. But they all took.''
   They engaged in the scheme by saying that Mariotta, who is
Hispanic, was the majority owner of Wedtech, and thus the company
was entitled to a federal program that allowed companies to get
government business without bidding, the government says.
   The minority member of the company must own more than 51 percent
of the firm. But in fact, Wilson charged, Mariotta owned less than
half.
   Biaggi at one point demanded 5 percent of Wedtech's revenues,
but that was too much for Wedtech officials, Wilson said, who then
gave him 5 percent of Wedtech stock that was put in his son's name.
   At another point, Biaggi asked for $50,000 for expediting a
lease before the city's Board of Estimate, the prosecutor said, and
the law firm his son worked for received the money the day after
the lease was signed.
   In addition, the law firm earned $1 million in retainers' fees
from Wedtech from 1978 to 1985, Wilson said.
   Simon, who was borough president from 1979 to 1987, demanded and
received over $50,000 that came in cash in envelopes, meals, chips
for gambling in Atlantic City casinos, pink marble in his home, a
trip to Rome and contributions in his name to charities, Wilson
said.
   He also got a job for his brother-in-law at Wedtech and took
half his raises over the years, Wilson said.
   Neglia as regional SBA head and then as acting chief of staff in
Washington was Wedtech's ``paid-for friend,'' Wilson said.
   Among other things, Wilson contended, Neglia warned the company
about a congressional inquiry, provided Navy specifications for
bidding on a pontoon contract Wedtech wanted and helped Wedtech
obtain contracts of increasing value.
   Neglia was paid with stock options, frequent meals,
contributions to the Republican Party in his name and the promise
of a job once he left office, Wilson said. Less than a month after
leaving the government in early 1986, he went to work for the law
firm Biaggi and Ehrlich.
   Mariotta embezzled about $1 million and sold Wedtech stock worth
between $6 million and $8 million, Wilson charges. Ehrlich was
``Mario Biaggi's partner in the plunder of Wedtech. When he got it,
he split it,'' Wilson charged.
   Richard Biaggi became a lawyer in 1982 and ``became the front
man in this case,'' Wilson said, sometimes taking money or stock in
his father's name. Betso was a smaller player who took stock
options in his name for his friend Neglia, Wilson alleged.
   Wilson said he would present testimony from Wedtech accountants,
supervisors, workers, Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, and four former
officials who have pleaded guilty to crimes involving Wedtech.
   Defense attorneys begin presenting their arguments Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880311-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 2027EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Hermit'sFarewell     03-11 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hermit's Farewell,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Funeral Held For ``Hermit Of Chestnut Hill''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In life, Bill Britt's refusal to budge from
his makeshift hut in the woods earned him the image of cantankerous
eccentric. But friends and family on Friday mourned the 52-year-old
hermit as a free spirit who loved nature.
   ``My father never really was a hermit,'' said his tearful
daughter, Ingrid Boughner, 28. ``He was a naturalist. ... He was
the most colorful and articulate human being. He loved me for being
me and he gave me the courage to be myself.''
   ``Bill Britt was a truly rare human being. There are not enough
accolades to describe him. He had a zest for life, a passion for
freedom, independence and the beauty of the woods,'' said Bill
Baird, the abortion activist who befriended Britt 20 years ago.
   Britt's daughter and son, Britton Steven Boughner, 30, as well
as his mother, Marion, 86, two brothers and many other relatives
gathered with his friends for the memorial service at a funeral
home.
   The oak casket at the front of the room was bedecked with
flowers. Someone had also placed on it a photograph of the hermit
hugging one of his beloved trees. There was also a stuffed toy
raccoon, a memory of the man's love for wild animals, and a
hand-made card written by his son and daughter.
   The family planned to cremate the body. Baird said he would
scatter the ashes Saturday at Britt's favorite tree despite
objections that a license is needed.
   Britt was once a married man with a house, three children and a
job in an office. It all crumbled when he divorced in 1969.
   Britt cast off his three-piece suits and his three-piece name,
Britton William Boughner. He began to spend time in the woods at
the state-owned Chestnut Hill reservoir, near the affluent suburb
of the same name where he was born and raised. They called him the
``Hermit of Chestnut Hill.''
   But he was hardly a recluse.
   Britt was shrewd and stubborn, given to tears when he didn't get
his way. He resembled a tall child as he rode the trolleys and
hunted for pay phones to call reporters, clad in cast-off clothing
and dragging a clattering armful of plastic buckets that served as
his portable office.
   Bear-shaped and nearly toothless, Britt had blind eyes swollen
with infection. He refused welfare and lived on the nickels he got
for empty bottles and cans.
   Two years ago, Britt became the subject of legal efforts to pry
him from the patch of state land.
   Britt fought back by cultivating the image of misunderstood
hermit who wanted only to be left alone among the trees. It landed
him a spot on ``Late Night with David Letterman.'' Actor Mickey
Rooney suggested making a TV movie about Britt's life.
   A sympathetic judge respected Britt's wish for a suburban Eden
and ordered the state to find a suitable alternative site.
   Britt refused them all.
   Last July, he was finally forced from state land and moved to
the adjacent Boston cemetry.
   Officials said Britt froze to death about two weeks before his
body was found Monday at the Chestnut Hill cemetery. His remains
were found by his daughter and son, inside the lean-to where he
lived.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
