<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Afghanistan     03-11 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Afghanistan,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Department Questions Legitimacy Of Kabul Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Friday questioned the
right of the Soviet Union to provide arms to the government in
Afghanistan, denouncing the regime in Kabul as ``a faction in the
Afghan civil strife.''
   In a strong statement, department spokesman Charles E. Redman
said U.S. aid to the Afghan rebels who have waged a civil war for
more than eight years would not be halted until the Soviets stopped
their assistance to the Kabul government.
   ``There will be no cutoff of support for the resistance under
any other circumstances,'' Redman said.
   On Thursday, Nikolai Kozyrev, the Soviet foreign ministry's
adviser on Afghan affairs, declared that Moscow would not stop
arming the Kabul government as part of an agreement for an Afghan
cease-fire.
   The official accused Pakistan and the United States of holding
up a peace agreement that would end the war and allow the Soviets
to withdraw an estimated 120,000 troops from the country.
   It was not immediately clear what impact the U.S. and Soviet
disagreement on aiding the rival groups would have on negotiations
the United Nations is holding in Geneva between Pakistan and
Afghanistan.
   Soviet General Secretary Mikhail S. Gorbachev had offered to
begin a troop withdrawal on May 15 if an agreement was concluded by
next Tuesday.
   The Geneva draft agreement calls for ``noninterference'' in
Afghanistan.
   Redman said it was ``only logical'' that the provision apply to
the Soviet Union as well as the United States.
   ``The Soviets cannot claim a right to aid a faction in the
Afghan civil strife just because that particular faction tries to
call itself the government of Afghanistan,'' the spokesman said.
   ``The war in Afghanistan, in fact, is on this central issue,
concerning the very legitimacy of the Kabul regime,'' he said.
   Even with Soviet support, Redman said, ``the present Kabul
regime has been barely able to secure the capital and a few other
cities.''
   The U.S. official did not mention the U.S. weapons, including
Stinger anti-aircraft missiles, that Washington has sent the rebels
through Pakistan.
   The Stingers have downed Soviet and Afghan aircraft and
helicopters and forced pilots to fly higher, reducing the
effectiveness of air power against the guerrillas.
</TEXT>
