<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Economy-Glance     03-11 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economy-Glance,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retail Sales Up in February, Wholesale Prices Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are developments in the economic picture
Friday:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>RETAIL SALES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Retail sales edged up 0.6 percent in February, but sales in
January were much weaker than previously believed.
   Instead of a 0.5 percent rise, sales actually fell 0.2 percent
during January, showing the consumer sector is weaker than
previously believed.
   Auto sales in February increased 1.6 percent following a 2
percent advance in January. February sales accounted for almost
one-fourth of total retail spending during the month.
   Without the strength in auto sales bolstered by new incentive
programs, total retail sales would have risen a smaller 0.3 percent.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WHOLESALE PRICES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Wholesale prices fell 0.2 percent in February, pushed down by
drops in both food and energy costs.
   For the first two months of the year, the Labor Department said
prices have been rising at an annual rate of 1.1 percent, half the
2.2 percent increase in 1987. Analysts expect inflation to remain
moderate for the rest of the year.
   Food prices declined 1.1 percent in February while energy prices
dropped 0.8 percent. The cost of lettuce, which had skyrocketed
through the late fall and early winter, fell a dramatic 70 percent.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>U.S. STOCK MARKET</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The Dow Jones average, down more than 20 points at midafternoon,
closed with a gain of 8.95 at 2,034.98. For the week the average
lost 22.88 points.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DOLLAR</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell against other major currencies in quiet
European trading. In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 127.80 Japanese
yen, down from Thursday's close of 128.20 yen. Later in London, it
fell to 127.80 yen.
   The British pound continued to climb against the dollar, trading
at $1.8535 up from $1.8435 late Thursday. The pound has leaped by 4
percent in value against the dollar this week.
   Dealers said trading was light and without direction both in
typical pre-weekend fashion and because traders were waiting for
the January U.S. trade report to be issued next Thursday.
</TEXT>
