<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Dancer'sMom     03-11 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dancer's Mom,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Father of Dead Teen Dancer Waives Rights To TV Movie About
Daughter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The father of a teen-age nude
dancer who killed herself said he signed away his rights to the
story ``to clear my conscience for being a failure,'' a newspaper
reported Friday.
   Robert Mancini said he signed the waiver for South Florida
promoter Ron Sachs, who is negotiating with Warner Brothers on a
made-for-television movie about Tina Mancini. The 17-year-old
killed herself two years ago.
   Last October, Theresa Jackson, Tina's mother, was convicted on
three felony child abuse charges by jurors who agreed she had
coerced her daughter into working in nude-dance bars.
   Mrs. Jackson is free on bail while she appeals the convictions
and one-year jail sentence. She has been prevented from profiting
from her daughter's suicide under the state's so-called ``Son of
Sam'' law, in which a felon can be denied some or all of the money
or ``any other thing of value accruing ... for an accounting of
that convicted felon's crime.''
   Mancini, 47, who said he and Mrs. Jackson divorced while she was
pregnant with Tina, their second child, said he waived his rights
``to clear my conscience for being a failure ... for failing to
reach Tina.''
   He said in an interview from his home near Los Angeles that he
didn't see his daughter until she was 14 when she visited him for a
few months.
   ``I tried to give her a normal life for a while _ Disneyland and
hiking in the mountains,'' Mancini said. ``I always wish I'd have
been smart enough to keep her here. It would be nice if we could
save some other kids.''
   Sachs told the Fort Lauderdale News and Sun-Sentinel that Warner
Brothers made an offer to make a television movie based on a
proposal he presented and would co-produce. He can now depict
Mancini in the movie about Tina.
   Mancini said he will receive no money for the waiver.
   ``We're pretty much in accord on the story,'' said Sachs, who
owns the story rights of Tina's grandfather, Charles Gouveia. ``I
am almost certainly going to make a deal with Warner Brothers.''
</TEXT>
