<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SocialSecurity     03-11 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Social Security,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survey Finds Concern Over Staff Cuts, Poor Morale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixty-three percent of Social Security
managers said in an internal survey that they were uncomfortable
with deep staff cuts and most said staff morale was poor, a union
reported Friday.
   Kenneth T. Blaylock, president of the American Federation of
Government Employees, released what he called a bootleg copy of the
survey and said, ``Dorcas Hardy got more than she bargained for in
this survey.''
   He said it backs up union complaints to Congress about the
Reagan administration's cuts in Social Security's staff. The
agency, which had nearly 80,000 workers in 1984, is now down to
69,345, with 6,000 more jobs slated for elimination by 1990.
   Phil Gambino, a spokesman for the Social Security
Administration, confirmed that Commissioner Dorcas Hardy ordered
the survey of her managers last August ``and it showed there is
quite a bit of concern and anxiety.''
   ``We're aware there are a lot of anxieties and we're going to
act on that,'' said Gambino. Hardy plans to start meeting in April
with managers in each of Social Security's 10 regions to discuss
their concerns.
   At the same time, Gambino said, ``the performance of our
employees is excellent and client satisfaction has never been
higher.'' A recent check by the General Accounting Office indicated
that most people are pleased with the service they get from Social
Security.
   According to AFGE, the survey was distributed to all 9,000
Social Security supervisors grades 14 or below, and more than 4,700
responded.
   Asked if they were comfortable with the way the agency was
managing staff cuts, 67.2 percent said they were not, 14.2 percent
said they were comfortable and 18.5 percent were undecided.
   Asked to judge employee morale, 53.5 percent said it was poor or
extremely poor. Fifty-five percent said they would not recommend
Social Security to friends as a good place to work.
   The union said some of the responses to the survey corroborated
AFGE's charges that Social Security encourages ``cheating'' to meet
productivity deadlines.
   It quoted one anonymous supervisor as writing on the
questionnaire: ``Everything looks great on paper, but the reality
is SSA is going to pot.''
   AFGE represents 60,000 Social Security workers.
   Blaylock said the survey was ``a strong testimonial for an
independent Social Security Administration run by competent career
federal employees instead of political appointees who know little
or nothing of what SSA is all about.''
</TEXT>
