<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson     03-11 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Stumps South Carolina Ahead of Caucuses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson campaigned across his native
state on the eve of its Democratic presidential caucus, stressing
that his candidacy stands for blacks and whites.
   Jackson emphasized issues he said blacks and whites alike
believe in: raising the minimum wage, cleaning toxic waste dumps,
reducing the flow of drugs into the country, subsidizing day care
and saving the family farm.
   ``It's not so much black versus white as it is barracudas eating
us small fish. They don't eat fish by color. They eat fish by size.
   ``What makes South Carolina one today? We meet not in
confrontation. We meet at the plant gate ... we meet at the toxic
waste dump ... we meet on the corner where drugs are being
distributed and killing the people.''
   The candidate said a new challenge for the new South is to
``find common ground where the people can come together.''
   The South Carolina Education Association conference at a
Columbia motel was at a standstill as teachers waited in the halls
and entrances for more than an hour to see Jackson. The cooks and
maids stopped working to join the greeting line when the Greenville
native arrived.
   When he arrived, they screamed, cried, reached out to shake his
hand or just tried to touch him.
   ``I'm delighted to be home again,'' Jackson said as he stood on
a chair in an impromptu speech.
   ``You taught me,'' said the candidate who was educated through
high school in Greenville. ``You can have somebody in the White
House that you taught. Send me...''
   Jackson told crowds Friday that half of the states have held
primaries or caucuses and he has finished first or second in all
but a few of them.
   South Carolina and Louisiana were the only states Jackson won in
1984. Most political experts and campaign officials concede that
Jackson should win the lion's share of 44 delegates at stake
Saturday.
   A survey of Democratic chairmen and vice chairmen indicated
Jackson is the front-runner, with Gore a distant second.
   Twenty-five said Jackson was likely to win their counties, five
indicated they thought Gore would win their counties, two said Rep.
Richard Gephardt might win and none predicted Dukakis or Sen. Paul
Simon would win their counties.
</TEXT>
