<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Trade     03-11 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Trade,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Renews Threat To Veto Trade Legislation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Friday renewed his threat
to veto trade legislation under consideration by a House-Senate
conference committee if it is ``anti-consumer, anti-jobs and
anti-growth.''
   Speaking to representatives of a trade coalition gathered in the
auditorium of the Old Executive Office Building, Reagan said, ``I
would note that on Tuesday, those who had predicted that
protectionism would be embraced in the South were proven wrong.''
   Reagan was referring to election returns on Super Tuesday in
which Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., a proponent of tough trade
sanctions against other nations, managed to win only one of 20
states, his homestate of Missouri.
   ``Too many backers of the trade bill talk about making America
more competitive but support provisions that would bench some of
the best competitors on our team,'' the president said. ``They talk
about saving jobs, but they want provisions that have the potential
to destroy thousands if not millions of American jobs.''
   Reagan said that any trade bill passed by Congress should not
violate accords the United States has signed in the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
   He also said the provisions of any such legislation should not
``provoke retaliation against our bombing export business,''
bringing a roar of laughter from the audience. Reagan quickly
corrected himself, saying, ``wait a minute _ our booming export
business.''
</TEXT>
