<1ST_LINE>u p AM-AlaskaDemocrats     03-11 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Alaska Democrats,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson First, Dukakis a Close Second in Alaska Preference Poll</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN FOSDICK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alaska Democrats gave Jesse Jackson a
narrow victory over Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis in a
precinct caucus preference poll, announced Friday.
   But it was the large bloc of uncommitted delegates that
generated the most interest among the presidential campaigners.
   With about 90 percent of Alaska's 442 precincts reporting,
Jackson claimed 872 delegates, or 34.9 percent of the total, to
Dukakis' 769 delegates, or 31 percent. A close third were the 768
delegates, or 30.8 percent, who remained uncommitted.
   The winners will attend 27 district caucuses on April 9-10,
selecting 390 delegates to attend the state convention in Fairbanks
on May 13-15.
   The 12 delegates emerging from the state convention will attend
the Democratic National Convention in Atlanta in July and will be
bound to a specific candidate at least for the first ballot. In
Atlanta the state also will have five ``super delegates,'' the
governor and four members of the Democratic National Committee.
   Commenting on the results of the preference poll, conducted
among delegates selected at the precinct caucuses Thursday night,
Bob Speed, executive director of the Alaska Democratic Party, said,
``That huge uncommitted figure represents a lot of people who want
to support a Democratic candidate but who haven't made up their
minds.''
   He added, ``The strong showing by the Jackson and Dukakis people
shows the level of their campaigns. It was the lack of organization
by the other candidates rather than apathy on the part of the
delegates that made them go uncommitted.''
   Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. finished far back with 47
delegates or about 2 percent, followed by Illinois Sen. Paul Simon
with 18 delegates, and Missouri Congressman Dick Gephardt, who had
16 delegates, less than 1 percent each.
   Russ Meekins, state chairman of the Dukakis campaign, said
organizers will be trying to sway the uncommitted delegates before
next month's district caucuses.
   As of now, counting the Gore, Simon and Gephardt supporters as
uncommitted for purposes of selecting national delegates, the
breakdown is five for Jackson, three for Dukakis and four
uncommitted.
   Henry Lancaster, statewide coordinator for the Jackson campaign,
said with blacks comprising just 3 percent of Alaska's population,
his candidate's appeal was based on the anti-drug and economic
issues he's been voicing around the nation.
   ``This state has a lot of working-class people who've come from
the South, the Midwest and the Northwest,'' Lancaster said. ``In
down times, people are looking for solutions. And this is a down
time.''
   That reference was to the collapse of Alaska's oil-fired
economy. About 85 percent of the state's budget is supported by oil
revenues, and world oil prices are less than half what they were
three years ago.
   The Democrats chose 2,496 delegates in caucuses around the state
Thursday night. The caucuses were open to any registered Democrat
and anyone who wished to register at the door.
</TEXT>
