<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MiamiPolice     03-11 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Miami Police,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Principal Miami Police Corruption Witness Gets 10 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former officer who was the principal witness in a
series of Miami police corruption trials was sentenced Friday to 10
years in prison for his part in a cocaine ripoff ring.
   Rodolfo Arias, 32, had pleaded guilty to tax fraud and
conspiracy to possess cocaine with intent to distribute.
   ``His testimony has opened many cans of worms,'' U.S. District
Judge Kenneth Ryskamp said of Arias, who helped convict three
officers of drug-related corruption in the so-called Miami River
Cops trials in recent months.
   The case was named after the officers' most highly publicized
theft, a 1985 raid on a smuggling boat on the Miami River in which
three drug guards drowned after jumping into the water. The
officers stole millions of dollars in cocaine for resale.
   Arias' cooperation was also instrumental in obtaining a dozen
guilty pleas before the trials, as well as the suspension or
investigation of nearly 100 Miami officers whose names surfaced
during the investigation.
   ``When this plea agreement was signed, we never realized what
that cooperation will be. There will be more indictments yet to
come,'' said special federal prosecutor Russell Killinger.
   Arias could have received up to 20 years, but Ryskamp honored
the government's recommendation for a 10-year maximum.
   Arias will receive credit for time spent in the federal witness
protection program and could be free in five years, said his
attorney, Eugene Sauls.
   ``This court has ambivalent feelings about this case,'' said the
judge, acknowledging Arias' cooperation but adding that the former
officer's crimes ``cry out for retribution.''
   Another officer who cooperated with prosecutors received a
15-year sentence Friday. Carlos Pedrera, 27, had pleaded guilty to
the same counts.
   Arias and Pedrera were among a large group of officers the
Police Department was forced to hire quickly after the Mariel
boatlift and Liberty City riots in the early 1980s.
   Many of the officers worked the midnight shift, and Arias
testified that his increasingly corrupt group turned Miami's
streets into its private crime kingdom.
   The officers routinely took small quantities of drugs and cash
from suspects they detained, then expanded into stealing drugs
directly from dealers.

</TEXT>
