<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dole 2ndLd-Writethru a0721 03-11 0756</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dole, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0721,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede MOLINE, Ill.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dole Staying in Race, ``Hanging by Our Fingernails''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 12 grafs with Dole TV show, some other ads
running, picking up in 9th graf pvs, Throughout the</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Sen. Bob Dole, scrambling to salvage
his presidential campaign, challenged GOP front-runner George Bush
on Friday to show up for a live 30-minute television show Dole has
purchased for Saturday night.
   Earlier Friday, as he campaigned around Illinois, Dole vowed to
stay in the race at least through the state's primary on Tuesday,
though he said he would reassess his chances after that.
   Dole, who pulled most of his TV ads off the air in Illinois
earlier this week, said he had bought television time on a Chicago
station and would broadcast live from a small college in Galesburg,
Ill.
   He challenged Vice President Bush to join him there for a debate
at Knox College, which was the site of one of the famous
Lincoln-Douglas debates.
   Bush has declined Dole's repeated challenges to a one-on-one
debate. But Dole said, ``In any event, I'll be there to discuss the
issues. I dare George Bush to have a debate with Bob Dole.''
   Bush is tentatively scheduled to be in Galesburg Saturday night
to attend a GOP dinner.
   Earlier in the day, Dole had joked with reporters that he might
have a cardboard cutout of Bush on the stage if the vice president
wouldn't show up in person.
   ``We're hanging by our fingernails,'' Dole said at an airport
news conference in Moline. ``We need to somehow capture the
attention of the Illinois voters.''
   Dole, campaigning across central and western Illinois, denied
reports that he and his aides had discussed the possibility of
pulling out of the race. But he conceded there had been some
discussion of another less drastic option.
   ``There was some talk about maybe just canceling a couple of
days' events to heighten whatever we're going to do later,'' Dole
said at a stop in Bloomington, where he spoke to Illinois Farm
Bureau leaders.
   Dole said his deep staff cutbacks were ``just good management,''
made to save money and because most of the workers were no longer
needed after Super Tuesday.
   Campaign aides said Dole also was buying television time to air
ads on Sunday.
   Throughout the day, Dole made it clear that his task in
Illinois, if he is to overtake Bush, is to draw the vice president
out on issues and to separate him from the good will that many
Republicans feel for President Reagan.
   ``I'm sort of running against the ghost of Ronald Reagn,'' the
senator said.
   In addition, Dole said that Bush's victories on Tuesday had
given him a big boost in polls.
   ``What we need to do is slow down this Super Tuesday momentum,''
Dole said.
   One effort by Dole is to continue to press Bush to participate
in one-on-one debates even though the vice president has declined.
   ``If we could just discuss the issues in one state ... I will
win,'' Dole said. ``It's pretty hard to slow down a freight train
if you don't talk about the issues.''
   One issue on which he has pressed Bush is the vice president's
involvement in the Iran-Contra affair, a subject that was back in
the news Friday as former National Security Adviser Robert C.
McFarlane agreed to plead guilty to four misdemeanor charges that
he withheld information from Congress.
   ``It is going to revive that whole issue again and I've said
from the start that it's not going to go away. That's why it should
be addressed,'' Dole said. Bush ``is going to have all these things
happening through the summer,'' he said.
   One uncertain element in Dole's strategy is how Illinois voters
will react to the possibility that a Bush victory in their state
could effectively end the GOP nominating race. Dole maintains there
are many voters who have yet to decide which candidate they will
back.
   ``I know there are a lot of people, probably 20 percent, who are
just now beginning to focus on who the candidates are,'' said Dole.
``It's like last-minute Christmas shoppers. Some people don't even
know what they're going to buy until the last 24 hours and then
they buy whatever is left. We don't want that to happen.''
   Asked whether he would abandon the race if he loses next week,
Dole said, ``We will reassess after Illinois. I am going to be very
realistic about this.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
