<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChiefCharged     03-11 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chief Charged,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Little Rock Police Chief Pleads Innocent to Theft</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT CHARTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police Chief Jess ``Doc'' Hale was
suspended Friday after being charged with taking less than $200
from a drugstore cash register.
   Hale, 47, was released on his own recognizance after pleading
innocent to the misdemeanor charge. Trial was set for May 24. He
declined comment after the court appearance.
   Pulaski County Chief Deputy Prosecutor Lloyd King said Hale took
money over the past several weeks from Buice Drug Store, a popular
coffee stop for police officers.
   The amount was not disclosed, but the misdemeanor charge means
it was less than $200. Buice Drug Store is owned by state Rep.
George Wimberly.
   King said the prosecutor's office was tipped off by a resident
of the county, but he would not elaborate. Radio station KARN,
citing unidentified sources in the State Police, said police
secretly videotaped Hale taking money.
   City Manager Tom Dalton announced Hale's suspension with pay.
   ``When I have sufficient information to determine whether the
chief has violated the rules,'' Dalton said, ``I will at that time
make my decision as to whether or not to institute formal
disciplinary action against the chief.''
   Hale earns $64,070 a year and also collects a pension of $18,766
from the Police Department, from which he retired as an assistant
chief in 1982 after a 20-year career.
   He rejoined the force as chief 17 months ago after running the
Medicaid Fraud Division of the state attorney general's office.
</TEXT>
