<2ND_LINE>AM-Simon,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simon Insists He Has ``As Good A Chance As Anyone''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Paul Simon, insisting he has ``as good a
chance as anyone'' to become the Democratic presidential nominee,
campaigned Friday for home-state support in next Tuesday's Illinois
primary.
   Simon sought the votes of educators and college students in his
bid to beat Illinois rival Jesse Jackson, his chief challenger in
the state primary according to a new poll.
   ``We want to send a message to the nation from Illinois,'' Simon
said in asking educators to help him win the primary. ``Part of
that message is that for people who need quality education, this
administration has been out to lunch,'' he added.
   Next, it was off to Northwestern University in Evanston where he
drew applause from a crowd of about 1,000 students when he called
for increasing grants and government loans to college students.
   Saying again that he figures it will take more than one ballot
for the party to settle on a White House nominee at the Democratic
National Convention in Atlanta in July, Simon said at a North Side
pancake restaurant: ``I think I have as good a chance as anyone.''
   A Washington Post-ABC News poll published Friday said Simon and
Jackson were in a virtual dead heat in Illinois at 38 percent and
33 percent, respectively, among 402 likely Democratic voters, while
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis was third at 16 percent. The
difference between Simon and Jackson was within the poll's margin
of error of plus or minus 8 percentage points.
   After being endorsed by the Polish Daily Zgoda, a Polish
language newspaper, Simon campaigned on friendly turf at the
Illinois Education Association's representative assembly meeting.
   Simon, who serves on the Senate Labor and Human Resources
Committee's subcommittee on education, arts and humanities, noted
that the educators' union had supported him in his successful 1984
bid to oust Republican Sen. Charles Percy against long odds.
   ``Four years ago when I was running for the U.S. Senate, there
was not a single poll that showed Paul Simon winning. But the IEA
hung in there and didn't listen to the polls and, believe it or
not, there was one final poll on a Tuesday that showed Paul Simon
winning,'' he said as the crowd applauded and cheered.
   He told the 750 union delegates and alternates what they wanted
to hear. If elected president, he said, he would seek to raise
teachers' salaries, improve preschool education programs and
increase public school funding. He also called for a ``massive
assault'' on illiteracy.
   ``I am the only candidate running for president who, either in
state legislative service or in congressional service, has ever
requested to be on the education committee,'' Simon said.
   ``I mention that to show you I'm not just giving you another
speech. I'm giving you a commitment to education that's been there
for my whole lifetime,'' Simon said.
</TEXT>
