<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Austria 1stLd-Writethru a0690 03-11 0723</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Austria, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0690,0739</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Austria Marks Anschluss Anniversary Amid Anti-Waldheim Protests</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto VIE3</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 13 grafs, including more Vranitzky quotes; picks
u
14th `Six of'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was 50 years Friday that the Nazis
annexed this country. Austrians honored the dead and demonstrated
against President Kurt Waldheim, who was made a silent spectator by
his questionable wartime past.
   Conservative and Socialist politicans emphasized that some
Austrians committed atrocities in the Nazi era, challenging the
long-held view that the nation was a victim of the Nazis. Huge
crowds cheered Adolf Hitler's troops when they marched into his
homeland March 11, 1938.
   A minute of silence drew little response Friday on the streets
of Vienna and few people turned out in the early morning to watch
political leaders lay wreaths at monuments to fallen soldiers and
victims of the Nazis.
   Shops, businesses and schools were open.
   About 300 protesters gathered outside the presidential offices
in the imperial Hofburg Palace, demanding that Waldheim resign, and
dozens vowed to hold a three-day vigil. Waldheim has said he will
not leave office until his term expires in 1992.
   At a memorial ceremony in the Hofburg, Foreign Minister Alois
Mock praised Waldheim as having given Austria ``prestige in the
world'' in his decade as U.N. secretary-general, which ended in
1982.
   Mock heads the conservative People's Party, which backed
Waldheim for president in 1986. He was the only official to mention
him directly at Friday's ceremonies marking the annexation, or
Anschluss.
   Waldheim was forced to cancel a speech at the ceremony because
of unresolved questions about whether he committed war crimes while
serving as a German army lieutanant in the Balkans in 1942-45. Some
prominent Austrians had said they would not attend if he spoke.
   Franz Vranitzky, the Socialist chancellor, told a special
Cabinet session Austrians must ``recognize the fact of historical
guilt (and) draw lessons from the past failures of society.''
   He dismissed the idea that Austria was just a victim of the
Nazis.
   Many Austrians unwillingly donned German uniforms, he said, but
others ``did not see a shameful coercion in this, but a simple test
of strength in which _ for the most varied reasons _ they fulfilled
their assigned duties.''
   Addressing about 900 students later, he urged young Austrians
not to ``make blanket accusations against an older generation or to
reproach them ... after the fact with moral mistakes, blindness,
bias and a lack of will to defend themselves.''
   He said one of the terrible aspects of Nazism was that it arose
in countries that regarded themselves as cradles of culture and
guarantors of Western traditions.
   Six of the seven parliamentary deputies of the small Greens
party walked out as soon as Waldheim entered a special session of
Parliament. The Greens invited Austrians to join them in marking
the anniversary at the site of a former concentration camp.
   In a leaflet, they said they boycotted the parliamentary
ceremony because Waldheim was there.
   ``On this particular day, the presence ... of a guest who `like
hundreds of thousands of others only did his duty,' is not
representative of the Austria we want to remember,'' the leaflet
said.
   The flier was referring to Waldheim's repeated declarations that
he was only doing his duty during the war.
   Waldheim kept his war past a secret until March 1986, when it
surfaced during his presidential campaign. A panel of historians
concluded last month that Waldheim was in close proximity to Nazi
war crimes but did nothing to prevent them.
   The report left open the question of Waldheim's guilt or
innocence in atrocities, and Waldheim has always denied wrongdoing,
but he has come under increased pressure to resign.
   Dozens of anti-Waldheim protesters chanted ``We do not accept
Waldheim, Resistance is our duty!'' as survivors of Nazi
concentration camps and resistance fighters met on the square where
the feared Gestapo had its Vienna headquarters.
   Speaking in front of a monument to the victims of Nazism, the
Socialist minister of social affairs, Alfred Dallinger, stressed
that ``not only those who can be clearly identified as perpetrators
were guilty.''
   ``Guilt was also shared by the many who allowed what was carried
out by others: those who ran along, who concurred, who adapted
themselves or looked away,'' he said, to loud applause.
</TEXT>
