<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BatteringRam     03-11 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Battering Ram,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>L.A. Police Ram `Rock' Houses; Seize Drugs and Suspected Dealers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Police Department rolled out its fabled
battering ram after a two-year absence to break into two fortified
houses where crack allegedly was being sold.
   Civil-rights lawyers who in 1986 forced police to garage the ram
expressed satisfaction with the way the use of the armored vehicle
was authorized under new guidelines but promised to keep a close
watch on future deployments.
   In a Thursday night raid, police used the vehicle with a 14-foot
metal pole to smash into a house in south central Los Angeles.
Officers arrested five suspected drug dealers and seized drugs,
weapons and hundreds of dollars in cash.
   Police also raided four other houses without the ram in the same
operation and took more than 25 people taken into custody.
   On Wednesday night, police seized about $10,000 worth of cocaine
and about $500 in marijuana after ramming into another south
central house where rock cocaine, a crystalline form of the drug
also called crack, allegedly was being sold.
   ``It was the most heavily fortified rock house we've seen in a
couple of years,'' said police spokesman Cmdr. William Booth. The
house was reinforced with gun turrets, metal bars and steel mesh,
he said.
   Police Chief Daryl Gates, who arrived after the Thursday night
raid, pointed out the security measures used by the suspected drug
dealers.
   ``See how the bolts come all the way through?'' Gates said,
pointing to a steel-barred window. ``There's no way you can pull
those bars off. You need a ram.''
   Police said they had not used the ram in drug raids since
February 1986. They wheeled it out in October when an armed man
barricaded himself in a house, but did not use it.
   Joan Howarth, an attorney for the American Civil Liberties Union
who had challenged the Police Department's use of the ram and
forced its suspension, said she was satisfied with the way it was
used.
   ``The judge told the LAPD it could not use the ram until they
did a surveillance of the locale to make sure there were no
children present,'' she said.
   Ms. Howarth had represented a woman whose house was the first
target of the ram, in 1985. The ram burst into a room only moments
after the woman's 5-year-old son and two other children left it.
   As a result of that case, the state Supreme Court ruled that
police must get a judge's certification and a search warrant before
using the ram, a ruling the U.S. Supreme Court upheld in October.
   Booth said obtaining judicial approval for use of the ram this
week was not difficult.
   ``We just don't run up and use it. Part of our tactics is to
make a purchase just minutes before entering,'' which enables
undercover officers to look inside the house, he said.
   The ram has become a featured part of TV shows and films. In
last summer's ``Dragnet'' movie, it was used to raid a suspected
drug factory that turned out to be a dairy processing plant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
