<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-PLO, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0803,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief Protests U.S. Plan to Close PLO Office</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-PLO Shut</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-10 UPDATE with PLO comment, other detail. Picks
up 7th graf pvs, The letter ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Nations issued a strong protest
at the U.S. decision Friday to go ahead with closing the Palestine
Liberation Organization's observer mission.
   The PLO called it a ``stab in the back'' to the Middle East
peace process.
   U.S. Ambassador Herbert Okun informed Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar of the Justice Department decision Friday morning,
said U.N. spokesman Francois Giuliani.
   He said Perez de Cuellar ``strongly protested this violation of
the headquarters agreement,'' the 1947 treaty under which New York
became home to the United Nations.
   The U.S. State Department also has said closing the PLO mission
would violate the pact, and even America's closest allies have
denounced the closure. Giuliani said Perez de Cuellar's legal staff
is studying several options. He refused to elaborate, but one
possibility would be a legal challenge when the Justice Department
seeks a court order closing the mission.
   Zehdi Labib Terzi, the PLO's United Nations observer, said the
PLO would not challenge the Justice Department move in court.
   ``We will not go into American court. We will have nothing to do
with American courts,'' he told reporters after meeting with U.N.
legal advisers. ``This is a matter between the United States and
the United Nations.''
   He said the PLO would ask Arab nations to request a meeting of
the General Assembly to consider whether U.N. headquarters should
remain in New York.
   Calling the U.S. decision a ``stab in the back'' to Mideast
peace efforts, Terzi asked, ``How could the United States really
look like a peace broker when they want to throw out the
representative of the Palestinian people, which is the principle
party to the conflict?''
   The letter Okun handed Perez de Cuellar said the Justice
Department will initiate legal action to close the mission around
March 21. It said the United States will not try to shut the
offices until the litigation ends.
   The mission is located in a four-story townhouse the PLO owns on
Manhattan's fashionable Upper East Side.
   The United Nations released copies of Okun's letter at a
briefing.
   The United States has refused binding arbitration of the
dispute, its worst with United Nations.
   At a special meeting last week, the 159-nation General Assembly
asked the World Court in The Hague to rule on whether the United
States must agree to arbitration. Arguments before the court are
set for April 11.
   Congress passed an anti-terrorism law in December ordering the
mission closed by March 21.
   U.N. officials and many diplomats regard the threat to the PLO
mission as a challenge to the independence of the United Nations.
   ``It's a very serious development,'' said Norwegian Ambassador
Tom Eric Vraalsen. ``It goes beyond the PLO because it violates the
headquarters agreement.''
   Several Arab diplomats have suggested moving the General
Assembly to Geneva if the mission is shuttered. Other diplomats say
Western nations probably would block such a step.
   Last year, the State Department closed down the only other PLO
office in the United States, a Washington information office, in an
attempt to head off legislation to close the U.N. mission.
   The United States and Israel consider the PLO a terrorist
organization. The United Nations recognizes it as the only
legitimate representative for Palestinians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
