<2ND_LINE>AM-Gore,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Says Momentum Will Carry Him To The Presidency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Albert Gore Jr., calling himself the
candidate with campaign momentum that will eventually carry him to
the presidency, said Friday he expects to do extremely well in
South Carolina's Democratic caucuses Saturday.
   The Tennessee senator, campaigning in the state's largest cities
on caucus eve, told a crowd of a few hundred supporters at the
Statehouse that his strong Super Tuesday showing, when he won six
of the 21 Democratic events, surprised everyone.
   ``I believe that momentum is going to continue right through the
convention in Atlanta and right through November,'' he said. ``I'm
excited about the possibility of victory.''
   Gore is expected to finish a strong second to Jesse Jackson in
the South Carolina caucuses.
   Asked what state in the North he could win to prove he is not
just a Southern regional favorite, Gore refused to be specific,
saying only that he figured he would do well in Illinois and
Michigan.
   Gore said he has been in South Carolina more than any of the
other candidates and his campaign has bought the most television
ads in the days before the caucus sessions.
   ``We have worked very hard in this state and I think we have an
opportunity to extremely well here,'' Gore said.
   Gore noted that he supported legislation to restrict the growth
of textile imports. Such imports have caused plant closings and job
losses in the state's largest industry.
   Current textile trade agreements are being ``brazenly
violated,'' Gore said, adding that as president he would be sure
that agreements are enforced.
   In the upstate Friday, Gore spoke to textile employees in Lyman
where he said the Reagan administration is aiding the wealthy in
the hope that others will eventually benefit.
   ``Rather than asking what's best for those who are already well
off, I want to ask what is best for the man and the woman who work
in the textile mills, who work in the apparel industry, the person
who is behind the typewriter, the small businessperson, the small
farmer, and the person at the grass roots,'' he said.
