<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chile-Election     03-11 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile-Election,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pinochet Rejects Opposition Demand to Allow Open Presidential
Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Augusto Pinochet on Friday
rejected an opposition demand to allow more than one candidate to
run for president, saying it would create ``chaos and anarchy.''
   Pinochet, the army commander who has ruled Chile since a 1973
coup, vowed to carry out the government's plan for a single
candidate in a yes-or-no plebiscite sometime this year.
   Pinochet made the remarks in an address to the nation to mark
the seventh anniversary of the military-drafted constitution, which
the opposition wants amended.
   In a pre-dawn attack before Pinochet's speech, leftist
guerrillas fired submachine guns and at least two rocket grenades
at a suburban Santiago police station, wounding two officers and
three civilians, officials reported.
   They said several ``extremists'' in two cars carried out the
attack and one of the injured policemen was in serious condition.
   Officials reported three other guerrilla attacks early Friday in
the Santiago area, but no casualties.
   Another police station and a patrol car were fired at, they
said, and at least four electric-power pylons were damaged by
bombs, blacking out some neighborhoods.
   Army patrols in combat gear were deployed in this capital city
of 4.5 million people before Pinochet's speech, which was broadcast
on national radio and television.
   According to the constitution, the commanders in chief of the
army, navy and air force and the head of the national police will
pick a single presidential candidate for a yes-or-no vote.
   Pinochet, 72, is allowed by the constitution to seek election
for the 1989-97 term, and appears to be seeking the nomination. He
led the coup that ousted the elected government of Marxist
President Salvador Allende in September 1973.
   No date has been set for the plebiscite, but government
officials have said it will be in the second half of this year.
   In his 35-minute speech, Pinochet made no reference to his
candidacy but said the next president ``must identify himself''
with the constitution imposed by the military.
   If the government granted the opposition demand to amend the
constitution and block the government's election plan, ``a
situation of public unrest and serious uncertanties would follow,''
he said.
   According to the constitution, if voters reject the military
candidate in the plebiscite this year, an open presidential
election must be called in 1990 with Pinochet remaining in power
until then.
   Several thousand people gathered in front of a government
building in downtown Santiago as Pinochet, in a general's uniform,
arrived to make his speech. Some said they were government
employees and had been ordered to go there.
   Police said there were scattered scuffles in Santiago between
government supporters and dissidents after Pinochet's speech.
</TEXT>
