<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 2203EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TaxSwindle     03-11 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tax Swindle,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three In $1.3 Billion Tax Scheme Sentenced</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three men convicted in a scheme to create more
than $350 million in bogus tax deductions for celebrities such as
Andy Warhol, Lorne Green and Sidney Poitier drew sentences Friday
ranging from probation to two years in prison.
   IRS officials believe the scheme was the largest tax-fraud case
in U.S. history, said Assitant U.S. Attorney Stuart Abrams said
late last year.
   The three promoters of the scheme were indicted in 1987 on
charges of creating more than $1.3 billion in fraudulent losses and
interest expenses while trading in Treasury bill futures and other
government securities.
   Those losses generated bogus tax deductions for investors such
as actor Michael Landon, former Postmaster General Preston R.
Tisch, Tisch's brother, CBS president Laurence A. Tisch, the late
Lorne Greene and TV producer Norman Lear.
   The investors are not accused of wrongdoing but will have to
square accounts with the IRS. They had expected to receive $4 in
tax deductions for every $1 invested.
   Charles Agee Atkins, 33, of Amelia Island Plantation, Fla., was
sentenced by U.S. District Judge Morris Lasker to two years in
prison, four years' probation and 500 hours a year of community
service.
   Atkins is the son of former Ashland Oil Co. chairman Orin E.
Atkins
   William Hack, 62, of New York City was sentenced to four months
in prison, four years, eight months' probation, and 1,000 hours a
year in community service. He was fined $25,000.
   Ernest Grunebaum, 52, of Chappaqua, N.Y., was placed on
probation for five years and ordered to do 400 hours of community
service a year.
   The three were convicted in December of conspiring to defraud
the Internal Revenue Service; they could have received five years
in prison on that count alone. Atkins and Hack were also convicted
of numerous tax offenses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880311-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 2203EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Punishment     03-11 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Punishment,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tass Says Soviets Debating Whether to Retain Death Penalty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet citizens are engaged in ``heated
discussions'' about whether a new criminal code now being written
should retain capital punishment, Tass said Friday.
   In a report from Riga, capital of Latvia, the official Soviet
news agency said a final decision will be made after nationwide
discussion. Defendants sentenced to death in the Soviet Union are
executed by firing squads.
   ``Heated discussions are going on over the problem of capital
punishment,'' Tass said. ``Some people insist that it should be
repealed altogether, while others insist that it should be
preserved for some special cases. The latter view predominates at
the moment.''
   The state-run media occasionally report executions of people
convicted of such crimes as treason, murder and wide-scale bribery
and corruption. The reports have not indicated how frequently the
death penalty is imposed.
   In an interview with Igor Karpets, a Latvian law professor, Tass
said the revised code will contain a new section covering
punishments for ``crimes against peace and humanity.''
   What behavior that section is intended to discourage was not
clear, but one possibility is terrorism.
   Soviet officials have referred frequently to the review of the
28-year-old criminal code, but have not said when the draft will be
completed.
</TEXT>
