<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 2203EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StrandedKids     03-11 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stranded Kids,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Busloads of Children Hole Up at Farms Amid Storm</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Storm Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-one children forced to take
refuge at two farms when a late-season blizzard waylaid their two
school buses settled in for a second night of campstove meals and
makeshift bedding Friday.
   One of the farms had no electricity.
   ``The storm hit a little faster than we thought,'' said bus
driver Sharon Grubbs, who had eight children with her when the
storm bore down Thursday afternoon, with heavy snow and winds up to
55 mph reducing visibility to zero.
   She said she and fellow driver Linda Barrett, who had 13
children on her bus, were in radio contact when they decided to
find shelter rather than continue taking children home from the
Banner County school in Harrisburg.
   Ms. Grubbs' crew landed at Jack and Karen Holt's farm about 17
miles west of Harrisburg. Holt was snowed in elsewhere.
   The storm knocked out electricity at the farm late Thursday and
things were still chilly Friday afternoon as the wind buffeted the
farmhouse, said Ms. Grubbs.
   Ms. Grubbs and Mrs. Holt used a camping stove to cook meals as
children huddled in their coats and under blankets. ``We're kind of
hurting,'' said Ms. Grubbs. ``We've tried to fix one hot thing for
every meal.''
   The three boys and five girls, ages 7 to 13, have been playing
games and listening to a battery-operated radio. They telephoned
their parents to let them know they were safe, said Ms. Grubbs, a
10-year veteran bus driver.
   ``They've been super for us,'' she said. ``They've cooperated so
well, but they ride the bus together every day.''
   Mrs. Barrett and her 13 passengers found refuge at Agnes Wynne's
farm, about 20 miles from Harrisburg.
   Mrs. Wynne, who lives alone, said she was worried the food won't
last. ``We've managed so far,'' she said. ``I guess we just take
each day as it comes.''
   Menus so far have included chili and homemade noodles, Mrs.
Barrett said. Children were sleeping wall-to-wall in the
two-bedroom farmhouse, said Mrs. Wynne.
   The children have been playing games and even doing homework,
since many had their school and library books, Mrs. Barrett said.
   ``The kids have been really good,'' she said. ``We have one
kindergartner and I don't think he's ever been away from home
before.''
   Mrs. Barrett said the youngest spoke with his parents on the
phone and seemed to be coping well.
</TEXT>
