<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslav-Soviet     03-11 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslav-Soviet,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev to Sign New Declaration with Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev is to visit
Belgrade next week and sign a new guarantee of Yugoslavia's
independence, which the late President Tito declared forcefully in
1948 by breaking with the Soviet Union.
   Senior Yugoslav officials said Friday the declaration also
appears to indicate the future course of Soviet relations with
other nations.
   Gorbachev is scheduled to arrive Monday and stay four days on
the first official visit to this nonaligned communist country by a
Soviet leader since 1976.
   The new document will update previous declarations of 1955 and
1956 and ``further confirm principles of non-interference on the
basis of equality and sovereignty,'' Ilija Djukic, the deputy
foreign minister, told reporters.
   The late Leonid I. Brezhnev was the last Kremlin leader to pay
an official visit to Yugoslavia, which broke with the Soviet bloc
over ideological issues in 1948 but maintained economic and
political links.
   Brezhnev attended Tito's funeral in May 1980. Tito had visited
Moscow in 1979.
   The declaration calls for ``non-interference of any kind in the
internal matters of the two countries,'' a senior official said on
condition of anonymity.
   He said the document also appears to represent a message about a
general change in Soviet policy under Gorbachev.
   The declaration, to be made public during the visit, is said to
call for cooperation with all nations and parties ``regardless of
ideological differences'' and ``full and principled implementation
of human rights in the whole world,'' the official said.
</TEXT>
