<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 2230EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HighwaySiege     03-11 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Highway Siege,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trucker Charged With Shooting at Wife, Holding Police at Bay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE GEISSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VACAVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A truck driver barged into his
estranged wife's home and blasted away inside with a shotgun
Friday, then jackknifed his rig on a busy freeway and held officers
at bay for five hours, police said.
   Ronald Stone, 34, put down his double-barreled shotgun and
surrendered at 7:20 a.m. after threatening to shoot anyone who
approached, police said. No serious injuries were reported.
   Stone, who had engaged police in an armed standoff a decade ago,
was taken to the Solano County Jail and booked for investigation of
attempted murder, said Police Chief Gary Tatum.
   The standoff closed Interstate 80, the east-west artery between
San Francisco and Sacramento, forcing miles of backed-up traffic
onto bypass routes.
   Stone's brother, Jim, 38, of Grass Valley, said Stone went to
his wife's house, ``thinking everything was all right again. But
she said, `Get out of here.' That's when he wigged.''
   Stone's wife, Jackie, said: ``I thought I was going to die.''
   Tatum said Stone's wife had called police at 12:46 a.m. to
report that her husband, from whom she had been separated for about
a month, was at the door and appeared drunk. By the time officers
arrived, he was gone.
   Tatum said they received a second call about half an hour later
from one of Stone's children saying Stone had returned.
   Lt. Gary Mallory said Stone kicked his way into the house where
Mrs. Stone, their three young children, and Mrs. Stone's mother
were staying. According to Mallory, Stone told the children, ``It's
time for your mother and I to die.''
   Stone's mother-in-law and the children fled as Stone went
upstairs, found Mrs. Stone, who had been hiding, and attacked her,
Mallory said.
   She escaped, but Stone fired four blasts from a 12-gauge shotgun
inside the house, then two more from the porch after she ran
outside, said Mallory.
   When police arrived, Stone threatened to kill himself, Mallory
said. Then he leaped into his tractor-trailer and drove for an hour
at speeds of up to 90 mph, with police pursuing.
   On the freeway, he jackknifed the empty truck, apparently on
purpose, Mallory said. Police closed the freeway in both
directions. Stone sat in the vehicle with ``lots of ammunition,''
said Mallory.
   Police talked with Stone, first by CB radio and then via a
military-style field telephone tossed into the cab. ``He was
distraught and felt as though his marriage was on the rocks. He no
longer wanted to live,'' said Tatum.
   Stone gave up after five hours, firing a final blast out the
truck window. He suffered minor powder burns but was otherwise
unhurt.
   In 1978 in Vacaville, Stone held off police with a gun in a
domestic dispute, Tatum said. No shots were fired and no one was
injured, according to police, who had no further details. Relatives
said he spent some time in jail as a result.
</TEXT>
