<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 2117EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-RevenueSharing     03-11 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Revenue Sharing,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Rule Revenue Sharing Funds Don't Have To Be Released</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court on Friday upheld the
Reagan administration's refusal to release $180 million in revenue
sharing funds that had been withheld two years ago under the
Gramm-Rudman deficit-reduction law.
   The ruling, by a three-judge panel of the U.S. Court of Appeals
for the District of Columbia Circuit, reverses a lower court which
had ordered Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III to release the
money.
   An attorney for three associations representing local
governments said an appeal of the latest decision was ``virtually
certain.''
   ``My sense is the court did not fully comprehend the nature of
our legal arguments. ... I think it's virtually certain we'll ask
the court to reconsider its decision,'' said David C. Vladek, a
lawyer for the National Association of Counties, the National
League of Cities, the U.S. Conference of Mayors and 10 city and
county governments.
   The dispute involves President Reagan's Feb. 1, 1986 order under
the Gramm-Rudman law that set aside 4.3 percent of budget items,
including $180 million from that year's $4.2 billion appropriation
to the revenue sharing trust fund.
   The local governments argued that the law provided that
sequestered 1986 budget money should remain in government trust
funds and be paid out in 1987. They argued that even though
Congress had abolished revenue sharing after 1986, it intended that
any money remaining in the trust fund be distributed.
   Revenue sharing, begun under the Nixon administration, provided
nearly all local governments with unrestricted federal grants.
   U.S. District Judge Joyce Hens Green, in a ruling last July 28,
found in favor of the local governments, and said Baker had
illegally transferred the revenue sharing money from the trust fund
to the general fund.
   However, Judge John R. Gibson, who wrote the appeals panel's
decision reversing Judge Green, said Congress' intent with the
Gramm-Rudman law was clearly to reduce the federal budget deficit.
   ``Merely freezing (the monies in 1986) and resuscitating them
(in 1987) would not result in any meaningful deficit reduction and
could be characterized by critics to be a sham,'' said Gibson, who
was joined by Judges Patricia M. Wald and David Santelle.
   ``The result in this case may be harsh, but we believe it is
consistent with congressional intent,'' wrote Gibson, who was
designated to the case from the U.S. Court of Appeals for the
Eighth Circuit in St. Louis.
   Among the plaintiffs are New York City, Kansas City, Mo.;
Milwaukee County, Wis., and Cuyahoga County, Ohio, which includes
Cleveland.
   The U.S. Conference of Mayors, at the time of the original
district court decision last summer, had estimated that New York
would receive $10 million; Chicago, $2.6 million; Los Angeles, $2.2
million, and Detroit $1.3 million of the money.
   Other estimates were $606,000 for New Orleans, $554,000 for
Indianapolis, $677,000 for Washington, D.C., $440,000 for Denver
and $104,000 for Des Moines. Estimates for other cities were not
provided.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
