<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Uruguay-BritishPlane     03-11 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Uruguay-British Plane,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Warplane Leaves Uruguay On Condition It Returns Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTEVIDEO, Uruguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British Air Force transport that
made an emergency landing en route to the Falkland Islands left
Thursday after Britain agreed it would return to Ascension Island,
Uruguayan officials said.
   The Hercules C-130, carrying a crew of seven and a cargo of
tires, cylinders of oxygen and munitions, left Carrasco
International Airport outside Montevideo at nearly two days after
landing here, airport authorities said.
   The plane developed an oil leak while flying from its base on
Ascension to Mount Stanley in the Falklands, British Ambassador
Eric Vines said.
   Officials said the return to Ascension was a condition set by
Uruguaya's foreign minister, Luis Barrios Tassano, the former
ambassador to Argentina.
   Argentine authorities claimed the landing was no accident but
part of the controversial military manuevers that Britain began
Monday in the Falklands.
   Argentina and Britain fought in 1982 over sovereignty of the
remote South Atlantic islands. The 74-day war, won by Britain,
killed 712 Argentines and 256 Britons.
   Argentine Foreign Minister Dante Caputo said the emergency
landing was actually a test to find out how Uruguay would react in
case of actual need during a similar wartime situation.
   Vines denied it.
</TEXT>
