<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DayHospitalized     03-11 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Day Hospitalized,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Singer Dennis Day in Critical, Unstable Condition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dennis Day, a tenor who appeared on
Jack Benny's TV and radio shows and recorded ``Danny Boy'' and
other Irish ballads, was hospitalized in critical and unstable
condition, a hospital spokesman said Friday.
   The 71-year-old singer whose trademark line was a sprightly
``Gee, Mr. Benny!'' was brought to the emergency room Wednesday
after a fall at his home, said Armen Markarian, a spokesman at
St.John's Hospital and Health Center.
   While in the emergency room, Day complained of a severe
headache. A scan showed bleeding in the brain and he was rushed
into surgery, Markarian said. ``He's been in critical condition
since then,'' the hospital spokesman added.
   In July, Day's spokesman announced that he had been diagnosed
with amyotropic lateral sclerosis, a degenerative nerve disease
also known as Lou Gehrig's disease. However, Markarian said Day's
condition did not appear to be related.
   Day was born Eugene Denis McNulty in New York City. His singing
career began in 1939 as a naive kid with a golden voice on Jack
Benny's radio show.
   He recorded such songs as ``Peg of My Heart'' and ``Clancy
Lowered the Boom,'' and appeared in several films, including ``Buck
Benny Rides Again,'' ``Music in Manhattan,'' ``One Sunday
Afternoon'' and ``The Girl Next Door.''
</TEXT>
