<NOTE>$adv16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs March 16 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>U.S.-Aided Fund Trying to Create Jobs in Northern Ireland</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With help from a U.S.-led aid
program, a rundown site dividing Roman Catholic and Protestant
areas of Belfast is being transformed into an industrial park for
fledgling businessmen.
   It is one of about 40 projects that have been promised money
from the multimillion-dollar International Fund for Ireland, the
most tangible outgrowth of the Anglo-Irish Agreement of 1985 that
aims to help reconcile feuding Catholics and Protestants in
Northern Ireland.
   The $1.6 million-Townsend Enterprise Park will create space for
45 new businesses near the towering ``peace wall'' dividing the
Protestant Shankill Road district from the Catholic Falls Road.
   Frank Murphy, the project head, said it would not have gone
forward without the fund's $440,000 contribution.
   But just as the fund is getting off the ground, its future has
been put in question following an announcement that the U.S. State
Department is dropping the fund from its 1989 allocations. Of the
fund's present kitty of $86.8 million, $85 million has come from
Washington with $35 million more due this year.
   The rationale behind the fund is that in a province with a
17-percent unemployment rate and the collapse of its traditional
heavy industries, only economic revival can eliminate slums,
joblessness and resentment.
   Another project helped by the fund aims at turning the
first-century ruin of Navan Fort in County Armagh into a tourist
site. Another has given $4,500 to Frank O'Donnell, a 24-year-old
Londonderry Catholic unemployed for two years, to open his own
business selling hand-carved fireplace mantels.
   When the fund was set up in 1986, the U.S. Congress approved
$120 million over three years to stimulate economic regeneration
and foster Catholic-Protestant reconciliation. Seventy-five percent
was earmarked for Northern Ireland and 25 percent for border
counties in the Irish republic to the south.
   Some Protestants are suspicious, since the Anglo-Irish Agreement
grants the Irish republican government in Dublin a say in their
affairs. The Rev. Ian Paisley, the Northern Irish Protestant
hardliner, called the fund ``Yankee blood money'' and urged a
boycott of its projects.
   The European Economic Community, which had been expected to make
a major donation, has held back because London and Dublin can't
agree on a joint application for funds. Canada is contributing $10
million spread over 10 years, and New Zealand has given a one-time
$300,000 payment.
   Bob Myers, U.S. consul general in Belfast, said in an interview
the United States wants more countries to contribute to the fund.
   But concern rose in Ireland in February when U.S. Deputy
Secretary of State John Whitehead said the United States ``does not
receive a real return'' on its contribution to the fund and was
dropping it from the State Department's 1989 foreign aid
allocations.
   In its present state, the fund would die without the U.S.
donation, and Irish-American congressmen, such as Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy, D-Mass., say they are confident Congress will continue to
support the International Fund.
   The fund's board has so far allocated only 20 percent of its
money, about $16 million, to some 40 projects. It says about 2,000
applications have come from both Catholics and Protestants, despite
Paisley's call for a boycott, and hopes to have distributed the
whole amount within 18 months.
   ``I would have liked to see quicker progress. ... But I'm
absolutely certain if we plunged in, spending money like drunken
sailors, it would have been disastrous,'' said Charles E.B. Brett,
the lawyer and former public official who chairs the fund's
seven-member board.
   The board gives priority to job-creation programs, tourism and
venture capital companies. One idea never tried before is the joint
marketing of Irish goods from both north and south.
   The board has also approved projects to help universities
develop marketable products and more than half a dozen programs to
launch entrepreneurs like O'Donnell in Londonderry.
   Danny Morrison, publicity director for Sinn Fein, the outlawed
Irish Republican Army's legal political wing, and the Rev. Matthew
Wallace, a Catholic priest on the Townsend Park board in Belfast,
complained that the fund was putting too little into Catholic areas
where unemployment is 2{ times higher than in Protestant areas.
   Wallace said he preferred to see American companies investing in
Northern Ireland and creating real jobs.
   ``That's more important than the money itself from the fund _
the money will do nothing,'' the priest said.
   ``I don't think we can expect violence to end unless we do
something about unemployment,'' said Franklin Adair, a banker who
heads the Youth Enterprise Scheme _ YES. The fund's first grant of
$88,500 went to YES, which is helping hundreds of people under 25
to start businesses.
   ``We must give young people something to hold on to,'' Adair
said. ``Otherwise, what do they have to lose? That's where I think
the American funds can be best used _ in positive creation of
employment. That's the way to achieve peace.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Wed PMs March 16</NOTE>
