<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Mali-LivingPoor Adv18   03-11 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mali-Living Poor, Adv 18,0673</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs March 18 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Drought and Economic Problems Keep Mali Poor</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY LARRY JAMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAMAKO, Mali (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even in the 100-degree heat of midday, the
Niger Valley echoes with the sounds of the women beating their wash
against the stones on the river bank.
   Their back-breaking day's work will earn them an average of 250
West African francs (88 cents).
   The women, their hard work and low pay epitomize the problems
facing this West African nation shackled by constant drought and
the economic difficulties that arise from it. The World Bank ranks
Mali as one of the five poorest countries in the world, with a per
capita income of $148 a year.
   The washerwomen, all from the Dogon tribe, were driven out of
their homes in the north to Bamako four years ago by the
devastating Sahelian drought. They remain excellent vegetable
farmers and the river banks behind them bloom with radishes,
tomatoes and strawberries.
   But they live in isolation, on the outskirts of this city of 1
million. They do not speak French, Mali's official language, nor do
they know Bambara, the lingua franca of the region.
   They are tolerated by their countrymen because, for the moment,
there is no other room for them and there is still residual
sympathy for the suffering they endured in the drought of 1983 and
1984. But another dry spell could quickly make them unwanted,
another burden on a country already unable to feed itself.
   Average rainfall varies from 47.2 inches in the south, to the
desert north with less than 8 inches.
   The next drought will mean the loss of more farm land and even
more people will be forced south, toward Bamako, to compete for the
scant resources.
   This huge, largely desert or semidesert country, with its 8.4
million people spread across an area larger than California and
Texas combined has never known prosperity. According to the
economic-trends report from the U.S. Embassy, it will need
continued foreign help for the forseeable future.
   ``Despite a national commitment to economic reform and
relatively good soils in the south, cereal production has fallen in
recent years,'' the report said. ``Over the past 10 years the
climate throughout Mali, particularly the great inland delta of the
Niger, has become drier. This has resulted in serious losses of
crops and cattle, declining agricultural productivity, and
increased reliance upon donations of grains from the West.''
   The report says Mali has made serious attempts at mending its
ailing economy, forcing retirements and imposing staff cutbacks in
the public sector, but 70,000 government employees remain on the
roles, three-fourths of all salaried workers in the country.
   In 1986, while under the squeeze of economic reform, the bottom
fell out. The price of cotton, the country's chief export,
plummeted. The government discontinued much of an austerity package
that formed the basis for loans from the International Monetary
Fund and World Bank, but the IMF money stoppoed coming because the
government gave up on the austerity commitment.
   Now Mali is broke.
   Teachers, on strike since mid-February for salaries three months
in arrears, have been joined by students demanding that scholarship
payments be brought up to date.
   President Moussa Traore said recently he hoped the 18-month-long
``misunderstanding'' with the IMF could be cleared up and loans
would be coming again.
   ``We have said that we favor the structural adjustment program,
but we also favor the preservation of our human dignity, and
despite our difficulties, the world economic situation, and drought
_ which we do not control _ we want people to understand us,'' he
told a news conference.
   ``Structural adjustment does not mean throwing workers into the
streets without compensation. Nor does it mean dismantling the
economy of a country or destroying the basis of an economy. We are
still expecting help from our partners.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs March 18</NOTE>
</DOC>
