<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 1155EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-CBSComedies Adv14   03-11 0875</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-CBS Comedies, Adv 14,0893</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs, March 14, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>CBS Beefing Up Schedule with Comedies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS is beefing up its schedule with four new
comedies, but from the looks of the first three, the shows
themselves will need some beefing up before they will help CBS.
   Because of its hour-drama-heavy schedule, the network wants more
half-hour sitcoms. Thus ``Eisenhower & Lutz'' premieres tonight in
two half hours, before and after ``Newhart.'' Its regular time
period will be Monday in place of ``Frank's Place,'' which moves to
Tuesday.
   ``Trial and Error'' and ``Coming of Age'' make their debuts
Tuesday. A fourth comedy, ``The Dictator,'' also was to have
premiered Tuesday, but it has been delayed by the writers' strike.
In the meantime, CBS will bring back ``My Sister Sam.''
   The most promising of the three new comedies is ``Trial and
Error.'' It falters occasionally in the premiere half hour, but
mostly lands on its feet, thanks to the comic abilities of its two
stars, Eddie Velez and Paul Rodriguez.
   Velez plays John Hernandez, a clean-cut young lawyer just hired
by a big Los Angeles law firm. His childhood friend and now
roommate, Tony Rivera (Rodriguez), is a T-shirt entrepreneur.
   Rodriguez, a stand-up comic, delivers the one-liners with
professional aplomb. He takes his buddy to a fancy restaurant to
celebrate his new job. The waiter lists the specials, including
goat cheese, $8: ``Goat cheese eight dollars?'' complains Rivera.
``I got a buddy in Alhambra who'll sell me the whole goat for
four.''
   Velez's forte is physical comedy. Acting cool in his new office
with his modular phone, he whips the receiver around on its
elasticized wire, but ends up having to hide from it when it gets
out of control.
   The show doesn't make any heavy social points, but does manage a
meaningful plotline when Hernandez faces the fact that he was hired
by the law firm because he is Hispanic. The senior partner
dismisses his protests by telling him there was a time he would
have been rejected because of it. At Rivera's urging, he decides to
take the break for what it's worth.
   ``Eisenhower & Lutz'' also shows promise with occasionally crisp
writing and a likable star, Scott Bakula, playing a Palm Springs
shyster who's practicing alone but thought Eisenhower on the firm's
name sounded prestigious.
   His secretary quits over her pay. ``Remember two months ago when
I interviewed for a job and we discussed salary and I said, yes, I
wanted one?''
   So his girlfriend (DeLane Matthews), a cocktail waitress, fills
in, typing up his resume before his meeting with a big law firm he
thinks might hire him. He notes she included his alma mater,
Southeast School of Law. ``I thought we were going to dress that up
a little,'' says he. Says she, ``I took `and acupuncture' off.''
   The series is from MTM Productions and executive producer Allan
Burns, an Emmy-winning writer formerly with ``The Mary Tyler Moore
Show.'' The lines are smart enough, but the series needs to develop
some heart.
   ``Coming of Age'' was apparently meant to be kind of a co-ed
``Golden Girls.'' It stars Paul Dooley as Dick Hale, a
wise-cracking former airline pilot from Pittsburgh reluctantly
relocated to a sunny retirement village in the Southwest with his
wife, Ginny (Phyllis Newman).
   The comedy in the premiere episode is broad and sluggish, though
Dooley can almost pull it off. ``That's 27,'' he says, gazing out
the window as his wife unpacks. ``What are you counting?'' she
asks. ``Gray heads,'' he says.
   Alan Young and Glynis Johns play neighbors Ed and Trudie Pepper,
who come over bearing a welcome pie. Turns out Ed baked the pie.
   ``So, basically, Ed,'' says Dick, ``you retired and became a
woman.''
   Even Dooley can't manage for long with material like this.
   The fourth comedy, ``The Dictator,'' features Christopher Lloyd,
best known to TV audiences as Rev. Jim on ``Taxi,'' as Joseph
Domino, supreme ruler of the South Sea island nation of Bando.
After the overthrow of his government, he is exiled to Rego Park,
Queens. The premise sounds great, but it's a bad sign if the series
has to be halted because there are too few scripts for even a
limited spring run. When the series does premiere, look forward to
seeing Bob Elliott of the comedy team Bob and Ray as guest star.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   PHIL FILLS IN _ Phil Donahue will fill in for Bryant Gumbel on
the ``Today'' show the week of April 4. Gumbel is taking off time
in preparation for his anchor duties when NBC broadcasts the
Olympics from Seoul later this summer. Gumbel will also be off the
week of April 18, and former ``Today'' host Jim Hartz will fill in
that week. ...
   NO NUKES _ ``Crime Story'' is filming a climactic, three-part
season finale in Acapulco, Mexico. The occasion for the locale is a
plotline that has Torello and his strike force chasing villain Ray
Luca and his crime empire to a small Latin American country. In
last year's season finale, Luca was caught in a nuclear blast.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, March 14</NOTE>
