<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 0800EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:JewishExhibit Adv15   03-11 0610</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Jewish Exhibit, Adv 15,0625</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tue AMs, March 15 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Most Important Private Collection of Jewish Art in Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty years after the Nazis closed the
world's first museum of Jewish art in Vienna, a private exhibit of
Jewish ritual objects has been drawing large crowds of visitors.
   Some 800 items displayed at the ``Judentum in Wien'' (``Jews in
Vienna'') exhibit housed by the Museum of the History of Vienna are
all loans from a private Judaica collection, regarded by art
historians as one the most important private collections of Jewish
life.
   According to Max Berger, owner of the collection, most of the
drawings, paintings, sculptures, medals, coins, manuscripts and
handicraft on show were in danger of being destroyed or lost after
Austria's annexation by Nazi Germany in 1938.
   Berger, a Viennese businessman who survived a Nazi concentration
camp, pieced together his collection over years and this is the
first time it has been shown in public.
   The exhibit displays mementoes of Jewish life from the early
18th century until present, focusing on Vienna as an important
center in the history of European Jewry. Museum officials said it
is the first step toward opening a permanent Jewish museum here in
the next two or three years.
   About 6,000 Jews live in Vienna today, compared with 200,000 who
helped make this city a capital of science, culture and the arts
before World War II. They included Sigmund Freud, Gustav Mahler,
Stefan Zweig, Arnold Schoenberg and hundreds of others.
   Some 65,000 Austrian Jews perished in Nazi concentration and
death camps during the war.
   The exhibit is divided into eight sections, including ritual
objects and Hebrew writings, the Jewish year and life, the history
of the Viennese Jews, Zionism, anti-semitism and persecution and
Jewish contributions to art and culture.
   ``It's the first time that the most important private Judaica
collection in Europe is displayed for the Austrian public after the
war,'' Karl-Albrecht Weinberger, a curator who helped set up the
display, said in an interview.
   By March 3, the exhibit had been visited by some 30,000 people.
   ``On Saturdays and Sundays we have up to 500 visitors a day,''
Weinberger said, adding that recently Austrian school authorities
advised schools to come and see the exhibit as part of their
history classes.
   More young Austrians gradually have been educated about the Nazi
past and the Holocaust in the two years since the first disclosures
that President Kurt Waldheim had covered up his wartime past as a
German army lieutenant in the Balkans.
   Weinberger said the exhibit was planned before Waldheim became
president.
   The most valuable objects displayed are a silver-and-gold torah
crown made in Austria in 1810 and a torah plaque made in 1806 of
gold-covered silver.
   The oldest display is a torah curtain made around 1700 of red
velvet laced with silver threads.
   Weinberger said the first Jewish Museum in the world opened in
Vienna in 1895, with a very big collection of Jewish art.
   The Nazis dismantled it in 1938. While some items were lost or
destroyed, others were taken by the Germans to Prague where they
planned to open a big anti-semitic Jewish museum. The museum never
materialized but some objects have remained in the Prague Jewish
Museum which opened after the war.
   Asked if the Austrians ever asked the Czechs to return the items
held by the Vienna Museum, Weinberger said they never did.
   ``It's difficult to prove what objects belonged to the Jewish
Vienna Museum as all catalog were destroyed during the war,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tue AMs, March 15</NOTE>
</DOC>
