<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 1335EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Byways-ArcticCity Adv20-2Takes   03-11 0761</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Byways-Arctic City, Adv 20-2 Takes,0775</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 20 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>WORLD BYWAYS: Soviet Arctic City _ Polar Bears on the Streets</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Your eyelids freeze, it's dark much of the time,
polar bears stroll the streets every so often, and a heat wave is
when the temperature goes above 40 degrees in the summer. Not many
outsiders go to the world's northernmost city, but a Moscow-based
Associated Press correspondent did and wrote this story when she
thawed out. It is one of a series of periodic AP reports on life
and culture in the byways of the world.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DICKSON, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Igor Perlovsky is a big man in Dickson.
He runs the only bar in town. He owns the only VCR.
   And for the 5,000 Soviets who inhabit the world's northernmost
city on the ice-bound Kara Sea, drinks and movies at Perlovsky's
``Coupole'' lounge are a cherished escape from the 10 months of
winter when temperatures plunge to 75 degrees below zero and the
wind freezes the moisture in the corners of people's eyes.
   Outdoor sports are out of the question on the desolate ice
desert that stretches more than 300 miles from here to the south.
Even for those hardy enough to play outdoors, it's hard to see a
soccer ball during the three-month polar night. Nor is there
swimming during the two-month ``summer,'' when the mercury climbs
to an average high of 40.
   There used to be an automobile in Dickson, which is reachable
only by air and sea, but the novelty of driving on the city's three
or four roads wore off, and the 11-year-old Moskvich subcompact has
been garaged with only 70 kilometers (44 miles) on the odometer.
   Every few weeks, a resident sights a polar bear lumbering along
the moguled ice paths that pass for streets, and telling tales of
narrow escapes from the Arctic's natural inhabitants is a popular
pasttime.
   Police sometimes are summoned to chase the bears away by firing
rifles into the air, but they are forbidden to shoot the beasts
except in life-threatening situations: polar bears are protected by
the Soviet Red Book, the endangered species list.
   At first glance, Dickson appears uninhabited. The plume from a
single smokestack atop the city's steam-generating plant provides
the first sign of life. On closer inspection, a few fur-hatted
pedestrians can be seen bobbing between the snowbanks. The silence
is broken by the roar of a jeep or the thrashing of a tracked
``vezdekhod'' _ the refitted armored personnel carriers that serve
as Dickson's police cars, ambulances and buses.
   The city, which lies 500 miles inside the Arctic Circle and
1,100 miles below the North Pole, is named for Oskar Dickson, a
Swedish brewer and financier who bankrolled the international
expedition that discovered the port in 1875. Dickson's retention of
his name through a century of political tumult in Russia is
evidence of its isolation from Moscow and the official penchant for
renaming places for Soviet heroes.
   The first settlers arrived in Dickson in 1915 to operate a radio
transmitter at the port. By World War II, a few hundred were living
here to handle shipping on the Yenisei River that flows into the
Kara just to the south.
   Today, Dickson's port is the gateway to the Northern Sea Route
that provides Europe's only direct sealink to the Pacific Ocean.
   Gennady M. Svetkov, deputy chief of the city's governing
council, said the port, which is the only major enterprise in
Dickson, generates revenues of 6 million rubles ($10 million) a
year. That figure could skyrocket if the Soviet Union reopens the
Northern Sea Route as Communist Party chief Mikhail S. Gorbachev
proposed last October. It has been closed to all but Soviet vessels
since 1964.
   In winter, supply ships, shepherded by icebreakers, make their
way into the frozen port every month or so. But in July and August
the waterfront bustles as Soviet cargo ships ply the Arctic Ocean
with goods bound for Japan, China and points south.
   Increased ship traffic and the arrival of foreign crews could
change this Arctic outpost, but Dickson's city fathers regard an
international port as a distant prospect.
   ``Such decisions are in the hands of the mainlanders,'' said
Svetkov, referring to those who live beyond the tundra.
   For now, Dickson's residents appear content to bear with the
hardships to keep the sea lanes open and gather data from eight
weather research stations drifting in the Arctic Ocean.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880311-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 1344EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Byways-ArcticCity Adv20-1stAdd   03-11 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Byways-Arctic City, Adv 20-1st Add,0584</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 20 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>DICKSON: Arctic Ocean.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``It's not so cold here,'' said 20-year-old Marina Rovenska.
``It's just boring.'' Miss Rovenska, a clerk at Dickson's shopping
center, came here with her parents from the Ukraine eight years ago.
   She and a friend, Yelena Cherevik, said young workers flock to
Perlovsky's bar several times a week for the best Dickson has in
social life.
   Perlovsky, a 36-year-old native who returned after a few years
as a seaman in Odessa on the Black Sea, where it's warm, is a
respected businessman among Dickson's youth, who are paid double
salaries for working under hardship. Perlovsky bought a German-made
video deck last year for a 10,000 rubles ($16,000) _ two years' his
salary as a state bartender _ from a friend of a friend of a
diplomat. His tapes, recorded from Finnish television or Soviet
film libraries, have been collected through a farflung network of
friends and connections. His library of about 100 titles cost him
about 100 rubles ($160) each .
   While Perlovsky is a state bartender, he is a private video
operator at the ``Coupole,'' a wood-paneled anteroom of Cafeteria
No. 1. He operates in part ``na levo'' (literally, on the left), a
Russian expression for doing things outside the law. But his video
bar exemplifies the freer hand Soviets have in remote communities
to bend the rules to make their system work.
   For 1.50 rubles ($2.50), or three times the price of a movie
ticket elsewhere in the Soviet Union, a Dickson resident can settle
down at Perlovsky's bar and watch a Soviet film classic or Western
rock video _ once everyone has agreed on the night's selection.
Liquor appears to be in greater supply here than in most areas of
the Soviet Union, again illustrating a concession from Moscow,
where Gorbachev's tough anti-drinking crusade has made alcohol both
expensive and hard to find.
   ``Some guys come in here and drink themselves into such a state
that they have to be helped home,'' said Perlovsky, who as a former
national rowing champion is equal to the task of bouncer. ``But I
wouldn't say we have an acute problem with drunkenness, at least
not like in central Russia where guys will drink up their last
kopek. Most people just want a place where they can gather.''
   Older residents cite its advantages over other areas of the
country. Crime rates are low, they say, because thieves can't flee
the city and stolen goods are hard to hide in housing that is
mostly communal.
   ``The north is like a sifter,'' observed Gennady Ilchenko, the
director of the weather station who has lived in Dickson for 37
years. ``Those who are weak or lazy or untalented fall out
quickly.''
   Schoolteacher Larissa Duvinets, a 28-year resident, says
children are taught in the city's two schools to value the northern
lifestyle and plan for futures in their parents' footsteps.
   But city officials concede that at least 20 percent of Dickson's
population turns over each year.
   ``I don't think I'll stay here after school days,'' said
13-year-old Sergei Lutsenko as he led visitors on a tour of the
city's three-room museum. ``I feel it's cut off from the outside
world.''
   He and his friends said they long for big-city life with subways
and buses _ and the simple pleasures of summer, like swimming and
going barefoot.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880311-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 1353EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-EdwinEdwardsFarewell Adv13   03-11 1190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Edwin Edwards Farewell, Adv 13,1228</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 13 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Au Revoir, Edwin Edwards _ Flamboyant Governor Leaves Office</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNCTION, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Texas Hill Country seemed an odd
backdrop to talk with a man who ruled Louisiana much like a king
when he wasn't rolling dice in Monte Carlo and Las Vegas, flirting
with beautiful women or fighting off racketeering charges.
   But Gov. Edwin Edwards is preparing to leave office Monday, and
his Texas ranch has been a hideaway used more frequently by the
governor who became the most propular official in the Bayou State
since Huey Long _ until he was undone by the collapse of oil and
questions about his honesty that wouldn't go away.
   In a recent interview at the ranch overlooking the greenish
waters of the South Llano River, Edwards spoke softly about his
political career and about leaving it all behind.
   The 1,400-acre ranch is dotted with scrub oaks stunted by the
scant rainfall, a far cry from Edwards' Louisiana estate, with its
massive moss-covered oaks and enough green grass in the yard to
more than feed the 60 head of cattle barely surviving on what they
can find here.
   Still, the Texas spread is far from the swirl of politics and
controversy that has been his life.
   Edwards' brother once said, ``He's an introvert trying to be an
extrovert.''
   ``That's accurate,'' said Edwards, gently rocking and fiddling
with the bottom button of a down jacket. ``It's almost ludicrous to
say that but I've done a good job in overcoming it. I have a basic
tendency to get away. That's why I have this ranch.''
   The ranch is not so much a place to relax for Edwards, who at
60, still doesn't know how to take it easy.
   ``If he's not hunting, he's on that tractor or using a
bushhog,'' an aide told a reporter.
   The reporter recalled a comment years ago by Edwards'
brother-in-law: ``He's not relaxed like a normal Frenchman.''
   ``Maybe that's because he's ambitious,'' said Edwards'
mother-in-law.
   Edwards sprouted from impoverished south Louisiana, the son of a
sharecropper. Education was the only escape route.
   At 21 he had finished law school, and six years later, in 1954,
he was elected to the Crowley City Council. From there he was
elected to the state Senate, to Congress and finally to the
governor's office in 1972 and again in 1976.
   He never lost an election.
   He was adored by the people because he brought ``les bons
temps'' _ good times _ by prodding the Legislature to tax oil at a
percentage of value in 1973 just before prices soared. Government
was on easy street and the economy was beautiful.
   People were tolerant, even proud, of his candor when Edwards
commented that ``gambling turns me on.'' They smiled when he
flirted openly with women.
   He left office after serving two consecutive terms, the most
allowed by law, but returned in 1984 for an unprecedented third
term, overwhelming one-term Republican Dave Treen.
   Edwards was so powerful that while the Republican served, the
populist Cajun opened an unofficial governor's office and began
collecting $13 million for a campaign that kept Treen looking over
his shoulder.
   Edwards won with nearly 63 percent of the vote despite
unfavorable publicity during his first two terms:
   _ He had acknowledged receiving $20,000 from a South Korean
whose dealings with congressmen and others led to the ``Koreagate''
investigations.
   _ He had shrugged off a book written by a former aide who
accused Edwards of selling state jobs and conquering legions of
women.
   _ He was investigated by the Internal Revenue Service after all
of the publicity about his gambling.
   _ He was investigated during the FBI ``Brilab'' probe that led
to the conviction of a top aide.
   Edwards survived it all.
   But in these last four years, the king was felled by the
collapse of oil prices, which devastated the state's economy, and
continued attacks on his honesty.
   Louisiana has one of the highest unemployment rates in the
nation and the government is nearly bankrupt.
   His answer to economic woes this term was a lottery and casino
gambling, something lawmakers would not buy. Edwards lost control
of the Legislature partly because of his two federal racketeering
trials.
   He went on trial in 1985, accused of brokering hospital permits
obtained while in and out of office. The jury was hung with all but
two voting for acquittal.
   In 1986, a second jury acquitted Edwards and all other
co-defendants, including his brother, Marion, and several friends
and aides.
   ``I was shunned by the Legislature during and between trials,''
Edwards said, planting his boots on the ground to stop the rocking
chair. ``They saw how U.S. Attorney John Volz used the federal
grand juries. They were scared. `If they can do that to you, I
don't want to be close to you.' There was an aura of fear in
Louisiana. If Volz and the other Republicans could do that to me,
what could they do to legislators? That was the feeling.''
   The polls showed that the people went along with the lottery
idea and feeling the masses were still behind him, Edwards tried
last year for a fourth term.
   As a 44-year-old congressman, he had first swept into the
governor's office on a reform platform. At age 60, he was beaten by
Buddy Roemer, a 44-year-old congressman who used a reform platform,
complaining that Edwards had given Louisiana a banana republic
image.
   ``There's always been a mania to knock the man from the top of
the mountain,'' said Edwards. ``But it took them a lot of years.
It's been a costly journey to the top.
   ``In the last four years, it's been even worse. My family has
suffered. My net worth has gone down considerably. I've paid an
awesome price, onslaughts on my integrity from unfair
investigations, indictments. But I think I've faced it
realistically and altruistically.''
   In a 1979 interview, Edwards was reminded that he said that what
he would like more than anything else ``is to convince people I'm
honest.''
   ``I guess that is more what I would like to do now than ever,
but it seems like it is something that is going to escape me,'' he
said.
   ``But I remind the people that despite all of the money spent,
all of the efforts made by people over the years, they've yet to
prove anything.''
   What's going to happen now? Can Edwards relax?
   ``For about four days,'' he said, grinning. ``I guess the phones
will continue ringing, people will still come to see me. I feel
nothing is going to happen with a new administration. If that's
true, I will be sought out. If not, I'll try to accept that.''
   In the meantime, Edwards will practice law with one of his sons
and offer himself to the nation's universities as a lecturer for
$5,000 per appearance. He'll talk about legalized gambling and his
career.
   He'll also hunt, gamble and, yes, flirt.
   ``I don't believe I've mellowed with age,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880311-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 1602EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-SelmaRevisited Adv13   03-11 1215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Selma Revisited, Adv 13,1246</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 13, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Ballot Box Brings Big Changes To Selma</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STRAT DOUTHAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SELMA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spring has come to central Alabama: the
redbuds are blooming, the fire ants are pushing up fresh mounds of
earth and Jesse Jackson is the people's choice in Dallas County,
where the infamous ``bloody Sunday'' attack at the Edmund Pettus
Bridge shocked the nation 23 years ago.
   Jackson overwhelmed the presidential primary field here Tuesday,
23 years and one day after Alabama state troopers savagely beat
black voting rights advocates attempting to march from Selma to
Montgomery. The episode, shown on national television, helped
galvanize Congress to pass the federal Voting Rights Act later that
year.
   On Tuesday, Jackson carried Alabama by a narrow margin. But he
held better than a 5-to-1 edge over his nearest Democratic
challenger in Dallas County, where blacks constitute 55 percent of
the 50,000 residents.
   The official county tally showed Jackson with 4,872 votes to 923
for the runner-up, Sen. Albert Gore of Tennessee. Vice President
George Bush easily won the Republican race with 1,282 votes.
   Selma Mayor Joe Smitherman, who was serving his first term when
bloody Sunday took place, said he thinks a lot of white Democrats
didn't vote but would have gone for Bush if they'd been able to
cross over. However, he acknowledges that blacks gave Jackson an
undeniably smashing victory in Selma and Dallas County.
   ``The black community really turned out for Jesse. He was here a
week before the election, and I accompanied him as he walked
through a poor, black section of town,'' said Smitherman, who
admits he was a segregationist back when it was fashionable.
   ``You had to be a segregationist to be elected in the South when
I was starting out,'' said the 58-year-old mayor. ``But we've
matured, I've matured. We were wrong to try and deny people their
right to vote, and I'm sorry for what we did.''
   Given the changes that have occurred in Selma, Smitherman said,
it's really no surprise Jackson did so well.
   However, the man who led the bloody Sunday march, Rep. John
Lewis, D-Ga., professed amazement that a black could score such a
victory in Dallas County.
   ``To me it is simply unbelievable,'' said Lewis, when contacted
at his Washington, D.C., office. ``When Hosea Williams and I led
that march back in 1965, only 2.1 percent of Dallas County's black
residents were registered to vote.''
   Since then, Smitherman points out, a lot of the Alabama River
has flowed beneath the Edmund Pettus Bridge.
   ``When I was first elected mayor in 1964 only 50 percent of our
streets were paved and less than half of our homes were connected
to the sewage system. But after 1965 we started taking advantage of
the federal programs and grants that existed at the time. Now,
every street is paved and the sewage system is all over town.
   ``Also, we now have an appointed black county school
superintendent who makes more damned money than I do. Half of the
city council is black and the assistant police chief is black.
Blacks probably have made more progress in Selma than in any other
white-controlled city in the Alabama.''
   The Rev. Joseph Rembert, pastor of Brown's Chapel where the
bloody Sunday march began, acknowledges there have been changes in
Selma. But he adds that whites still hold most of the power and
that many of the changes have come about as the result of federal
court actions initiated by blacks.
   ``Attitudes are slowly changing in Selma,'' he said. ``But, like
most places, we've still got a long way to go. What we really need
here, desperately, is jobs; our county unemployment rate runs about
16 percent and it's probably as high as 25 percent for blacks.''
   Rembert adds, though, that he would rather be one of Selma's
27,000 residents than live in a big, Northern city like New York.
   ``We don't have a utopia here but at least when we stage a
protest these days nobody gets hurt. Blacks and whites may fight to
the bone over an issue but when it's over they also may go off and
have lunch together, and that's a big change from the past.''
   Edwin Moss, one of the city's three black city councilmen, said
he has seen many changes during the 73 years he has lived in Selma.
   ``We've made some big political strides in this county, and
we've made social progress, too,'' said Moss, who founded and
manages a federal credit union with a largely black membership.
   ``Now,'' he added, ``we need economic progress. We need jobs. We
need financing for black-owned businesses.''
   Smitherman, in the midst of his sixth four-year term, agrees
Selma needs more jobs, but he's obviously proud of his city, with
its wide main street and gracious neighborhoods. He points out he
couldn't be mayor without the support of both blacks and whites and
is quick to show visitors his accomplishments in integrating
government and improving the local standard of living.
   ``That's why I, personally, like Jesse Jackson's message,'' he
said. ``He's talking about the same things I deal with as mayor.
He's talking about jobs, about the problems of working people,
about the homeless and the poor.''
   ``You know,'' he said, ``Jesse reminds me a lot of George
Wallace, 20 years ago. They're both populists.''
   Yet, he said, neither he nor most other local whites voted for
Jackson last Tuesday.
   ``It's funny, but you'll hear a group of whites talking politics
and somebody will say, `Jesse makes more sense than any of them.'
Then he'll up and add that he's voting for Bush or Gore. A black's
just not going to get many white votes around here, not yet at
least,'' Smitherman said. ``I don't know why I didn't vote for
Jesse, maybe it's because I don't think he can win.''
   At present, there is only one elected black county official in
Dallas County, which is under a federal court mandate to create
four voting districts _ two predominantly white and two
predominantly black _ by the fall election.
   That one black official is District Judge Nathaniel Walker, who
left Selma and got his law degree at Fordham University, then
returned home. Walker, the first black to hold countywide office
here, said he is heartened by the changes he has seen in his
hometown.
   ``I was among the marchers who were attacked on bloody Sunday,''
he said. ``Back then, the courthouse was off limits for blacks, it
was a place to be feared.
   ``But Jesse's victory is an example of what we were fighting
for. Last Tuesday's election shows that the people recognize just
how dear is their right to vote and that they're determined to
exercise their franchise.''
   John Lewis, who was hospitalized for two days with injuries he
received on bloody Sunday, said much the same thing.
   ``That's what the civil rights movement was all about,'' Lewis
said. ``We were trying to build a bi-racial democracy in Alabama
and throughout the South. Jesse Jackson's overwhelming victory in a
place like Selma proves this is possible.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Strat Douthat is the AP Southeast regional
reporter, based in Atlanta.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 13</NOTE>
