<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canadian liquor giant Seagram Co. Ltd. has
proposed buying orange juice producer Tropicana Products Inc. for
$1.2 billion to expand Seagram's share of the beverage market.
   The Canadian liquor-and-beverage giant's acquisition of
Tropicana from Beatrice U.S. Food Corp. marks a ``diversification
and an expansion'' of Seagram's product line, Seagram Chairman
Edgar M. Bronfman said Thursday.
   Securities analysts said the move into the juice business was a
logical step for Seagram, which has limited growth potential from
its liquor products.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CULVER CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investor Marvin Davis has made an
unsolicited $780.3 million offer for loss-plagued Lorimar
Telepictures Corp.
   Lorimar, based in this Los Angeles suburb, said Thursday that
Davis made the $17-a-share cash offer in a letter asking that
takeover negotiations be arranged between him and Lorimar's
management.
   The announcement came just three days after Lorimar disclosed it
was holding preliminary talks on the possibility of being acquired
by New York-based entertainment giant Warner Communications Inc.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers Group Inc., a leading insurer, says
its board unanimously has rejected an unsolicited $63 per share, or
$4.4 billion, tender offer from the U.S. subsidiary of Britain's
BAT Industries PLC.
   Farmers also said Thursday it was urging shareholders to reject
the offer.
   Farmers consistently has spurned BAT's overtures since the
British company proposed a friendly $60-per-share merger in January.
   Batus had no comment on the rejection by Farmers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colt Industries Inc., a large defense
contractor, has accepted a $526.6 million cash buyout offer from a
group led by senior management and a unit of Morgan Stanley Group
Inc.
   The $17-a-share bid for all of Colt's nearly 31 million common
shares outstanding was approved by the company's board of directors
and is expected to begin within the next five days, a spokesman
said Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment partnership which previously
indicated it would top a $940 million buyout bid for AFG Industries
Inc. has decided against making an offer for the glassmaking
concern.
   Forstmann Little & Co. said Thursday it decided against making
an offer based on its review of AFG's internal records and its own
``adherence to strict acquisition criteria.'' It declined to
elaborate.
   A group led by AFG's founder and chairman, R.D. Hubbard, said
from AFG's headquarters in Irvine, Calif., that it intended to
proceed with its earlier offer to take AFG private in buyout valued
at $33 a share.
</TEXT>
