<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0524</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World oil-producing nations, aware that they
cannot afford another 1986-style market collapse, probably will
succeed in bringing an end to the recent erosion of prices _ at
least temporarily, analysts say.
   After three months of declines, hopes of a turnaround stirred
with a report from Paris that officials of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries were studying a plan to shave 5
percent off the production of all 13 members except Iraq.
   Analysts said the report sent oil futures broadly higher
Thursday on the New York Mercantile Exchange, even though it later
was denied by OPEC officials.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 2.4 million jobs are expected to be
created in the United States this year, fewer than the 3 million
created in 1987 but ``still a very healthy number,'' a business
research company says.
   Manufacturers and companies with fewer than 20 employees again
will be leaders in creating jobs, according to Dun & Bradstreet
Corp.
   The company on Thursday announced the results of its annual
survey of employment expectations at 5,000 companies.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The union representing 6,700 flight
attendants for Northwest Airlines says the contract the airline
plans to impose April 1 is unacceptable and warned travelers about
the possibility of a strike during spring break.
   But Dennis Quinn, the Teamsters' national strike coordinator,
stopped short Thursday of saying flight attendants actually would
strike.
   This is a continuation of the threat the union has made since a
Feb. 26 strike deadline passed, he said. Since then, the attendants
have been free to strike but have not done so, and the airline had
been free to impose its latest contract offer.
   Meanwhile, union members at a rally in Philadelphia accused
Eastern Airline's parent company of trying to financially cripple
the air carrier to win wage concessions.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Auto Workers union has agreed to early
contract negotiations with Chrysler Corp. and the two sides soon
will set a date for the start of talks, UAW President Owen Bieber
said.
   Bieber said Thursday the talks could begin by mid-April.
   The union's main reason for granting Chrysler's request for
early talks is that the contract expiring Sept. 14 doesn't contain
protections negotiated last year at Ford Motor Co., Bieber said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RACINE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Case IH, a worldwide maker of agriculture
and construction equipment, says it will reduce employment this
year by 3,000 workers, or approximately 10 percent.
   The company, a subsidiary of Houston-based Tenneco Inc., said
Thursday the reductions would occur through layoffs of hourly and
salaried workers, retirements, attrition, termination of temporary
employees and a hiring freeze.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market fell sharply Thursday, as the Dow Jones average
of 30 industrials tumbled 48.24 to 2,026.03.
   Bond prices fell as energy and precious metals prices rose.
   The dollar was mixed in foreign exchange trading.
   Grain and soybean prices retreated and livestock and meat
futures were mixed.
