<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 0226EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ComputerProfits     03-11 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Computer Profits,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survey Finds Low Profits In Computer, Communications Hardware</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Companies making computer hardware and
communications equipment may be growing rapidly, but a private
survey released today finds many have been less profitable than the
general run of American companies during recent years.
   Intense competition from Japan and other foreign rivals is one
reason for the profit squeeze on those companies, according to
Harvey Poppel, a partner in Broadview Associates of Fort Lee, N.J.,
the investment banking firm that conducted the survey.
   A Broadview survey of 269 U.S.-based hardware and equipment
companies found they had a median return on equity of 6.5 percent
in 1987, with a large number of poorly performing small companies
dragging down the results.
   Poppel said the median return on equity for major American
companies is typically about 11 or 12 percent.
   Return on equity is a widely used measure of a company's
performance. It is the company's profit as a percentage of its
shareholders' equity, or net worth.
   When the survey results were adjusted to give the heaviest
weight to the companies with the biggest stock market values, such
as highly profitable International Business Machines Corp., the
average return on equity was 10.7 percent, roughly in line with the
average for American business.
   Broadview Associates specializes in mergers and acquisitions in
the computer software and services industry. Poppel said a survey
of nearly 200 of those companies found their return on equity was
above average _ about 18.6 percent last year.
   Poppel cited several reasons for the difficulties of the
computer hardware and communications equipment companies:
   _Japan and other aggressive competitors are willing to accept
lower profit margins to gain shares of the world market.
   _Many nations protect their home markets and domestic companies,
especially in the case of Western Europe with telecommunications
equipment.
   _Products have short life cycles, giving companies only a short
time to recoup their heavy investments.
   _It is easy for new companies to enter the market, especially at
the low end, because the basic components such as computer chips
are readily available.
   In contrast, Poppel said the information services companies have
higher return on equity because their offerings cannot easily be
rendered obsolete with new technology and are protected by high
barriers to entry of new competitors.
   Prices of products such as software and database services can be
kept relatively high and companies have fewer expensive assets such
as factories, Poppel noted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880311-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 0227EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Canada-Hyundai Bjt   03-11 0774</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada-Hyundai, Bjt,0800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Dumping Showdown In Canada Over Hyundai</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: All dollar figures are U.S. unless otherwise noted.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was a marketing phenomenon that turned into
the focus of an international battle with multibillion-dollar
implications.
   Within a year of introducing its $4,500 Pony subcompact to North
America in 1984, Hyundai Corp. of South Korea captured 7 percent of
the Canadian market. It then invaded the United States and sold
168,182 of its Excels in just 10 months.
   But were the Koreans exploiting a market void or unfairly
dumping the autos at below-cost prices in order to grab a share of
the lucrative market?
   The Canadian Import Tribunal is considering evidence from four
weeks of hearings that concluded Thursday over claims by domestic
automakers such as General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co. of
unfair pricing by Hyundai. Hyundai could be slapped with a 26
percent duty if found to be dumping cars.
   The case has worldwide implications as America's car giants
compete against Asian rivals who've grabbed more than 25 percent of
their auto market.
   A ruling is expected March 23 and both sides have the right to
appeal.
   In anti-dumping hearings held in Ottawa, GM and Ford
subsidiaries in Canada accused Hyundai of purposely setting
below-cost prices to grab a niche in the competitive small-car
market.
   The carmakers asked the Canadian Import Tribunal to uphold
Revenue Canada's preliminary finding last November that Hyundai has
been dumping Pony, Excel and Stellar hatchbacks and sedans in
Canada at an average 26 percent cheaper than they cost in South
Korea.
   A 26-percent duty would add more than $1,000 to the price of
Hyundais in 182 showrooms across Canada and could lead to similar
cases against other foreign makes.
   GM and Ford told the tribunal they were forced to slash prices
and offer cash rebates in order to compete with Hyundai's
bargain-basement approach.
   ``Future injury is going to take the form of reduced production,
reduced employment and reduced utilization of productive
capacity,'' Penny Bonner, legal counsel for the two companies,
testified Thursday.
   Hyundai acknowledged using Canada as a spearhead to penetrate
the American market, but argued that it never hurt GM or Ford
because the rear-wheel-drive Pony had no direct competition at the
bottom end of the market.
   ``The Pony was swept along because in a real sense there was no
competition,'' said Hyundai lawyer Richard Gottlieb. He termed the
success of the ``nice little car'' a fluke, coming right at the end
of a recession when American carmakers virtually had given up on
the sub-compact market.
   In surprising testimony on Thursday, lawyers for the Canadian
government's Consumer Affairs Department supported Hyundai. They
said the Korean company answered a need ignored by North American
manufacturers, thereby helping consumers.
   Hyundai zoomed to a 21 percent share of the small-car market in
Canada in 1985 with sales of 79,072 Ponies and Stellars.
   But since the preliminary anti-dumping ruling, the Canadian
subsidiary has been in a tailspin and some dealers have resigned,
according to company spokesman Greg Young.
   ``It destroyed us in the marketplace in terms of public
perception and confidence in the product,'' Young said.
   While still the third-ranked import behind Honda and Toyota,
Hyundai expects to sell just 45,000 cars this year, led by the
Excel, which starts at $5,835.
   ``People may say, `I like the Honda Civic but before making up
my mind I'm going to take a look at the Excel.' But the Honda
salesman just says, `Why bother?' because of the possible duties,''
Young said.
   But he said the bad publicity has not reached the United States,
and American Hyundai sales are still climbing after reaching
263,610 cars last year.
   To save the day in Canada, Hyundai has launched a ``Here To Stay
and Proud Of It'' TV and newspaper advertising campaign.
   It pledged to proceed with a $259 million manufacturing plant in
Bromont, Quebec, and $16 million parts factory in Newmarket,
Ontario. Scheduled to open later this year, the plants will create
1,300 jobs and give Hyundai the capacity to make 100,000 new-model
compacts a year.
   The plants will expand a Canadian car industry that grew out of
the milestone 1965 Auto Pact with the United States which permits
vehicles and parts to move duty-free across the border. Dominated
by GM, Ford and Chrysler subsidiaries, the Canadian car and truck
plants employ 140,000 workers with another 400,000 related jobs.
   Young said Hyundai will remain in business here, but may be
forced to reassess operations if anti-dumping duties are imposed.
   ``It may be step one against all import car companies, against
all competition,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
