<DOCNO> AP880311-0276 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 0228EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Lorimar-Davis Bjt   03-11 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lorimar-Davis, Bjt,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lorimar Gets $780 Million Bid from Marvin Davis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER GILLOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CULVER CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investor Marvin Davis is seeking to
get back into the entertainment business by making an unsolicited
$770.1 million offer for troubled Lorimar Telepictures Corp. and
has indicated he may be willing to go even higher.
   Davis' $17-per-share cash buyout offer was disclosed Thursday,
only three days after Lorimar announced it was holding preliminary
talks about a possible acquisition by New York-based entertainment
conglomerate Warner Communications Inc.
   A source close to the situation indicated Davis, the former
owner of 20th Century Fox Film Corp., was ``very serious'' about
acquiring Lorimar, the Culver City-based entertainment concern best
known as the producer of such television programs as `Dallas'' and
``Knots Landing.''
   Lorimar appeared to give short shrift to the proposal, stating
that it ``would bear Davis' letter in mind.''
   Lorimar stock rose $1 to close at $15.37{ on the American Stock
Exchange after the announcement of Davis' offer. The company has
45.3 million common shares outstanding.
   Davis made his offer in a letter to Lorimar management.
   On Monday, Lorimar and Warner announced they had entered
preliminary merger talks over the weekend.
   Analysts have suggested Lorimar's stock is worth between $14 and
$20 per share.
   Lorimar is a leading producer of original television
programming, but in recent years has been troubled as its ambitious
plans to expand into other areas disintegrated, sometimes causing
the company to incur losses or heavy costs that depressed earnings.
   For the first nine months of its current fiscal year, Lorimar
posted a loss of $82.6 million on revenue of $616.8 million. The
deficit included $45 million in writedowns on five movies and $22
million in reserves for possible future losses in its home-video
unit.
   The company replaced managements of both the movie and
home-video units.
   For the fiscal year ended last March 31, the company lost $58.6
million, mostly because of restructuring costs, on revenue of
$766.2 million.
   Davis has been seeking to get back into the entertainment
industry since selling Fox to media magnate Rupert Murdoch in 1985
for $575 million. Davis had owned Fox for four years, but the
company was beset by persistent losses.
   Last year, he made an unsuccessful $321.9 million bid for the
90.6 percent he didn't already own of Texas-based Spectradyne Inc.,
the nation's largest supplier of cable television and pay-per-view
movies for hotels.
   On Wednesday, four disgruntled shareholders filed a class action
lawsuit against Lorimar in federal court alleging the company
overstated its income and net worth and did not reveal problems
with its home-video unit, thereby causing investors to pay more for
stock then they believed they should have.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880311-0277 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 0242EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AFGOffer Bjt   03-11 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AFG Offer, Bjt,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AFG Suitor Presses Buyout Bid as Investment Firm Bows Out</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AFG Industries Inc. is left with a single suitor
following an investment partnership's decision not to top the $940
million buyout bid the glassmaker already has accepted from its
chairman.
   Forstmann Little & Co., which previously indicated it might be
willing to make a higher offer, said Thursday it decided against
making an offer based on its review of AFG's internal records and
its ``adherence to strict acquisition criteria.''
   A company led by AFG's founder and chairman, R.D. Hubbard,
stated from AFG headquarters in Irvine, Calif., that it intended to
proceed with its earlier offer to take AFG private in buyout valued
at $33 a share.
   AFG's stock finished down $5 a share at $31.62{ in trading on
the New York Stock Exchange.
   Larry Selwitz, a securities analyst for the investment firm
Bateman Eichler, Hill Richards in Los Angeles, said the odds
favored Hubbard's bid for the company. ``I would be really
hard-pressed to see who might come into it now,'' he said.
   Another analyst, Donald Pattison of Cyrus J. Lawrence, Morgan
Grenfell in New York, said Forstmann probably decided against
proceeding because of the strong possibility that Hubbard would
leave the company. ``He'd go off with his own company and probably
eat their lunch,'' Pattison said.
   Forstmann Little announced March 2 that it proposed paying more
than $33 a share in cash for all of AFG's common stock, subject to
a review of AFG's internal corporate information and meeting with
AFG management.
   On Thursday, Forstmann Little said it had completed the review,
that AFG had promptly furnished requested confidential information
and that AFG management had cooperated fully in the review.
   ``Based on this review and Forstmann Little's adherence to
strict acquisition criteria, it has determined that it will not
make an offer to acquire AFG,'' the New York-based leveraged buyout
specialist said.
   The firm declined to elaborate.
   AFG announced Feb. 25 that it had agreed to a buyout by a new
company headed by Hubbard that would pay $33 a share in cash for 94
percent of AFG's common stock and $33 per share in preferred stock
or a combination of cash and stock for the rest of the shares.
   AFG has 28.5 million common shares outstanding.
   AFG is one of the leading manufacturers of window glass and has
a range of specialty glass products.
   Hubbard's offer is being made by Hubbard's Clarity Industries
Corp., which is offering to buy up to 26.8 million AFG common
shares.
   Meantime, Clarity said two AFG shareholders had filed
class-action complaints in Delaware seeking to block its tender
offer.
   Clarity said the shareholders alleged the agreement between
Clarity and AFG to take the company private constitutes
self-dealing, deception and unfair dealing and breaches the
fiduciary duties owed AFG shareholders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
