<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Sugarman-MediaGeneral     03-11 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sugarman-Media General,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sugarman Boosts Media General Stake, Seeks to Force Vote on
Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An impending battle for Media
General Inc. is heating up, with television producer Burt Sugarman
boosting his stake in the company and signaling a fight to force a
shareholder vote on his $1.75 billion buyout bid.
   Sugarman said Thursday that two companies he controls boosted
their stake in Media General, the Virginia-based broadcasting and
publishing corporation to 10 percent from 9.8 percent.
   Sugarman also repeated his contention that Media General's board
of directors was legally bound to put his buyout plan to a
shareholder vote.
   However, Media General disputed Sugarman's contentions on how
the company's two classifications of stock would be allowed to vote
on a merger.
   Media General has 28 million shares of Class A common stock
entitled to one vote each and 559,168 Class B shares that have
disproportionate voting rights and elect seven of the company's 10
directors.
   The family of Media General's chairman, D. Tennant Bryan, owns
71 percent of the company's Class B stock.
   Shortly after Sugarman made his $61.50-per-share takeover offer
late last month, the Bryan family said it wasn't interested in
selling the company.
   In a letter sent Thursday to Media General's president and chief
executive officer, James S. Evans, Sugarman contended that under
Media General's charter all shareholders should have equal voting
rights in deciding on a proposed acquisition of the company by
someone holding at least 10 percent of its stock.
   In all other cases, the Class B stock would retain its special
voting rights, Sugarman contended.
   Sugarman reiterated that if Media General directors failed to
put the proposed merger before shareholders, they ``will be
breaching their fiduciary duty.''
   Media General disputed Sugarman's claims, saying ``company
counsel found Sugarman's legal reasoning incorrect.''
   Media General said that under its charter any merger would
require the vote of two-thirds of each class of stock. In addition
to the charter requirement, the company said, Virginia law requires
that a merger be approved by more than two-thirds of the Class B
stock.
   Media General owns a number of daily papers, including the
Richmond (Va.) Times-Dispatch and News Leader, the Winston-Salem
(N.C.) Journal and the Tampa (Fla.) Tribune, plus 32 weeklie in
Southern California and a 40 percent interest in Garden State
Newspapers Inc., which owns 18 dailies and four weeklies in eight
states. It also owns television stations, including WCBD-TV in
Charleston, S.C., WJKS-TV in Jacksonville, Fla., and WXFL-TV in
Tampa, Fla.
   Sugarman is making his takeover bid through two companies he
controls _ Barris Industries Inc., the creator of TV programs such
as ``The Dating Game,'' ``The Newlywed Game'' and ``The Gong
Show,'' and Giant Group Ltd., the parent of Keystone Cement Co. and
Giant Cement Co. with units in Pennsylvania and South Carolina.
</TEXT>
