<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Seagram-Beatrice Bjt   03-11 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Seagram-Beatrice, Bjt,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seagram-Tropicana Deal A Tasty Mix, Analysts Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Take one liquor company, add one orange juice
company, and the resulting mix could be a satisfying corporate
cocktail _ at least that's how some industry experts characterized
Seagram Co. Ltd.'s plans to buy Tropicana Products Inc.
   The $1.2 billion deal announced Thursday will expand Seagram's
share of the beverage market and could result in a wider line of
Tropicana products, said Robert S. Reitzes, who follows Seagram for
the investment firm Mabon, Nugent & Co. in New York.
   ``It's a good fit,'' Reitzes said ``It makes sense in their
business.''
   The Canadian liquor-and-beverage giant's acquisition of
Tropicana from Beatrice U.S. Food Corp. marks a diversification and
expansion of Seagram's product lines, Seagram Chairman Edgar M.
Bronfman stated in announcing the deal.
   ``We have already broadened our base with Seagram's (wine)
coolers, and Tropicana is another step in this direction,''
Bronfman said.
   Analysts said the move into the juice business was a logical
step for Seagram, which faced limited growth potential from its
liquor business.
   ``They understand the business, and it's growing unlike most of
their liquor products,'' said Ian Osler, an analyst with
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in Toronto.
   Seagram will finance the acquisition _ to be made through the
company's U.S. subsidiary, Joseph E. Seagram & Sons Inc. _
initially with a combination of bank loans and short-term
borrowings, Seagram said.
   Montreal-based Seagram, best known for its distilled spirits and
wines, in recent years moved into production of wine coolers and
the sale of mixers such as tonic and ginger ale under the Seagram
name.
   Seagram also is in the process of acquiring French cognac
producer Martell & Co. in a deal valued at $930 million. It also
owns a 23 percent stake in Du Pont Co.
   Tropicana, headquartered in Bradenton, Fla., is a leading
manufacturer and distributor of ready-to-serve orange juice and
frozen concentrate. It had sales of about $750 million in its last
fiscal year, which ended Feb. 29, said Marcelline Thomson, a
Seagram spokeswoman in New York.
   Seagram had net income of nearly $423.5 billion on sales of $3.3
billion in the fiscal year ended Jan. 31, 1987. It reported a
profit of more than $402.4 million on sales of $2.6 billion for the
nine months ended Oct. 31.
   Chicago-based Beatrice U.S. Food Corp. is a division of
closely-held Beatrice Co., which put itself up for sale last
September. The company also is considering the sale of its
Hunt-Wesson operations, which produce vegetable oils, ketchup and
La Choy brand Chinese food.
   Beatrice Co.'s predecessor, Beatrice Cos., was taken private in
1986 in a $6.2 billion leveraged buyout led by Kohlberg Kravis
Roberts & Co. Since then it has sold most of its major assets,
including Avis car rental, International Playtex Inc. and its
international foods business.
   A number of Beatrice's consumer products businesses were spun
off as E-II Holdings Inc., which last month agreed to be acquired
by American Brands Inc. after making a brief takeover move against
the company.
   Beatrice Chairman Donald Kelly, who also is chairman of E-II,
had hoped to sell Beatrice whole but could not find a buyer at his
asking price, reportedly $4.5 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
