<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 0251EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BananaTravel     03-11 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Banana Travel,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Banana Republic Clothing Chain Launches Travel Magazine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The credo of Banana Republic's new travel
magazine is simple _ people shouldn't travel halfway around the
world only to find the same hamburger joints they've got back home.
   ``We are on the brink of becoming McGlobe,'' warns Mel Ziegler,
president of the San Francisco-based clothier and editor-in-chief
of Trips, a quarterly launched nationwide this week.
   Ziegler says 300,000 customers already have expressed interest
in $10-a-year subscriptions to the magazine, which promises to
``lead you down the back alleys of Cairo, onto forbidden islands or
through your own hometown, in search of stories that will transcend
the distinctions between traveler and fantasist...''
   ``We wanted to publish the world's first honest travel
magazine,'' he said in a recent interview. ``If you read most
travel magazines, you get the idea travel is painless, nothing ever
goes wrong. We all know nobody ever takes a trip like that.''
   Trips, which takes an iconoclastic approach to globe-trotting,
is aimed at the same affluent urbanites who made such a success of
the 10-year-old adventure-wear company, which was sold to The Gap
clothing chain for an undisclosed sum in 1983.
   It also attempts to latch onto a recent boom in travel magazines
that has seen a handful of new publications in recent months.
   The inaugural issue is a trek into the offbeat and bizarre.
   Articles include a journey through the apartheid world of South
Africa, bicycling with the 400-pound king of Tonga in the South
Pacific and sneaking onto a secret Hawaiian island.
   An interview with Rod Nordland, a correspondent-at-large for
Newsweek magazine, is billed as ``a palm-greasing primer'' on the
art of baksheesh, the Arabic word for petty bribery.
   But the advice doesn't just center on money: the article advises
that a pack of cigarettes may convince a taxi driver in Angola to
get you to the airport and a bottle of liquor or contact points for
a '57 Chevy can get you just about anything in Burma.
   Also included is a section where world-weary travelers pass on
tips to surviving off the beaten path.
   These include suggestions to carry a golf ball in your luggage,
because many of the world's hotels don't have drain plugs, and to
carry a roll of toilet paper not only for obvious uses but also for
insulating boots, wrapping wounds, and serving as barter.
   Trips is entering a rapidly expanding market. In 1986, the most
recent year for which figures are available, Americans spent $257
billion on domestic travel and $24.5 billion overseas, according to
The New York Times.
   As a result, travel magazines are enjoying a renaissance. The
Newhouse media conglomerate in September began publishing Conde
Nast's Traveler which, like Trips, promises not to whitewash
getaway spots. Fairchild Publications' Travel Today, a weekly
tabloid, hit newsstands in January.
   Ziegler says many Americans he meets traveling these days are
not on ``tour packages seeing foreign ports from a bubble, nor are
they backpackers....
   ``These are working people who have saved some money who like to
enjoy cultures fully by immersing themselves in it.''
</TEXT>
