<1ST_LINE>r f PM-NorthwestAirlines     03-11 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northwest Airlines,0589</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northwest Attendants' Union Calls Contract To Be Imposed
`Unacceptable'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA WILKINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The union representing 6,700 Northwest
Airlines flight attendants is warning travelers about the
possibility of a strike during the busy spring break.
   ``As the travel increases over spring break and Easter, it is to
our advantage to keep ready for a strike,'' Dennis Quinn, the
Teamsters' national strike coordinator, told a news conference
Thursday.
   However, he added, ``We have not set a firm strike deadline at
this time.''
   Quinn's comments came as the union termed unacceptable the
contract which Northwest plans to impose April 1.
   The Minneapolis airline has been free to impose the contract
since a Feb. 26 strike deadline passed and the union has been free
to strike.
   Terry Erskine, Northwest's vice president of law and labor
relations, said he would not rule out making changes in the
contract before April 1 if the union comes forward with suggestions.
   But Quinn said, ``Northwest intends to force a strike. It is
moving into a situation where there are no other alternatives but a
work stoppage, and that it is a very good reason for you to
indicate, yes, we are serious.''
   Northwest spokesman Redmond Tyler denounced the Teamster
announcement as ``rhetoric'' and said spring travelers would
encounter no problems even in the event of a strike.
   ``Continue to plan your travel because we anticipate no
disruption in service,'' Tyler said. ``We regret any attempt to
intimidate ... We are disappointed our employees would take this
tactic to confuse their company's customers.''
   Meanwhile, a taped message on a Teamsters hotline for flight
attendants criticized the contract and said the company's move did
not end the union's right to strike.
   ``Northwest assumes you will accept this substandard contract.
Please show them how wrong they are,'' Dottie Malinsky, president
of Teamsters Local 2747, which represents the Minneapolis unit,
told attendants on the taped message.
   ``This company action will backfire on them. Nickel and diming
the employees is not going to change the bad management at
Northwest,'' she said.
   Teamsters have called a strategy meeting Monday in Washington,
D.C., for local union officers and strike captains at Northwest.
Leaders of the unions representing Northwest ground workers and
pilots are expected to attend that meeting, Malinsky said.
   Claudia Bushbaum, secretary-treasurer for Teamsters Local 2747,
said the airline's offer to negotiate on the contract was
meaningless. Northwest is unwilling to bend on the issue of when to
elevate lower-paid employees, who are on what the company and union
call a B pay scale, to higher pay scales, she said.
   ``If the company does not come back to the table and negotiate
and move off of their position of the extended B pay scale, there
is all likelihood we will strike when the time is right,'' Bushbaum
said. ``They're willing to sit across the table from you and say
they're going to negotiate, but sitting across the table from you
and saying `no' is not negotiations. And that is exactly the way
Northwest negotiates when we talk about the B pay scale.''
   Under the new contract, Northwest says union membership would no
longer be a condition of employment. Bushbaum, who called that a
``union-busting tactic,'' said Teamsters' attorneys were reviewing
the legality of this action.
   Erskine said Wednesday that if attendants decide to strike now,
the airline is prepared to hire permanent replacements.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
