<1ST_LINE>u f PM-MinimumWage 1stLd-Writethru f0027 03-11 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Minimum Wage, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0027,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor Secretary Criticizes Plan To Increase Minimum Wage</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 1-4 grafts to UPDATE with McLaughlin comments.
Picks up 3rd graf pvs, The subcommittee ... A version moving on
general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor Secretary Ann McLaughlin today said a
proposal to raise the federal minimum wage to $5.05 an hour over
the next four years may sound ``like the right thing to do'' but it
actually would cause a loss of jobs.
   Mrs. McLaughlin said the proposed increase, likely to be
approved next week by the House Education and Labor Committee,
would be particularly hard on young people with no skills who are
seeking their first jobs.
   ``This is a tough one. $5.05 an hour, I'm afraid would make
almost any economist have some jitters,'' Mrs. McLaughlin said in
an interview on NBC-TV's ``Today'' show. ``The body of economic
thinking is that the increase in the minimum wage, while
well-intentioned and it sounds like the right thing to do, actually
will cause a loss of jobs, particularly impacting on young people
who need to get into the workforce.''
   Education and Labor Committee Chairman Augustus F. Hawkins,
D-Calif., scheduled a session next Wednesday for final action on
the minimum wage bill. The panel had been unable on Thursday to
address all the amendments to a proposal that was approved by the
House labor standards subcommittee a week ago.
   The subcommittee approved an increase from $3.35 to $4.65 an
hour over a three-year period, with a 50-cent raise in 1989 and a
40-cent jump in both 1990 and 1991.
   During the full committee's hearing, Rep. Carl C. Perkins,
D-Ky., proposed an amendment for an increase of another 40 cents in
1992 in an effort to keep the federal minimum at approximately one
half of the nation's average wage.
   The committee approved the Perkins amendment on a vote of 18-14
with only two Democrats, Reps. Austin J. Murphy of Pennsylvania and
Timothy J. Penny of Minnesota, joining Republicans in opposing the
proposal.
   Murphy, chairman of the labor standards subcommittee, said his
panel had fashioned a measure which would be acceptable to the full
House and the Senate and possibly the White House.
   ``We don't know what impact the fourth year will have on the
loss of jobs,'' Murphy said.
   Rep. Stephen J. Solarz, D-N.Y., however, read from a letter
written to Hawkins by Labor Secretary Ann McLaughlin who said
senior White House advisers would recommend to President Reagan
that he veto any legislation increasing the minimum wage.
   ``It doesn't matter what we do; the executive will be against
it,'' he said.
   Rep. Dick Armey, R-Tex., who opposes any increase, proposed an
amendment to the Perkins measure to raise the base to $20 an hour,
but withdrew it after Hawkins called it absurd.
   The committee approved 20-13 an amendment by Rep. Tommy F.
Robinson, D-Ark., to increase the ``tip credit'' for restaurant
employers.
   Current law allows employers of workers who regularly receive
tips _ such as waiters and waitresses _ to count the tips as earned
wages equivalent to 40 percent of the minimum wage.
   Thus, a restaurant owner could pay a worker $2.01 an hour, with
the remaining $1.34 _ 40 percent of today's $3.35-an-hour minimum
wage _ supposed to come from tips.
   The Robinson proposal would increase the credit to 50 percent.
   The Senate has a companion bill, sponsored by Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy, D-Mass., chairman of the Labor and Human Resources
Committee, which raises the minimum wage to $4.65 an hour over a
three-year period.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880311-0283 </DOCNO>
