<1ST_LINE>u f PM-RetailSales 1stLd-Writethru f0033 03-11 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Retail Sales, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0033,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retail Sales Up In February</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 7 grafs additional detail. A version moving on general
news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retail sales, boosted by strength in autos,
rose 0.6 percent in February, following a January decline, the
government reported today.
   The Commerce Department said that retail sales rose a seasonally
adjusted $714 million to $127.99 billion last month.
   While the February increase was generally in line with
expectations, the government revised the January report to show a
small decline of 0.2 percent, instead of an originally reported
increase of 0.5 percent.
   Even with the January decline, analysts said the retail sales
report generally reflected that the October stock market crash has
had little effect on consumer buying plans.
   Ever since the record 508-point drop in stock prices which
occurred on Oct. 19, economists have been closely watching to see
whether the consumer sector would weaken.
   Since consumer spending accounts for two-thirds of overall
economic activity, any significant faltering in this area could
topple the country into a recession.
   Continued strong gains in employment growth have apparently
calmed initial jitters over the stock market. Many economists have
recently revised up their growth forecasts for 1988.
   The February report said that retail sales rose to the highest
monthly total since August 1987.
   Much of the strength came from a 1.6 percent rise in auto sales,
which followed an even stronger 2 percent increase in new car sales
in January.
   Without the gain in autos, which accounted for almost one-fourth
of total sales last month, retail sales would have risen a smaller
0.3 percent in February.
   The important general merchandise category, which includes
department store sales, suffered a 1.6 percent decline in sales in
February following a small 0.1 percent drop in January sales.
   Sales of all durable goods, items expected to last three or more
years, were up 1.6 percent in February while sales of non-durable
goods edged down 0.1 percent.
   In the durable goods category, sales at building materials and
hardware stores jumped a sharp 2.3 percent.
   Sales at furniture and appliance stores were up 0.3 percent in
February following an even stronger 2.7 percent January increase.
   Sales at specialty clothing stores climbed 0.6 percent in
February, only a partial rebound following a giant 3.3 percent
January decline.
   Sales at gasoline stations fell 1.6 percent in February while
sales at restaurants edged up 0.1 percent and sales at drug stores
posted a 0.6 percent increase.
   Sales at grocery stores enjoyed a 0.7 percent rise in sales in
February, reversing a 0.6 percent January decline.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880311-0284 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 0931EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Colt 1stLd-Writethru   03-11 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Colt, 1st Ld-Writethru,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Colt Industries To Be Taken Private In Leveraged Buyout</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS first 2 grafs to CORRECT total figure, which includes
options and expenses, and total outstanding shares.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colt Industries Inc., a major defense contractor
and industrial concern, has agreed to be taken private in a $660
million leveraged buyout led by senior management and the
investment firm Morgan Stanley Group Inc.
   The board of Colt, whose name may be best known from its
firearms business, approved an offer of $17 a share for all of its
approximately 31.65 million common shares outstanding late
Wednesday and announced the plan on Thursday. The price of Colt
stock options and expenses was included in the total price of the
buyout.
   The offer was subject to several conditions, including a
majority of the shares being tendered.
   Colt shares surged $4.87{ to $18.12{ on the New York Stock
Exchange on Thursday, indicating some speculators believed an offer
higher than the group's $17 a share bid would emerge.
   Under the transaction, Colt would become a wholly-owned
subsidiary of Colt Holdings Inc., a new company formed by the
management team and Morgan Stanley Leveraged Equity Fund II, Colt
stated. About $1.4 billion of Colt debt would remain outstanding,
it said.
   The Morgan Stanley Leveraged Equity Fund II is a limited
partnership that invests in leveraged buyouts, or deals in which a
company is acquired largely with borrowed funds repaid through the
target company's profits or sale of its assets.
   Colt said Morgan Stanley and its equity fund unit have agreed to
provide $460 million in short-term bridge financing for Colt
Holdings, which would be repaid through a public or private
offering of long-term debt.
   Investors in Colt Holdings would put up another $200 million,
Colt said.
   Colt Chairman David I. Margolis said the merger agreement would
give Colt ``the opportunity to establish and implement a more
aggressive business program, including acquisition, than we could
have undertaken alone.''
   Colt is a leading supplier of aerospace, automotive and
industrial products. It employs about 22,000 people.
</TEXT>
