<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 0933EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Kuwait-BP     03-11 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Kuwait-BP,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kuwait Declares 21.25 Percent Stake in BP</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kuwait said Friday that it has raised its stake in
British Petroleum Co. PLC to 21.25 percent, breaching the level BP
has said was acceptable.
   The Kuwait Investment Office, an agency set up for the purpose
of BP investments, said it intended to push the stake to 22.5
percent when market conditions permit. The group said it now holds
1.269 billion BP shares.
   BP Chairman Sir Peter Walters said last month that 20 percent
was an acceptable holding.
   BP has declined to comment on the Kuwaiti group's latest
disclosure.
   In February the KIO declared a 19.53 percent stake, or 1.165
billion shares.
   Analysts say BP and the British government have failed to obtain
Kuwaiti assurances that it will stop buying the shares.
   ``I think BP will be very unhappy about the increased stake,''
said Chris Grudniewicz, an analyst at Smith New Court Research.
``BP will probably now try to get the British government to lean on
the Kuwaitis to get some assurance they'll stop buying.''
   Recent heavy turnover in BP new shares had already raised
speculation that the KIO was building on its stake in BP.
</TEXT>
