<HEAD>Oil Shares Buck Overall Negative Trend</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The London stock market remained largely depressed
Friday following a steep fall on Wall Street, but oil shares bucked
the trend in heavy trading.
   At 2 p.m. local time, the Financial Times Index of 100 leading
shares hit the low for the day of 1814.4 points, down 20.2.
   The Financial Times 30-share index was down 23.1 points at
1,449.2. Volume was a high 502.5 million shares.
   After a steep fall in New York, the Dow Jones industrial average
closed off 48.24 points at 2,026.03.
   Oil stocks, however, proved an exception with heavy trading
continuing in British Petroleum shares. Total trading in the
company amounted to more than a quarter of total stock exchange
volume.
   The Kuwait Investment Office confirmed Friday it raised its
stake in the company to 21.25 percent, or 1.269 billion shares. The
new stake broke the 20 percent ceiling British Petroleum had viewed
as an acceptable holding for the Kuwait office.
