<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ManufacturersHanover     03-11 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Manufacturers Hanover,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Manufacturers Hanover Predicts Gain From Asset Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manufacturers Hanover Corp., the nation's
sixth-largest bank holding company, says it expects to net at least
$807 million this year, and that the number would be much higher if
Brazil resumes payments on its debt.
   Brazil is negotiating terms of an agreement to restart those
payments, which it suspended last year. Should that happen,
Manufacturers Hanover's net earnings ``would kick up by another
$150 million after tax,'' James Hambleton, a senior vice president
of the bank, said today.
   In its annual report released Thursday, the bank said it will
pick up about $230 million from the sale of ``undervalued assets''
in 1988.
   Operating earnings should total at least $377 million, including
$95 million after a restructuring announced earlier this year,
according to figures contained in the report.
   In addition, it said it planned to apply about $200 million of
tax benefits to its 1988 balance sheet. The benefits come from $342
million in tax benefits remaining from the $1.7 billion addition to
loan-loss reserves last year.
   The huge loan-loss provision, which was made to cover shaky
Third World debt, was largely responsible for a $1.14 billion loss
in 1987. Several other major banks also suffered losses or
decreased earnings due to the foreign debt crisis.
   Manufacturers Hanover said that as a result of the sale of
``undervalued assets,'' which it did not name, and the tax
benefits, it expected to improve shareholders' equity.
   Shareholders' equity is a corporation's net worth after
subtracting all liabilities.
   ``Restoring common shareholders' equity to 4 percent, the ratio
prior to the reserving action, is our overriding priority,'' the
company said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
