<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 1120EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-TickerTalk Adv14   03-11 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 14,0651</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday March 14</NOTE>
<HEAD>Closed-End Bond Funds Hot In A Cool Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While the market for new stocks has turned
chilly since Black Monday last Oct. 19, Wall Street has found
strong demand for one category of new issue _ closed-end bond funds.
   In the first two months of 1988, Standard & Poor's reports,
investors snapped up more than $3.5 billion in shares of these
investments.
   On Friday, Massachusetts Financial Services of Boston added $2
billion more to the total with the debut of its MFS Intermediate
Income Trust, in what stands as the largest initial public stock
offering ever.
   The attraction of these funds is not the hope of spectacular
growth or quick trading profits, but rather yields as high as the
10 percent to 11{ percent range.
   There is no denying the appeal of such returns, especially in a
period when interest rates have been generally declining, pushing
the yield available on long-term government bonds below 8.5 percent.
   But some analysts wonder whether all the eager buyers look
beyond the yield to gain a full understanding of this particular
breed of security and how it has often behaved in the past.
   A closed-end fund operates very much like a mutual fund, with
one very important difference.
   Mutual funds stand continuously ready to sell new shares and
redeem old ones, at a price that is determined by the net asset
value of their portfolios on any given day.
   Shares of closed-end funds, by contrast, are traded like any
other stock on an exchange or in the over-the-counter market.
   The number of shares remains fixed, except for special occasions
on which the fund might decide to increase it with a new offering
or reduce it by buying in some of its stock.
   So while the operating performance of a mutual fund is the sole
determinant of its price, a closed-end fund's price is also
influenced by supply and demand forces in the open market.
   Its shares can trade at a premium above net asset value, or a
discount below net asset value.
   ``During periods of strength in fixed-income markets, such as at
present, some bond funds may temporarily sell at a premium to
NAV,'' Standard & Poor's analysts observe in the firm's weekly
publication The Outlook.
   ``If history is any guide, however, the premiums tend to shrink
and give way to discounts once interest rates begin to rise.''
   Closed-end funds of all types have enjoyed a revival of interest
in the past few years. Fund managers say they like the format
because it allows them to pursue their investment strategies
undisturbed by the ebb and flow of money that can occur in mutual
funds.
   In theory at least, a popular mutual fund may have to make
bigger or riskier bets than it would like when money pours into its
coffers. Conversely, it may have to sell securities it would rather
keep when redemptions increase.
   The recent evidence lends some support to this view. S&P quotes
statistics from Lipper Analytical Services showing an average total
return of 85 percent over the last five years for closed-end bond
funds.
   In the same period, a comparable group of fixed-income mutual
funds averaged a total return of 72 percent.
   Nevertheless, veteran observers of closed-end funds say, when
you are approached by a broker recommending a new fund, it makes
sense to look at the similar alternatives that may be available in
existing funds.
   Says S&P: ``Consider acquiring a closed-end fund in the
after-market, when premiums often shrink after a few months and you
need pay only a normal brokerage commission and not a built-in
initial underwriting fee of about 7 percent.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon March 14</NOTE>
</DOC>
