<2ND_LINE>PM-Federated,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Campeau Gets More Financing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campeau Corp. says it has moved closer to
completing the financing for its $6.18 billion tender offer for
Federated Department Stores Inc.
   Campeau is fighting a competing $6.1 billion offer by R.H. Macy
& Co. Inc. to buy Federated, the nation's fifth-largest retailing
company. Seeking support for its bid, Campeau has announced each
step in its efforts to win financing as they have been reached.
   Campeau said Thursday that Citibank of New York and the New York
branch of Sumitomo of Japan have agreed to provide $1.5 billion of
a $2.66 billion secured loan that would be used in connection with
purchase of Federated shares.
   The Toronto-based retailer said in a statement the two banks
were confident the remaining $1.16 billion needed for the loan
could be obtained through a syndicate of banks.
   Campeau also said Citibank would provide $1 billion and Sumitomo
$500 million of $3.13 billion in long term financing for the
Federated acquisition after the tender offer.
   Campeau has offered to pay $75 a share in cash for 80 percent of
Federated's stock and $44 a share in cash for the remaining 20
percent.
   The Macy proposal, which is backed by Federated management and
the company's board of directors, would pay $74.50 a share in cash
for 80 percent of Federated's shares and stock in the merged
company, Macy's-Federated Inc., for the remaining 20 percent.
   Campeau earlier announced $1.5 billion in bridge financing from
First Boston Corp., its financial adviser, and $1.4 billion in
equity to put into the Federated acquisition.
   The equity includes a $480 million loan from Youngstown
developer Edward J. DeBartolo, $500 million in secured bank loans,
$260 million in debentures from Olympia & York Developments Ltd.,
and a portion of the $770 million Campeau expects to realize from
the proposed sale of the Brooks Brothers division of its Allied
Stores Corp.
   Besides the $3.13 billion in bank financing, Campeau has agreed
to sell Federated's Filene's stores in Boston and Foley's in
Houston to St. Louis-based May Department Stores Inc. for between
$1.3 billion and $1.5 billion in cash and notes.
   Campeau and Macy have both indicated they would sell Federated's
non-department store holdings, which include Ralphs supermarkets,
Gold Circle discount stores and Children's Place and Main Street
specialty retailers.
   In a filing this week with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, Macy indicated $2.9 billion in Federated assets would
be sold if its bid is successful. Macy said the non-department
store divisions would be put up for sale as well as ``certain other
assets.''
   Analysts believe Macy would sell two department store divisions,
Abraham & Straus and Rich's, which directly compete with Macy
Stores.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
