<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened mixed
today on the Chicago Board of Trade in the absence of strong
market-affecting factors.
   Wheat futures opened slightly higher in an early attempt to
rebound from four weeks of falling prices, analysts said.
   ``Wheat's been plunging here for 20-some sessions and the
market's getting way oversold on a strictly technical basis,'' said
Walter Spilka, an analyst for Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co. in
New York.
   Soybean futures were mixed with the nearby March contract
slightly lower, reflecting the market's continuing fear of a large
South American soybean harvest, Spilka said.
   Corn was slightly lower while oats were sharply higher in a
reversal from Thursday's losses.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent to 1\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $2.91 a bushel; corn was
unchanged to } cent lower with March at $1.97 a bushel; oats were \
cent lower to 6\ cents higher with March at $1.87{ a bushel;
soybeans were } cent lower to 1{ cents higher with March at $6.03 a
bushel.
   Livestock futures were mostly higher while pork belly futures
were lower in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .15 cent to .45 cent higher with April at 73.37
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .08 cent to .50 cent higher with
March at 82.05 cents a pound; hogs were .25 cent lower to .15 cent
higher with April at 43.37 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.10 cent to .17 cent lower with March at 51.55 cents a pound.
   Live cattle futures closed higher on Thursday but other
livestock and meat futures ended mostly lower.
