<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mixed
Friday in lackluster trading on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Most soybean contracts advanced on higher soybean oil prices and
on talk that U.S. soybean plantings will not exceed 60 million
acres this year, analysts said.
   Traders have been worried about the possibility of a sharper
increase in planted soybean acreage, which totaled 57.4 million
acres in 1987.
   The USDA will release its first estimate of grain plantings for
the new season on March 31.
   Wheat futures ended fractionally higher, corn was slightly lower
and oats closed modestly higher.
   Trading volume was light as some traders headed for Orlando,
Fla., the site of next week's National Grain and Feed Association
Convention, said Gordon Linn, president of Linnco Futures Inc. in
Chicago.
   At the close, wheat was unchanged to } cent higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $2.90{ a bushel; corn was \ cent
to 1 cent lower with March at $1.96} a bushel; oats were 2\ cents
to 4} cents higher with March at $1.86 a bushel; soybeans were {
cent lower to 2 cents higher with March at $6.03{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
