<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Panama-BankofBoston     03-11 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Bank of Boston,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank of Boston Agrees To Freeze Panamanian Transactions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The First National Bank of Boston agreed Friday to
freeze activity on Panamanian government accounts until the State
Department lifts sanctions against the nation.
   The action stems from a civil suit filed earlier this week by
Panama's U.S. ambassador, Juan B. Sosa, the recognized
representative of the government of deposed President Eric Arturo
Delvalle.
   A federal judge Tuesday issued a temporary injunction against
payments to any Panamanian government agency from accounts at Bank
of Boston and four Florida-based banks. In addition, a restraining
order was issued Friday by a federal judge in New York against the
Bank of Boston International, which holds a Panama government
clearing account.
   Under a settlement filed in U.S. District Court in Boston, the
Bank of Boston prohibits transactions against any account of the
Republic of Panama, Banco Nationale de Panama or Petroterminale de
Panama, unless approved by Sosa.
   Bank of Boston, however, can transfer up to $4 million a month
to Petroterminale from its Panama branch to cover salaries and
operating expenses for the company, which runs a ship fuel pipeline
alongside the Panama canal.
   The settlement, presented to District Judge Edward Harrington,
was reached following talks between lawyers representing the bank
and the Delvalle government, overthrown in late February by Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Attorney Michael Gardener, representing the Delvalle government,
estimated the Bank of Boston handles ``several million dollars'' in
Panamanian government assets.
   Bank spokesman Wayne Taylor declined to estimate a figure, but
said the bank's settlement may set a precedent for Sosa's suit
against the Florida banks.
   Defendants in that suit are the Citizens and Southern
International Bank, Republic National Bank of Miami, Barnett Bank
of Florida and the Bank of New England International.
   A federal judge in Miami has scheduled a March 16 hearing for
the suit.
   On March 7, a federal judge in New York added 10 days to a
restraining order preventing Marine Midland and Bankers Trust from
transferring an estimated $50 million to the Banco Nationale de
Panama.
   Irving Trust was dropped from that order after agreeing not to
transfer any money to the Panama bank. Last Wednesday, another
defendant, Republic National Bank of New York, was dropped when it
agreed to transfer $10 million in Panamanian funds to the Federal
Reserve Bank.
   Delvalle is still recognized by the U.S. government as the
legitimate head of Panama.
   Two U.S. grand juries in Florida indicted Noriega on drug
charges Feb. 4. Delvalle sought to dismiss Noriega Feb. 25, but was
ousted the next day by Noriega supporters and went into hiding.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880311-0314 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 2102EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ContractorSentencing     03-11 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contractor Sentencing,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Litton Executive Sentenced to 3 Years in Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former defense industry official was
sentenced Friday to three years in prison and fined $5,000 for his
part in a scheme that overcharged the government nearly $9 million
in military contracts.
   Roland Edward Fisher, 57, of suburban Drexel Hill, former vice
president and general manager of Litton Systems, Inc., pleaded
unsuccessfully for leniency through his attorney before U.S.
District Judge Robert Kelly.
   Litton was earlier fined $6.3 million for its part in the
price-rigging conspiracy.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Nicholas Harbest, in seeking lengthy
incarceration, said ``Fisher was entrusted with the taxpayer's
funds and abused that trust. A prison sentence will send a ringing
message to other defense industry executives that this type of
conduct will no longer go unnoticed and unpunished.''
   Harbest told the judge that Fisher, between January 1975 and
December 1984, set prices for the goverment contracts Litton
obtained that were well above the real costs to produce the item
and that other individual defendants participated in the scheme.
   Specifically, Fisher was found guilty of racketeering,
obstruction of a government agency's proceedings, making false
statements and mail fraud.
   Two other Litton employees were sentenced earlier in the case.
   Michael Millspaugh, 35, a former controller from Buffalo Grove,
Ill., received one year and a $10,000 fine, while Joseph DiLiberto,
69, a former materials manager, of Levittown, Pa., received 5
years' probation and a $10,000 fine.
   Both had pleaded guilty.
</TEXT>
