<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   03-11 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0520</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market staged a strong recovery near
the close Friday to finish higher after a broad early selloff.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down more than 20
points at midafternoon, closed with a gain of 8.95 at 2,034.98. For
the week the average lost 22.88 points.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 7 to 5 on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 856 up, 676 down and 464 unchanged.
Earlier, declines had predominated by as much as 2 to 1.
   Big Board volume totaled 200.02 million shares, against 197.26
million in the previous session. The NYSE's composite index rose
.53 to 149.45.
   Analysts said traders were a bit unnerved by Thursday's drop in
stock prices, when the Dow Jones industrials fell 48.24 points for
their largest loss in more than two months.
   But a midsession slide gave way to buying Friday as the Dow
dropped to near the 2,000 level.
   Stocks drew some support from falling interest rates in the
credit markets, where prices of long-term Treasury bonds rose more
than $5 for each $1,000 in face value.
   The bond market got a lift from news of an unexpected 0.2
percent decline in the producer price index last month and a
relatively modest 0.6 percent rise in retail sales for the same
period.
   A big chunk of Friday's activity came in the stock of MFS
Intermediate Income Trust, which traded at 10 on turnover of more
than 35 million shares after a 200 million-share initial offering
at that price.
   The debut of the closed-end investment company specializing in
interest-bearing securities with maturities of 10 years or less
marked the largest initial public stock offering ever in the U.S.
market.
   Among actively traded blue chips, General Electric gained | to
43|; International Business Machines 1} to 115{, and Exxon { to
42[. American Telephone & Telegraph slipped \ to 28 and Eastman
Kodak was down ] at 41}.
   Home Shopping Network, traded on the American Stock Exchange,
fell 1] to 6[. The company reported a 44 percent earnings decline
for its latest fiscal quarter.
   Super Valu Stores finished unchanged at 23 after trading as high
as 24[. The company, which has been the subject of takeover
speculation, said it hadn't received any offers and knew of no
reason for the recent activity in its stock.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $5.93 billion, or 0.23
percent, in value.
   Nationwide turnover in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 224.82 million shares.
   Standard & Poor's index of 400 industrials rose 1.14 to 307.39,
and S&P's 500-stock composite index was up 1.10 at 264.94.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
dropped 1.28 to 375.48. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 296.09, up .09.
