<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     03-11 0723</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0749</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cotton Futures Leap On Technical Factors; Drop In Deliverable
Supplies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices for May and July delivery of cotton surged Friday on a
combination of technical factors, bargain hunting and concerns
about a drop in supplies, analysts said.
   On other markets, livestock and meat futures finished mostly
higher in a volatile session; precious metals were mixed; grains
and soybeans were mixed; energy futures advanced; and stock-index
futures moved higher.
   Strong technical buying boosted near-month cotton futures prices
on the New York Cotton Exchange, but fundamental factors also
played a role in the rally, said Ernest Simon, cotton specialist in
New York for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   ``From a fundamental point of view, the futures market is the
cheapest market around for U.S. cotton,'' Simon said.
   With futures priced three to five cents below cash, cotton users
who do not need supplies immediately can buy cotton at a bargain on
the futures market.
   But the buying interest also tends to raise futures prices,
effectively bringing the futures markets more in line with cash
prices.
   Simon also noted some ``decertifications'' of deliverable
stocks, indicating a company with obligations to deliver cotton
planned to make those shipments using the type of cotton traded on
the Cotton Exchange.
   Cotton settled .60 cent to 1.45 cents higher with the contract
for delivery in May at 63.20 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures ended higher on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange
in a volatile session marked by a failed attempt to rally the live
cattle market above its previous highs.
   Traders bid the April contract up to 73.50 cents a pound, just
.05 cent shy of the contract's lifetime high. But buying interest
disappeared at that point and the April contract dropped to 72.67
cents on profit-taking late in the day, said Philip Stanley, an
analyst with Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in Chicago. Prices
rebounded before the close, however.
   Hog futures contracts advanced despite the week's slaughter of
nearly 1.68 million head, the largest weekly slaughter of the
spring. Frozen pork bellies settled mostly lower on indications of
growing supplies.
   Live cattle settled .13 cent to .40 cent higher with April at
73.32 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .03 cent to .45 cent higher
with March at 82 cents a pound; hogs were .25 cent lower to .10
cent higher with April at 43.25 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .45 cent lower to .70 cent higher with March at 51.20 cents a
pound.
   Gold and silver futures retreated on New York's Commodity
Exchange in reaction to the Labor Department's Producer Price Index
report showing a 0.2 percent drop in wholesale prices last month,
analysts said.
   Gold settled $1.80 to $2.60 lower with April at $442.20 a troy
ounce; silver was 3.5 cents to 8.7 cents lower with March at $6.23
a troy ounce.
   Grain and soybean futures settled mixed in lackluster trading on
the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Most soybean contracts advanced on higher soybean oil prices and
on talk that U.S. soybean plantings will not exceed 60 million
acres this year, analysts said.
   Traders have been worried about the possibility of a sharper
increase in planted soybean acreage, which totaled 57.4 million
acres in 1987.
   Wheat futures ended fractionally higher, corn was slightly lower
and oats closed modestly higher.
   Wheat settled unchanged to } cent higher with March at $2.90{ a
bushel; corn was \ cent to 1 cent lower with March at $1.96} a
bushel; oats were 2\ cents to 4} cents higher with March at $1.86 a
bushel; soybeans were { cent lower to 2 cents higher with March at
$6.03{ a bushel.
   Crude oil futures prices advanced above the $16-a-barrel level
reached Thursday on the New York Mercantile Exchange. Prices for
future delivery of distilled products also advanced.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 16 cents to 22 cents
higher with April at $16.20 a barrel; heating oil was .52 cent to
.85 cent higher with April at 44.45 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .27 cent to .47 cent higher with April at 45.60 cents
a gallon.
   Stock-index futures moved higher on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for March delivery of the Standard &
Poor's 500 index settled 2.70 points higher at 161.45. The
underlying spot index advanced 3.50 points, closing at 169.25.
</TEXT>
