<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SantaFe-Henley     03-11 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Santa Fe-Henley,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delaware Court Denies Henley Request for Injunction against Santa
Fe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Delaware chancery court judge Friday denied
Henley Group Inc.'s request for a preliminary injunction against
Santa Fe Southern Pacific Corp., clearing the way for Santa Fe's
restructuring plan to proceed.
   The legal action is the latest in a series of manuevers
involving Santa Fe and a pair of companies _ Henley and Olympia &
York of Toronto, Canada _ vying to take over the Chicago-based
railroad and energy conglomerate.
   The court's denial means Santa Fe will immediately begin issuing
debentures of $5 per share to stockholders who already received a
special cash dividend of $25 per share, Santa Fe spokesman Bob
Gehrt said.
   The debentures, at 16 percent interest, come due in 2004. The
payments are part of a restructuring plan aimed at thwarting a
hostile takeover bid from Henley of La Jolla, Calif.
   Henley had filed a lawsuit seeking an injunction to block
issuance of the debentures.
   The lawsuit also asked the court to declare Santa Fe's recently
enacted shareholder-rights plan invalid, to rescind the appointment
of two Olympia & York executives to the Santa Fe board, and to
allow Henley to propose an amendment that would make it possible
for Henley to elect a majority of directors at the Santa Fe's
annual meeting May 24.
   Vice Chancellor Jack B. Jacobs denied all four requests.
   ``We're studying the ruling and considering our alternatives,''
said Henley spokesman Norman Ritter.
   Olympia & York, controlled by the Canada's Reichmann family, had
launched a tender offer to boost its own holdings in Santa Fe, but
agreed to support the restructuring in exchange for board
representation.
</TEXT>
