<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Mulheren     03-11 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mulheren,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Releases Wall Street Speculator to Psychiatric
Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street speculator John Mulheren, accused of
plotting to kill convicted financier Ivan Boesky and a former
Boesky aide, arrived at a private psychiatric hospital Thursday
after a federal appeals court lifted an order preventing his
release from prison detention.
   Mulheren went to the Carrier Foundation in Belle Mead, N.J.,
following the morning ruling by the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in Manhattan.
   ``The family and John are delighted with the results and look
forward to the day when John can be home with them,'' said one of
Mulheren's attorneys, Otto Obermaier.
   The court denied the government's motion to continue holding
Mulheren in the Metropolitan Correctional Center, saying evidence
provided by a psychiatrist showed the speculator presented no
danger.
   The government had argued that the private facility was not
secure enough to house Mulheren, the senior partner at Jamie
Securities Co. and a former friend of Boesky, central figure in an
insider trading scandal.
   Mulheren, carrying a loaded assault rifle, was arrested Feb. 18
by the police outside his Rumson, N.J., home.
   He was charged with threatening to kill Boesky and Michael
Davidoff, Boesky's former head trader. The men reportedly have
implicated Mulheren in possible securities law violations.
   Mulheren's lawyers argue that he is a manic depressive who had
failed to take a drug used to control impulses.
</TEXT>
