<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 1933EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AtkinsSentencing     03-11 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Atkins Sentencing,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Atkins Sentenced to Two Years in Prison, Four Years Probation in
Tax Fraud</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles Agee Atkins, the convicted promoter of a
billion-dollar tax scheme that attracted celebrities, was sentenced
Friday to two years in prison and four years' probation.
   Atkins told U.S. District Judge Morris Lasker that he felt
``deep remorse and I accept the responsibility for what occurred.''
   Lasker told Atkins that he felt the defendant was the ``most
culpable'' of the three defendants, but noted that he had received
hundreds of letters on his behalf.
   A co-defendant, William Hack, was sentenced to four months in
prison, four years, eight months on probation and fined $25,000.
The judge ordered him to perform 1,000 hours a year in community
service during probation.
   The third co-defendant, Ernest Grunebaum, was given a six-month
suspended sentence, probation of five years and ordered to do 400
hours of community service a year during probation.
   They remained free on bail and their sentences were stayed by
the judge pending the outcome of their appeals, according to James
A. Moss, Atkins' attorney.
   A 31-count indictment in March 1987 accused the three of
creating more than $1.3 billion in fraudulent losses and interest
expenses while trading in Treasury bill futures and other
government securities.
   Those losses generated more than $350 million in bogus tax
deductions for the investors, among them actor Michael Landon, the
late Andy Warhol and Postmaster General Preston R. Tisch.
   Others include Tisch's brother, CBS President and Chief
Executive Laurence A. Tisch, the late Lorne Greene, television
producer Norman Lear and actor Sidney Poitier.
   Lasker also sentenced Atkins to spend the first six months of
probation at a community center and then do 500 hours a year of
community service for the remaining time. Moss said the center is a
halfway house for those getting out of prison.
   The three were convicted in December of conspiring to defraud
the Internal Revenue Service; they could have received five years
in prison on that count alone.
   Atkins, of Amelia Island Plantation, Fla., also was convicted of
27 other tax-related counts; Hack, of New York City, was convicted
of three; Grunebaum, of Chappaqua, N.Y., was convicted on 13 more
counts. Grunebaum was acquitted on two counts.
   Those who invested are not accused of wrongdoing but will have
to square accounts with the IRS about back taxes on the $4 in tax
deductions they were supposed to get for every $1 invested.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
