<DOCNO> AP880311-0326 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 1946EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Farmers-BATUS     03-11 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farmers-BATUS,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Orders Farmers Group to Put BATUS Proposal Before
Shareholders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge in Nevada on Friday ordered
insurer Farmers Group Inc. to put a merger proposal from unwanted
suitor BATUS Inc. before shareholders at Farmers' annual meeting
May 20.
   The court also ordered Farmers to make its shareholder lists
available to BATUS by next Wednesday so BATUS can effectively
solicit proxies for its proposal.
   However, the judge did instruct that the non-binding proposal be
revised to recommend only that Farmers' board reconsider its
decision not to negotiate with Louisville, Ky.-based BATUS, the
U.S. subsidiary of BAT Industries PLC of Britain.
   As initially drafted, BATUS' proposal recommended that Farmers
immediately enter negotiations with BATUS.
   Earlier this month, BATUS began a hostile $63-a-share, or $4.4
billion, tender offer after its initial friendly overtures were
spurned by Farmers. The offer expires March 30.
   BATUS said it was ``very pleased'' with the court action, which
requires Farmers to include BATUS' negotiation proposal in Farmers'
proxy cards being sent to shareholders for the annual meeting.
   In a separate statement, Farmers didn't go beyond outlining the
decision and reiterating its opposition to BATUS' takeover effort.
   Farmers, based in Los Angeles, filed suit in Nevada because that
is where it is incorporated.
   The judge's decision came just one day after Farmers' board of
directors unanimously rejected the BATUS offer as inadequate and
urged its shareholders to do likewise.
   Farmers said Thursday it was exploring a variety of alternatives
to a BATUS takeover, including restructuring or merging with
another company, adding that it has held discussions with an
unidentified third party about a possible leveraged buyout.
   BATUS has asked repeatedly to meet with Farmers management to
discuss all conditions of its takeover bid including price, but
Farmers has said it is not interested in such a meeting and
believes BATUS' offer is substantially less than the company is
worth.
   Farmers is the nation's third-largest home and auto insurer
after State Farm and Allstate and is the seventh-largest property
and casualty insurer.
</TEXT>
