<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Thiokol-Layoffs     03-11 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thiokol-Layoffs,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thiokol Cuts Space Division Work Force</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIGHAM CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA reductions in shuttle redesign
efforts have been blamed for Morton Thiokol Inc.'s layoff of more
than 100 workers from its Space Division.
   Morton Thiokol spokesman Rocky Raab said Friday that another 100
employees have been transferred from the division to other jobs in
the company's Wasatch Operations.
   The Space Division has a work force of more than 2,600.
   Raab said the layoffs came after the company learned NASA is
going to limit some small-scale tests and other analyses in the
shuttle redesign efforts.
   However, none of the large-scale tests will be cut, he said.
   The company has been working on a redesigned shuttle booster
rocket since the Jan. 28, 1986, Challenger disaster. A presidential
commission blamed a leaking rocket seal for igniting the explosion
that destroyed the shuttle and killed its seven-member crew.
   Meantime, Morton Thiokol also is reorganizing management in its
Strategic Division to improve safety control and efficiency, Raab
said.
   Two other divisions under the Aerospace Group, tactical and
automotive products, won't be affected by the changes, he said.
   Raab offered few details of the management restructuring, but
the Standard-Examiner reported Friday that a Morton Thiokol
employee, who asked to remain anonymous, said the move was at least
partially due to the Dec. 29, 1987, fire at an MX missile motor
plant that killed five workers.
   ``I think that put the icing on the cake,'' said the employee.
</TEXT>
