<FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 0715EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Greenspan     03-11 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Greenspan,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greenspan Asks Deficit Reduction, Hold On Taxes, Inflation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation must take ``bold controversial
actions'' to control federal spending in order to reduce the huge
budget deficit, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said
Thursday.
   Greenspan also indicated the Fed would continue making the
battle against high inflation the cornerstone of its long-term
monetary policy.
   Greenspan, at a luncheon of the Federal Reserve's 12th District
banks, emphasized that future federal budget cuts _ not tax
increases _ would be a major factor in bringing down the massive
deficit.
   Hiking taxes ``carries with it the risk that expenditures also
will be raised, and that the resulting deficit improvement will be
small,'' Greenspan said.
   He referred to the tax resistance movement of the 1970s, chiefly
triggered by California's successful tax-limiting Proposition 13
ballot initiative.
   Greenspan _ who previously has called for slashing the budget
deficit _ reiterated the Federal Reserve's recent report to
Congress that gross national product was expected to grow by 2.5
percent in 1988, while time prices were expected to climb between 3
percent and 4 percent.
   The nation could not count on continued foreign capital inflows
to help finance the deficit, Greenspan said, calling such a trend
``neither a satisfactory nor a sustainable solution over the long
run.''
   Greenspan also said that keeping inflation pressures under
control was critical to continued progress in reducing the deficit.
   ``In this regard, monetary policy must maintain, as a long-run
objective, establishing reasonable price stability,'' he said.
   Greenspan praised what he said was the public's alertness to the
dangers of inflation, and said he sensed ``there is still a deep
reservoir of support for policies to keep inflation in check.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
